<html><head><title>The Arc's Q&A on Residential Options</title></head><body>

<h1> Residential Options for People with Mental </h1>

<p><strong> How have our beliefs about living arrangements for people with mental retardation changed over the years? </strong></p>

<p> Years ago all people with mental retardation remained in the family home, usually hidden from public view.  Then in the 1800s, large institutions were built where people could live protected lives and pose no risk to society.  </p>
<p> Eventually, advocates realized people in institutions were prevented from enjoying the diversity of community life.  In the late 1960s and early 1970s, a movement began to provide opportunities for everyone to live in the community.  Group homes and other community residential programs were developed to serve people even with the most severe mental retardation, behavioral or physical disabilities. </p>
<p> A new concern emerged in the 1980s.  Many community residential programs were criticized because they had, to a large extent, simply transferred institutional practices to the community.  Many residents remained isolated and dependent on paid staff instead of becoming active participants in their communities.  Advocates are now exploring new ways to support people with mental retardation in choosing the kind of home they want to live in and enabling them to live as independently as they desire.  On the following list of options, this is referred to as "own home."  It may also be referred to as "supported living." </p>

<p><strong> What community residential options exist today for people with mental retardation? </strong></p>

<p> A variety of options currently exist.  The most common are described below: </p>
<p> Group home.  Staff provide care, supervision and training for one to eight nonrelated people with mental retardation. </p>
<p> Supervised home or apartment.  People live alone or with roommates in semi-independent units or apartments.  Staff live in a separate unit in the same location.   </p>
<p> Adult foster care.  One or more people with mental retardation live with a family who provides care as needed.   </p>
<p> Personal care home.  Staff provide assistance with dressing, bathing or other personal care, but provide no training for residents. </p>
<p> Board-and-care home.  A staff-supervised program that provides sleeping rooms and meals.  Staff do not provide formal training or assist with dressing, bathing or other usual personal care. </p>
<p> Nursing home.  A facility for people who have extensive health care needs.  Nursing homes provide daily nursing care but little or no training. </p>
<p> Own home.  People with mental retardation live in the same kinds of housing as other people in the community, including apartments, condominiums, rented or owned houses, mobile homes and so on.  They are provided supports based on their individual needs and wishes. </p>

<p><strong> How many people are being provided residential services? </strong></p>

<p> The University of Minnesota Research and Training Center on Residential Services and Community Living periodically collects data on state licensed or operated residential services for people with mental retardation and related conditions.  In 1992, 294,026 people with mental retardation and related conditions were receiving residential services.  Of these, 210,132 (71.5%)  received services from nonstate organizations, and 83,894 (28.5%) received services from state-operated facilities (Mangan et al., 1994). </p>

<p><strong> In what size residences are people living? </strong></p>

<p> In 1992, 59 percent (173,683) of all people in the survey were living in settings with 15 or fewer people (Mangan et al., 1994).  Forty-one percent (119,675) were living in residences with six or fewer people.  Forty-one percent, or 120,343 people with mental retardation and related conditions, live in settings of 16 or more people, both private and state-operated. </p>

<p><strong> What is happening to large state institutions providing residential services to people with mental retardation? </strong></p>

<p> The number of people living in large state institutions is declining each year, and states are gradually closing such state-operated institutions.  In 1992, 74,538 people lived in large, state-operated residential facilities (Mangan et al., 1994).  A recent survey estimates that before the end of 1993, the number of individuals residing in large, state-operated residential facilities will have declined to slightly under 71,000 (Carson, 1993).  Over the past several years, the population decline has been about 4 percent annually. </p>
<p> From 1960 to 1992, 84 large state institutions closed; an additional 38 institutions are projected to close by 1996.  New Hampshire was the first state to totally close its institutions, followed by Vermont and Rhode Island.  Michigan and the District of Columbia plan to close all their institutions by the end of 1996 (Mangan et al., 1994). </p>

<p><strong> Who are the people remaining in large state institutions? </strong></p>

<p> People with extensive needs for support comprise an increasing percentage of the total remaining population.  In 1977, 75 percent of people with mental retardation in institutions were labeled with "severe" or "profound" mental retardation.  By 1991, 84 percent of people remaining in institutions had that label.  However, while the proportion of persons with extensive needs for supports in state institutions increased, the actual number decreased between 1977 and 1991 by about 17,500 persons (Lakin et al., 1993).   </p>

<p><strong> How have people who moved out of institutions adjusted to life in the community? </strong></p>

<p> An analysis of 18 studies of individuals' ability to adapt to life in community settings revealed significant improvement in either overall adaptive behavior or in the basic self-help/domestic domain associated with movement to the community (Larson & Lakin, 1989).  Parents reported a positive impact of the community setting on their sons or daughters.  Parents also thought the services and qualities of the environment were better (Larson & Lakin, 1991). </p>

<p><strong> How much is spent per person for residential services? </strong></p>

<p> The dollar costs per person each day for residential services varies widely from state to state.  For instance, the daily cost per person for small state-operated programs in New York averages $264.75.  Large state-operated residential programs in New York average $350.00.  In Texas small and large state-operated programs average $109.00 and $166.73 respectively.  On a national average, small state-operated programs cost $250.16 per person, per day; and large state-operated programs cost $210.88 (Mangan et al., 1994).  The national average yearly cost per person in small, state-operated programs is $91,308.  In large, state-operated programs, the national average yearly cost per person is to $76,971. </p>

<p><strong> What are the public expenditures for institutional and community services? </strong></p>

<p> In 1992 institutional services (all residential programs serving 16 people or more) in the United States cost $7.5 billion.  This expenditure included all operating funds for state institutions, large private residential centers, developmental centers, training centers, state schools and mental retardation units in state hospitals.  The federal government contributed approximately 50 percent of institutional costs while the individual states picked up the rest (Braddock et al., 1994).   </p>
<p> The cost of community-based services (residential programs serving 15 or fewer people) was $9.7 billion with the states contributing 67 percent and the federal government contributing 33 percent of the total costs.   </p>
<p> The federal government contributes more to institutional services than community-based services.  In 1992, the federal share was about $3.7 billion for 123,690 people in large public and private institutions and $3.2 billion for 170,072 people in community-based residences.  The federal share of the cost of large institutional services increased from 26 to 50 percent between 1977-1992. </p>

<p><strong> What about waiting lists for community residential services? </strong></p>

<p> Surveys conducted in 1987 (The Arc) and 1991 (University of Minnesota) identified approximately 61,000-67,000 individuals with mental retardation and related disabilities on waiting lists for residential services.   </p>
<p> Based on the estimated 4.3 to 5.2 million adults with mental retardation in the United States, it is apparent that most adults with mental retardation live independently or with their families.  The 294,026 identified as recipients of state-licensed and state-operated residential services represent only 6-7 percent of the total population of people with mental retardation. </p>

<p><strong> References </strong></p>
<p> Braddock, D.L., Hemp, R., Bachelder, L. & Fujiura, G.  (1994).  Fourth National Study of Public Spending for Mental Retardation and Developmental Disabilities in the United States:: Summary of the Study (A Working Paper): Chicago: The University of Illinois at Chicago, University Affiliated Program in Developmental Disabilities. </p>
<p> Carson, S.A. Ed.  (June 1993).  ICF/MR Services: Present Status and Recent Trends.  New Directions.  Alexandria, VA: National Association of State Directors of Developmental Disabilities Services. </p>
<p> Lakin, K.C., Blake, E.M., Prouty, R.W., Mangan, T., & Bruininks, R.H. (1993).  Residential Services for Persons with Developmental Disabilities: Status and Trends Through 1991.  Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Center on Residential Services and Community Living, Institute on Community Integration/UAP. </p>
<p> Larson, S.A. &  Lakin, C.K. Deinstitutionalization of Persons with Mental Retardation: Behavioral Outcomes.  (1989). JASH, 14, 324-332. </p>
<p> Larson, S.A. &  Lakin, C.K. (1991).  Parent Attitudes About Residential Placement Before and After Deinstitutionalization: A Research Synthesis.  JASH, 16, 25-38. </p>
<p> Mangan, T., Blake, E.M., Prouty, R.W., & Lakin, K.C. (1994). Residential Services for Persons with Mental Retardation and Related Conditions: Status and Trends Through 1992. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Research and Training Center on Residential Services and Community Living, Institute on Community Integration/UAP. </p>
<p> The Arc (1988).  A Status Report on Waiting Lists for Community Services.  Q&A.  Arlington, TX </p>
<p> University of Minnesota (1992). Adults with Mental Retardation and Other Developmental Disabilities Waiting for Community-Based Services in the United States. Policy Research Brief. Minneapolis, MN: Center on Residential Services and Community Living. </p>
<p> Related publications from The Arc.  To receive single copies, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope:  </p>
<ul>
<li> Community Living. Q&A. </li>
<li> A Home of One's Own. Community Integration Report. </li>
</ul>

