<html><head><title>The Arc's Q&A on HIV / AIDS and Mental Retardation</title></head><body>
<center><H1>HIV / AIDS and Mental Retardation</H1></center>
 
 <P><I>Marc Lerro, M.L.A.
 <br>Project Director, HIV Prevention Project</I>
 
 <P><B>What is AIDS?</B>
 
 <P>AIDS stands for Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome.  It is a disease caused by 
 the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV), the AIDS virus.
 
 <P>HIV may live in the human body for years before it causes noticeable signs of 
 illness.  It makes people unable to fight other diseases, and these other diseases can 
 be fatal.  Someone with HIV infection might look normal and feel healthy, but the 
 virus is still present.  Once a person is infected with HIV, he or she is infected for 
 life.
 
 <P>The AIDS / HIV epidemic appeared in the 1970s and 1980s.  HIV is now present in 
 countries around the world.  It has already infected millions of people, and the 
 numbers are still rising.
 
<P><B> How do people get the AIDS virus?</B>
 
 <P>There are three ways to get HIV, the AIDS virus.  First, someone can become 
 infected by having sex with a person who already has HIV.  The AIDS virus can be 
 spread during oral, vaginal, or anal sex with an infected person.
 
 <P>Second, someone can get HIV by getting infected blood in her or his body.  If a 
 person shares drug needles and syringes with an infected individual, he or she can 
 get the AIDS virus.
 
 <P>Finally, babies of HIV-infected women may be born with the infection.  HIV can be 
 transmitted before or during birth.  If the woman breast feeds her baby, she may 
 transmit the AIDS virus during feeding.
 
 <P><B>What about people with mental retardation and HIV?</B>
 
 <P>The HIV / AIDS epidemic has a strong impact on people with mental retardation in 
 two ways.
 
 <P>First, adults with mental retardation may be the victims of sexual abuse and sexual 
 exploitation.  In the age of safer sex, some people refuse to take precautions.  
 Sometimes, their sexual partners are adults with mental retardation.  One study 
 identified 45 adults with mental retardation and advanced HIV infection or AIDS in 
 44 states (Marchetti, et al., 1989), but it is estimated that hundreds of such cases 
 already exist.  People living in group settings, as well as people living 
 independently, are at risk.
 
 <P>Second, babies born with HIV infections are living longer than ever before, but as 
 they grow, 90 percent have neurological impairment or mental retardation 
 (Ultmann et al., 1987).  HIV infection is a cause of mental retardation.
 
 <P><B>What about testing?</B>
 
 <P>When a person is infected with HIV, his or her immune system begins producing 
 HIV antibodies.  Blood tests for HIV antibodies are widely available throughout the 
 United States.  These blood tests are not AIDS tests.  They are tests for HIV 
 antibodies.  The tests are highly reliable, but not perfect.  If someone gets an HIV 
 antibody test within a few weeks of infection, the test results may indicate no sign 
 of antibodies even though the person is infected.  Counseling by a trained 
 professional should always accompany HIV antibody testing.
 
 <P>In most communities, the local health department or blood bank can provide 
 counseling and testing at a low cost.  Physicians or private health care providers 
 may charge more for the same services.
 
 <P>Testing for HIV antibodies does nothing to prevent the spread of the disease.  Only 
 changing behaviors can stop the spread of HIV and AIDS.
 
 <P><B>Why not isolate people who are infected?</B>
 
 <P>There are serious legal and ethical reasons against isolating people with HIV 
 infection or AIDS, but there are also several practical reasons against quarantine.
 
 <P>Isolating adults or children with HIV infection will not stop the epidemic. Too many 
 people around the world have HIV.  It is impossible to regularly test everyone or to 
 build and maintain the quarantine facilities that would be necessary.
 
 <P>In the United States alone, it is estimated that over one million people are already 
 infected with HIV, with more people becoming infected every day.  In general, these 
 people are living longer, healthier lives, thanks to advances in drug therapies and 
 healthier lifestyles.  It is hoped that one day AIDS will become a chronic disease, 
 such as diabetes, and may be controlled throughout a persons lifetime.
 
 <P><B>Can people with mental retardation protect themselves from HIV?</B>
 
 <P>Yes.  In communities around the country, people with mental retardation are 
 learning how to protect themselves from the AIDS virus and other sexually 
 transmitted diseases.  Materials designed by The Arc and other organizations are 
 used to teach safer sex and to reinforce appropriate behaviors.  People are learning 
 about their sexual rights and their sexual responsibilities.  Some people learn faster 
 than others, and some people require patience and encouragement as they learn to 
 make safer choices.
 
 <P>Materials should always be clear.  They should be presented sensitively by trained 
 individuals.  Safer sex training should never be forced upon someone who is 
 unwilling to participate.  Because of the sexual nature of the information, training 
 is best offered in small groups or in individual sessions.
 
 <P><B>What are the sexual rights and responsibilities of people with mental 
 retardation?</B>
 
 <P>The Arcs Position Statement on Sexuality adopted by the delegate body states that 
 The Arc believes that people with mental retardation have the right on an 
 individual basis to:
 
<UL>
<LI>have privacy
<LI>love and be loved
<LI>develop friendships and emotional relationships
<LI>choose friends
<LI>learn about sex, sexual problems, sexual abuse, safe sex, and other issues 
<LI>regarding sexuality
<LI>exercise their rights and responsibilities in regard to privacy, sexual expression, 
<LI>and the pursuit of happiness
<LI>marry and have children
</UL>

 
<P> The position also states that education should be available for people of all ages to 
 assist in and, where appropriate, teach expressions of sexuality and responsible 
 sexual behaviors with respect for the rights of others.  People with mental 
 retardation should be educated and receive proper supports to protect themselves 
 from abuse, exploitation, unwanted pregnancy and sexually transmitted diseases 
 while safeguarding dignity and rights (The Arc, 1990).
 
 <P>Any individual with a communicable disease such as HIV has a responsibility to 
 attempt, to the best of his or her ability, to prevent the spread of the disease.  Since 
 HIV presents no signs of illness for months or years after infection, people who have 
 been sexually active with others may be infected.  They should consider whether an 
 HIV antibody test is appropriate.  Sexually active adults should know about safer 
 sex, and should use safer sex unless they are attempting to have a child or are 
 certain that they and their partners have no serious communicable disease.
 
 <P>Women who are thinking about having a baby should talk with their doctors and 
 consider HIV antibody testing before they become pregnant.  If a pregnant woman 
 learns she is infected with HIV, she should also be informed that her baby may or 
 may not be infected.  Not all babies born to HIV-infected women will themselves be 
 infected.
 
 <P><B>What is safer sex?</B>
 
<P> The only fully safe sex is no sex.  That is why people use the term safer sex.  
 Safer sex involves activities which lower the risk of infection with the AIDS virus 
 and other diseases.  Safer sex also reduces the risk of unwanted pregnancy.
 
 <P>Safer sex involves limiting the number of ones sexual partners, minimizing the 
 exchange of body fluids, using water-based lubricants and latex (rubber) condoms, 
 and minimizing the use of drugs or alcohol to enhance sex.  Safer sex includes 
 massage, masturbation, and licking or kissing healthy, unbroken skin.
 
 <P>Safer sex minimizes the exchange of semen, vaginal secretions and blood, body 
 fluids containing high concentrations of HIV.  The risk of infection from other body 
 fluids is extremely low or nonexistent.  Reducing exposure to semen, blood and 
 vaginal secretions during sex almost eliminates the risk of sexually transmitted 
 diseases.
 
 <P><B>What is dangerous, and what is safer?</B>
 
 <P>Dangerous activities include:
<UL>
<LI> unprotected vaginal intercourse (without a latex condom)
<LI> unprotected anal intercourse (with a latex condom)
<LI> ingesting urine or semen
<LI> injecting drugs
<LI> sharing drug needles
<LI> inserting unprotected fingers into partner
<LI> oral-anal contact
</UL>

 
<P> Risky activities include:
<UL>
<LI> oral sex without a condom
<LI> wet kissing
<LI> masturbation on broken skin/cuts
<LI> oral sex on a woman
<LI> alcohol, marijuana, other drugs
</UL>

 
 <P>Safer activities:
 <UL>
<LI> protected vaginal intercourse (with a latex condom)
<LI> protected anal intercourse (with a latex condom)
</UL>

 
 <P>Much safer activities:
<UL>
<LI> dry kissing
<LI> masturbation / mutual masturbation
<LI> oral sex with a condom
<LI> urine or semen on healthy skin
<LI> touching, hugging, massage
<LI> fantasy
</UL>

<P><I>(adapted from the American College Health Association)</I>
 
 <P><B>References</B>
 
 <P>American College Health Association.  (1987) Making sex safer, (1989) Safe sex.
 <P>The Arc (1990).  Position statement on sexuality.
 <P>Marchetti, A.G., Nathanson, R.S., Kastner, T.A. (1989).  AIDS and developmental 
 disability agencies:  A national survey.  American Journal of Public Health.
 <P>Ultmann, M.H., Diamon, G.W., Ruff, H.A., Belman, A.L., Novick, B.E., Rubinstein, 
 A., & Cohen, H.J. (1987).  Developmental abnormalities in children with acquired 
 immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS):  A follow-up study.  International Journal of 
 Neuroscience, 32, 661-667.
 
<P> <B>Resources</B>
 
 <P>National HIV and AIDS Information Service 
   <br>Education, information, referrals
   <br>1-800-342-AIDS (English)
<br>   1-800-344-SIDA (Spanish)
<br>   1-800-AIDS-TTY (Deaf)
<P> National AIDS Clearinghouse
<br>   Database of materials, services, bulk literature
<br>   1-800-458-5231
 <P>CDC Grant #H62\CCH604497-03
 

<P>Call or write The Arc for HIV and mental retardation materials:
<hr>
<p><em>The Arc<br>National Headquarters<br>P.O. Box 1047<br>Arlington, Texas 76004<br>(817)261-6003<br>(817)277-0553 TDD<br><a href="mailto:thearc@metronet.com">thearc@metronet.com</a> (e-mail)</em></p>

<P> August 1991

