<html><heading><title>The Arc's Q&A on Immunizations</title></heading><body>



<center><H1>Facts About Childhood Immunizations</H1></center>





<P><B>Why are immunizations important for all children?</B>



<P>There are now nine contagious diseases for which there are effective childhood vaccines.  However, three in 10 infants and toddlers are going without adequate childhood immunizations, leaving them at risk for life-threatening or disabling illnesses.  In 1990, for example, almost 28,000 cases of measles were reported in the United States, and 89 children died.



<P>Unnecessary outbreaks of preventable childhood diseases must be eliminated.  Children can be vaccinated against measles, mumps, rubella, polio, diphtheria, pertussis (whooping cough), tetanus, haemophilus influenza type b (Hib disease), and hepatitis B through a series of shots beginning as early as birth.  Children should have most of their vaccinations in their first two years.  Waiting until they enter school may be too late.





<P><B>What vaccines protect against these nine diseases?</B>



<P>DTP (Diphtheria and tetanus toxoids and pertussis vaccine) protects against the following diseases:

<UL>

<LI><B>Diphtheria (the D of the DTP vaccine)</B> is a very serious disease easily spread through coughing and sneezing.  Early symptoms are a sore throat, fever, and a grayish film in the throat.  It can make a person unable to breathe, cause paralysis or heart failure.  About one out of every 10 people who get diphtheria dies of it.  Only a few cases of diphtheria were reported in the United States during the past few years.  This is mostly because people have had shots to protect them.
<br>
<br>

<LI><B>Tetanus (the T of the DTP vaccine)</B>, sometimes called lockjaw, is a life-threatening disease that can occur after a cut or wound lets the germ into the body.  It makes a person unable to open his or her mouth or swallow, and causes serious muscle spasms.  People with tetanus usually have to stay in the hospital a long time.  In the United States, tetanus kills three out of every 10 people who get the disease.  Since 1975, only 50-90 cases of tetanus have been reported each year.  Almost no cases occur in children or young adults because they have taken the shots and are usually protected.
<br>
<br>
<LI><B>Pertussis (the P of the DTP vaccine)</B>, sometimes called whooping cough, may be a mild or serious disease.  It is easily passed from one person to another.  Pertussis can cause spells of coughing and choking that make it hard to eat, drink or breathe.  The coughing can last for several weeks. Pertussis is most dangerous to babies who are often so sick they must go to the hospital.  As many as 16 babies out of 100 get pneumonia, and as many as two out of 100 may have convulsions.  Pertussis causes brain problems that may last a lifetime in one of 200 babies.  About 4,200 cases of pertussis are reported annually in the United States. 
<br>
<br>

<LI><B>Polio Vaccine protects children against polio</B>, a very dangerous disease caused by a virus.  Some children and adults who get a serious case of polio become paralyzed.  Some may need a machine to help them breathe.  They may even die from the disease.  Mild cases of polio may last only a few days and may cause the person to have a fever, sore throat, stomachache and headache.  There are no drugs or special treatments that will cure people who get polio. Although there are few cases of polio in the United States now, there are still many thousands each year in other countries.  Therefore, it is important to protect children with the vaccine so that they cannot get the disease when someone brings the virus into the United States from another country.
<br>
<br>

<LI>MMR vaccine protects children against measles, mumps and rubella.  

<br>

<br><B>- Measles</B> is a serious disease very easily passed from one person to another.  It causes a high fever, cough, and a rash and lasts for one to two weeks.  One out of every 10 children who catch measles will also have an ear infection or pneumonia.   Measles can also cause an infection of the brain (encephalitis) that could lead to convulsions, hearing loss and mental retardation.  This happens to about one out of every 1,000 children who get it.  In recent years, 3,000 to 28,000 cases of measles have been reported yearly in the United States.  One child out of every 500 to 10,000 who gets measles dies from it.   

<br>

<br><B>- Mumps</B> causes fever, headache and swollen, painful glands under the jaw.  Mumps sometimes can be a very serious disease and is easily passed from person to person.  It can cause a mild inflammation of the coverings of the brain and spinal cord (meningitis) in about one person in every 10 who gets it.  Swelling or inflammation of the brain is reported in about one case out of every 200.  Before there was a mumps vaccine, many children had hearing loss caused by mumps.  In recent years, 4,500 to 13,000 cases of mumps have been reported in the United States, and outbreaks still occur.  

<br>

<br><B>- Rubella</B> is also called German measles.  It is usually a mild disease that lasts a short time.  People who catch rubella usually have mild fever, swollen glands in the neck, and a rash that last up to three days.  Rubella may cause soreness in the joints and swelling of the joints (arthritis). If a pregnant woman catches the disease, it is very dangerous to her unborn baby.  Up to half the women who catch rubella when they are pregnant will lose their babies or have babies born with heart disease, or babies who will be blind or deaf or who have mental retardation.  People who do not get the rubella vaccine are in danger of catching rubella and passing it on to a pregnant woman.  About one out of every 10 women in the United States is not protected against rubella.
<br><br>
<LI><B>Hib vaccine</B> protects children against Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib disease), a common cause of bacterial meningitis.  The Hib bacteria primarily attacks children under age 5.  The illness often starts out mimicking the symptoms of a cold or earache.  In some children, symptoms of meningitis develop rapidly.  Even with prompt treatment, about one in 20 children dies of the illness.  Of those who survive, 25 to 35 percent suffer permanent brain damage, including mental retardation.  Prior to the time the vaccine became available, one in every 200 children contracted Hib disease within the first five years of life.

<br><br>
<LI><B>Hepatitis B vaccine (HBV)</B> protects children against the hepatitis B virus which causes an inflammation of the liver.  Symptoms include jaundice (yellowing of the skin), poor appetite, weight loss and dark urine.  Most people get better on their own, but one in 10 people develops a chronic infection, often leading to cirrhosis or liver cancer.  Hospitalization is required in 5 percent of the cases, and one person in 1,000 will die due to direct consequences of the disease.  Although victims of the disease are almost always adults, infants born to hepatitis B infected mothers have up to an 85 percent chance of getting the infection.  They should be given a complete series of shots starting at birth.

</UL>

<P>In 1991, the Immunizations Practices Advisory Committee of the Public Health Service recommended that all children be vaccinated.  The Centers for Disease Control estimates that from 200,000 to 300,000 cases occur annually, because adults have been reluctant to get the vaccine that has been on the market for over 10 years.



<P><B>What schedule is recommended for the above vaccines?</B>



<P>The schedule for childhood vaccinations recommended by the Public Health Service's Immunization Practices Advisory Committee is as follows. 

<UL>

<LI>Birth - HBV - if your doctor recommends

<LI>2 months - DTP, Polio, Hib, HBV

<LI>4 months - DTP, Polio, Hib, HBV - if your doctor recommends

<LI>6 months - DTP, Hib - if your doctor recommends

<LI>6-18 months- HBV

<LI>12 months - Hib - if your doctor recommends

<LI>15 months - DTP, Polio, MMR, Hib - if your doctor recommends

<LI>4-6 years - DTP, Polio, MMR

</UL>

<P><B>Do these vaccines have side effects?</B>              



<P>Reactions to the vaccines may occur, but they are rarely serious.  They are usually mild and brief, such as low fever, sore arm, or malaise after taking the shot.



<P>Health care providers should inform parents about the benefits and risks of a specific vaccine before immunizing their child.  The National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act required the government to prepare written materials on the benefits and risks of vaccines for diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, measles, mumps, rubella and polio in order for parents to be able to make informed choices about their child's vaccinations.  Effective April 1992, health care providers must provide written information to each adult or to the legal representative of each child before administering these vaccines.

<P>Vaccines work best when they are given at the recommended time and on a regular schedule.  All health officials agree that the benefits of vaccination are greater than the small risk of possible side effects from the vaccine.





<P><B>What is being done to improve the immunization protection of the nation's children?</B>



<P>Several private and public national efforts are being implemented to help achieve universal immunization of all children.  These include:

<P><B>The Public Health Service Action Plan to Improve Access to Immunization Services.</B>  The Interagency Committee to Improve Access to Immunization Services (ICI) developed a plan for improving immunization services nationwide by (a) increasing coordination among federal health, income, housing, education and nutrition programs; (b) reducing barriers that limit access to immunizations for many people; and (c) strengthening the system for providing vaccinations.

<P><B>The National Immunization Campaign</B> is a project to educate families about immunization and to make sure that children - especially babies - get the vaccinations and regular health care they need.  The campaign is a partnership of the Children's Action Network and the American Academy of Pediatrics and has produced a colorful brochure for parents.



<P><B>Child Health Day</B> is celebrated annually by a coalition of private and federal agencies concerned with children's health.  The theme selected for the 1992 celebration of Child Health Day, Oct. 5, is childhood immunization that is age-appropriate and complete.  The aim is to promote the importance of universal immunization of children in communities across the nation.



<P><B>Resources</B>

<P>Available from The Arc: 

<UL>

<LI>Facts About Hib Disease

<LI>Facts About Hepatitis B

<LI>You and Your Baby.

</UL>



<P>Available from the National Immunization Campaign:

<UL>

<LI>10 Questions & Answers About How to Help Protect Your Child from Getting Deadly Diseases - a free brochure for parents available in quantities in English or Spanish by calling 800-525-6789.

</UL>

<P>Available from your Public Health Department:

<UL>

<LI>Measles, Mumps, and Rubella - What You Need to Know;

<LI>Polio - What You Need to Know;

<LI>Diphtheria, Tetanus, and Pertussis - What You Need to Know.

</UL>

<HR>

