<html><head><title>The Arc's Q&A on Healthy People 2000</title></head><body>
<center><H1>Healthy People 2000 and Mental Retardation</H1></center>

<P><I>by Jeri Nelson, M.D.</I>

<P><B>What is Healthy People 2000?</B>

<P>Healthy People 2000 is a ten-year plan consisting of 298 national health objectives concerned with reducing preventable death, disease and disabilities in children and adults.  More than 270 national organizations and 50 state health departments participated in the three-year effort to develop these objectives.  These organizations form the Healthy People 2000 Consortium which continues to provide the core of support for achieving the objectives.  

<P>The U. S. Public Health Service hopes that having a national set of common objectives will create a more unified effort to achieve healthier lives for Americans in the targeted health areas.  Many consortium members have already initiated activities to help achieve the objectives.


<P><B>Why is the Healthy People 2000 Project important to The Arc?</B>


<P>
The Arc participated in the development of the health objectives and is a member of the consortium.  We advocated for goals which would reduce the incidence of disabilities and promote good health in individuals with disabilities.  Such goals, because of their inclusion, will have state, federal and local support toward their attainment.


<P>
<B>How do the objectives deal with health promotion for people with mental retardation?
</B>

<P>
Healthy People 2000 recognizes that certain populations have "above average incidences of death, disease and disability."  These populations are defined specifically as low-income groups, minority groups and people with disabilities.  Mental retardation is one among a vast array of disabilities.  All objectives toward improving health in the general population relate to people with disabilities: for example, reducing dietary fat, reducing coronary heart disease deaths, and reducing periodontal disease.


<P>
There is a specific objective for the establishment of  services in all 50 states which would allow children with or at risk of chronic and disabling conditions to have access to comprehensive, community-based, coordinated, and family-centered services.  These services will help prevent chronic and disabling conditions, reverse or slow the progress of existing conditions and minimize the impact of the conditions in children.  Such services will also strengthen the ability of families to care for children with chronic and disabling conditions at home.


<P>
Another objective seeks to improve physical and mental health as a by-product of high quality and developmentally appropriate preschool programs for children with disabilities.  There is even an objective to increase the number of worksites that have an established policy or program for hiring people with disabilities.  Working people with disabilities are more satisfied with life and have better access to health insurance coverage and worksite health promotion programs.


<P>
<B>How do the objectives address prevention of mental retardation?</B>


<P>
Preventive health care is a priority of Healthy People 2000, and there are a number of objectives directed at prevention of disabilities.  


<P>
One objective specifically calls for reducing the prevalence of serious mental retardation in school-aged children to not more than 2 per 1,000 children by the year 2000.  Based on a Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) study in metropolitan Atlanta, 2.7 per 1,000 children aged 10 have serious mental retardation, an IQ less than 50.  Some approaches suggested to attain the goal are the provision of early intervention services to children with conditions associated with serious mental retardation, screening and treatment for phenylketonuria and hypothyroidism in newborns and reducing the incidence of clinical disorders that are associated with mental retardation.  


<P>
<B>What are some other specific prevention objectives of interest to The Arc?</B>

<UL>
<LI>Reduce the incidence of fetal alcohol syndrome to no more than 0.12 per 1,000 live births.  CDC's Birth Defects Monitoring System recorded 0.22 per 1,000 live births in 1987.  CDC estimates that the prevalence of FAS is actually about 1.5 per 1,000.  FAS can be prevented by abstinence from alcohol by pregnant women.  
<LI>Increase immunization levels among children under age 2 to at least 90 percent.   In 1989, 70-80 percent were immunized. 
<LI>Increase immunization levels among children in licensed child care facilities and kindergarten through post-secondary education institutions to at least 95 percent.  (Rates are already in the  94 - 97 percent range for child care facilities and children entering kindergarten.  Post-secondary rate is  unknown.)
<LI>Increase to at least 95 percent the proportion of newborns screened by state-sponsored programs for genetic disorders and other disabling conditions and to 90 percent the proportion of newborns testing positive for disease who receive appropriate treatment.  Screening for PKU and congenital hypothyrodism is virtually  universal.  About 33 percent of babies are screened for sickle cell anemia and about 70 percent for galactosemia.
<LI>Reduce the prevalence of unsafe blood lead levels among children aged 6 months through 5 years.  Lead is especially harmful to children who get it in their bodies by breathing or eating it.  Even small amounts can harm a child's brain, kidneys and stomach.  Currently 3 - 4 million children have levels considered harmful.
<LI>Perform testing for lead-based paint in at least 50 percent of homes built before 1950.  The amount of lead in paint was reduced in 1950 and again in 1978.   Homes built prior to 1950 are especially dangerous if lead paint has not been abated.
<LI>Reduce low birth weight to an incidence of no more than 5 percent of live births and very low birth weight to no more than 1 percent of live births.  Infants with very low birth weight, primarily those born prematurely have a higher than average risk of having mental retardation.  In 1987, 6.9 and 1.2 percent respectively were affected.
<LI>Increase abstinence from tobacco use by pregnant women to at least 90 percent and increase abstinence from alcohol, cocaine, and marijuana by pregnant women by at least 20 percent.  Smoking is closely associated with low birth weight; heavy alcohol consumption with fetal alcohol syndrome and illicit drug use with fetal distress and impaired fetal growth.  Currently, 75 percent of pregnant women abstain from tobacco use.
<LI>Increase to at least 80 percent the proportion of providers of primary care for children who routinely refer or screen infants and children for impairments of vision, hearing, speech and language, and assess other developmental milestones as part of well-child care.  Based on limited data, it is estimated that fewer than 15 percent of all birth- to 5-year-old children receive regular screening.
</UL>



<P>
Other objectives also target prevention of mental retardation.  Mental retardation in children due to traumatic brain injury can be reduced by measures to reduce motor vehicle, bicycle and other injuries.  Several objectives address prevention of injuries.


<P>
The risk of mental retardation among children born in families with psychosocial deprivation can be reduced through the objective calling for intellectual enrichment provided by high quality early intervention and preschool programs.


<P>
HIV infection is a cause of mental retardation in children that can be reduced through interventions which help women avoid contracting HIV infection.  Babies contract the infection from their mothers during the pregnancy and when nursing.  Several objectives outline actions to reduce the incidence of HIV infection.


<P>
<B>What is The Arc doing to promote Healthy People 2000 objectives?</B>


<P>
The Arc participated with four other organizations in an advisory task force which focused on objectives affecting people with disabilities.  The task force sponsored a 1991 conference which resulted in a manual covering systems of health care, service models, standards, resources and additional needs such as  research, data collection, financing and training.  (See Resources.)


<P>
The Arc's board of directors adopted a strategic plan outcome to "achieve significant impact in reducing the incidence of mental retardation by 1995."  The plan specifically calls for reducing the incidence of fetal alcohol syndrome and alcohol-related birth defects by 25 percent.  To accomplish this, The Arc is conducting a national public awareness and education campaign on prevention of fetal alcohol syndrome and is disseminating information and materials for its chapters to assist them in their local prevention efforts.


<P>
Information on other prevention activities is also regularly disseminated for use by the prevention advocates who are members of The Arc's state level Prevention Information Network.  Forty-three states are represented.


<P>
The Arc's board of directors also adopts annual legislative goals related to health promotion and prevention of mental retardation.  The Washington-based staff advocate for legislation and appropriations for health-related federal and state initiatives.


<P>
<B>References</B>


<P>
American Association of University Affiliated Programs for Persons with Developmental Disabilities (1991).  Health Care for Youth and Adults with Developmental Disabilities:  Policies and Partnerships.  Proceedings of a Conference, March 4-5, 1991.


<P>
U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services, Public Health Service.  Healthy People 2000:  National Health Promotion and Disease Prevention Objectives (1990).  DHHS Publication No. (PHS) 91-50212.  Washington, DC:  U.S. Government Printing Office.


<P>
The Arc has several Q&As and other publications related to health promotion and disease prevention.  Write to The Arc for a free publications list.

<HR>
<P>
<I>The Arc thanks Dr. Jeri Nelson for assistance in writing this Q&A.  Dr. Nelson represented The Arc on the Advisory Task Force for the Healthy People  2000 objective development and implementation.</I>
<p><em>The Arc<br>National Headquarters<br>P.O. Box 1047<br>Arlington, Texas 76004<br>(817)261-6003<br>(817)277-0553 TDD<br><a href="mailto:thearc@metronet.com">thearc@metronet.com</a> (e-mail)</em></p>

