<HR>
<H4>Important Information</H4>
<P>
Take this vision information sheet to the next eye exam. The questions
below may help you remember what information to obtain from the
eye care specialist at the end of the examination. Take along
a pad of paper and a pencil or pen to make notes. Also, offer
to let the eye care specialist make a copy of this information
sheet for other patients who could benefit from this material.
(Remember also to take information to the eye care specialist.
Refer to the section titled, &quot;What information will be helpful
to the eye care specialist?&quot; on page above).
<P>
1. How well can the person see?
<P>
2. If she has low vision, what is s/he able to see and not able
to see?
<P>
3. If she has low vision, can it be corrected?
<P>
4. If it cannot be corrected, what suggestions do you have to
make the most out of her/his remaining vision?
<P>
5. Is there an eye disease present? If yes, what is it?
<P>
6. What was the cause of the disease?
<P>
7. Will it get better, get worse or stay the same?
<P>
8. Will anything improve or worsen the condition, e.g. medications,
diet, surgery, use of the eyes, glasses?
<P>
9. What follow-up care is needed and how often?
<P>
10. Are relatives at risk for developing this disease?
<P>
11. Are there any rehabilitation services or agencies that could
be helpful?
<B></B>
