<html><head><title>Psychiatric Inpatient Stay for A Person with Developmental Disabilities</title></head><Body>
 <center><H4>REPRINTED WITH PERMISSION FROM:    "THE HABILITATIVE MENTAL HEALTHCARE NEWSLETTER"
			       January/February 1995,  Vol. 14, No. 1</H4></center>

<center><H2>HOW LONG SHOULD A PSYCHIATRIC INPATIENT STAY BE FOR A PERSON WITH DEVELOPMENTAL DISABILITIES?</H2></center>
	<center><H3>ROBERT SOVNER, M.D., JOAN BEASLEY, M.ED., L.M.H.C., and 
ANNE DESNOYERS HURLEY, PH.D.</H3></center>

<P>In this era of managed healthcare, setting standards for length-of-stay at psychiatric inpatient units becomes an important issue in providing cost-effective healthcare services. Psychiatric inpatient treatment is expensive and it is not surprising, therefore, that insurance companies are vigorously monitoring length-of-stay and insisting that the patient be discharged as soon as possible. 

<P>This can create a significant problem, however, for persons with psychiatric and developmental disabilities who need inpatient treatment, because they may require longer lengths-of-stay than other patients with the same mental disorder. In some cases, managed healthcare agencies are failing to make allowances for the presence of cognitive and psychosocial deficits associated with mental retardation. They are insisting that "active treatment," (usually the initiation of psychotropic drug therapy) begin immediately after admission and that lengths-of-stay for developmentally disabled persons be similar to those for non-disabled persons with the same psychiatric disorder.  In other cases, the developmentally disabled patient is viewed as merely having a  "behavioral" problem because once admitted to the highly structured milieu of the inpatient service, he or she does not display the aggression or self-injury that precipitated the hospitalization. This "honeymoon" effect can result in the patient being precipitously discharged, and perpetuates a cycle of brief admissions, return of the problematic behavior post-discharge, and emergency re-hospitalizations.

<P>Data provided by a managed health organization for a psychiatric inpatient unit that provides services for S.T.A.R.T.  Clinical Services is illustrative of this issue.  (The mission and organization S.T.A.R.T. were described in a previous newsletter issue.1)  The facility is a private psychiatric hospital in the greater Boston area.  The hospital's 20 bed acute, locked inpatient service has been deemed to be a primary referral inpatient unit for persons with developmental disabilities whose admissions are paid for by Medicaid.  At any given time, 12 to 18 of the unit's patients are persons with developmental disabilities.  In 1994, the hospital's performance with respect to a managed healthcare contract was evaluated based upon admission and discharge data. The reviewers commented that the hospital had a high length-of-stay and readmission rate compared to other psychiatric facilities (Mean length of stay in days was 15.35 compared with a regional average of 10.73 days and a state average of 10.08 days.  Readmission within 30 days of discharge was 27% compared with the regional average of 21% and the state average of 22%).  

<P>In  this article, we  will argue  that the  norms for length-of-stay for psychiatric inpatients cannot be applied to persons with developmental disabilities without significant modifications.  This arises because there are issues intrinsic to treating a person who has both psychiatric and developmental disabilities(references 7,10,11) that have not been addressed by those agencies that provide psychiatric inpatient care and those that pay for it.

<H3>FACTORS THAT COMPLICATE INPATIENT TREATMENT OF PERSONS WITH DEVELOPMENTAL DISABILITIES</H3>

<P>The following factors make it difficult to treat adults with developmental disabilities in 
acute care settings (references 10,11)


<UL>
<LI>Mental illness often presents in a nonspecific way, usually with maladaptive behavior.
</UL>

<P>In general, patients with developmental disabilities are admitted because they have been aggressive or have been engaging in self-injurious acts.  These behaviors are too nonspecific to represent treatable conditions from a psychiatric perspective,(reference 6) but can be the presenting complaint of a mental illness (references 3, 5).  Unless an adequate diagnostic evaluation has already been carried out, it may take one or two weeks to assess the cause of the maladaptive behavior (references 7, 8).  This may require extensive review of records (which have to first be requested from community providers and other healthcare staff) and several meetings with caregivers and family members.  In addition, an extensive medical evaluation may be necessary to rule out physical illness as a cause of the behavior problem.

<UL>
<LI>Inpatient staff cannot rely on patient self-reports for diagnosing mental illness.
</UL>

<P>Limited verbal skills usually preclude basing the diagnosis on the developmentally disabled persons's self-reports (reference 9).  Also, community informants may be helpful, but they are often unsophisticated from a psychiatric perspective and it may be difficult for them to draw conclusions about changes in behavior over time.  This means that it may take several weeks of observation to draw conclusions about the patient's behavior.  Determination of whether a patient is rapid-cycling, for example, may take weeks of behavioral monitoring.  Families and many community residences may lack the resources to accomplish this task.

<UL>
<LI>Objective behavioral data is often necessary to make a valid psychiatric diagnosis.
</UL>

<P>In many cases, sleep charting, counts of specific behaviors, and general observations of the persons mood state over time are necessary before the diagnosis is apparent.  Our clinical experience suggests that many persons with developmental and psychiatric disabilities are not adequately diagnosed unless they are being cared for by a community clinical team that specializes in this population. Consequently, a complete diagnostic reassessment is often necessary once the patient is hospitalized before effective treatment, other than sedation, can be prescribed.  This may take one or two weeks to accomplish.

<UL>
<LI>Outpatient treatment may be masking diagnostically-relevant symptomatology.
</UL>

<P>A corollary to the previous factor is that medication may have been inappropriately 
prescribed.  Treatment with clonazepam (Klonopin &reg;), a sedating antianxiety agent, and/or treatment with neuroleptic therapy thioridazine (Mellaril &reg;) or haloperidol (Haldol &reg;) may have already been started for symptom-control, and such treatment may mask diagnostically-relevant behavior, e.g., middle of the night awakening.

<h3>PROPOSAL FOR SUBTYPING PSYCHIATRIC ADMISSIONS</H3>

<P>In the previous section, we have argued that the norms for the lengths-of-stay of developmentally disabled psychiatric inpatients should reflect the special circumstances involved in working with this population.  We expect, therefore, that a significant proportion of patients with developmental and psychiatric disabilities will require longer lengths-of-stay than is usual for other populations.  This does not mean that all developmentally disabled patients require months of inpatient treatment for adequate care, but it is important to identify those individuals for whom an extended inpatient stay is appropriate prior to admission or shortly thereafter.

<P>We propose that when a hospitalization is being considered for a symptomatic individual 
with developmental disabilities, clinicians and medical insurers attempt to classify the   expected length-of-stay according to the treatment mission and not psychiatric diagnosis.  In our classification schema, there are four main types of admission based upon specific treatment goals: 

<H4>Type I Hospitalization
</H4>
<P>Description:  The psychiatric diagnosis has been established and hospitalization is for rapidly implementing a specific treatment or the management of acute side-effects.

<P>Length of Stay:  3-5 days to 14 days 

<P>Expected Outcome: Partial or complete symptom remission

<P>Comment:  This is short-term admission for the initiation of a drug regimen.  The diagnosis would 
already be known and a rapid titration protocol can be followed.  For example, starting valproate therapy for an acutely manic individual, using the protocol described by Keck et al,(reference 4) would be an indication for a relatively brief hospital stay.  In many respects, Type I admissions are very cost-effective because the diagnosis is already known and treatment implementation, which might have taken weeks in the community, can be accomplished in a few days on an inpatient service. 

<H4>Type II Hospitalization</H4>

<P>Description:  Patient is out-of-control.  Admission is for emergency containment and a review of current psychiatric diagnosis and out-patient drug therapy is indicated.

<P>Length of Stay:  1-3 weeks

<P>Expected Outcome

<OL>
<LI>stabilize behavior
<li>establish provisional psychiatric diagnosis
<li>make treatment recommendations
</ol>

<P>Comments:  This would be for the emergency management of out-of-control behavior, and once stabilized, the patient should be discharged.  Aggressive and self-injurious behavior, per se, are not reasons for an extended admission to a psychiatric inpatient unit except when the behavior can clearly be demonstrated to be a sign of an active mental illness. 

<H4>Type III and IV Hospitalizations</H4>

<P>These admissions would be reserved for those individuals for whom an extended stay is necessary to establish a primary diagnosis and/or effecting medication withdrawal  trial  that could not be accomplished in another setting.  There is often a need to  completely reassess the diagnositc conclusions and the efficacy of currently prescribed psychotropic medications.

<H4>Type III Hospitalization</H4>
<P>Description:  Psychiatric diagnosis has not been established and hospitalization is for determining whether patient has a drug-responsive psychiatric disorder.

<P>Estimated Length of Stay:  4-6 weeks

<P>Expected Outcome:
<OL>
<LI>establish psychiatric diagnosis
<LI>treatment initiation
<LI>partial or complete symptom remission 
</OL>

<P>Comments:  Initially, detailed behavioral monitoring is required to make a diagnosis and this may take several weeks.

<H4>Type IV Hospitalization</H4>
<P>Description:  Psychiatric diagnosis has not been established.  Patient is on a complicated and ineffective drug regimen.  Hospitalization is for discontinuing drug therapy, determining whether the patient has a drug-responsive disorder and implementing treatment.

<P>Expected Length of Stay:  4-12 weeks

<P>Expected Outcome:  partial or complete symptom remission

<P>Comments:  Some patients have two psychiatric illnesses, e.g., bipolar disorder and autism, each of which requires separate treatment.

<H3>SIX QUALITY OF CARE FUNCTIONS FOR AN INPATIENT PSYCHIATRIC UNIT</H3>

<P>We do not believe that all psychiatric inpatient units are able to provide the kinds of services required for Types III and IV admissions.  It has been our experience that an extended stay on some inpatient services is problematic. When a rapid patient turnover is coupled with a nursing/occupational therapy staff that has not been trained to work with developmentally disabled inpatients and lacks the necessary personnel, disabled patients tend to have an increase in behavioral problems.

<P>We provide a list of six functions that we believe are necessary to provide inpatient services to persons with developmental disabilities.  We propose them because a unit must provide more than a willingness to keep patients for several weeks and make a commitment to training psychiatrists, mental health workers, and social workers in issues related to working with patients who have a developmental disability.  We also advocate rigorous quality assurance reviews to insure that units are providing quality services.

<UL>
<LI>The unit is able to monitor clinical course and treatment efficacy using objective measures of change 24 hours per day.  
</UL>

<P>The diagnosis and assessment of treatment effects requires the use of objective data collection.  The unit should be skilled in the use of rating scales and counts of specific behaviors for assessment and treatment.  A behavioral psychologist should be available on a consulting basis.

<UL>
<LI>The unit is able to use nonpharmacological interventions to manage out-of-control behavior.
</UL>

<P>The predominant use of psychotropic medication to control behavior is detrimental to persons with developmental disabilities.  In many cases, such behavior represents a nonspecific stress response that can be managed without the use of sedation.  Psychiatric units that treat persons with developmental disabilities require regular behavioral consultations and a staff willing to implement such programs that often seem counterintuitive.  By "behavioral consultation" we mean assessments that help the staff to appreciate the adaptive components of an individual's responses and design programs that teach alternative ways of dealing with stress.

<UL>
<LI>The unit creates psychiatric formulations that take into account developmental and social factors.
</UL>

<P>How developmental disabilities influences the clinical presentation of a mental illness must be considered.  This requires a knowledge of psychiatric illness, behavioral principles, and an understanding of how persons with developmental disabilities handle stress.  It is important that crisis prevention planning be part of the treatment planning process.
<UL>
<LI>
<LI>Unit psychiatrists prescribe psychotropic medication only when there is a clear formulation based upon a syndrome or symptom cluster model.
</UL>

<P>Indiscriminate use of drug therapy to maintain control is rarely helpful.  Drug therapy should implemented only when it can be demonstrated that the person has a drug-responsive disorder and symptom complex.

<UL>
<LI>The unit provides meaningful activities.
</UL>

<P>In unstructured settings, persons with developmental disabilities often regress.  If the inpatient stay is to be more than a week or two, some type of active programming is needed.

<UL>
<LI>Family members, community careproviders, and patient advocates are included in clinical decision-making. 
</UL>

<P>It is vital that persons who know the patient best be included in decision-making, especially regarding whether or not the problem is resolved.  We strongly recommend that community caregivers and family members be actively incorporated into the treatment team within 24 hours of admission.

<H3>RECOMMENDATIONS</H3>

<P>In order to create a psychiatric inpatient care system for patients with developmental disabilities that is both cost-effective and flexible enough to allow for lengths-of-stay based upon therapeutic mission, we have five recommendations.

<UL>
<LI>Whenever possible, have the individual first evaluated as an outpatient.
</UL>
<P>Completing the assessment process prior to admission greatly shortens the length-of-stay because treatment can begin on the first day of hospitalization.  Optimally, this may include the acquisition of the patient's complete educational and medical records (which are then used to create a biopsychosocial timeline and an abstract of relevant treatment experiences), psychological testing, and the collection of behavioral/symptom checklist data over a period of weeks or months.  It has been our experience that clinical teams working in the community and funded or subsidized by appropriate state agencies are usually necessary due to the complexity of some cases.  Fee-for-service clinicians simply do not have the time to provide the coordination of care necessary to accomplish this task.

<UL>
<LI>State agencies should fund alternatives to inpatient units for persons with developmental 
<LI>disabilities who present with a mix of "behavioral" and psychiatric problems.
</UL>

<P>Many such individuals could be treated in semi-secure community facilities that would be significantly less expensive to operate than inpatient units.  We believe that they can provide better mental healthcare services because they can be organized on a behavioral/habilitation model that is better suited for treating this population.  A collaboration between an agency providing residential services and one providing mental health services, in which residential and psychiatric care are integrated, is necessary to insure a high quality of care.

<UL>
<LI>Service contracts should not be awarded to facilities that simply promise short-term length-of-stays.
</UL>

<P>Units should have to prove that they have expertise in the treatment of this type of patient.  The rapid initiation of drug therapy on admission is not evidence of such expertise. 

<UL>
<LI>Patients for whom Type I or II hospitalizations are being implemented should not be isolated in special units.
</UL>

<P>In our experience, persons with developmental disabilities, who are experiencing acute crises, can be readily integrated in existing psychiatric units, provided that consultations with knowledgeable clinicians are readily available.  On a short term basis, these units provide a more normalizing experience and promote reintegration in the community compared to specialized units (reference 2)  Also, "MR" or "behavioral" inpatient units tend to be set up on vacant wards of state hospitals.  These units may become long-stay facilities, especially in communities that do not have an extensive network of community housing options.  Community agencies providing residential services view such units as a place to dispose of their more  "behaviorally" involved clients and the unit cannot find a community placement for the individual when he or she is ready to be discharged. 

<UL>
<LI>Hospitals providing inpatient services to persons with developmental disabilities must demonstrate that they have a viable outreach component that will follow through with the treatment plan.
</UL>

<P>Unless the community care system and inpatient service form a coherent service provision network, there is a danger that any gains achieved during the hospitalization will be undone by the failure to follow through with interventions initiated in the hospital.

<H3>CONCLUSIONS</H3>

<P>In many cases, persons with psychiatric and developmental disabilities can be treated in 
community acute inpatient units.  (In effect, refusing to admit a person with developmental disabilities because he or she is "retarded" is not any different than refusing to admit a person in a wheel chair because he or she is physically disabled.) At the same time, however, there must be alternatives to this system because of the needs of those patients with subacute illnesses, who require extended periods of intensive psychiatric treatment.  There is no need to return to a institution-based model.  Such treatment can and should be provided within a community service delivery system.

<P>The authors acknowledge the helpful comments and recommendations made by Susan Roberts, Ph.D., Fuller Memorial Hospital, Attleboro, Massachusetts.

<H4>References</H4>
<OL>
<LI>Beasley J, Kroll J, Sovner R.  Community-based crisis mental health services for persons with developmental disabilities: The S.T.A.R.T. model.  Habil Ment Healthcare Newslett 1992;11:55-58.

<LI>Emerson E, Beasley F, Offord G, Mansell J.  An evaluation of hospital-based specialized staffed housing for people with seriously challenging behaviours.  J Intell Disabil Res 1992;36:291-307.

