<html><head><title>Problem Solving Skills Training</title></head><Body>
 <center><H4>REPRINTED WITH PERMISSION FROM:    "THE HABILITATIVE MENTAL HEALTHCARE NEWSLETTER"
			       January/February 1995,  Vol. 14, No. 1</H4></center>

<center><H2>PSYCHOSOCIAL INTERVENTIONS UPDATE:  PROBLEM SOLVING SKILLS TRAINING</H2></center>
	<center><H3>BETSEY A. BENSON, PH.D.</H3></center>

<P>Training in problem solving skills can be useful for persons with mental retardation and 
mental illness who are likely to have problem solving deficits.  Of special interest is training to 
improve social or interpersonal problem solving, in contrast to cognitive problem solving.  
Training in social problem solving is often part of cognitive-behavioral treatment "packages" 
such as Valenti-Hein and Mueser's Dating Skills Program (reference 18) and Benson's Anger Management 
Program (reference 1).

<H4>Process vs. Performance Training</H4>
<P>In describing the various methods of training problem-solving skills, a distinction is often 
made between those that emphasize process training and those that emphasize performance 
training.  Process training teaches a general template that one follows in a step-wise fashion to 
define and solve problems.  Probably the best known approach of this type was developed by 
D'Zurilla and Goldfried (reference 6) who described four steps of problem solving:  1. define the problem; 2.  
generate alternative solutions; 3. choose the best solution, make a plan, and execute it; and 4. 
evaluate the outcome.  Camp, Blom, Herbert, & Van Doorninck (reference 3) adapted the four steps for 
aggressive, nonretarded children in a program called "Think Aloud."  Proponents of the process 
training method assert that this approach is more likely to lead to generalization of problem 
solving skills to situations and settings other than those trained.

<P>Performance training focuses on the behaviors the individual engages in while enacting a 
problem solution.  These include both verbal and nonverbal characteristics of the response.  Eye 
contact, voice tone, voice volume, gestures, as well as who one talks to and what is said are all 
possible targets of training.  These elements are usually rehearsed through role playing, 
modeling, and feedback. Another way to describe the difference between the two approaches to 
problem solving training is that process training helps one decide what the most appropriate 
response is, whereas performance training helps one to deliver an effective response.16  People 
with mental retardation often require training in both process and performance.  Problem solving 
training programs are most appropriate for persons functioning in the mild to moderate range of 
mental retardation.

<H4>Methods of Training</H4>

<P>To follow the format recommended by D'Zurilla and Goldfried (reference 6) one would go through each 
of the four steps in solving a problem.  In defining the problem, you are expected to state it in 
specific and concrete terms.  The problem is described from the point of view of each person in 
the interaction.  Consider what your goal is and what an acceptable outcome would be.  To 
generate alternative solutions, brainstorming is required.  Any and all solutions are considered at 
first.  Next, each potential solution is evaluated according to costs and benefits.  The solution 
with the best cost/benefit ratio is selected and a plan developed to implement it.  The plan is 
carried out and the outcome of the effort is evaluated.  Did it achieve the expected outcome?  If 
not, consider why, and whether you need to go back through the steps again.  

<P>When conducting problem solving skills training with persons with mental retardation, 
some adaptations are made.  Many programs have the trainer demonstrate the problem for the 
participants in a role play (references 1, 18).  Much assistance is provided in stating the problem during the 
initial phases of training.  The same is true for generating solutions.  Trainers model offering 
solutions that include silly and inappropriate ones to show that there are several potential 
solutions.  Many participants with mild mental retardation can state some of the anticipated 
consequences of response alternatives, although they may not perceive the long-term 
consequences without some assistance.  Once an alternative is selected, practice is required to 
insure that it is implemented effectively.

<H4>Types of Situations</H4>

<P>Many types of situations can be addressed with problem solving training.  Tymchuk, 
Andron & Rahbar (reference 17) trained mothers with mental retardation to make good child-care decisions.  
Situations with varying degrees of risk to the child were included, such as, your child is listless, 
your child is choking, your child has a fight at the playground.   More general community living 
skills have also been addressed with problem solving training (reference 11).  Six areas were covered in the 
Foxx et al (reference 11) program:  community awareness, authority figures, peer issues, stating one's rights, 
emergencies and injuries, and safety.  Students with moderate handicaps were given training in 
how to decide if they are early or late for their bus to work (reference 19).  Adult workers received training in 
asking questions to improve interactions with co-workers and supervisors on the job (reference 14). 

<H4>Training Supplements</H4>

<P>Discussion, reinforcement, and correction are generally present in training programs (reference 17).  
Supplemental instructional aids used in problem solving training are videotaped peer models of 
problems and solutions (reference 8) and an interactive video curriculum with accompanying workbook (reference 2).  
Visual representation of problems and situations has been achieved with picture prompt cards 
and photographs.  Picture prompt cards were used to help students determine if they were early 
or late for a bus (reference 19).  Pictures of a trainee interacting with a coworker in the lunchroom and in the 
work area were part of the employment training provided by O'Reilly and Rusch (reference 14).  A board 
game was designed by Foxx et al (reference 11) to maintain interest in community adjustment training.  Cards 
were drawn to present problem situations and correct answers entitled the participant to advance 
around the game board.

<H4>Training Incentives</H4>

<P>In addition to praise for correct performance, some training programs include other 
incentives.  In Tymchuk et al's (reference 17) training program, mothers were given a raffle ticket each session 
and there was a drawing for prizes after the last session.  Participants in Foxx et al's (reference 11) community 
skills program earned money for meeting predetermined performance criteria and a bonus for 
surpassing it.  Ross and Ross (reference 15) working with elementary school children awarded "small tangible 
rewards" for filling a score card to record correct responses.

<H4>Training Effectiveness, Maintenance, and Generalization</H4>

<P>It is discouraging for the trainer to see gains in problem solving skills, only to have them 
forgotten a short time later or not used when appropriate situations are presented in real life.  
Programs vary in the degree to which they have demonstrated long term results and 
generalization of the newly learned skills beyond the training environment.

<P>One factor that has hampered problem solving skills training effectiveness, according to 
Foxx (reference 9) has been the unquestioning acceptance of the D'Zurilla and Goldfried6 four-step model of 
problem solving.  Instead, Foxx (reference 9) proposes that training a series of questions to ask is simpler and 
makes more sense for persons with mental retardation and the types of problems they encounter.  
The questions are: Who should I talk to?",  "Where should I look for help?", and "What should I 
say?"  These three questions along with a fourth one addressed in training, "When will the 
problem be solved?" were useful in handling many problem situations encountered in community 
living (reference 10).  Of great interest is whether gains in problem solving skills are maintained and 
generalize to other situations and settings.  Some programs failed to demonstrate generalization 
of the skills to untrained situations4 while others succeeded (reference 11).  Certain strategies of training make 
it more likely  that the skills learned will be transferred to new situations.

<P>Training strategies that improve generalization of skills include  practicing  the  skills  in  
situations that are similar to those the person will encounter in real life.  Welch et al (reference 19) had participants p
ractice waiting for a bus in an area similar to the bus stop the person went to each day.  Another recommendation is 
for the training to include several similar examples of the problem to be solved (reference 7).  One would 
practice what to do if "I lost my wallet," "I lost my bus pass,"  "I lost my lunch money,"  for 
example.  Each situation is different, but the process of solving the problem is similar.

<P>Conditions outside of training that could increase generalization of problem solving skills 
are making sure that the environment will support the new skills.  Staff prompts and praise of 
problem solving can help maintain the behavior and extend it to new areas.  Foxx (reference 9) also 
recommends that problem solving skills could be improved by allowing clients more 
opportunities to solve problems themselves.  Too often staff or family solve problems for the 
person, even after problem solving training has been given, which reduces opportunities to 
practice the skills.

<H4>Assessment of Skills</H4>

<P>Identifying good and poor problem solvers may not be too difficult, but predicting which 
situations individuals will or will not be able to handle effectively can be.  Most problem solving 
training programs have developed assessment measures to evaluate the skills that are taught in 
their respective programs.  Role play assessment of problem solving skills allows one to assess 
the performance aspects of problem solving.  Participants are asked to role play their response to 
problem situations behaving as they would in real life.  Their response is rated for effectiveness (reference 4).  
The Problem Solving Test for Persons with Mental Retardation is a behavioral measure that 
addresses five problem situations, including making new friends and resolving a conflict with 
another person (reference 13).  The problem situation is described and the goal in the situation is stated.  Then, 
the subject is asked to answer several questions including, what is the problem, think of as many 
ideas as you can to solve the problem, and which one do you think will solve it?  Response 
quality is scored for effectiveness or relevance to the situation.  The number of situations covered 
in the assessment is rather limited, but could easily be expanded to deal with a variety of 
situations.

<P>Training programs have compared participant's performance to judge's or trainer's criteria of 
effective responses (reference 11).  It has been noted that in setting standards for performance we may over-
estimate the ability of normal adult problem solvers, resulting in standards that are unreasonably 
high (reference 7).  Further, little is known about the problem solving skills of persons with mental 
retardation who are considered good problem solvers.  An additional complication is that persons 
may show competence in solving problems of one type, but not another.  What standards we use 
to evaluate problem solving skills of persons with mental retardation clearly deserves further 
attention.

<H4>Problem Solving Orientation</H4>

<P>An important aspect of training in problem solving skills is the person's general approach to 
problems and the motivation to solve them.  How to develop a problem orientation (reference 5) is often not 
specifically detailed in the descriptions of training programs.  In the Nezu, Nezu, & Areans (reference 13) 
training, participants with dual diagnosis received training in problem orientation which included 
reducing the emotional response to problems and developing "a rational set toward the existence 
of problems." (p. 378) In Benson's Anger Management Training (reference 1) participants are taught that 
problems are a normal part of life and that anger is a signal that there is a problem to solve.  
Problem orientation also involves the belief that one can solve the problem and has the 
willingness to devote the time and energy needed to solve it (reference 5).  To some extent, experiencing 
success in solving problems during training will contribute to the expectation of success in future 
problem solving efforts.

<P>Motivation to solve problems is also affected by how important the problem is to the 
participant (reference 9).  Tymchuk et al (reference 17) asked participants to rate the importance of 50 child care situations 
and used the ratings to select the material to be trained.  In Anger Management Training (reference 1) 
problem situations suggested by counselors are supplemented with those brought up by 
participants.  Problem solving training programs will be more successful if they insure that the 
participants believe that solving the problems has a direct effect on them.

<H3>Summary</H3>

<P>There is general agreement that many people with mental retardation can profit from 
improved problem solving skills.  Various techniques, programs, and instructional aids have been 
developed to accomplish the goal.  The basic methods of training can be applied to a wide variety 
of problem situations encountered in everyday life.  Training effectiveness can be maximized by 
following some of the examples offered for increasing generalization and by creating 
opportunities for continued practice of the skills.

<P>1.	Benson BA.  Teaching Anger Management to Persons with Mental Retardation.  
Worthington OH: IDS Publishing, 1992.

