<html><head><title>Reinforcement Methods and Challenging Behaviors</title></head><Body>
 <center><H4>REPRINTED WITH PERMISSION FROM:    "THE HABILITATIVE MENTAL HEALTHCARE NEWSLETTER"
			       March/April 1995,  Vol. 14, No. 2</H4></center>

<center><H2>REINFORCEMENT METHODS AND VARIATIONS IN THE CLINICAL TREATMENT OF CHALLENGING BEHAVIORS</H2></center>
	<center><H3>JAMES K. LUISELLI, ED.D.</H3></center>

<P>Reinforcement procedures represent an integral component of clinical treatment for 
behavior disorders in persons with developmental disabilities. For example, it generally is 
recognized that any program of behavioral intervention must include strategies to 
reinforce (increase) compensatory skills, communication abilities, and adaptive, 
alternative responses. Virtually all regulatory guidelines specify that positive 
reinforcement approaches be instituted initially before more invasive methods of 
behavioral treatment are considered or implemented. Finally, treatment acceptability 
research demonstrates that practitioners usually prefer reinforcement-based procedures 
over punishment (negative) techniques (reference 12).
<P>Although a seemingly rudimentary and simple operation, the formulation, design, 
and application of reinforcement procedures in clinical treatment can be complex. There 
are, in fact, many parameters and variables that should be considered when reinforcement 
interventions are being planned. This article is a brief review of reinforcement methods 
and variations with emphasis on recent developments from applied research and clinical 
practice. The article focuses on three categories of particular relevance for practitioners: 
(1) stimulus preference assessment, (2) strategies to enhance reinforcer effectiveness, and 
(3) procedural variations.

<H3>OVERVIEW</H3>

<P>Before discussing procedural issues and variations, it would be instructive to review 
briefly some basic concepts of reinforcement. First, when the word "reinforcement" is 
used, the therapeutic intent is to produce an increase in clinically relevant behaviors. 
Positive reinforcement consists of the presentation of a consequence, contingent upon a 
response, which results in an increase in the occurrence of that response. Negative 
reinforcement (sometimes confused with punishment) also has the objective of 
increasing desirable behaviors but is based upon the programming of nonpreferred 
(some might say, "aversive") stimulation. When a person responds to postpone the 
presentation of stimulation, that behavior is reinforced negatively through avoidance. 
When a person responds to terminate ongoing stimulation, that behavior is reinforced 
negatively through escape.

<P>Positive and negative reinforcement frequently operate in concert and many times, it 
is difficult to perceive a distinction in their application. To illustrate, when a person turns 
up the thermostat in his or her home during the winter, is that behavior reinforced because 
it produces warmth (positive reinforcement) or removes cold (negative reinforcement)? 
Similarly, when a parent is confronted with a screaming child who wants a toy, the 
presentation of that object will positively reinforce the agitated behavior (i.e., the child 
learns to scream because it produces a desirable consequence) and, in turn, the response 
by the parent will be negatively reinforced (i.e., it results in the child being quiet). Like the preceding example, 
the interplay of positive and negative reinforcement is encountered in many clinical 
situations.
<P>Another important concept is that the effects of reinforcement must be determined 
functionally. A consequence can only be described as reinforcing if the preceding 
behavior does, in fact, increase in frequency. Put simply, it is the outcome from 
consequence manipulation (positive or negative) that defines reinforcement control. A 
working "rule of thumb" is that no object, activity, or stimulus can be considered 
reinforcing a priori but instead, must be subjected to empirical verification.

<H3>STIMULUS PREFERENCE ASSESSMENT</H3>

<P>In order for reinforcement to be therapeutically effective, a person's preferences 
must be identified. Behavioral clinicians usually determine potential reinforcers in two 
ways. First, observations of a client are conducted when he or she has free-choice 
opportunities. That is, by watching someone behave in the absence of demands or 
otherwise limiting conditions, it is possible to document what he or she finds pleasurable. 
For example, by direct observation a practitioner could determine whether a client prefers 
a particular type of music, engages in certain topics of conversation, selects specific 
magazines, eats distinctive foods, performs active or sedentary activities, and so on. 
These objects and events then can be incorporated into a systematic program of positive 
reinforcement.

<P>The second common method of preference assessment is to solicit information from 
persons who interact regularly with a client such as a parent, teacher, or aide. These 
individuals would be asked to name any objects, activities, or experiences that the client 
seems to enjoy and their responses would be noted. This informant-based method, of 
course, relies on subjective impressions and, therefore, it usually is desirable to gather 
information from several individuals so that consensus can be achieved on select items. In 
some cases, it may be desirable to elicit such information via a standardized, rating 
checklist such as the Reinforcement Survey Schedule (reference 1) or the Reinforcement Preference 
Schedule for Adults with Developmental Disabilities (reference 5).

<P>In recent years, there has been an emphasis on the development of more empirical 
methods of stimulus preference assessment (references 9, 13)  particularly as it applies to persons with 
severe and multiple handicaps. These approaches generally include the following steps. 
First, a variety of stimuli are selected based upon their purported reinforcing qualities. 
These stimuli typically are grouped according to sensory modality, for example, gustatory 
(foods, liquids), olfactory (scents, cologne, perfume), visual (sources of illumination), 
auditory (music, chimes), and tactile (textures, toys, manipulatives) categories. Second, a 
student or client would be presented with the selected stimuli in a series of discrete trials. 
Data are gathered for each trial to determine whether the individual showed interest in the 
stimulus by making an approach towards it (e.g., reaching out), grasping and 
manipulating it, or displaying a positive emotional reaction. These responses would 
suggest that the presented stimulus was pleasurable and, therefore, potentially 
reinforcing. If a student or client pushed the stimulus away, withdrew from contact with 
it, or exhibited negative verbalizations, the presented stimulus would not be considered a 
preference. The third step is to deliver the identified stimulus preferences contingent upon 
desirable behaviors to verify the reinforcing effects from this contingency arrangement. 
As noted previously, if the behaviors increase in frequency, these stimuli would be 
considered reinforcing. The importance of conducting empirically-based stimulus 
preference assessment should be noted because as demonstrated by Green et al. (reference 3) the 
outcome from such an assessment may not be in agreement with the subjective opinions 
of significant others. That is, what others consider to be reinforcing for a student or client 
may not be verified through objective evaluation of preferences.

<H3>ENHANCING REINFORCER EFFECTIVENESS</H3>

<P>Several variables have been studied in an effort to identify parameters which 
enhance the effectiveness of positive reinforcement.

<H4>Variation</H4>

<P>If the same objects and activities are used as reinforcers for extended periods of 
time, it is possible that they will lose their reinforcing effect. The reduction in reinforcer 
strength as a function of repetitive presentation is said to occur due to satiation. 
Therefore, the provision of stimulus preferences should be varied routinely in clinical 
practice (reference 2).  It is useful, for example, to have a selection of reinforcers available so that the 
student or client is able to sample multiple preferences. An illustration would be a 
"Reinforcer Menu Board" that includes a listing of photographs, line-drawings, or printed 
words of available reinforcers. These items would be alternated on a regular basis so that 
functional, but varied, preferences are always programmed.

<H4>Choice</H4>

<P>Reinforcement effects can be enhanced if a student or client is able to choose (i.e., 
self-select) from available preferences in contrast to having those items or activities 
presented arbitrarily by another person (reference 8).  The comparison would be the difference 
between a teacher allowing a student to pick one of four available reinforcers when he or 
she responds correctly on an academic task versus the teacher picking a reinforcer and 
presenting it to the student. In cases where a student or client is not able to make 
functional choices in daily living, it would be desirable to teach this skill since choice-
making ability can bolster reinforcer effectiveness (reference 16).

<H4>Establishing Operations</H4>

<P>An establishing operation, also described as a setting event, represents an 
interpersonal interaction or environmental arrangement that effects a person's subsequent 
response to behavior-reinforcement contingencies. As an illustration, imagine that you 
have exercised by running four miles. Shortly thereafter, a friend invites you to take a 
long walk, visit the town center, and go shopping. Although spending time with your 
friend in this way typically is a positive experience, the pleasurable features of this 
activity would tend to be lessened (i.e., are less reinforcing) when it is preceded by 
strenuous exercise. In this example, the four mile run functions as an establishing 
operation.

<P>In clinical practice, establishing operations can be manipulated both to enhance the 
effectiveness of reinforcement for desirable responses and to change conditions that 
reinforce behavior problems. Procedures that induce deprivation and satiation, for 
example, can be introduced to influence the potency of primary reinforcement such as 
food and liquids. One illustration would be a student who receives food rewards when he 
or she participates compliantly during a difficult instructional task. It is likely that the 
student will respond better if instruction is conducted preceding, instead of following, 
the lunch meal. In this case, the establishing operation of mild food deprivation that exists 
at the time of the lunch meal enhances subsequent contact with programmed 
reinforcement. Similarly, if a client received liquids in a program of positive 
reinforcement, allowing that person to consume salty foods (e.g., pretzels, potato chips) 
would be an establishing operation to increase reinforcer effectiveness. Finally, for a 
student or client who enjoys social attention, it would be possible to manipulate the 
availability of such attention before certain activities so that subsequent social 
interactions would be more reinforcing.

<P>Conversely, satiation provides an approach to reduce the reinforcing consequences 
for clinical disorders. An example of this operation is the use of food satiation diets to 
treat chronic ruminative vomiting (reference 14).  Because some persons engage in rumination due to 
the sensory pleasurable effects of re-swallowing regurgitated stomach contents, providing 
them with increased, and sometimes unlimited, portions of food at meals attenuates the 
reinforcing outcome from re-consumption, thereby making it less likely that vomiting 
will occur.
 
<H3>PROCEDURAL VARIATIONS</H3>

<H4>Differential Reinforcement Schedules</H4>

<P>There are many ways to implement reinforcement procedures for therapeutic change. 
A common, and very effective approach, is to deliver stimulus preferences on a 
differential reinforcement schedule. Procedurally, this entails establishing a 
predetermined time interval (e.g., 5 minutes) and providing reinforcement when one of 
more target behaviors do not occur during the interval (DRO: Differential Reinforcement 
of Other Behavior) or when designated alternative responses are displayed (DRA: 
Differential Reinforcement of Alternative Behavior).
<P>As gleaned from research studies and clinical practice, several guidelines and 
procedural parameters should be considered in the process of implementing differential 
reinforcement schedules:
<H4>
1.	Selection of the Interval for Reinforcement.</H4>

<P>The interval for reinforcement in a differential reinforcement schedule specifies the 
duration of time that must elapse in order for reinforcement to be presented. For example, 
a DRO: 15-minute schedule would mean that the student or client must refrain from 
exhibiting the target behavior(s) for 15 minutes to receive reinforcement. A critical step 
in this regard is the selection of an initial time interval. Ideally, this choice should be 
based on the pretreatment (baseline) rate of behavior. A student who engages in a 
challenging behavior 10 times per hour during baseline, for instance, averages 1 response 
every 6 minutes. For practical purposes, this student's teacher might decide that he/she 
could have access to a preferred activity, every 30 minutes, as long as the target behavior 
did not occur during that time. However, given the student's rate of responding, he/she 
would rarely, if ever, achieve the specified interval for reinforcement.
Although there is not an absolute formula to determine the initial interval for 
reinforcement, two empirical methods are available. First, the practitioner can record the 
latency between the display of target behaviors and then, set the interval for 
reinforcement at the average of these measures. Latency is the amount of time that passes 
from the completion of one response to the initiation of the next response. Second, the 
rate of responding for a target behavior can be computed and the interval for 
reinforcement would begin at 50% of this measure. In the earlier example, the baseline 
rate of 1 response every 6 minutes would yield a beginning interval for reinforcement at 3 
minutes. By using empirically-derived measures when starting a program of differential 
reinforcement, there is greater confidence that the student or client will receive 
reinforcement and thereby, be more likely to benefit therapeutically.

<H4>2.	Adjusting the Interval for Reinforcement.</H4>

<P>Once an interval for reinforcement has been set initially, and behavior deceleration 
is achieved, it is advantageous to increase the interval duration. By teaching a student or 
client to go longer periods of time before reinforcement is received, greater resistance to 
extinction is insured. Research indicates that the increase in reinforcement intervals 
should be done gradually so that the newly established control over target behaviors will 
not be disrupted.  By adjusting the interval so that the 
student or client consistently contacts the programmed reinforcement, a better therapeutic 
response should be possible. This objective is addressed by always linking the 
reinforcement interval to the present rate of behavior.

<H4>3.	Whole-Interval versus Momentary-Interval Schedules.</H4>

<P>A study by Repp et al (reference 15) compared the effects of whole-interval versus momentary-
interval DRO schedules in the treatment of challenging behaviors by persons with 
disabilities. With the whole-interval method, there had to be an absence of the target 
behaviors for the entire interval in order for reinforcement to be delivered. With the 
momentary method, reinforcement was presented as long as the target behaviors were not 
occurring for a brief duration preceding the end of the interval. Behaviors that occurred 
at other times during the interval did not effect receipt of reinforcement.
The results from this research indicated that target behaviors were reduced more 
effectively when DRO was implemented using the whole-interval method. Once response 
reduction was achieved with this approach, however, the momentary method could be 
used to sustain the individual's improved behavior. Therefore, these findings suggest that 
one procedural variation when using differential reinforcement interventions is to include 
the momentary method of reinforcement delivery as a strategy to enhance response 
maintenance once challenging behaviors have been eliminated or reduced significantly.

<H4>4.	DRO versus DRA Schedules.</H4>

<P>A final procedural variation is whether reinforcement should be contingent on the 
absence of behavior during specified intervals (DRO) or the occurrence of specific 
responses which are alternatives to the target behaviors (DRA). Early research indicates 
that DRA appears to be a more productive approach towards behavior deceleration.17 This 
outcome appears to be the case because as presented earlier, when DRO is implemented it 
is the absence of responding that is reinforced whereas with DRA, the practitioner 
designates particular, alternative responses that produce reinforcement. This latter 
technique makes it more likely that a student or client will learn what to do so that 
adaptive skills and responses are acquired. As always, teaching someone how to respond 
more efficiently, effectively, and functionally is the best approach toward the treatment of 
challenging behaviors.  

<H4>5.	Contingent versus Noncontingent Reinforcement.</H4>

<P>A guiding principle of reinforcement is that it should be applied contingent on the 
occurrence of desirable behavior. For a child who enjoyed adult attention, for example, 
social reinforcement in this form would be delivered when the child responds 
appropriately and not when challenging behaviors occur. Similarly, for an adult client 
who enjoys listening to music, such an activity would be programmed following 
successful completion of work tasks but not when he or she was disruptive.
Recently, researchers have evaluated the comparative effects from contingent 
versus noncontingent reinforcement procedures. Although noncontingent reinforcement 
might seem to be contraindicated, Vollmer et al (reference 18) suggested that it could be more 
efficacious when compared to behavior-contingent procedures because it is easier to 
implement, is less time-intensive, and is more practical for direct-care providers. Also, 
because the presentation of noncontingent reinforcement is not linked to response rate, it 
could be more therapeutically effective with high-frequency challenging behaviors. For 
example, when programming differential reinforcement procedures such as DRO and 
DRA, it is customary to re-set the interval for reinforcement when target behaviors occur. 
This contingency delays access to reinforcement, an outcome that would be obviated with 
a noncontingent procedure.

<P>In a study with three adults who had developmental disabilities and self-injurious 
behaviors, Vollmer et al (reference 18) compared contingent and noncontingent reinforcement. 
Contingent reinforcement consisted of a DRO procedure in which the adults received 
verbal praise from staff when they refrained from self-injury for specified time periods. 
Noncontingent reinforcement was delivered by having staff praise the adults on a 
schedule that was unrelated to the presence or absence of self-injury. The results from this 
research were that both contingent and noncontingent reinforcement procedures were 
equally effective in reducing self-injurious behaviors. It should be emphasized that the 
use of social attention as reinforcement was based on the outcome from functional 
assessment that was performed preceding treatment and which indicated that social 
consequences were pleasurable for the adults.

<P>The clinical benefits from noncontingent reinforcement also were evaluated by 
Luiselli (reference 10) but in contrast to social attention that was evaluated in the research by Vollmer 
et al (reference 18) this study concerned sensory stimulation as the reinforcing stimulus. The 
participant was an 8-year-old girl with post traumatic neurological impairment who 
displayed stereotypic grabbing and mouthing of objects. These behaviors were presumed 
to be reinforced by tactile sensory consequences. The programmed sensory reinforcement 
was oral stimulation made accessible to the child by allowing her to chew on a designated 
and acceptable stimulus noncontingently during instructional sessions that were 
associated with high rates of stereotypy. Both object-grabbing and object-mouthing 
behaviors decreased to near-zero levels as a result of the noncontingent reinforcement 
intervention. In addition to documenting therapeutic effects from noncontingent 
reinforcement, these results also suggest that sensory stimulation might be considered as 
an alternative source of reinforcement for persons with developmental disabilities for 
whom social stimuli are not pleasurable.

<H4>6.	Negative Reinforcement.</H4>

<P>In clinical practice, positive reinforcement far exceeds the application of negative 
reinforcement procedures. This finding can be explained because as noted previously, 
negative reinforcement operates by programming nonpreferred stimulation that either can 
be avoided or terminated contingent on a target response. Since it is undesirable to expose 
clients to discomfort, or to increase the distress in their lives, negative reinforcement 
procedures are minimized.
<P>Despite this qualification, there are occasions where negative reinforcement might 
be warranted and could be implemented efficaciously (reference 6).  There are, in fact, several 
research examples that describe the appropriate application of negative reinforcement  
approaches.  Kennedy and Haring (reference 7) combined "reward" and "escape" DRO methods to 
reduce interfering behaviors of three students with disabilities. The "reward" DRO 
procedure provided the students with tokens when they did not display designated 
behaviors for a specified duration of time during instructional sessions. The tokens were 
exchanged for pleasurable activities. The "escape" DRO procedure was similar to the 
"reward" contingency except that accumulated tokens enabled the students to terminate 
the instructional session. The combination of these two DRO methods was highly 
successful in reducing the frequencies of interfering behaviors.

<P>Another example of negative reinforcement is provided in a study by Hoch et al. (reference 4).  
They treated food refusal in two children with disabilities initially by presenting positive 
reinforcement (praise, physical contact, access to toys) when they consumed food or 
liquid from a trainer within 5 seconds of presentation (a spoon or cup was touched to the 
lips). When this approach was unsuccessful, the food presentation contingency was 
changed such that the trainer presented the spoon or cup to the child's lips but instead of 
removing either stimulus following 5 seconds of nonconsumption, it remained in physical 
contact until the food or liquid entered the mouth. This strategy produced immediate 
increases in food acceptance by both children. One interpretation of these findings is that 
the physical presentation of the spoon or cup was nonpreferred and this condition was 
terminated upon the children opening their mouths and accepting the food or liquid. Food 
and liquid acceptance, therefore, was negatively reinforced.
<P>In his discussion of negative reinforcement approaches towards treatment, Iwata (reference 6) 
suggested that, "as with punishment, we should conduct research on negative 
reinforcement with great care and under the appropriate conditions to determine how it 
might be used effectively and humanely, its limitations, and its proper role within the 
larger realm of currently available treatment."  It cannot be stressed enough that a 
decision to introduce negative reinforcement must be carefully considered and, like the 
clinical examples described earlier, should include the manipulation of conditions that are 
minimally distressing for the student or client (e.g., having to finish a task before 
"escaping" demands).  Negative reinforcement procedures that require the presentation of 
noxious stimulation such as distasteful solutions, offensive odors, or tactile contact (e.g., 
water sprays, spanking) have no place in the clinical treatment of persons with 
disabilities.
	

<H3>
SUMMARY</H3>

<P>Reinforcement-based procedures are critical for the treatment of challenging 
behaviors in persons with disabilities. This article reviewed definitions of positive and 
negative reinforcement and included a discussion of several conceptual areas. It is 
essential to conduct stimulus preference assessments so that functional reinforcers can be 
identified for use in a treatment program. Reinforcement effectiveness can be enhanced 
by varying the types of identified stimuli, allowing persons to choose earned reinforcers, 
and manipulating establishing operations. When incorporating differential reinforcement 
procedures, determining an initial interval for reinforcement, gradually increasing these 
intervals, and reinforcing alternatives to challenging behaviors are important 
considerations. Finally, noncontingent and negative reinforcement strategies represent 
possible treatment variations.

<P>1.	Cautela JR,  Lynch E.  Reinforcement survey schedule: Scoring, administration and 
complete research.  Psych Rep 1983:53:447-465.

<P>2.	Egel AL.  Reinforcer variation: Implications for motivating developmentally 
disabled children.   J Appl Behav Anal 1981:14:345-350.

<P>3.	Green CW, Reid DH, White LK, Halford RC, Brittain DP, Gardner SM.  Identifying 
reinforcers for persons with profound handicaps.  J Appl Behav Anal 1988; 21:31-
43. 

