<html><head><title>Sexuality Update:  Loving and Disability -- Not Just Theoretical"</title></head><Body>
 <center><H4>REPRINTED WITH PERMISSION FROM:    "THE HABILITATIVE MENTAL HEALTHCARE NEWSLETTER"
			       March/April 1995,  Vol. 14, No. 2</H4></center>
<center><H2>SEXUALITY UPDATE: Loving and Disability: Not Just Theoretical</H2><BR>

	<H3>DAVID HINGSBURGER, M.ED.</H3></center>

	

<P>Publications regarding sexuality and people with developmental disabilities are becoming more available.  Unfortunately most of these books are more us and how we deal with them and their sexuality than they are about sex, love and pleasure.  These books, while helpful, often look at disability and sexuality from the perspective of "problem."  This cannot be said about a new publication from Woodbine House by Karin Melberg Schwier called <B>Couples with Intellectual Disabilities Talk about Living and Loving</B>.  This book lives up to its title and hands the microphone to people with disabilities.
<P>Melberg Schwier is developing a reputation as a writer who serves the purpose of giving voice to people with disabilities.  An earlier book for Pro-Ed, Speakeasy allowed elderly people with disabilities to talk about life.  This book focuses specifically on people with developmental disabilities who are in love.  More than that it will force readers to examine long held prejudices.  The couples speak freely and plainly about even controversial issues such as parenthood.  One sees from the perspective of people who have walked the walk court battles and custody issues.
<P>What Melberg Schwier does is notable because, while you hear her strong opinions in the Forward to the book you do not hear her in the interviews.  Her questions serve to illuminate the points the speakers want to make.  One feels that there is no manipulation of either material or the voices of the people with disabilities.  The hidden message here is that it is possible to talk with a person with a disability in a respectful manner and with the intent of simply learning.
<P>This book is more than a good read.  I have used it successfully as a book for parents of people with disabilities who are facing the issue of sexuality.  The book makes it clear that people with disabilities are loving people...not in that special way...but in a deeply human way.  It is impossible to read this book and not begin to think about the future of children with disabilities in new ways.  I gave the book to a woman who has just had a child with Downs syndrome and her response was to write the name of her child on one of the four hearts pictured on the cover of the book.  In discussing the impact of the book with me, she said that until she read the book she had not thought of her child as having a loving future.  The idea of sexuality had only vaguely crossed her mind and when it did, it seemed terrifying.  Now the issue of loneliness and the need to recognize human relationships has become tantamount to her.
<P>Therapy.  That is what happened between that mother in the privacy of her home and the pages of Melberg Schwiers book.  Those who believe in the right of people with developmental disabilities need a resource to make the point clearer.  When talking to parents (and indeed a lot of service providers), sex educators often see that "Yeah, right" look appear on listeners faces when the issue of marriage and parenthood is discussed.  This book can serve to allow those who care for people with disabilities to hear the hopes and dreams of a people desperate to live lives of significance.
<P>One of the interviews which I particularly liked was one wherein a young teenage girl with a developmental disability talks about her love for a movie star.  This section is charming and shows the fantasy life of a teen with a disability as not particularly different than other teens.  She talks about her fantasy with the same intensity two girls I know here in Quebec talk about their love of rock musicians.
The book has only one proviso and that is there are no couples with disabilities who are gay or lesbian.  In discussing this with Melberg Schwier, she indicated that she looked for them but did not find any.  An acknowledgment of this search in her Forward would have been helpful in making the point that it might even be more dangerous for same sex couples with disabilities to go public.  Even with this omission, the book still achieves its goal.  It is impossible to leave the reading of the book without a renewed conviction to make sure that those we serve get to live and love.
<P><B>Couples with Intellectual Disabilities Talk about Living and Loving</B> is available from Woodbine House, 5615 Fishers Lane, Rockville, MD 20852.  US: $15.95.  In Canada, the book is available through Monarch Books of Canada, 5000 Dufferin Street, Downsview M3H 5T5, Canada.  Canada: $22.95.

<P>David Hingsburger, M.Ed. is a consultant in private practice in Quebec, Canada.
