<html><head><title>Group Counseling for People with Mental Retardation</title></head><Body>
 <center><H4>REPRINTED WITH PERMISSION FROM:    "THE HABILITATIVE MENTAL HEALTHCARE NEWSLETTER"
			       May/June 1995,  Vol. 14, No. 3</H4></center>
<center><H2>THE HEALING CROWD:  PROCESS, CONTENT AND TECHNIQUE ISSUES
	IN GROUP COUNSELING FOR PEOPLE WITH MENTAL RETARDATION</h2><BR>

	<H3>DANIEL J. TOMASULO, PH.D., T.E.P., 
	ELLEN KELLER, M.A., M.S., and 
	AL PFADT, PH.D.</H3><BR></center>


<P>Within the field of human services, the use of group therapy for people with mental retardation and people with psychiatric and developmental disabilities has been extremely limited (reference 18).  However, over the past twenty years or so there have been a number of noteworthy exceptions (references 5, 6, 7, 8, 19, 20, 24).  While varied in their approach and focus it is important to note that many of these formats have included role playing as the method of choice. 
<P>Although many clinicians have not regarded people with mental retardation as suitable candidates for any form of psychotherapy (references 10, 13) there are many case reports on the effectiveness of individual psychotherapy (reference 10) as well as for group psychotherapy (reference 19).  Psychotherapy for people with mental retardation has been most effective when a directive style with structured sessions is used (references 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 17, 22, 25).  Additionally the use of active/interactive techniques stimulates more sensory and affective modes of learning than the verbal modality alone (references 13, 26).

	<H3>GROUP THERAPY OVERVIEW</H3>

<P>Despite the evidence of effectiveness and recommendations by researchers to use a group method, group psychotherapy for people with mental retardation is usually not considered as a viable therapeutic modality.  Historically, the research on this matter showed that people with mental retardation could not profit from insight oriented interactive therapy because they lacked specific cognitive abilities thought necessary for therapeutic change.  While this may be the primary reason that psychotherapy is overlooked as a treatment modality for people with mental retardation, there have been a series of erroneous assumptions on the part of practitioners.  Consider the following major suppositions:

<P>1.	Since many developmentally disabled people are not verbal (or have difficulty verbalizing) they are thought to be unable to produce clues to regulating their behavior.

<P>2.	The secondary disabilities that often are associated  with mental retardation (short attention span, auditory and visual handicaps, seizure activity, etc.) are thought to provide insurmountable obstacles to interactive group therapy.

<P>3.	People with mental retardation lack the cognitive ability to profit from insight into the causes and consequences of their behavior.

<P>4.	Many practitioners understand the emotional disorders displayed by people with mental retardation as a side 
effect of a biochemical brain dysfunction.  As such they feel there is little that psychotherapy can offer.

<P>5.	Somehow the emotional and behavioral problems of people with mental retardation are understood as being the result of mental illness or behavior disorder.  With such elementary discriminations only psychopharmacological or behavioral treatments alone are sought.  The use of psychotherapy to help ameliorate these problems is rarely considered.

<P>The reality is that even if an astute and aware clinician were to recommend psychotherapy the task of finding someone knowledgeable and competent to deliver such services would often be a difficult job.  Although more and more providers are beginning groups and developing their group skills, group psychotherapy is only now beginning to emerge as a treatment option on a wider scale.
One other reason why group therapy is the least used therapy for people with mental retardation (in addition to the ones listed above) may be that the dissemination of information on how to do such counseling was limited by the scarcity of research showing which method(s) were effective.  In other words while there may have been good indications that group therapy could be possible, volume of such information was not sufficient to offset the assumptions of practitioners.

<H3>Advantages of Group Therapy	</H3>

<P>The time has come for greater attention to be given to the group process.  To begin with, using group counseling for people with mental retardation makes good clinical and economic sense.  Consider the advantages of using a group format:

<P>1.	The skills to run an effective group can be taught in a brief period of time (2-3 months for a novice and considerably less for the more experienced).

<P>2.	In the same amount of time it takes to run a teaching based skill-training group a more richly interactive group can take place through facilitation rather than teaching.

<P>3.	More people can be served in a group counseling format than can be served in an individual setting.

<P>4.	It can be argued that the treatment in a group is more effective than individual counseling.

<P>5.	On all pay scales, the cost to an individual for group psychotherapy is cheaper than individual therapy.

<P>6.	Specific topics may target selected groups for particular problems (anger management groups, sex offender groups, bereavement groups, job readiness, etc.) In this way people with similar issues may gain support in ways not possible in individual counseling.  

<P>7.	This kind of peer support is not limited to homogeneous groups.  Interpersonal support from peers struggling with different issues is not available in any other format.

	<H3>THE INTERACTIVE-BEHAVIORAL MODEL
	OF GROUP THERAPY</H3>

<P>The Interactive-Behavioral Model (reference 25) has focused on fourteen therapeutic factors that have empirical validity with respect to group therapy in general. A therapeutic factor is defined as a component of group therapy that benefits a member's condition.  This improvement comes as a result of actions by the group facilitator, the members, and the individual him or herself. 
While it is beyond the scope of this article to fully elaborate the details of these factors (this has been done elsewhere, see references 4, 5, 8), it is important to note that these factors are:

<P>1.	Acceptance/cohesion<BR>
2.	Universality <BR>
3.	Altruism<BR>
4.	Installation of hope<BR>
5.	Guidance<BR>
6.	Vicarious Learning/Modeling<BR>
7.	Catharsis<BR>
8.	Imparting of information<BR>
9.	Self-Disclosure<BR>
10.	Self-understanding<BR>
11.	Interpersonal learning<BR>
12.	Corrective Recapitulation of the Primary Family<BR>
13.	Development of Socializing Techniques<BR>
14.	Existential Factors

<P>The Interactive-Behavioral Model uses these therapeutic factors, which are the most effective and well established features of group psychotherapy, and establishes their presence and vitalization within groups for people with mental retardation.  What has evolved is a four stage format for group psychotherapy which adapts processes and techniques that are effective with other populations, while introducing interventions created specifically for people with mental retardation.
<P>This model uses a 45-minute to one-hour, four stage arrangement.  It combines theoretically sound techniques for activating therapeutic factors from the field of psychodrama (reference 26) with some modifications specific to people with dual diagnosis (e.g., the orientation and affirmation stages).  The four stages of this model are:  1)  orientation; 2)  warm-up and sharing;  3)  enactment; and 4)  affirmation.

<H4>The Orientation Stage</H4>

<P>The orientation stage was designed to help with the initial difficulty encountered in establishing a group with the potential for therapeutic factors to emerge.  Poor eye contact, difficulty with short-term recognition or memory, impaired hearing, delayed responding, confusion, echolalia, inattention, distractibility, speech impediments and hyperactivity are just some of the obstacles to interaction between members. 
<P> It, therefore, becomes a primary function of the facilitators to do what is called  "cognitive networking."  This is an effort to establish basic interactions between and among the group's members by having them repeat, acknowledge or otherwise support what was said by another member in the group.  Physically orienting towards the person speaking, looking at them and echoing back what was heard are central elements to cognitive networking.
<P>This process begins in the orientation stage but will continue throughout the group.  Without such rudimentary interaction there is a diminished opportunity for therapeutic factors to emerge and be reinforced.  As such, the orientation stage is characterized by the facilitator(s) assisting members in interacting with each other and participating in the group process.   Having members repeat what was said to them, turn toward the person speaking, acknowledge what was said, and/or in some way participate in the group process through interaction is the goal of this first stage.  If the members fail to attend to each other, any other therapeutic, corrective, or instructional goals within the group will not be realized.

<H4>The Warm-Up and Sharing Stage</H4>

<P>The second stage of the group ushers in more intimate interactions between members.  In the warm-up and sharing stage the facilitator invites the members to speak within the group.  This is a process-driven group, and as such, the content of their presentations is of less importance.  In other words, the facilitator's concern is with the dynamics of the group.  The facilitator's job is to pay attention to the nature of the interactions between the various members.  During this second stage the group members take turns making their self-disclosures, and the cognitive networking begun in the orientation stage is continued.  For example, the facilitator may ask the member, who has just finished speaking, to select the next member to go.  In this way, members are again encouraged to pay attention to and interact with each other rather than with the facilitator exclusively.  
<P>Following this level of participation, the facilitator will then ask the members if any of them has a problem to work on in the group.  It is during this deeper level of sharing that the members will experience a greater sense of emotional involvement within the group. The group becomes more cohesive, and the stage is set for action to take place.

<H4>The Enactment Stage</H4>

<P>The central feature of the Interactive-Behavioral Model is the enactment stage.  All of the features of the enactment stage are modifications derived from the field of psychodrama (reference 26)  Psychodrama is a particular type of group psychotherapy.  It involves both  theory and techniques.  In fact, psychodrama is the original form of group work developed by the creator of the term "group therapy," Jacob Moreno, M.D.  
<P>Over the years techniques from psychodrama (reflecting issues unique to an individual's life)  and sociodrama (issues which reflect a collective concern) have been used with people with mental retardation.  However, the primary use of role playing was for role training.  More specifically, these techniques were used almost exclusively for social-skills training rather than for the purpose of facilitating therapeutic interactions. The teachers in these groups fostered interaction between themselves and the participants rather than between and among the participants.  Since the emphasis was on teaching a skill, the attention had to be focused on the teacher/trainer.  In the interactive-behavioral format, the emphasis is on interaction between the participants for the purpose of creating a therapeutic environment.  As such there is a major shift from a teaching/training model to a peer support/interaction model where behaviors having therapeutic value are reinforced as a way of strengthening viable group processes.
<P>It is during the enactment stage that techniques such as role playing and the double are used.  The issues presented in the warm-up and sharing stage are formulated into characters with the help of the facilitator.  Although only certain group members may take part in the enactment, the entire group's focus of attention is on the action taking place.  Of the four stages, the enactment stage is the core focus of the group.  Within the enactment stage there are a number of techniques used to stimulate interaction between group members.
<P>One of the most useful of those techniques is the double (reference 26).  Broadly stated, a double is a role played by one or more group members as they give voice to the feelings and thoughts of another member who is struggling with a given problem.  The use of the double can be a tremendous asset in groups for people with mental retardation, chronic psychiatric illness and dual diagnoses.  
The double has several purposes.  It can provide emotional support, give emotional expression and/or reorganize perceptions.  The process and techniques used in doubling include speaking the unspoken (what the person needs to say but is not saying), exaggerating, minimizing, introducing alternatives, restating, amplifying (highlighting the key part of the statement), verbalizing the resistance (why the person doesn't want to say something) and introducing paradoxes.

<H4>The Affirmation Stage</H4>

<P>Finally, in the affirmation stage the facilitator validates the participation of each of the members in the group.  This is done with specific attention to the therapeutic factors (references 4, 28).  Each member is verbally acknowledged for his or her interactive contributions to the group.  This reinforces the member's new social skills and has the added benefit of helping the affective intensity of the enactment stage to scale down somewhat.

<H4>	ISSUES RELATED TO GROUP THERAPY</H4>

 <P>With all these potential advantages it would appear that group therapy should be given a more central role in treatment planning.  While this is slowly beginning to happen, there are still a few obstacles which may be inhibiting the use of group counseling.
The first and perhaps greatest of these obstacles may be empirical.  In general the entire field of group psychotherapy struggles with scientific validation of process and outcome (reference 28).  Even sophisticated publications on the mechanics of running and maintaining a group leave out any mention of the validity of the group process (reference 1).  The challenge before those who are involved in group work with people with mental retardation is to provide data showing the similarities and differences between these groups and those with non-developmentally disabled people.  Additionally, the necessary modifications as well as the effectiveness of the process on behavior outside of group must be addressed.
<P>The evaluation of the effectiveness of group therapy is arguably the most difficult of all therapeutic validation efforts.  Process and outcome research is greatly hampered by issues surrounding criteria, meaningful dependent variables and proper methodology.  Indeed the difficulty in assessment of psychotherapy has been related by Nuffield (reference 18) to be attributed to the following conditions: "[t]he fuzzy and poor description of the therapeutic process, the inadequate description of the context, the failure to describe the intercurrent events that may be important, and the lack of objective outcome measures that are meaningful and that can be considered to be empirically valid." 
<P>In using group therapy for people with mental retardation the question of validity becomes more critical to demonstrate, yet more difficult to design.  This difficulty has not been encountered directly perhaps due to the fundamental difference between training and counseling.  As prior indications were that group work was not an appropriate means of therapy, the need for skill development was installed as the chief function of the group meeting.  Role playing was most often used as the primary vehicle for instruction.  The criteria became clear as to the effectiveness of the group.  Could the person demonstrate the skill rehearsed in the training group?  If so, the group was successful.  If not, another facilitator, another group, or another strategy were employed. 
The current state of development reflects a need for a shift from "training" group approach to a more interactive and therapeutic counseling format.  In doing this the emphasis on evaluating the acquisition of a particular skill with an individual in the group remains an important criteria for determining the effectiveness of the group process.  However, the exclusive focusing on specific skill development often neglects the rich potential to provide generalized support, (not limited to specific skill acquisition) on-going encouragement, a sense of belongingness, hope and other (re)habilitative elements that accompany a positive group experience.
The transformation is from content driven skill oriented groups, to those which are focused on process.   This shift would seem to require that a type of concurrent validity be established.  By this we mean to take what has been accomplished in group therapy in general and extrapolate from these findings for groups with people with mental retardation.  This approach has been identified as a primary vehicle for making group psychotherapy available to mentally retarded persons by Pfadt (reference 19).  Along these lines and particularly with regard to process, Yalom (reference 28) along with Bloch and Crouch (reference 4) have advanced one of the most comprehensive research based investigations of group psychotherapy available. Yalom has proposed that a collection of therapeutic factors account for the effectiveness of a group.  These factors, when present, indicate the viability of group process, and consequently, the therapeutic potential for group members.  A logical place to begin then would be to look for these factors in groups for people with dual diagnosis and further, to look for those efforts which activate these factors.
Since process would then be viewed (at least initially) as more essential than content, two important questions concerning the validity of the process emerge. 

<P>1.	Can therapeutic factors that emerge in other groups be demonstrated to exist in a group specifically designed to work with people who are dually diagnosed?

<P>2.	The second question is aimed at the difference in interaction from a skills training group: can it be demonstrated that interactions between facilitator and participants decrease over time as interactions between members increase?

	<H3>CONCLUSIONS </H3>

<P>As noted earlier, the shift towards group counseling from skill training groups may require that the content of the group become secondary to its process.  The Interactive-Behavioral Model has enjoyed wide usage.  To a great degree this is due to the fact the model describes a process taken from well established principles in group psychotherapy that have been modified for people with mental retardation.  It, therefore, can be adapted for use with various curricula.  Examples include:  anger management; AIDS awareness training; relationship counseling; sexual abuse avoidance training; mental health counseling; vocational readiness; behavior management; travel training; independent living readiness; sex education; socialization; educational readiness; parent-child education; birth control; and advocacy groups.
<P>Such a broad base use of the model seems to indicate that the four stage process of the group is more essential to the functioning of the group than is the content of the group.  The presence of therapeutic factors within the groups sets the stage for corrective work to be done.  Future research should focus on the validity of the process of the groups run for people with mental retardation.

<P> In conclusion, group counseling for people with mental retardation is a treatment whose time has come.  The need and desire for a therapeutic format in which learning can occur is present.  There is a need for peer support groups, with or without a particular curricula attached to them.  There is also the need for counseling groups designed for its members to not only change their behaviors, but feel different and better about themselves.  More clinicians are willing to develop the necessary skills and the participants are desirous of the kind of peer support only found through the group process.  It is time for those of us interested in the field to define the quality, and character, of the "Healing Crowd."

<P>1.	Bernard H, MacKenzie K (eds).  Basics of Group Psychotherapy.   New York: Guilford Press, 1994.

<P>2.	Blatner A.  Acting-In.  New York: Springer Publishing, 1973.

<P>3.	Blatner A, Blatner A.  Foundations of Psychodrama History, Theory & Practice.  New York: Springer Publishing, 1988.

