<html><head><title>Resources for Emotions Training</title></head><Body>
 <center><H4>REPRINTED WITH PERMISSION FROM:    "THE HABILITATIVE MENTAL HEALTHCARE NEWSLETTER"
			       May/June 1995,  Vol. 14, No. 3</H4></center>
<center><H2>PSYCHOSOCIAL INTERVENTIONS UPDATE: Resources for Emotions Training </h2><BR>


	<H3>BETSEY A. BENSON, PH.D.</H3></center>

	
<P>Difficulties in interpersonal functioning can arise when someone is not aware of his or her feelings, has trouble expressing emotions, expresses them inappropriately, or misinterprets the feelings of others. Recognizing emotions in oneself and others, therefore, can be one focus of psychotherapy with persons with mental retardation. For example, in the Anger Management Program (reference 1) recognizing one's emotions is the first component in the cognitive behavioral approach to learning self-control skills.  To effectively use self-control skills to manage anger, you have to notice when you are angry, preferably when you are starting to become angry. Also, recognizing the emotions of others  is also important to social functioning.  Realizing that someone is reacting negatively to what you are doing can help guide your behavior and perhaps help you avoid more serious confrontations in the future. 
<P>There has been considerable research on emotions recognition in persons with mental retardation.  In general, accuracy in emotion recognition tasks is correlated with mental age; people with a higher mental age do better than those with a lower mental age (reference 3).   Happiness is the easiest to identify, while anger, sadness, fear, surprise and disgust are more difficult to recognize (reference 9).  Some researchers have proposed an emotion specificity hypothesis, which states that emotion tasks are even more difficult for people with mental retardation to accomplish even taking into account mental age alone (reference 10).  In addition, some studies have revealed that individuals with autism have more difficulties with emotion labeling tasks than matched counterparts with mental retardation (reference 4).
<P>It may also be true that persons with behavior or emotional problems have greater than expected difficulties with emotion labeling tasks.   Walz,(reference 12) a graduate student at the University of Illinois at Chicago, found that aggressive and nonaggressive men performed equally on an emotion labeling task. Aggressive individuals, however, were more likely to make errors by labeling faces as angry when they were not than was the case with the nonaggressive participants.  The aggressive people seemed to see anger in others when it was not there.  Whether people with mental retardation and depression would make the error of labeling sadness more frequently is not known.  Misperceiving the emotions of others could lead one to incorrectly anticipate the other person's behavior, leading to a vicious circle of  misperception and misbehavior.

	<H3>TRAINING RESOURCES</H3>

<P>In a previous issue, Ludwig and Hingsburger (reference 6) described a <I>Feelings Curriculum</I> to improve emotion recognition and expression for individuals or groups.  There are also commercially available materials to improve skills in this area as well.  A difficulty with some materials developed for adults in the general population is that they deal with too many emotions. This can be a problem for persons with limited verbal skills. On the other hand, many materials developed for children in the general population, although they address fewer emotions, are not appropriate for adults with mental retardation.  Some middle ground is needed in which individuals can supplement the basic emotion labels (happy, sad, angry, surprised, fear, disgust) with their own terms (such as yukky, disappointed, frustrated).  The following are a few of the available resources on this topic.
<P>Probably most useful for research purposes are the Friesen and Ekman (reference 2) <I>Pictures of Facial Affect</I>.  There are 110 black-and-white slides of 14 primarily Caucasian men and women displaying six emotions, including happiness, sadness, anger, fear, surprise and disgust.  The slides were published in 1976 and can be obtained from Consulting Psychologists Press.
<P><I>Feelings are Real</I>, by Kristi Lane (reference 5) and published by Accelerated Development, is a series designed for classroom teachers and children without mental retardation.  There is a leader manual and two workbooks, one for Grades 2-3 and one for Grades 4-6.  This is a structured program with step-by-step procedures for each exercise. It can be adapted for persons with mental retardation.  
<P>Accelerated Development also publishes <I>Feelings:  The 3 R's - Receiving, Reflecting, Responding</I> (reference 11).  This publication includes 48 feeling faces in a sturdy three-ring notebook.  To adapt this book for persons with mental retardation, one could select a subset of feelings.
<P>Some resources can be found at teacher supply stores.  These are most useful for working with children, although with some adaptations they could be appropriate for adults as well.  Constructive Playthings stocks a series of teaching pictures on a wide range of topics for preschool through elementary grades.  One set is called <I>Moods and Emotions</I> (reference 7).  The packet includes 16 large pictures (12 X 17 in) and a 40-page manual.  The photos show a culturally diverse selection of children alone, interacting with other children, and interacting with adults.  The photos were published in 1970 and the clothing and hairstyles appear outdated now.  The manual suggests several ways to incorporate the photos into emotion education activities, includes stories, poems, and a list of children's books to supplement.  If adults with mental retardation are shown the photos, they can label the emotion expressed in the picture, tell a story about what might have happened, and use the story as a jumping-off point to talk about a time when they experienced the feeling.  Adults with mental retardation respond to these pictures by telling stories from their childhood, in keeping with the age of the characters in the pictures, but they can then share a recent experience in which the same emotion occurred.
	<H3>EMOTIONS TRAINING RESEARCH</H3>

<P>Most research on emotion recognition has studied the deficits of people with mental retardation in comparison to other groups.  One study, however, evaluated a training program to improve recognition of facial cues of emotion.  Photos of the Friesen and Ekman (reference 4) slides were used to teach emotion recognition to seven adults with mental retardation, including six who were functioning in the moderate range and one in the severe range of intellectual functioning.  Training was given on the distinctive facial features that correspond to the six basic emotions.  First, the participants identified parts of the face, e.g., eyebrows, lips, nose, eyes.  Once these were correctly identified, they were shown two photos of the same facial expression.  The trainer identified the emotion depicted in the photo and pointed to the facial cues that are most often associated with that emotion.  For example, if the emotion was disgust, the participant was told that "when people feel disgusted they have a) a wrinkled nose, b) cheeks that are raised, c) a brow that is lowered, and d) an upper lip that is raised" (p. 566).  The trainer pointed to each of these characteristics on the photos and then the participant did the same.  
<P>When all six emotions were successfully learned in this manner, the participant was shown pictures without a label and asked what the person was feeling.  Training progressed based on the individual's performance.  Participants were also shown videotaped role plays of the same emotions to determine their ability to generalize the training to other stimuli.  All participants improved following training and there was significant retention of the skill nine months later.

	<H3>APPLYING THE SKILLS</H3>

<P>Labeling feelings in drawings or photos of strangers can help develop a feelings vocabulary, but does not ensure that the individual can recognize emotions in people he or she knows.  With the cooperation of staff or family members, a photo album of feelings could be made to show familiar people with the facial expressions of emotions such as happy, sad, angry, fear, surprise and disgust.  The familiar persons could also supply a list of situations in which they experienced the feelings to create a matching task to use with the photos.  The same process could be followed with photos of the person with mental retardation and a list of situations in which the emotions tend to occur.  Individuals may need help in posing some emotions, however.  Although the face supplies many of the cues we use to recognize emotions in others, it is not the only source of information.  Training in labeling emotions should include other characteristics as well, such as gestures, voice tone, voice loudness, and body posture.  
<P>Staff and family can be asked to explicitly label their feelings more frequently and to supply explanations of the feelings such as: "I felt angry today when I lost my keys;" "I was happy that my car could be fixed quickly." Care should be taken to sound genuine and not artificial.  Individuals can also take advantage of opportunities to prompt the person with mental retardation to label his or her feelings more often.  When prompting for emotion labels, staff and family should avoid assuming that the person with mental retardation would have the same feeling that they would in the situation.  Starting with an open-ended question about feelings, waiting for a reply, and continuing with a more direct question if no answer is forthcoming is one way to prompt feeling statements.  For example,  "How did you feel when your mother stopped by today unexpectedly?  Were you surprised?" 
<P>Staff and family should also be cautioned not to deny the emotional labels offered.  This difficulty occurred with an individual I was seeing at an outpatient clinic.  The woman with Down syndrome and diabetes participated in individual psychotherapy sessions to address issues related to diet compliance.  She had an assignment to mark a chart each day to indicate her feelings (happy, sad, angry, O.K.) and whether she followed her diet.  While visiting a family member, she noted angry feelings on the chart after being told that she could not have the drink she wanted.  The family member told her that she should not feel angry, but should be happy, because the refusal meant that the family member cared about her enough to want to help her stick to her diet.  Although the family member was well-meaning, he was, in effect, denying the woman's feelings.  A better response would have been to acknowledge her angry feelings, and then explain the reason for refusing her request.  When addressing emotion recognition in psychotherapy, it is important that staff and family are aware of the goals so that they can support the process. 
	
<H3>SUMMARY</H3>
<P>Emotion recognition and expression can be one focus of psychotherapy with persons with mental retardation.  Some commercially available resources on emotions training were described.  One study was reported in which persons with moderate to severe mental retardation received training in emotion recognition.  Staff and family can facilitate emotion recognition skills by explicitly labeling their own emotions more frequently and by asking the person with mental retardation to do the same.  

<P>1.	Benson BA.  Teaching Anger Management to Persons with Mental Retardation.  Worthington, OH:  IDS Publishing, 1992.

<P>2.	Friesen WV, Ekman P.  Pictures of Facial Affect.  Palo Alto, CA:  Consulting Psychologists Press, 1976.

<P>3.	Gray JM, Fraser WL, Leudar I.  Recognition of emotion from facial expression in mental handicap.  Br J Psychiatry 1983;142:566-571.

<P>4.	Hobson RP, Lee A.  Emotion-related and abstract concepts in autistic people:  Evidence from the British Picture Vocabulary Scale.  J Autism Dev Dis 1989;19:601-623.

<P>5.	Lane K.  Feelings are Real.  Bristol, PA:  Accelerated Development, 1991.

<P>6.	Ludwig S, Hingsburger D.  Preparation for counseling and psychotherapy:  Teaching about feelings.  PAMR Rev 1989;8:1-7.

<P>7.	Marvel Education Company.  Moods and Emotions.  New York: Marvel Education Company, 1970.

<P>8.	McAlpine C, Singh NN, Ellis CR, Kendall KA, Hampton C.  Enhancing the ability of adults with mental retardation to recognize facial expressions of emotion.  Behav Modif 1992;16,559-573.

<P>9.	McAlpine C, Singh NN, Kendall KA, Ellis CR.  Recognition of facial expressions of emotion by persons with mental retardation.  Behav Modif 1992;16:543-557.

<P>10.	Rojahn J, Rabold DE, Schneider F.  Emotion specificity and mental retardation.  Am J Ment Retard 1995;99:477-486.

<P>11.	Tindall JA, Salmon-White S.  Feelings:  The 3 R's - Receiving, Reflecting, Responding. Bristol, PA:  Accelerated Development, 1993.  

<P>12.	Walz NC.  Recognition of facial expressions by aggressive and nonaggressive adult males with mental retardation.  Unpublished master's thesis, University of Illinois at Chicago, 1994.  

<P>Betsey A. Benson, Ph.D. is a psychologist at the Nisonger Center UAP, Ohio State University.  Her mailing address is Nisonger Center UAP, 1581 Dodd Drive, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH  43210-1296.
