In Reply to: <a href="986.html">When a life is worth living </a> posted by VINCENT J . CAFFARELLO on November 29, 1996 at 08:23:04:<p>
: I am a parent of a Down Syndrome Child who happened to view a story from the London Times on the arguments over eugenics. This story was written on November 29,1996. It basically states how pre-natal testing is being used as a means to avoid birth defects that will pollute the gene pool. There were several references that I found very hard to comprehend. The one that bothered me the most was of Jeffrey Greenspoon who is the Director of the High-Risk obstetric unit at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles. He admits that he approves of weeding out babies who don't have a vaible future. I firmly believe that a man like this should not be in the position he currently holds. I would like to hear from people on how we can respond to people who think like Mr. Greenspoon. <p>Bravo Vincente!!<p>This will become a major issue as more control is exerted over the "gene pool".  To understand how large a problem it is for those of us who sense the moral and ethical calamity this present us all with, a viewing of Nightline on the topic a few months ago sent chills up my spine.  It was about midgets and genetically engineering them out of existence.  There was very little reference to the moral or ethical questions of it, but an emphasis on the practical problems it presented to the society and the midgets.  There was even a midget acting as spokesman for other midgets who supported them being engineered out of existence.  I couldn't help but feel that this is a commentary on the present state of our culture.  People appear to  increasingly be wandering the landscape like Zombies with no hearts.  What is happening to all of us?  Read my "QIM Tunes" (link provided) to experience another angle on this problem.  
