<b>I have a daughter Amber Nicole and she is Down's, but I cannot even
begin to tell you how muchd joy and pride she bring to our family, she
is the apple of her fathers' eye and the sunshine she brings to her two
oldest brothers everyday in so amazing. Spoiled yea I guess but when your 
only daughter is born with so many obstacles in her way you kind of take 
advantage that as long as she know mom, dad, and brothers will always be
there for her she will be alright.  Amber is a little girl with lots of guts
and life within herself, she is strong, and abled to handle tuff situations. 
we have raised amber just as we raised our boys as normal as possible and it 
has paid off, right now is is going to school full time morning she is in 
kindergarden and the afternoon she is in the Resourse room, she has made lots
friends and everyone from the Principal of the school down to the students in 
the higher grades know her very well.  Her communications skill are improving 
everyday.  We are now working on her verbal communication and she has picked up
alot of everyday words. she understands everything, and she is up to about 40 
signs languages.  Anyway I could go on forever taking about my Amby{Her nickname]
but it'll take me days.  I just wanted you all to know that yes there are alot of 
hard times raising a special needs child, but let me tell you this the Good Times
sure as heck out weigh the bad and there is a real treasure at the end of the 
rainbow.  If there is anyone out there who would like to keep in touch with me 
