<TITLE>The Arc's Officers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="arcback2.gif">

<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Meet the Officers of</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>The Arc of the United States<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Quincy S. Abbot</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>President</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>West Hartford, Conn.<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
 With more than 25 years of experience as a volunteer with The
Arc of the United States at the community, state and national
levels, Abbot was elected national president by the association's
national convention delegate body in November 1996.  He is retired
as a senior vice president for CIGNA Corporation where he built
and managed the company's tax department.  He and his wife Zelia
have four adult daughters including one with mental retardation.
  <BR>
<P>
 <I>&quot;As every parent knows, individuals learn by watching
and copying people around them more than by what they are told.
 That is why it is important for people with mental retardation
to be included with other persons in all aspects of their life---where
they live, where they work, where they play and where they learn.&quot;
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Brenda Doss</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Vice President</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>Jasper, Ala.<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
 Doss has been executive director of the Walker County Mental
Retardation/Developmental Disabilities Board since 1994.  She
has 22 years of experience as a  special education teacher and
is the mother of  an adult daughter with mental retardation. 
For the past 12 years, she has been a member of The Arc's national
board of directors and has held various state and community volunteer
positions since 1976.  <BR>
<P>
<I>&quot;I believe it is society's responsibility to develop in
each person an awareness of every person's value and worth and
potential contributions to that society; to promote the growth
of every person's abilities, skills or talents to ensure that
person achieves a productive lifestyle; and to provide every person
with sufficient rewards to make life meaningful, enjoyable and
worth of living.&quot; <BR>
</I>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Richard A. Robleto</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Treasurer</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>Wilmington, Del.<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
 When his daughter was born with mental retardation more than
18 years ago, Robleto began volunteering with The Arc.  Professionally,
he is vice president of Blue Cross &amp; Blue Shield of Delaware's
International Division and is general manager of the company's
subsidiary, Allnation Life Insurance Company.<BR>
<P>
<I>&quot;Over the last 18 years, we have come a heck of a long
way.  Thanks to the efforts of the National Headquarters and local
chapters of The Arc, we have brought about changes in education,
housing and in other areas.  That means that people with mental
retardation can have 'normal' lives.&quot;<BR>
</I>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>Karen Staley</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Secretary</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>Beaverton, Ore.<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
 As a middle school teacher in the Beaverton School District,
Staley is a life skills instructor to students with severe to
profound disabilities.  She has also taught communication classes
to students with language impairments and has worked with special
education classes.  The mother of a son with mental retardation,
she has been a volunteer with The Arc since 1976.<BR>
<P>
 <I> &quot;It is up to us as an organization to ensure that every
individual with mental retardation and other disabilities has
the supports necessary to be the best that he or she can be. 
...Our work will not be completed until every person with mental
retardation and other disabilities has the same rights as anyone
else.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<HR>Return to The Arc's <a href="http://TheArc.org/welcome.html">welcome page</a>

</BODY>
</HTML>





