<center><H1>Access To Justice
<br>National Resource List
</H1></center>
<P>
<HR noshade width=50% size2>
<P>
<P><H2>People with Mental Retardation and the Criminal
<br> Justice System
</H2>
<P>The printed programs and materials listed are not an endorsement from The Arc.  The intent of this preliminary resource list is to promote further investigation of the topic, and will be updated as new materials and programs are created and/or are discovered.  Some materials may be easier to obtain than others.  Prices quoted for these materials are current at time of printing.  You should contact the organization for the availability, cost and content of the materials before ordering.  The Arc is not responsible for the quality or availability of the programs or materials in the resource list.


<P><H2>Programs and Projects</H2>

<P><B>The Arc Michigan's Criminal Justice Task Force</B>
<br>The Arc/Michigan
<br>333 S. Washington Sq., S-200
<br>Lansing, MI   48933
<br>(517) 487-5426
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Florence Ann Kozak

<P>The task force advocates for people with developmental disabilities in any phase of involvement within the criminal justice system and is a member of a statewide interagency task force, spearheaded by the Office of Community Corrections.  The task force hopes to be involved in staff training at the state correctional level and at the local court and police levels.

<P><B>The Center for Intensive Treatment</B>
<br>New York State Office of Mental Retardation 
<br>and Developmental Disabilities
<br>44 Holland Avenue
<br>Albany, NY  12229
<br>(518) 474-6309
<br><B>Contact:</B>  John Finn, Director of Forensic Service

<P>The Center for Intensive Treatment (CIT) is a highly structured and secure treatment and habilitative residential program for offenders with mental retardation.  The mission of the program is to provide a safe and secure environment in which programs and services can be provided.  The CIT receives referrals from throughout New York state and contains four houses and a day program center.  The individuals receive training on basic skills, such as proper personal hygiene and academic skills, as well as training on building socialization skills through recreation and mentor programs.

<P><B>Community Partnerships Police Training Project</B>
<br>Oregon Developmental Disabilities Council
<br>540 24th Place N.E.
<br>Salem, OR   97301-4517
<br>(800) 292-4154
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Michael T. Bailey

<P>This project developed a training curriculum for police officers consisting of a film, definitions, demographic information, anecdotes, services, vocational and residential programs, and questions and answers.  Police officers are trained to call the Developmental Disability program for information and assistance when in contact with a person who has mental retardation.

<P><B>Cooperative Service Plan</B>
<br>Division of Mental Hygiene and Mental Retardation
<br>Sierra Regional Center
<br>605 S. 21st Street
<br>Sparks, NV   89431
<br>(702) 359-6100 
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Darden Bynum

<P>A Cooperative Service Plan (CSP) effectively intervenes with people who have mental retardation by using a cooperative plan for dealing with illegal behavior.  The CSP has been implemented only a few number of times and is still being studied for its overall effectiveness.  The CSP focuses on providing treatment as an alternative to incarceration.

<P><B>D. D. Offender Program</B>
<br>Pueblo County Board for Developmental Disabilities
<br>115 West 2nd 
<br>Pueblo, CO  81003
<br>(719) 546-0577
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Larry Velasco

<P>This program began in 1989 in response to a long-term need for more intensive specialized community-based services for offenders with mental retardation.  Components of the program include:  highly structured residential setting, integrated community employment, case management and psychological services.  The program focuses on a team approach and emphasizes proactive planning.

<P><B>The Developmentally Disabled Offender Program</B>
<br>The Arc of New Jersey
<br>985 Livingston Ave.
<br>North Brunswick, NJ   08902
<br>(908) 246-2525
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Suzanne Lustig, Esq., Director

<P>The DDOP is a clearinghouse for information about offenders with mental retardation.  Program services include advocacy, case management, education and training.  Generic and specialized training is provided for law enforcement and court personnel.  Brochures are available for legal and law enforcement professionals that explain what mental retardation is and highlights the unique problems a person with this disability faces throughout the stages of the criminal justice process.

<P><B>Involuntary Institutionalization Division</B>
<br>Public Defender Service
<br>George M. Taylor Multi-Service Center
<br>7500 Ritchie Highway
<br>Glen Burnie, MD   21061
<br>(410) 508-2253
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Lois I. Fisher, Esq.

<P>The Involuntary Institutionalization Division, commonly known as the Mental Health Division, provides pre-trial assistance to the attorneys in the Public Defender Service who represent criminal defendants with mental retardation.  The Mental Health Division attorneys assume representation of criminal defendants with mental retardation who have been found not competent to stand trial or not criminally responsible (not guilty by reason of insanity).

<P><B>Joint Mental Hygiene Administration/Developmental</B>
<br>Disabilities Administration
<br>Forensic Pre-Trial Evaluation Program
<br>Community Forensic Services
<br>Department of Health and Mental Hygiene 
<br>8450 Dorsey Run Road, P. O. Box 1000
<br>Jessup, MD   20794-1000
<br>(410) 792-7020
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Beverly Wise, LCSW-C; Roxanne Castaneda, MS OTR/L; or Larry Fitch, Esq.

<P>Since 1985 this program has provided expert pre-trial psychiatric/psychological assessments on court order for defendants in criminal cases who have mental retardation.  Evaluators offer courts treatment suggestions as an alternative to incarceration.  A separate program provides a liaison to the Developmental Disabilities Administration to assure expert joint forensic evaluations.  Another program focuses on utilizing a "person centered" approach to developing individual plans for the person and the systems that support his or her life in the community.  The three programs work together to emphasize advocacy for the person with mental retardation in order to prevent or minimize reoffense.

<P><B>Justice Advocacy & Training Program</B>
<br>The Arc of New Mexico
<br>3500 Comanche N.E., Bldg. G
<br>Albuquerque, NM   87107
<br>(800) 358-6493
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Michelle Baca, Esq.

<P>This program conducts specialized training for law enforcement, the judiciary, probation, correctional and parole officers.  Advocacy services are provided statewide to adults and juveniles with developmental disabilities who are detained by the police.  The program provides education and brochures for self-advocates to help them know what to do if they are ever stopped or arrested by police.

<P><B>Lancaster County's Special Offenders Program</B>
<br>225 West King Street
<br>Lancaster, PA 17603
<br>(717) 299-8184
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Wayne Geltz

<P>Lancaster County Office of Special Offenders Program began in 1980.  It provides individualized and specialized services to juveniles and adults who have mental retardation and are on probation or parole.  County probation officers and case managers share the same caseload and responsibility of providing services to clients.

<P><B>Manfred S. Guttmacher Forensic Education Fund, Inc.</B>
<br>c/o Greater Forensic Center
<br>Professional Office Building, Suite 812
<br>301 Saint Paul Place
<br>Baltimore, MD   21202
<br>(410) 396-5013
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Thomas Oglesby, M.D.

<P>A non-profit/private organization formed to further education in the area of forensic psychiatry and psychology.  The members are developing resource materials for mental health professionals and attorneys who work with individuals with mental retardation and other similar disabilities.

<P><B>Massachusetts Community Assistance Parole</B> 
<br><B>Program (MassCAPP)</B>
<br>Massachusetts Parole Board and the Massachusetts 
<br>Community Assistance Parole Program
<br>27-43 Wormwood Street, Suite 300
<br>Boston, MA  02210
<br>(617) 727-3271

<P>The MassCAPP program was created in 1973 to provide parolees with developmental disabilities necessary social, occupational and academic tools to function as productive members of society.  The program utilizes volunteers (Community Assistants) to assist the parolee in seeking employment, housing or further education.  The main goal of the program is for each client to achieve self-sufficiency in the community and to take responsibility for his or her own actions.

<P><B>Mentally Retarded Offender Program of Cuyahoga County</B>
<br>Center for Mental Retardation / Formerly Arc
<br>1621 Euclid Avenue, Suite 514
<br>Cleveland, OH   44115
<br>(216) 621-0221
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Ben M. Bonanno, Executive Director

<P>Cuyahoga County Court of Common Pleas began this program in 1979 to address the special needs of offenders with mental retardation.  The program provides services that prevent individuals with special needs from "falling through the cracks" of the criminal justice system.

<P><B>Mentally Retarded Offenders Program (MROP)</B>
<br>Skyview-Hodge Unit
<br>P. O. Box 999
<br>Rusk, TX   75785-0007
<br>(903) 683-5781
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Frank Glenn, Acting Director of Programs

<P>The MROP was established to minimize the negative effects of incarceration and to maximize the likelihood of successful re-integration into the community.  All inmates entering the Texas Department of Criminal Justice Institutional Division (TDCJ-ID) are given a group intelligence test.  Inmates identified as having mental retardation are transferred to a specialized unit where they receive habilitative, social support, continuity of care and security services.

<P><B>Project TURN</B>
<br>4476 S. Century Dr.  Suite D
<br>Murray, UT  84123
<br>(801) 263-8782
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Kerry Hawkes

<P>Project TURN is a non-profit, residential program for offenders with mental retardation that encompasses all areas of a client's life.  Services such as housing, therapy, education, vocational, employment and recreation are provided within the program.

<P><B>Texas Council on Offenders with Mental Impairments (TCOMI)</B>
<br>8610 Shoal Creek Blvd.
<br>Austin, TX   78757
<br>(512) 406-5406
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Dee Kifowit, Director

<P>TCOMI was created to address the growing population of people with mental impairments who are associated with the criminal justice system.  The council funds a number of programs for offenders with mental retardation within Texas, such as Project CHANCE and Project ACTION.

<P><B>Volunteers of America Developmentally Disabled Offenders Program</B>
<br>Volunteers of America, Northern Texas
<br>2710 Avenue J
<br>Fort Worth, TX  76105
<br>(817) 535-0853
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Kim Guenthner, Case Manager

<P>In 1987, Volunteers of America began working with the Tarrant County Adult Probation Department to develop a specialized program for offenders who have mental retardation.  The goals of the twenty-four hour residential program include:  stabilize the individual's behavior, eliminate drug and alcohol problems, obtain employment for the resident, develop basic hygiene and survival skills and eliminate further criminal offenses.  The program also serves people from other counties.

<P><H2>Materials for Court Personnel</H2>

<P><I>ACCESS:  Final report of the Wisconsin Supreme Court Interdisciplinary Committee on the
<br>Court Related Needs of the Elderly and People with Disabilities</I> (1993)
<br>Elder Law Center/CWAG
<br>1245 E. Washington Ave.
<br>Madison, WI  53703
<br>(608) 257-5660
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $10.00

<P>This report includes the committee's recommendations for physical and communications access, as well as access to the jury process.  Training recommendations for all court employees and funding issues are outlined.

<P><I>Access To Justice:  Making North Carolina's Courthouses Accessible to People with Disabilities</I> (1993)
<br>Carolina Legal Assistance
<br>224 S. Dawson Street
<br>Raleigh, NC   27602-2446
<br>(919) 856-2121
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Deborah Greenblatt
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $15.00

<P>A 45 minute video that explains accommodations court personnel can use when in contact with people who have various disabilities, including mental retardation.

<P><I>Court-Related Needs of the Elderly and Disabled</I> (1991)
<br>American Bar Association
<br>Commission on Mental & Physical Disability Law
<br>188 M Street, NW
<br>Washington, DC  20036
<br>(202) 331-2240
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $20.00

<P>The book includes recommendations made by the National Conference on the Court-Related needs of the Elderly and Persons with Disabilities which was funded by the State Justice Institute.  Commentaries and background research papers accompany the recommendations.

<P><I>Defendants, Victims and Witnesses with Mental Retardation:
<br>An Instructional Guide for Judges and Judicial Educators</I> (1995)
<br>National Judicial College
<br>University of Nevada, Reno
<br>Reno, NV  89557
<br>(800) 25-JUDGE or (800) 255-8343
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $35.00

<P>This comprehensive training curriculum for judges contains extensive information and practical suggestions on how judges can accommodate people with mental retardation during courtroom proceedings.  Topics include identifying a person with mental retardation, facilitating communication in the courtroom, specific courtroom accommodations and court referral for community services.  Referral agencies for each state are listed within the manual.


<P><I>Disabled Youth and the Juvenile Court System</I> (1985) 
<br>Advocacy Center for the Elderly and Disabled
<br>210 O'Keefe Avenue, Suite 700
<br>New Orleans, LA  70112
<br>(504) 522-2337 or (800) 960-7705
<br><B>Cost:</B>  Single copies free

<P>This report focuses on the three most common disabilities encountered in the juvenile court system in Louisiana:  learning disabilities, emotional disturbances and mental retardation.  The purpose of the manual is to increase the awareness of judges, attorneys and members of the juvenile courts that these disabilities exist and provide an introduction to the most relevant statutes and rights applicable to children with disabilities.

<P><I>Into The Jury Box:  A Disability Accommodation Guide for State Courts</I> (1994)
<br>Commission on Mental & Physical Disability Law
<br>1800 M St., NW
<br>Washington, DC   20036
<br>(202) 331-2240
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $15.00

<P>This guide focuses on each phase of the jury process, offering concrete suggestions on how to modify existing practices to increase accessibility for people with disabilities.  Implications for jury service for people with mental retardation and mental illness are mentioned.

<P><I>Mental Disability Law:  A Primer</I>  (Fifth Edition, 1995)
<br>Commission on Mental and Physical Disability Law
<br>1800 M Street, NW
<br>Washington, DC   20036
<br>(202) 331-2240
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $15.00

<P>This booklet provides a comprehensive, easy to understand overview of mental disability law.  Key term definitions and tips on how to provide effective representation for clients are included.

<P><I>Mentally Retarded Criminal Defendants</I>
<br>by James Ellis & Ruth Luckasson 
<br>The George Washington Law Review
<br>March - May 1985, Vol. 53, Nos. 3-4, pp. 414-493

<P>This thorough article explains the overwhelming problems commonly faced by defendants with mental retardation when they become involved in the criminal justice system.  The lengthy document provides an in-depth analysis and historical overview of critical problems that plague defendants with mental retardation.  Extensive notes are included, providing an excellent resource for further study.

<P><I>The Mentally Retarded Offender: A Handbook for Attorneys</I>
<br>County of Summit Board of MR/DD
<br>89 E. Howe Road
<br>Tallmadge, OH   44278
<br>(216) 630-3091
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Steven Bremkamp
<br><B>Cost:</B>  Contact the above number for more information

<P>This handbook is designed to assist attorneys in becoming aware of the disadvantages people with developmental disabilities often face when they are arrested for committing a crime or are the victim of a crime.  The handbook is not intended to be an exhaustive resource for attorneys, but can be used as an initial reference before contacting organizations on mental retardation.  The handbook contains information directed toward Summit County but can be used as a model for other advocacy groups in developing similar materials.

<P><I>Opening The Courthouse Door:  An ADA Access Guide for State Courts</I> (1992)
<br>American Bar Association
<br>Commission on Mental & Physical Disability Law
<br>188 M Street, NW
<br>Washington, DC  20036
<br>(202) 331-2240
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $12.00

<P>A guide for state courts that provides practical suggestions on how court personnel can be in compliance with the public access provisions of the ADA.

<P><I>Survey Of Access To New York State Courts For Individuals With Disabilities</I> (1994)
<br>Commission on Quality of Care for the Mentally Disabled
<br>99 Washington Avenue, Suite 1002
<br>Albany, NY  12210-2895
<br>(518) 473-7378
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $10.00 

<P>This report surveyed the accessibility of 275 courts in 40 counties in New York State and found that most courts lacked plans or knowledge about how to assist people with mental retardation.


<P><H2>Materials for Law Enforcement Officers</H2>

<P><I>And Justice For All</I> (1988)
<br>Ohio Public Images, Inc.
<br>3894 Indian Ripple Road
<br>Dayton, OH   45440
<br>(513) 898-8828
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $49.95

<P>The purpose of this training is to help law enforcement personnel become familiar with people who have developmental disabilities.  The manual focuses on the topics of how to recognize and communicate with someone who has this disability and introduces community resources which are available for police officers when they come in contact with someone who has a developmental disability.

<P><I>ClearTalk:  Police Responding to Intellectual Disability</I> (1994)
<br>Charles Sturt University
<br>P. O. Box 588
<br>Wagga Wagga, New South Wales  2678
<br>(069) 33 2441
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Dr. Mark Brennan

<P>The ClearTalk manual was developed to help police respond to the communication needs of people with mental retardation.  The approximately 200 page manual consists of a study which examined responses of police service officers to people with mental retardation.  Through this study, the A.C.E. (Assessment of Communicative Effectiveness) procedure was designed for officers to use when in contact with people who have mental retardation.  The manual includes five "ClearTalk" modules which require the trainees to participate in various learning activities to facilitate their understanding of people with mental retardation.

<P><I>ECHO (Effectively Communicating with Handicapped Offenders)</I>  (1990)
<br>by Posluszny, Curry & Krask
<br>State University College, Exceptional Education Department
<br>1300 Elmwood Avenue
<br>Buffalo, NY   14222
<br>(716) 878-4000

<P>This training manual for law enforcement personnel has eight modules.  The characteristics of people with mild mental retardation, learning disabilities and emotional problems are discussed.  Tips for effective communication with people who have these disabilities are also mentioned.

<P><I>Effective Communication in Law Enforcement Services:  Guidelines for Compliance with the
<br>Title II Regulation of the Americans with Disabilities Act</I> (1995)
<br>American Speech-Language-Hearing Association
<br>Fullfilment Operations
<br>10801 Rockville Pike
<br>Rockville, MD  208525
<br>(301) 897-5700, ext. 218
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $24.00

<P>This manual explains various accommodations police officers can use when in contact with a person who has a communication disability (such as hearing, speech and language impairments).  People with cognitive disabilities are mentioned.  Information covered includes key ADA requirements, common communication problems, strategies for effective communication, selecting and using auxiliary aids and services and suggestions for ADA compliance.

<P><I>Improving the Police Response to the Mentally Disabled</I> (1986) 
<br>Police Executive Research Forum (PERF)
<br>1120 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Suite 930
<br>Washington, DC   20036
<br>(202) 466-7820
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $15.00

<P>A book that includes a comprehensive examination of the problems police agencies face when in contact with people who have developmental disabilities.  People with mental illness are highlighted.  People with mental retardation are briefly mentioned.

<P><I>Managing Persons with Mental Disabilities:  A Guide for Police Trainers</I> (1989)
<br>Police Executive Research Forum (PERF)
<br>1120 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Suite 930
<br>Washington, DC   20036
<br>(202) 466-7820
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $10.00

<P>The purpose of the curriculum is to help police officers effectively deal with people who have mental illness.  While the focus is on people with mental illness, people with mental retardation are briefly discussed.

<P><I>Mentally Retarded Offenders:  A Handbook for Criminal Justice Personnel</I>
<br>The Federation for Community Planning
<br>1001 Huron Road
<br>Cleveland, OH   44115
<br>(216) 781-2944 
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $7.95

<P>The handbook covers topics such as how an officer identifies, interviews and supervises people with mental retardation.  Legal aspects include preparing the court case and determining its disposition.

<P><I>Officer's Guide:  Interacting with Disabled People</I> (1991)
<br>Dayle McIntosh Center For The Disabled
<br>150 W. Cerritos, Bldg. 4
<br>Anaheim, CA   92805
<br>(714) 772-8285
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Norm Savage, ADA Project Coordinator
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $49.95

<P>A 15 minute training video created to educate and prepare law enforcement personnel for encounters with people who have disabilities.  People with various disabilities, such as mental retardation, cerebral palsy, autism, deafness, epilepsy, and those who use wheelchairs are discussed.  A handbook for police officers accompanies the video.

<P><I>Retardation and Criminal Justice:  Training Manual for Criminal Justice Personnel</I> (1979)
<br>by Santamour & West
<br>The Arc of New Jersey
<br>985 Livingston Avenue
<br>North Brunswick, NJ   08902
<br>(908) 246-2525
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Suzanne Lustig, Esq.

<P>This thorough training manual for criminal justice personnel includes topics such as 1) the myths and facts of someone with mental retardation; 2) the habilitative programs available to people with this disability; and, 3) the legal rights of an offender who has mental retardation.  Other associated disabilities such as autism and epilepsy are also mentioned.


<P><I>Training Key #353:  Contacts with People Who Have Mental Retardation</I> (in press)
International Association of Chiefs of Police (IACP)
<br>The Arc of the United States
<br>P. O. Box 1047
<br>Arlington, TX   76004
<br>(817) 261-6003
<br>(817) 277-0553 (TDD)
<br>thearc@metronet.com (e-mail)
<br><B>Cost:</B>  Single copies free

<P>This training key provides valuable information police officers need to know should they encounter a person with mental retardation.  The training key was developed by IACP and updated by The Arc.  It includes a discussion guide and question and answer guide to encourage active participation by police officer trainees during training sessions.

<P><I>What Can Happen When Persons with Retardation Encounter the Criminal Justice System</I>
<br>arc/Georgia
<br>1857 Ram Runway
<br>College Park, GA  30337
<br>(404) 761-3150

<P>This brochure for law enforcement personnel identifies common characteristics that people with mental retardation and other developmental disabilities may have when encountering the criminal justice system.

<P>When First Impressions Count (1989)
<br>Maricopa Advisory Council on Developmental Disabilities
<br>3333 East Camelback Road, Suite 185
<br>Phoenix, AZ   85018
<br>(602) 381-1595
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Kim Rispoli
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $40.00 within Arizona, $125.00 outside of Arizona

<P>An 11 minute video that illustrates typical situations law enforcement officers face when they encounter people with disabilities.  The video briefly highlights the basic rights and laws of daily living specific to people with disabilities. 

<P><I>When Persons with Mental Retardation Get Detained by the Police</I>
<br>District of Columbia Arc
<br>900 Varnum Street NE
<br>Washington, DC   20017
<br>(202) 636-2950 
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Karen Clay

<P>This brochure provides basic information about what mental retardation is and how to identify and communicate with someone who has this disability.

<P><H2>Materials - General</H2>

<P><I>A Passion For Justice</I> (1995)
<br>Hilltop Productions
<br>24 Park Place, Suite 24D
<br>Hartford, CT  06106
<br>(203) 951-3557
<br><B>Cost:</B>  Contact the above number for more information 

<P>A video featuring author and advocate Robert Perske.  The video, which was inspired by the book Unequal Justice written by Mr. Perske, reveals the injustices people with mental retardation often encounter when they are falsely accused of committing heinous crimes.

<P><I>Annual Report to the President:  Citizens with Retardation and the
<br>Criminal Justice System</I> (1991)
<br>DHHS Publication No. (ACT) 93-21046
<br>President's Committee on Mental Retardation (PCMR)
<br>U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
<br>Administration for Children and Families
<br>Washington, D.C.  20201-0000
<br>(202) 619-0634
<br><B>Cost:</B>  Single free copies are available from PCMR

<P>A report presenting the findings and recommendations of those who participated in the Presidential Forum on the Offender with Mental Retardation and the Criminal Justice System.  Various issues are analyzed as they relate to the three predominant segments of the criminal justice system (law enforcement, courts and corrections).

<P><I>Brother's Keeper</I> (1992)
<br>Creative Thinking International
<br>Box 256 Prince Station
<br>New York City, NY  10012
<br>(212) 629-5320
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $30.00

<P>A video depicting the events that took place when Delbert Ward, who has mental retardation, was accused of killing his brother William.  Mr. Ward was interrogated by police for four hours until he confessed to suffocating his brother.  Mr. Ward's small town rallied to raise money for his defense, and since trial evidence showed that William died in his sleep, the jury found Mr. Ward not guilty.

<P><I>The Council on Offenders with Mental Impairments:  Annual Report</I> (1994)
<br>Division of Developmental Disabilities, Division II
<br>P. O. Box 13178
<br>Tucson, AZ   85732-3178
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Karla Garis, Coordinator

<P>A report on how Arizona is organizing its procedures and evaluating the current state of services for offenders with developmental disabilities.

<P><I>Crime & Justice:  The Burden Study of Foundation Grantmaking Trends</I> (1991)
<br>The Foundation Center
<br>79 Fifth Avenue, Dept. JF
<br>New York, NY  10003-3076
<br>(800) 424-9836
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $35.00

<P>This report is a useful planning tool for grantmakers and grantseekers in the criminal justice field.  Grantmaking in crime and justice, as well as expert opinions about important crime and justice issues, is examined over a five year period (1983-1987) to determine trends in foundation giving, specifically in the area of criminal justice.

<P><I>Crime, Law Enforcement & Abuse Prevention</I> (1994/1995 Edition)
<br>The Foundation Center 
<br>79 Fifth Avenue, Dept. JF
<br>New York, NY  10003-3076
<br>(800) 424-9836
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $70.00

<P>This grant guide identifies grants for crime prevention, rehabilitation services for offenders, courts and the administration of justice, law enforcement agencies, and protection against and prevention of neglect, abuse, or exploitation of offenders.

<P><I>The Criminal Justice and Human Service System:  A Coordination Handbook</I> (1994)
<br>South Dakota UAP
<br>414 East Clark Street
<br>Vermillion, SD   57069-2390
<br>(800) 658-3080
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $10.00

<P>A handbook that provides information and assistance to people working in the human service or criminal justice system when both systems are impacting the life of a person with a developmental disability.

<P><I>The Criminal Justice System and Mental Retardation:  Defendants and Victims</I> (1992)
<br>by Conley, Luckasson & Bouthilet
<br>Paul H. Brooks Publishing Co.
<br>P.O. Box 10624
<br>Baltimore, MA   21285-0624
<br>(800) 638-3775
<B>Cost:</B>  $28.00

<P>A book describing what happens when people with mental retardation become involved in the criminal justice system.  This book is a good resource for advocates, service providers and legal representatives.  It includes the first attempt of an epidemiological analysis to discover the actual numbers of people with mental retardation who are involved with the criminal justice system in the country.  One chapter focuses exclusively on people with mental retardation as victims of crime.

<P><I>Deadly Innocence?</I> (1995)
<br>by Robert Perske
<br>Abingdon Press
<br>201 Eighth Avenue South
<br>Nashville, TN   37203
<br>(615) 749-6451
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $12.95

<P>This book traces the life and execution of Joe Arridy, a man with mental retardation, who was tried and convicted for the rape and murder of a teenage girl in 1936 after being led to confess to the crime.  The author provides unique insight into the miscarriage of justice that often results when individuals who have mental retardation are charged with capital crimes with little evidence, other than a coerced confession, to determine guilt.

<P><I>The Developmentally Disabled Offender:  Interfacing the Criminal Justice
<br>and Human Services System</I>
<br>Vida Publishing
<br>P.O. Box 331
<br>Willow Street, PA   17584
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $159.00

<P>A training video of four tapes (each tape approximately 60 minutes) of a seminar featuring John Finn, a nationally recognized forensics consultant and lecturer in the field of developmental disabilities.  A handbook is included that outlines the seminar's agenda.  Laminated cards for police officers that have helpful hints on how to deal with someone who has mental retardation and characteristics of someone with this disability are also included.

<P><I>Individual Justice Planning:  A Training Manual Developed for the
<br>State of North Dakota</I> (1988)
<br>North Dakota Protection & Advocacy Project
<br>400 E. Broadway, Suite 515
<br>Bismarck, ND   58501
<br>(701) 328-2972

<P>This training manual was developed for people involved in the coordination of services for offenders with mental retardation.  Emphasis of the training is on Individual Justice Plan (IJP).  The manual attempts to integrate issues from the area of developmental disabilities and the legal system.

<P><I>Persons with Developmental Disabilities and the Criminal Justice System in 
<br>Jefferson County Colorado Developmental Disabilities Planning Council</I>
<br>777 Grant, Suite 304
<br>Denver, CO   80203
<br>(303) 894-2345

<P>This research paper discusses issues surrounding the problem of  an ill-equipped criminal justice system in dealing with people who have developmental disabilities in Jefferson County, Colorado.

<P><I>Report of Massachusetts Task Force on Access of Victims and Witnesses with 
<br>Mental Retardation to the Criminal and Civil Justice Systems</I> (May 1993)
<br>25 Burlington Mall Road
<br>Burlington, MA   01803
<br>(617) 270-2201
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Joseph Buonomo, Vice Chairman

<P>The task force evolved in response to an incidence of sexual abuse in a group home.  As a result of the report, legislation was passed to improve access to justice for people with mental retardation.

<P><I>Report on the Adequacy of the System at the Department of 
<br>Juvenile Justice, South Carolina:  To Identify, Evaluate, Serve, and Monitor
<br>the Needs of Individuals with Disabilities</I> (1994)
<br>by Peter David Blanck, Ph.D., J.D.
<br>University of Iowa
<br>Iowa City, IA  52242-1113
<br>(310) 335-9043
<br><B>Cost:</B>  Single copies free

<P>A report on the juvenile justice system in South Carolina and its level of compliance according to the ADA.  Findings suggest conditions at the Department of Juvenile Justice (DJJ) violate the ADA.  Recommendations for compliance include promoting staff development, providing individualized services and transitional services, conducting self-evaluations and coordinating services.

<P><I>Unequal Justice:  The Case for Johnny Lee Wilson</I> (1995)
<br>The Institute on Disabilities - Pennsylvania's
<br>University Affiliated Program
<br>Temple University, College of Education 004-00
<br>Room 423 Ritter Hall Annex
<br>Philadelphia, PA  19122
<br>(215) 204-1356
<br><B>Contact:</B>  Lisa Sonneborn
<br><B>Cost:</B>  $35.00

<P>This video is a documentary of a man with mental retardation, Johnny Lee Wilson, who was coerced into giving a confession when he committed no crime.  Evidence that was found later clearly demonstrated his innocence.  Although many attempts were made by lawyers and advocates to appeal the courts ruling, he remained in prison for eight years until the governor issued a pardon for his release in 1995.

<P><I>Unequal Justice:  What Can Happen When Persons with Retardation or Other Developmental 
Disabilities Encounter the Criminal Justice System</I> (1991)
<br>by Robert Perske
<br>Abingdon Press
<br>201 Eighth Avenue South
<br>Nashville, TN  37203
<br>(615) 749-6451
<br><B>Cost:</B> $11.95

<P>This book presents dramatic incidents of people with mental retardation wrongly placed on death row.  The tragic experiences of what can happen when a person with this disability becomes a part of the criminal justice system are highlighted.

<P><H2>Materials for Self-Advocates</H2>

<P><I>Citizenship & the Law:  "TIPS"</I>
<br>James Stanfield Publishing Company
<br>Santa Monica, CA   90406
<br>(800) 421-6534
<br><B>Cost:</B> $599.00

<P>This training package includes nine videos and a teacher's guide to help students with special needs understand the law and how to interact with law enforcement personnel.

<P><I>If You Get Arrested</I>
<br>arc/Georgia
<br>1851 Ram Runway
<br>College Park, GA   30337
<br>(404) 761-3150

<P>A brochure for people with mental retardation that provides useful information on what to do if ever stopped or arrested by law enforcement.

<P><I>What To Do If You Get Arrested</I>
<br>District of Columbia Arc
<br>900 Varnum Street NE
<br>Washington, DC   20017
<br>(202) 636-2950 

<P>A brochure that provides people with mental retardation basic information on what to do when stopped or arrested by the police.
 
<P>The Arc is in the process of developing criminal justice-related materials for people with mental retardation, police officers and court officials.  Contact The Arc for more information.

<P><HR noshade width=50% size 2>

<P>The Arc of the United States
<br>500 E. Border Street, Suite 300
<br>Arlington, Texas 76010
<br>(817) 261-6003
<br>(817) 277-0553 (TDD)
<br>(817) 277-3491 (Fax)
<br><a href=mailto:thearc@metronet.com>thearc@metronet.com</a> (e-mail)

<P>The development and distribution of this resource list was prepared under a grant from the U.S. Department of Justice, Grant Project No. 94-CR-CX-0004.  While the Public Access Section of the Civil Rights Division has reviewed its contents, the programs and materials listed are not endorsed by the U.S. Department of Justice.


<P><B>October 1995</B>
<P>Return to <A HREF="/welcome.html">The Arc's Home Page</A>



