<TITLE>The Arc's Self-Determination Projects</TITLE><BODY BACKGROUND="test3.gif"><BODY TEXT="0000FF"><center><H1>The Arc's Self-Determination Projects</H1></center><P><center><img src=border1.gif></center><p>In response to The Arc's strategic plan outcome to "increase inclusion and choice for people with mental retardation", the <A HREF = "/depts/rpsdept.html">Department of Research and Program Services</A> has conducted a series of projects funded by the <A HREF = "http://www.ed.gov">U.S. Department of Education </A>to examine and support self-determination.  This page provides more information about self-determination, The Arc's projects to support this outcome for people with mental retardation and publications on this topic available from The Arc.<P><H2>What is self-determination?</H2><P>We're glad you asked!  We have looked at self-determination as an adult outcome.  Self-determination refers to "<I>acting as the primary causal agent in one's life and making choices and decisions regarding one's quality of life free from undue external influence or interference</I>" (Wehmeyer, 1994).  That means that people who are self-determined take control of their lives, make choices and decisions based on their interests, abilities and preferences, and take responsibility for their lives.  If you want more detailed information about self-determination and the results of our research and demonstration projects, check out the self-determination <A HREF = "sdetpub.html">publications list</A>.  <P><H2>Can people with mental retardation be self-determined?</H2><P>We're sorry we had to ask this question, but a lot of people think that people with mental retardation can't be self-determined because of their disability!  We don't believe this is true.  People with mental retardation can learn to make choices, participate in making decisions, solve problems, set goals and express their interests, preferences and abilities.  Too often they are just not provided the learning opportunities and experiences they need to develop these skills.<P><H2>What is The Arc doing to promote self-determination?</H2><P>The Arc strongly supports efforts to increase opportunities for people with mental retardation to express their preferences and choices and to be self-determined.  Through a series of education-related projects, The Arc is working to enable students with mental retardation and learning disabilities to become self-determined young people.  These have included model demonstration projects to develop and field-test curricula, research projects to examine factors promoting self-determination and develop a self-report measure of self-determination for adolescents with mental retardation and other cognitive disabilites.  More information about each specific project is located below:<P><UL><LI><A HREF = "sdetcurr.html">The Arc's Self-Determination Curriculum Project</A> (October, 1990 through December 1993)</UL><UL><LI><A HREF = "sdetass.html">The Arc's Self-Determination Assessment Project </A>(October, 1992 through March, 1995)</UL><UL><LI><A HREF = "sdetgend.html">Whose Future is it Anyway?</A> (October 1993 through September, 1995)</UL><UL><LI><A HREF = "sdfolup.html">The Arc's Self-Determination Follow-Up Project</A> (October, 1994 through September, 1995)</UL><UL><LI><A HREF = "sdressum.html">The Arc's Self-Determination Research Project</A> (October 1994 through September, 1999)</UL><center><img src=border1.gif></center><P><A HREF = "sdetpub.html">Publications </A>from The Arc's Self-Determination Projects are available from The Arc (see address on <A HREF = "/welcome.html">The Arc's Home Page</A>).  Address requests to Dr. Michael Wehmeyer, Assistant Director, Department of Research and Program Services.<P>
</DOC>
