<TITLE>The Arc's Self-Determination Assessment Project</TITLE><BODY BACKGROUND="test3.gif"><center><H1>The Arc's Self-Determination Assessment Project</H1></center><P><H4>Funded by U.S. Department of Education, Office of Special Education Programs, Division on Innovation and Development, Self-Determination Projects<br>Project Duration:  November 1, 1992 to March 31, 1995<br>Principal Investigator:  Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D.<br><P><center><img src=border1.gif></center><p><center><H4>Project Summary</H4></center>	The Arc (formerly Association for Retarded Citizens of the United States) is in the final year of a two-year project to conduct research on component elements of self-determination and to develop and field-test a student self-report assessment of self-determination.  <A HREF = "sdet.html">Self-determination</A> refers to <I>acting as a causal agent in one's life and making choices and decisions regarding one's quality of life free from undue external influence or interference</I> (Wehmeyer, 1992).  The Arc's research and development activities in self-determination are designed to identify variables that support or hinder this outcome for individuals with cognitive disabilities and provide instructional materials and activities that enable schools to support self-determination for all learners.  <P>	In year one of the project, personnel traveled to twenty self-advocacy groups in ten states across the nation, including Texas, New Jersey, New Mexico, Tennessee, South Dakota, Oregon, California, Oklahoma, Indiana and Ohio.  During these visits more than 400 adults with mental retardation and cognitive disabilities completed a series of self-report indicators of component elements of self-determination.   These assessments measured autonomy, problem-solving and goal-setting, self-concept, self-awareness, and individual perceptions of efficacy and control.  In addition, participants completed a survey, adapted from the National Consumer Survey, that provided an indicator of current self-determination status.  This survey provided information on the choice and control each individual experienced in the areas of employment, recreation and leisure, living and money management as well as providing information about the individual's leadership activities.  The subsequent analysis of these data provided information about the attitudes and abilities exhibited by self-determined adults with cognitive disabilities.  The four characteristics of self-determined individuals were that they acted autonomously, were self-regulating, psycholgically empowered and acted in a self-realizing manner.  For more information about this research and the characteristics of self-determination, visit the self-determination projects' <A HREF = "sdetpub.html">publications</A> page.<P>During the second year of the project, personnel used information obtained during the research phase to develop a student self-report measure of self-determination.  This assessment, called <I>The Arc's Self-Determination Scale</I>, assesses student attitudes and abilities in the areas of autonomy, self-regulation, psychological empowerment and self-realization.  The assessment is designed not as a diagnostic or prescriptive instrument, but instead as a self-evaluation tool.  Students could self-administer and score the assessment (with support from adults) and use the results to identify goals for transition and educational planning purposes.  In addition, the instrument will be a valuable tool for evaluating learning environments, instructional materials and teacher methodologies intended to increase self-determination.  Using the assessment as a baseline measure, students, researchers and educators could evaluate student gains in self-determination over time.  The assessment was field-tested with more than 300 students with mental retardation, learning disabilities as well as same-age peers without disabilities.  The psychometric characteristics of the scale were evaluated  by analyzing the data from the field-test, and the assessment is currently being printed.  An implementation guide will accompany the scale, and both should be available for purchase through The Arc in mid to late 1995.  Check into this page for updated information on the availability of<I> The Arc's Self-Determination Scale.</I><P>	Additional information about the project and the assessment can be obtained by writing:<P>Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D., Assistant Director<br>Department of Research and Program Services<br>The Arc National Headquarters<br>500 E. Border St., Suite 300<br>Arlington, TX 76010<P>Return to <A HREF = "/welcome.html">The Arc's Home Page</A>
</DOC>
