<TITLE>Self-Determination Follow-Up Project</TITLE>
<BODY BACKGROUND="test3.gif">
<BODY TEXT="238E68"><center><H1>Self-Determination Follow-Up Project</H1></center><P><H4>Funded by U.S. Department of Education, Office of Special Education Programs, Advancing and Improving the Research Knowledge Base Competition<br>Project Duration:  October 1, 1994 to September 30, 1995<br>Principal Investigator:  Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D.<br>Research Specialist:  Michelle Schwartz, M.A.</H4><P><center><img src=border1.gif></center><p><center><H4>Project Summary</H4></center>	<B>The Arc (formerly Association for Retarded Citizens of the United States) is conducting a one-year project to examine the relationship between self-determination and positive adult outcomes for youth with disabilities.  <A HREF = "sdet.html">Self-determination</A> refers to <I>acting as a causal agent in one's life and making choices and decisions regarding one's quality of life free from undue external influence or interference</I> (Wehmeyer, 1992).  The Arc's research activities in self-determination are designed to identify variables that support or hinder this outcome for individuals with cognitive disabilities and provide instructional materials and activities that enable schools to support self-determination for all learners.  We believe that self-determination emerges as certain component elements develop and that there needs to be more attention to these developmental aspects.<P>	Since 1991, project staff have worked with more than 500 adolescents with mental retardation and  learning disabilities to promote self-determination.  Many of these students participated in projects that developed curricular and assessment materials (see other <A HREF = "sdet.html">self-determination projects</A> conducted by The Arc).  While they were involved in these projects, they completed several assessments that provided information about their level of self-determination.  Many of these students have since graduated from school.  The Arc's <B>Self-Determination Follow-Up Project</B> is studying how well students have done since leaving high school.  We have developed a follow-up survey which will be used to evaluate the ex-student's current employment, post-secondary education, recreation and leisure and living outcomes.  Using this information, project personnel will be able to evaluate the relative importance of self-determination on positive post-school outcomes for students with mental retardation and learning disabilties.  We believe that students who were more self-determined at the time we evaluated them in high school will have achieved more positive adult outcomes.  The findings from this research should provide impetus to efforts to promote self-determination for youth with disabilities.  <P>	Additional information about the project can be obtained by writing:<P>Michael Wehmeyer Ph.D., Principal Investigator<br>The Arc National Headquarters<br>500 E. Border St., Suite 300<br>Arlington, TX 76010<P>Return to <A HREF = "/welcome.html">The Arc's Home Page</A></B>
</DOC>
