<TITLE>Research in Self-Determination</TITLE><BODY BACKGROUND="test3.gif">
<center><H1>Research in Self-Determination</H1></center><P><H4>Funded by U.S. Department of Education, Office of Special Education Programs, Division on Innovation and Development, Field-Initiated Projects<br>Project Duration:  October 1, 1994 to Septembe
r 30, 1999<br>Principal Investigator:  Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D.<br>Project Director: Susan Palmer, Ph.D.</H4><P><center><img src=border1.gif></center><p><center><H4>Project Summary</H4></center>	The Arc (formerly Association for Retarded Citizens of the Un
ited States) is conducting a five-year project to investigate the development of self-determination in students with cognitive disabilities.  Five research studies will be conducted to examine developmental components of self-determination with students w
ith mental retardation and learning disabilities.  Three chapters of The 
Arc (The Arc of Durham County, North Carolina; The Arc of  Douglas County, 
Lawrence Kansas; ARC-Alameda County, Hayward, California) will serve as 
field-site coordinators to organize reasear
ch activities and conduct data collection in school districts in their area.  In addition, one subset of high school graduates with cognitive disabilities will be followed longitudinally for three years after leaving school.   Over one thousand subjects w
ill be included in the various parts of the project.  Both students with mental retardation and their peers without disabilities will participate in the research activities.<P>	<A HREF = "sdet.html">Self-determinati
on</A> refers to <I>acting as a causal agent in one's life and making choices and decisions regarding one's quality of life free from undue external influence or interference</I> (Wehmeyer, 1992).  The Arc's research activities in self-determination are d
esigned to identify variables that support or hinder this outcome for individuals with cognitive disabilities and provide instructional materials and activities that enable schools to support self-determination for all learners.  We believe that self-dete
rmination emerges as certain component elements develop and that there needs to be more attention to these developmental aspects.<P>	In order to underscore the developmental nature of this process, several lines of investigation are included in this proje
ct.  One study will investigate the causal relationship between self-determination and positive adult outcomes through a longitudinal follow-along study of school graduates with cognitive disabilities such as mental retardation and learning disabilities. 
 A second study will describe the development of students' perceptions of self-determination using semi-longitudinal and cross-sectional research designs.    Two studies in the project will investigate attributions of causality and metarepresentational ab
ilities of children with mental retardation.  The project will also develop and validate a model of teaching which can be used to promote student self-awareness, self-efficacy, and other critical factors in self-determination.<P>	Additional information ab
out the project can be obtained by writing:<P>Susan Palmer, Ph.D., Project Director<br>The Arc National Headquarters<br>500 E. Border St., Suite 300<br>Arlington, TX 76010<P>Return to <A HREF = "/welcome.html">The Arc's H
ome Page</A>
