<TITLE>Whose Future is it Anyway?</TITLE><BODY BACKGROUND="test3.gif">
<center><H1>Whose Future is it Anyway?</H1></center><P><H4>Funded by U.S. Department of Education, Office of Elementary and Secondary Education, Women's Educational Equity Act Program<br>Project Duration:  October 1, 1993 to September 30, 1995<br>Principal Investigator:  Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D.<br>Research Specialist:  Margie Lawrence<P><center><img src=border1.gif></center><p><center><H4>Project Summary</H4></center>	The Arc (formerly Association for Retarded Citizens of the United States) is in the final year of a two-year project to develop and field-test a student-directed transition planning program.  Funded through the U.S. Department of Education's Women's Educational Equity Act Programs of General Significance, the project has developed a curriculum, titled <I>Whose Future is it Anyway?</I> to enable young women and young men with cognitive disabilities to take a greater role in their educational planning and decision-making process.  This project is one of several projects conducted by The Arc to promote self-determination for youth and adults with mental retardation.  <P><A HREF = "sdet.html">Self-determination</A> refers to <I>acting as a causal agent in one's life and making choices and decisions regarding one's quality of life free from undue external influence or interference</I> (Wehmeyer, 1992).  The Arc's research and development activities in self-determination are designed to identify variables that support or hinder this outcome for individuals with cognitive disabilities and provide instructional materials and activities that enable schools to support self-determination for all learners.  Our research has indicated that students with mental retardation do not have self-determination skills that enable them to assume control of their lives.  Low expectations held by others, highly structured environments and the lack of opportunities to engage in personal decision-making are barriers to the development of this outcome.  Females with cognitive disabilities experience a "double jeopary" due to the stereotypes and biases of disability and gender.<P>During the first year of the project personnel conducted an extensive review of the literature pertaining to gender equity and developmental disabilties.  Subsequently, project staff developed a six-part instructional program designed for use with adolescents with cognitive disabilities.  This program contains 36 unique sessions, each intended to be used by the student with support from teachers and other educators.  The sessions are written at a second to fourth grade reading level and provide an introduction to the educational planning and decision-making process, problem-solving and decision-making skills, goal setting and tracking, providing informed consent, and being an effective team member and leader.<P>During the second year of the project, personnel have conducted a field-test of the instructional program.  Ninety students with cognitive disabilities, enrolled in the Dallas Independent School District, have received instruction using the materials.  Based on the outcomes of the field-test, the curriculum will be revised and a facilitator's guide developed.  Currently it is anticipated that the curriculum will be published, either by the Women's Educational Equity Act Publishing Center in Boston or by The Arc.  In either case, the curriculum will become available through The Arc's Publication Catalog.<P>Additional information about the project and the curriculum can be obtained by writing:<P>Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D., Assistant Director<br>Department of Research and Program Services<br>The Arc National Headquarters<br>500 E. Border St., Suite 300<br>Arlington, TX 76010<P>Return to <A HREF = "/welcome.html">The Arc's Home Page</A>
</DOC>
