</DOCHDR>
<TITLE>The Arc's Self-Determination Curriculum Project</TITLE><BODY BACKGROUND="test3.gif"><CENTER><H1>The Arc's Self-Determination Curriculum Project</H1></CENTER><P><H4>Funded by U.S. Department of Education, Office of Special Education Programs, Secondary Education and Transition Services Branch, Projects to promote self-determination<br>Project Duration:  October 1, 1990 to December 31, 1993<br>Principal Investigator:  Sharon Davis, Ph.D.<br>Project Directorr:  Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D.</h4><br><P><center><img src=border1.gif></center><p><center><H4>Project Summary</H4></center>	From October, 1990 to December, 1993, The Arc (formerly Association for Retarded Citizens of the United States) conducted a model demonstration project funded by the Secondary Education and Transition Services' priority to develop practices that promote <A HREF= "sdet.html">self-determination</A>.  Working in conjunction with Dr. Donn Brolin at the University of Missouri at Columbia, project personnel utilized the <B>Life Centered Career Education Curriculum</B> (or LCCE) to promote self-determination skills for youth with mental retardation and learning disabilities.  The LCCE, a career education curriculum written by Dr. Brolin and published by the Council for Exceptional Children, provides a field-validated, readily available means of promoting self-determination.<P>Initial project activities focused on defining self-determination as an educational outcome.  Project personnel conducted an extensive review of the eduational and psychological literature related to self-determination, interviewed adults with mental retardation and surveyed parents and professionals to identify important characteristics of this construct.  The Arc defined self-determination as <I>acting as a causal agent in one's life and making choices and decisions regarding one's quality of life free from undue external influence or interference</I> (Wehmeyer, 1992).  The Arc's research and development activities in self-determination are designed to identify variables that support or hinder this outcome for individuals with cognitive disabilities and provide instructional materials and activities that enable schools to support self-determination for all learners.  <P>Following these definitional activities, project personnel worked with Dr. Brolin to identify LCCE competency and subcompetency areas that could be used to achieve self-determination.  The content of the resulting curricular materials involved four competency areas; a) self-awareness, b) self-confidence, c) choice and decision-making, and d) goal attainment behaviors consisting of more than 350 lesson plans.  The LCCE is structured such that topics are introduced through career awareness activities, students use career exploration activities to learn more about the topic and learning is reinforced through career performance activities.  <P>Once curriclar materials were identified, 250 students from Texas, Nebraska, Alabama, Virginia, Oregon and New Hampshire were recruited to field-test the materials.  These students were involved in instructional activities using the LCCE over the course of two years.  In addition to student data to validate the use of the LCCE, teachers and parents provided ongoing evaluation about the instructional activities.  One useful aspect of the LCCE is the criterion-referenced assessments that accompany the lesson plans.  Teachers can utilize the Knowledge Battery instrument to evaluate a student's knowledge about the area of instruction and the Performance Battery to examine the degree to which students put this knowledge into practice.  Project activities involved the design and field-testing of an additional assessment, the LCCE Self-Determination Scale, that provides information about student perceptions and beliefs related to self-determination.<P>The LCCE is available through the Council for Exceptional Chilldren.  The LCCE Self-Determination Scale will be published by CEC sometime during 1995.  For more information about the project and details about using the LCCE project to promote self-determination, visit the self-determination projects' <A HREF = "sdetpub.html">publications</A> page.<P>	Additional information about the project and the LCCE curriculum can be obained by writing:<P>Michael Wehmeyer, Ph.D., Assistant Director<br>Department of Research and Program Services<br>The Arc National Headquarters<br>500 E. Border St., Suite 300<br>Arlington, TX 76010<P>Return to <A HREF = "/welcome.html">The Arc's Home Page</A>
</DOC>
