<HEAD>
<TITLE>Action for M.E.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  background="../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif">
<h1 align=center><IMG SRC = ../images/logos/action.gif></h1>
<blockquote><hr>

<H1>Action for M.E.</H1>
<hr>

<B><I>Action for M.E.</I></B> is a national charitable trust which provides information and support services to people with M.E. (Myalgic Encephalomyelitis), their families, friends and carers, funds research and campaigns to change attitudes towards the disease:
<p>
<ul>
<li>by publishing and disseminating a journal and factsheets on M.E. and available therapies as well as advice sheets for doctors, employers, young people and their carers.
<li>by publicising and funding research both to demonstrate not only the real physical nature and mechanisms of the disease, but also to identify effective treatments to alleviate suffering in the short-term.
<li>by campaigning to government, the medical profession, the media and the general public to call attention to the financial, medical and social problems encountered by people with ME, and the difficulties they face when applying for medical care, benefits and social welfare.
</ul>
<p>
Action for M.E. recognises that both orthodox and complementary medicine play an important role in health care and the treatment and management of disease. Action for M.E. is an M.E. sufferer-led and grass-roots organisation. Its Council of Management and Executive comprise people with M.E. and family members. Action for M.E.'s president Clare Francis, the novelist and former yachtswoman, has ME, Action for M.E. policies and projects are defined by our members' experience and stated needs.
<p>
Action for M.E. works with trained professionals in every aspect of its work. Its research programme is monitored by experts in the fields of gastrenterology, biochemistry, paediatrics, epidemiology, research protocol and general practice. Its directors (both from successful campaigning backgrounds) have been recruited from the commercial fields of business and marketing consultancy, press and public relations. It has a full-time fundraiser.
<p>
Action for M.E. supports a network of over 200 groups and contacts throughout the United Kingdom which provides local information and support services to people with M.E., their families and carers and monitors the effectiveness of Action for M.E. campaigns.
<p>
Action for M.E. is funded principally by members subscriptions, donations from their families and friends and through grants from trusts and businesses. membership has just exeeded 6000 comprising both sufferers (90%) and non-sfferers (10%). Action for M.E. currently receives on average 45 membership applications a week.
<p>
Action for M.E.'s patrons, trustees and officers are: (Patrons) Lady Elizabeth Anson, Melvyn Bragge, Jimmy Hood MP, David Puttnam; (Trustees) Christopher Corin, Andrew Gray-Muir; (Council of Management) Clare Francis (also President), Martin Arber, Gill Jacobs, Jean Long, Francis Ommanney, Robert Quittenton, Valerie Rushton and John West.
<hr>
<H2>Ten good reasons why you should help!</H2>
<p>
<OL>
<LI>Because, although M.E. is listed by the World Health Organisation as a disease of the nervous system and although there are currently 150,000 plus sufferers in the UK (nearly twice as many as with MS), M.E. is a disease that is still poorly understood and thus severly marginalised.
<LI>Because ME is a disease which hits people from all walks of life, healthy and frail, from the very young to the very old. And because it mainly affects those in the prime of their lives - the late twenties. thirties and early forties - during that time when most of us fall in love, marry, have children and pursue a demanding career.
<li>Because M.E. is a lonely disease which often due to poor or late diagnosis, causes permanent disability in over 20% of sufferers with a further 60% never regaining full health.
<li>Because early diagnosis much improves the chances of recovery. At present only 20% of sufferers are diagnosed early enough to save them from the full ravages of the disease. 100% early diagnosis will only come through research, the development of simple conclusive diagnostic tests and education.
<li>Because, deprived of authoritative information or advice from the Department of Health, 61% of doctors are still unable - or unwilling - to recognise or diagnose ME. And because that lack of recognition and diagnosis often encourages disbelief and a lack of sympathy and support from family, friends and work colleagues. The social isolation can be as damaging as the disease.
<li>Because many M.E .sufferers, refused the diagnosis of M.E. necessary to obtain paid sick leave, work themselves into a hospital bed or permanent disablement, costing the NHS and the taxpayer far more in the long run.
<li>Because misdiagnosis often leads to inappropriate treatments. Not only does this cause additional suffering for the patient but also creates unproductive and avoidable work for an already over-burdened Health Service. the huge cost to the country in medical care, state benefits, wasted training and experience, and lost consumer purchasing power has yet to be calculated.
<li>Because M.E. is a disease which can destry family ties, break up relationships, decimate self-esteem and lead to total despair and even suicide.
<li>Because M.E. is a disease with, as yet, no cure. Research is increasingly suggesting that its symptoms are caused by an immune system dysfunction but other researchers believe that M.E. is due primarily to a persistant viral infection (though no single virus has yet been identified). Both may play a role. Much more research is urgently needed.
<li>And because, finally, M.E. is on the increase. There is a good chance that you already know someone with M.E. And it is certain that you soon will.
</OL>
<hr>
The best way to help Action for M.E. is to join as a member or supporter. The second best way is to make a donation: money, time, contacts, specialist skills, fame - all are extremely valuable in helping us win a better deal for people with M.E. Membership (for M.E. sufferers) costs £15 per annum, Action for M.E. supporter costs £15 (min) per annum.
<p>
Action for M.E. is a Scottish charity no. SC011909 founded in 1987 and is currently applying for registration in England.
<p>
For the latest information on research into the causes, mechanisms and diagnosis of M.E., its management and treatment, Action for M.E. campaigns or local ME support groups, please write with a large S.A.E. to:
<p>
Action for M.E.<br>
PO Box 1302<br>
Wells , Somerset BA5 2WE
<hr>

<IMG SRC = "http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/phone.gif" align=middle hspace=10> 01749-670799</b>
