<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<h1 align=center>Ataxia Northwest</h1>
<blockquote><hr>
<h3>What is Ataxia?</h3>
<p>
Ataxia is an umbrella term covering a vast number of nervous disorders, simply,
Ataxia   means  unsteadyness and clumsiness. Some forms of Ataxia are
more common than others and have specific names such as Friedreich's
Ataxia (the most common). Some Ataxias are caused by a genetic
abnormality and often symptoms first occur in childhood. Other forms can
occur in mid life and are known as Late Onset Ataxia. This whole group
of disorders are often refered to as Degenerative Ataxias as the
symptoms worsen with time.
</p><h3>What are the Symptoms?</h3>
<p>
The symptoms of Ataxia vary from one type to another, however, unsteadiness
and poor coordination are often the first signs. Slurred speech, and
difficulty walking are others.  Some Ataxias have other associated
problems such as spinal curvature(scolosis), diabetes, eye problems and
heart disease.
</p>
<h3>Can Ataxia be Cured?</h3>
<p>
As yet there is no known cure or treatment for Ataxia, however, international research
being carried out has already located several genes responsible for some<I>
not all</I> forms of Ataxia.  Researchers at St. Mary's in London, have
made several promising discoveries, but this research has to be paid for
by charities as there are no grants available from central government.
<p>
<h3>What does Ataxia Northwest do?</h3>
<p>
Ataxia Northwest is here to provide help and support to Ataxia victims across the Northwest of
England. U.K.  Telephone (or email) for advice on <I>most </I>Ataxia
reated problems. Our main task is carying out or coordinating
fundraising events in order to help pay for Ataxia research.
</p>
<h3>Can You Help Us?</h3>
<p>
If you would like to do a bit of fundraising (it's good for the soul!) to help Ataxia research, but need some friendly help or advice......or if you could possibly make a donation  however small,
please contact me (Chris Polhill) at the address below.
<hr>
<h4 align=center>Ataxia Northwest<br>
Telephone or Fax: 01925 631259<br>
Email: <a href=mailto:"chrome@mist.u-net.com"> chrome@mist.u-net.com</a></h4>
<hr>
<ul>
<li><a href="news:alt.support.ataxia">Ataxia Newsgroup</a>
