<head>
<title>M.I.N.D.</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<h1 align=center><img src=../images/logos/mind1.gif ALT="MIND"></h1>
<blockquote><hr>
<ul>
<li><a href="#whatsmind">What is MIND</a>
<li><a href="#mindlink">MINDlink</a>
<li><a href="#you">What You can do to Help</a>
<li><a href="#contacts">Contact Addresses</a>
<li><a href="break.html">The Break Through Campaign</a>
</ul>
<pre>



</pre>
<a name="whatsmind">
<h2>What is MIND?</h2>
<p>
One in four people experience some form of mental distress each year.
<p>
MIND is the leading mental health charity in England and Wales. It works for a better life for people diagnosed, labelled or treated as mentally ill and campaigns for their right to lead an active and valued life in the community. In all its activities MIND stresses the particular needs of black people, women and other oppressed groups.
<p>
Since its launch in 1946, MIND has grown into a movement with a solid network of supporters and local associations spread throughout England and Wales.
<p>
Drawing on the knowledge and skills both of people who provide and use the mental health services, MIND has established itself not only as the largest independent provider of good quality care in the community, but also as an influential commentator on Government policy in all areas of mental health.
<p>
<h3>Local Associations</h3>
MIND's 240 local associations are involved in a multitude of activities - from counselling to relatives' support schemes; employment projects to special needs housing; tranquillizer withdrawal workshops to running drop-in centres and a mental health bookshop. The bulk of the work is done by volunteers who form the backbone of MIND's mental health network.
<p>
<B>Information</B><br>
MIND's regional and national information workers advise on developments in mental health policy, the emotional problems people may encounter and the options available to deal with them.
<p>
<B>Legal</B><br>
MIND's legal service gives people guidance on all aspects of mental health legislation and represents clients in selected test cases.
<p>
<B>Education</B><br>
MIND's courses, workshops and conferences, held all year round and throughout Britain range from the very specialized "Code of Practice (Mental Health Act) training" for mental health professionals, to conferences on subjects such as the arts and mental health geared to all MIND supporters.
<p>
<B>Publishing</B><br>
MIND publishes books and leaflets. Some are useful to mental health professionals, but many are designed to be understood by the lay person.
<p>
For example, our series of award-winning advice leaflets deal with subjects such as anxiety, depression, caring, phobias, schizophrenia; and our special reports explain in easy to follow language what to expect from various medical treatments such as anti-depressants, ECT, and tranquillizers.
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top"> Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>





</pre>
<a name="mindlink">
<H2>MINDlink</H2>
<p>
MINDlink is about communication between service users and MIND's Policy and Campaigns. MINDlink's primary purpose is to be a consultative body to ensure that users and recipients of mental health services have a direct say in shaping MIND policy and campaigns. Although MINDlink operates primarily within MIND, it is also part of the broader user movement and has contact with other user organisations as well as statutory bodies.
<p>
<H4>The Functions of MINDlink</H4>
<p>
There are four key functions of MINDlink. These are:
<p>
<UL>
<LI>to have an input to MIND policy and campaigns through regular consultation and representation;
<LI>to act as an information and contact network for MINDlink members;
<LI>to put forward suggestions for MIND's future work;
<LI>to elect the members of the national MINDlink panel.
</UL>
<p>
<B>Coordination</B>
<p>
The coordination of MINDlink is currently undertaken by Madeline Chapman, a survivor of the psychiatric system. Madeline is working through her issues using complimentary and talking treatments. Coordination of MINDlink is based at MIND National offices in Stratford, East London.
<p>
<B>Membership</B>
<p>
Members are largely recruited through MIND Local Associations which are affiliated to MIND but are otherwise self-governing, through MIND Regional Offices and word of mouth. There has not been a recruitment campaign since 1987 when MINDlink was first begun but membership continues to grow - currently at the rate of about 100 -150 new members per year.  Membership is free in recognition of the valuable contribution that members make to MIND. Anyone with personal experience of mental health can join and, although it is not essential, membership of National MIND is encouraged. Names an address of members are not given out without prior permission of the individual and some members prefer to use an alias to preserve their anonymity.
<p>
<B>MINDWAVES and MINDlink Information Packs</B>
<p>
MINDWAVES is the name given to the bi-annual Newsletter containing poetry, long articles and prose written and produced by MINDlink members. In addition there are regular mailings of the MINDlink Information Packs which contain the latest information on MIND campaigns and policy, user news, readers letters, book reviews etc. It provides an opportunity for members to become better informed, to share their knowledge and to help empower others.
<p>
<B>Contacts List</B>
<p>
Members are invited to join the MINDlink Contacts List. The contacts list is for those members who are interested in communicating directly with other MINDlink members and is sent out to all new members when they join.
<p>
<B>Regional Contacts</B>
<p>
Each MIND Region (North, North-West, Trent & Yorkshire, West Midlands, South West and South East) has two MINDlink representatives who are elected on a three year basis to the MINDlink Advisory Panel (MAP). MINDlink representatives meet at the MIND offices to discuss national and local issues and to report on news from the committees they represent. The representatives also hold meetings regionally which offers an opportunity to meet with other local MINDlink members to share experiences and exchange views.
<p>
<B>Getting Heard</B>
<p>
MINDlink members' can influence MIND and the general public through a number of channels in addition to the regional route mentioned above. MINDlink has representatives on MIND's Regional Councils, the Policy Committee, and the Conference Committee. Additionally, if members are willing, they can speak with the Press, TV or Radio. Some members are also willing to run workshops or speak at conferences - and the Regional Representatives and the Coordinator will give support to help peole to move into these roles. Training is provided locally and a new programme of training is planned for the future. The Information Pack and the Newsletter is circulated to local MIND Associations, MINDlink members, the staff of MIND, Council of Management members as well as a growing number of individual and group subscribers.
<p>
<B>Why Join?</B>
<p>
The more that psychiatric service users - past and present - speak out, the more likely we are to eliminate the fear, prejudice and discrimination that mental health users are currently subjected to. If you would like to know more, want to join MINDlink or subscribe to MINDWAVES, please write to:
<p>
<b>
Madeline Chapman<br>
MINDlink Coordinator<br>
MIND<br>
Granta House<br>
15 -19 Broadway, Stratford E15 4BQ
</b>
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top"> Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>





</pre>
<a name="you">
<H2>What You Can Do For MIND</H2>
<p>
<B>Join Your Local Association</B>
<p>
Contact the Regional Office for your area from the addresses listed in the contacts list and they will let you have the name, address and the contact person for the nearest group in your area.
<p>
<B>Become a Volunteer</B>
<p>
MIND charity shops and local associations depend on the enthusiasm and energy of volunteer workers. Your help will be thoroughly appreciated.
<p>
<B>Join MIND's Consumer Network</B>
<p>
MINDlink, MIND's Consumer Network, has now over 500 members and a newsletter called MINDWAVES. It informs MIND's policy for greater understanding of users' views and for their involvement in planning and running mental health services.
<p>
<B>Join National MIND</B>
<p>
As a MIND member, you receive 10 per cent discount on MIND publications, £3 off the annual subscription rate to OPENMIND magazine and concessional rates on selected MIND courses and conferences. members also have the right to vote at MIND's Annual General Meeting.
<p>
<B>Raise Funds for MIND</B>
<p>
MIND's Appeals Department organizes a number of sponsored events including parachuting, motor racing, aerobatics, workouts, assault courses etc. You can use your skills and energy to help MIND help others. For details contact your nearest Regional Office.
<p>
<B>Give MIND Your Financial Support</B>
<p>
Many people do not wish to or are unable to become actively involved with the movement for mental health, but still want to support MIND in some way.
<p>
At a time when community mental health services are expanding and charities get less grany aid from Government, MIND needs all the financial help it can possibly get. If you wish to give us support in this way, please send your donation to MIND's Appeals Department.
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top"> Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>





</pre>
