<html>
<head>
<title>Fibromyalgia Association</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<H2 align=center>
<table width=80% border=4 cellspacing=2 cellpadding=0>
<tr>
<td align=center>
<font size=+4><b>The Fibromyalgia Association UK</b>
</td>
</tr></table></td></h2>
<blockquote>
<hr>
<ul>
<li><a href="#aboutus">Who are we?</a>
<li><a href="#whatis">What is Fibromyalgia?</a>
<li><a href="#contact">Contacting us</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<br><br><br>
<p>
<a name="aboutus">
Sufferers of the chronic condition fibromyalgias have been crying out for help and understanding for years. They knew the severe pain, fatigue and various health problems they had been experiencing were real, but until recently there was no diagnosis. Now help and information is at hand. There is now no need for a sufferer to cope alone.

<p>

In November 1992 the first fibromyalgia support group in the UK was founded by fibromyalgia sufferer Mrs Barbara Doodson, in Hazel Grove, Stockport. It soon became apparent that this was not the 'rare' condition first thought. Surveys abroad estimated that fibromyalgia affects between two and five percent of the population.

<p>

The group quickly received such a large response from sufferers, people experiencing health problems and medical professionals. It became apparent there was a need for a National Organisation and in July 1994 a Board of Trustees was formed. Dr. Robert Bernstein MA, MD, FRCP, Consultant Rheumatologist, was elected Chairman. Charity status was achieved in December 1994.

<p>

At a conference in Copenhagen in 1992, leading world experts reached a consensus on the characteristics and effects of fibromyalgia. They also noted that the World Health Organisation (WHO) had incorporated fibromyalgia into its International Classification of Diseases.

<hr>

<a name="whatis">

<h2>What is Fibromyalgia?</h2>

Fibromyalgia is a common condition, sometimes so severe that it interferes with personal and family life. It can occur alone or secondary to a condition like lupus, Sjogren's syndrome or arthritis. The name means fibrous tissue (fibro-) and muscles (-my-) are affected by pain (-algia) and tenderness. Not only do sufferers experience severe pain, (at times more severe than rheumatoid arthritis) for which there is rarely respite, but the condition may have wide-ranging health effects. Health problem may include irritable bowel, irritable bladder, muscle spasms, numbness and tingling, morning stiffness, memory lapses, and others. The overall descriptions given by fibromyalgia sufferers are:-

<p>

<h4 align=center>"I hurt all over" - "The pain is so severe, it is like someone stabbing and twisting a knife round and round" - "Even when I do get a good nights sleep, I feel as if I've run the London Marathon".</h4>

<p>

<b>Pain and Fatigue</b> are the most common characteristics, and occur in a never-ending circle.

<p>

<h2>What causes Fibromyalgia?</h2>

Fibromyalgia can come on for no apparent reason or can develop after an accident, a viral infection, childbirth or after an operation. Most recent research into fibromyalgia was stimulated by the finding of specific tender points and the discovery of sleep disturbance. Sleep laboratory studies during sleep have revealed that deep sleep is lost in most people with fibromyalgia. Deep, restorative sleep is repeatedly and excessively disturbed by lighter, dreaming sleep. Even in healthy volunteers, being woken up in each episode of deep sleep can lead to the typical symptoms and tender points of fibromyalgia.

<p>

<h2>Who is affected most by the condition?</h2>

Although the condition appears to be more common in women, it does occur in men (approximately ten percent) and children. Many sufferers report that they have had the symptoms since childhood and been told their problems were growing pains. So many people with fibromyalgia have been through years of pain and anguish.

<p>

<h2>How is Fibromyalgia treated?</h2>

Unfortunately there is no known cure for the condition at present. The condition is chronic but not life threatening. Treatment is aimed at relieving the symptoms and what works for one sufferer may not work for another. Various types of anti-depressant drugs are sometimes prescribed in low doses to help promote a deeper sleep, and painkillers to help with pain control. Relaxation techniques help to control the tension and the results can be calming for all symptoms, especially for the pain.

<p>

Keeping fit is important to each person who must find their own exercise limits. Gentle stretching exercises, low impact aerobic exercises and walking or swimming in a warm pool may be beneficial, but this may take many months and setbacks may occur. Getting no exercise can also make the pain worse, as muscles atrophy if they are not used every day. Hot baths or showers may offer relief but rest is vitally important - trying to work through the pain and fatigue makes matters worse.

<p>

Whatever the degree of fibromyalgia, lives are changed. We are not the people we used to be but there is one thing we'll never do :-



<h2 align=center>"WE WILL NEVER GIVE UP THE FIGHT"</h2>

<hr>

<a name="contact">

<h4 align=center>For further information on the condition and independent support groups in the UK, please write enclosing a large SAE (29p or 38p) to:</h4>

Fibromyalgia Association UK, (New Enquiries)<br>
8 Rochester Grove<br>
Hazel Grove<br>
Stockport<br>
Cheshire SK7 4JD<br>
<hr>

