<BODY  BACKGROUND=../images/logos/sdcbak.gif>
<a name="top"></a>
<H3><IMG SRC="../images/logos/sdclogo.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H3>
<h2><b>Stockport Day Centre Project Welcomes You</h2></b>
<hr>
<B>The project has a ten year history of helping those with
Mental Health problems, working closely with several other charities concerned with mental health such as <a href="mind.html">MIND</a> (National Association for Mental Health) who also publish a large selection of books covering all aspects of mental health. and also<a href="space.html"> Making Space</a> a Northern based charity and <a href="voices.html">Hearing Voices</a> a self-help support group network. The centre has also, with the assistance of MIND, Stockport Social Services, and the Health Authority helped form <a href="#svsm"> The Stockport Voluntary Sector Mental Health Project</a> and from May 1st 1996 has created a <a href="helpline.html"> Helpline</a>

<p>

Many of the Day Centre members have a literary talent and a <a href="work.html">selection of their poems</a> is available.
</B>
<p>
<h3>A Short History of Stockport Day Centre</h3>
<p>
<B>Stockport Day Centre originated ten years ago in May 1985.. It was started by local members of 
the community who had an interest in mental health,  and who identified a need for an informal 
drop-in centre for people who suffer from mental health problems. It was jointly funded by the 
Social Services Department and the Health Authority, assisted by donations and fundraising.
<P>
The centre aims to be supportive with very few rules and regulations. The members, workers, and 
volunteers got together and decided however, on certain guidelines which are necessary to 
enable a quality service to be provided. The emphasis in the centre is on self-help and member 
involvement. This is achieved by encouraging members to play an active role in regular meetings 
and by representation on the Management Committee.
<P>
Fundings allow the employment of two full time and four part time staff, who are assisted by 
around twelve active volunteers. It is hoped that with more donations, numbers of staff can be 
increased in the future to cope with the huge need for the centre. A need which makes the need 
for more staff urgent.
<P>
A range of activities are on offer to the members which include, Women's Groups, Men's Groups, 
walking, sewing circle, gym, pool, tennis, football, ten-pin bowling, arts &amp; crafts, and 
a variety of educational, vocational, and hobby interests. Self-expression through art, 
poetry, literature, and drama is encouraged, a newsletter is produced 
by the members and exhibitions of work done are held when possible.
<p>
<img src="../images/logos/back.gif"><a href="#top"> Back to the Top</a>
<hr>
Stockport Day Centre can be contacted at:
<p>
Stockport Day Centre Project<br>
18a Longshut Lane West<br>
Shaw Heath<br>
Stockport, Cheshire SK2 6RX
<p>
<IMG SRC = "http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/phone.gif" align=middle hspace=5> 0161-429-9744
<p>
<a name="svsm">
<H2>Stockport Voluntary Sector Mental Health Project</H2>
<hr>
This Project provides an innovative integrated approach towards meeting the needs of those with mental health problems in the Stockport area.
<p>
The team comprising of an Outreach Worker, Employment Worker, Community Link Worker and a Clerical Worker, is managed by a Joint Advisory Committee comprising of representatives from MIND, Stockport Social Services, Stockport Health Authority and Stockport Day Centre and also includes Carers and Users.
<p>
Drop-in centres at Brinnington and Tiviot Dale have been established with more planned soon with activities such as ten-pin bowling and theatre outings. A "Job Club" has been established at Stockport Day Centre and a similar one started at the occupational therapy department at Stepping Hill Hospital.
<p>
An essential element of the work is ensuring that those with mental health problems and their carers receive information on services provided by major agencies of care and to facilitate acces to any services that may be required.
<p>
The value of this small team working closely together, is acknowledged as an important element of a project which aims to counteract the gaps in mental health service provision.
<p>
It has now been active for over two years and is financed by  Stockport Social Services and the Mental Illness Specific Grant. A major difficulty for those experiencing mental health problems is the likelihood of people "slipping through the net", with the individual unable for, various reasons including lack of awareness, inaccessibility to information and difficulty in locating services they might feel they need.
<hr>
The Project is based at:
<p>
Stockport Voluntary Sector Mental Health Project<br>
York House<br>
21 Heaton Moor Road<br>
Heaton Moor, Stockport SK4 4LT
<p>
<IMG SRC = "http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/phone.gif" align=middle hspace=5> 0161-432-4704
<hr>
