<html>
<head>
<title>HERMES</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif>
<blockquote><br><hr>
<hr width=150><h1 align=center>HERMES</h1><hr width=150>
<h2 align=center>Health and Education Regarding M.E. in Stockport</h2>
<hr>

<h3 align=center>HERMES is the official newsletter of the Stockport M.E. Group.</h3>
<hr width=350>


<h4 align=center>[ <a href="#about">About us</a> ] [ <a href="#meets">Forthcoming Meetings</a> ] [ <a href="#news">Members News</a> ]<p> [ <a href="#info">Useful info</a> ] [ <a href="report.html">Meeting Reports</a> ] [ <a href="articles.html">Articles</a> ]</h4>

<hr><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<a name="about"></a>

<p> <b>The Stockport ME Group</b> was formed in 1988 by a small group of people with myalgic encephalomyelitis. Since then it has grown to encompass several hundred adults and children in Stockport and the surrounding areas.<p>
We are an indendent Group run entirely by volunteers, most of whom have M.E. We maintain close links nationally with the M.E. Association and Action for M.E.<p>
Our aim is to improve the quality of life for all M.E. sufferers.<p>
The Group provides local advice and information so that, largely through 'self-help', M.E. sufferers can manage their illness better and improve their recovery. The Group produces the newsletter HERMES which is sent, free of charge, to member's home adresses. It provides up-to-date local information, advice, comment and details of group activities. Monthly meetings are held at:<p>


<h4 align=center>The Alma Lodge Hotel<br>149 Buxton Road<br>Stockport<br>(on the A6)<p>They are held every second Friday of each month<br>starting at 10.30 am with speakers at 11.00 am</h4><p>

Newcomers are very welcome and transport can usually be arranged if required. The venue is 'wheelchair-friendly'. They are sympathetic, understanding, social gatherings usually with a speaker on relevant therapies, benefits and advice. 'Bring and Buy' sales and social events are also organised.<p>
A small library of books, tapes, videos etc. relevant to M.E. is available for loan or reference, as well as M.E. Association/Action for M.E. broadsheets, pamphlets and guidance notes for benefit applications. Two recommended books by the medical profession, 'ME - How to live with it'  by Dr. Ann MacIntyre and 'Living with ME' by Dr. Charles Shepherd are both held in the Group' library, or may be available from your local library.<p>
<hr>

<a name="meets"></a>
<h2>Friday 11th October</h2>

<h3>A Special Open Meeting</h3>

Friday 11th October is to be a very special meeting. We are holding an open coffee morning, to which we are asking you to bring your friends and relations. We are to have visits from some of our MPs, the Mayor, the Chairman of Stockport Healthcare Trust and the press. Although this is an informal occasion it will be a wonderful chance to gain publicity for our Group and raise our local profile.
This is your chance to meet influential people and have your say about our problems and needs.
We also hope to make a little money, by holding a bring-and-buy table and a crafts stall. For these we need your contributions and support. So come on all you clever fingered ones - how about it !?
There is to be our annual visit from "Wishes", who supply cards, gifts, stationery and wrapping paper of good quality - and at a reasonable price. For anyone who finds shopping difficult this is a good opportunity to stock up for a long time ahead. This will also help your Group as a percentage of the profits is kindly donated to us.
The people who will really matter on October 11th will be you. If this is your first visit or you are only an occasional attender please make that special effort to come. We have arranged this meeting to have a maximum impact on those who can influence many aspects of our lives. We really need your support on this one. So bring yourself, and friends if possible, to the Alma Lodge Hotel on October 11th from 10.30 am. You might even enjoy it!<p>                                              

<h2>Friday 8th November:</h2>

<h3>November Meeting - A.G.M.!</h3>

Although we keep as informal and friendly as possible, we do need to have a formal basis as a recognised Group. Because of this we will be holding an A.G.M. at this meeting. This will start at 10 a.m. Everyone is  welcome! If you would like to put something on the agenda, volunteer your services or speak on something close to your heart please let us know. Further details from the Chairman.
We shall hold our normal meeting from 10.30 am, when our speaker will be Sue Baker from Welfare Rights, a long time friend of the Group.
We will also hold a crafts stall to help raise funds. All contributions will be gratefully received.<p>
                                                   Diana Buller<p>


<h2>Friday 13th December:</h2>

<h3>Christmas Lunch</h3>

 11.30 Short meeting followed at 12.30 by Christmas Lunch. Traditional menu with several options (including vegetarian) available for 10.95. We need to give the Alma Lodge approximate numbers well in advance, so please give a 5 deposit to Jane McLean by the 30th October if possible.<p>

<hr>

<a name="news"></a>
<h3>Committee News & Nominations</h3>

Many thanks to Caroline Platt for all her hard work on investigating how we may become an independent charitable organisation - something we are considering for the future. Unfortunately Caroline had to stand down in June due to ME relapse. We hope to see her back in circulation before too long.
Should any member wish to stand for Committee then their name must be submitted (in writing) to the Group Secretary, Jean Holt, at least 14 days before the AGM (ie by October 25th).<p>
Derek Vernon<p>

<h3>Membership Subscriptions</h3>

Our Group has expanded dramatically over the last 18 months and we are now in contact with over 500 local ME sufferers.
The new leaflet "Stockport ME Group" explains our increasing range of activities from eg Support Services to campaigning for NHS improvements. All of this is done by a small team of unpaid volunteers, and all of which costs many £100's per year - money which we have not got!!
We have no state funding whatsoever and voluntary donations vary considerably from year to year. Please can you help us to put the Group on a secure financial footing by becoming a member?
If you have benefited in the past from the Group, or if you use our local services by phone, borrowing books, attending meetings etc. etc. then please will you join up now?
Completing the application form and paying £6 now gives you (and your family if appropriate) membership until 1st October 1997, and gives us the financial security to develop further services for the benefit of ME sufferers.
If you cannot afford the "subs" don't worry - we never turn anyone away but please do still complete the form and return it to Sally, our Membership Secretary. The more members we have (paid & unpaid) the greater our "strength" when negotiating with the NHS.
If you can afford a voluntary donation as well as your subs, then it will be most gratefully received.
Many, many thanks.<p>
                                                            Derek Vernon<p>

<h3>Parent Support Network</h3>

We have applied for a grant to be spent on copies of Action for ME's Children's Information Pack. We hope to use the internal mail to circulate these to schools in Stockport and North Derbyshire<p>


<h3>Jean's Bits and Pieces</h3>

We've had a display for a week in the Into Health shop with the opportunity for people to come in and talk.<p>
Into Health's Annual Report says that M.E. was the most enquired about condition between July and September 1995.<p>
We still have a few vacancies for hydrotherapy in Offerton House pool on Saturdays. Ring Inga (285 7583 pm) if you are interested.<p>
The HQ of the <a href="../charity/fmauk.html">Fibromyalgia Association</a> (a condition very similar to ME) is in Stockport. Our Group is a member, so we can pass on and receive any relevant information. For further details write, enclosing an A5 31p s.a.e. to: <p>
Fibromyalgia Association UK,                                     8, Rochester Grove, Hazel Grove,                             Stockport SK7 4JD  <p>      Jean Holt<p>


<h3>GPs/Nurses - "Managing ME" Seminar</h3>

Another Stockport first! All GPs and Practice Nurses are being invited to a course at Stepping Hill Hospital on Thursday 3rd October in the evening. The event is organised by Elaine Mayall and Val Kulkarni, from the NHS ME Support Programme.
Maybe you could ask your GP/Nurse whether they will be attending? They can get further information from Val on 0161-419-4462. <p>



<h3>Subnormal Temperature Study</h3>

Many thanks to Joan Bullock for organising the study and analysing the results, and to the 24 respondents. All basal (waking) temperatures were reduced by at least 1 yF and at most 3.5 yF from normal (98.4 yF). Those who got up at noon maintained a more normal temperature. 36% of the results surprisingly showed lower afternoon temperatures than waking temperatures. Due to the small sample size it is not possible to say that all people with ME have reduced basal temperature. If you have tested yours and it was normal please do let us know.<p>
The results are interesting since many factors affect body temperature including metabolic rate, stress level and the response to the nervous system and hormone gland output.<p>
A copy of Joan's full explanation of possible causes diagnostic tests and possible therapy can be obtained by sending an sae to Joan Bullock, 8 Worsley Crescent, Offerton, Stockport SK2 6AE.<p>



<h3>A Grand Day Out !</h3>

In July some of us spent the afternoon cruising down the Macclesfield Canal on the narrowboat, "New Horizons". As we floated past leafy banks and meadows, we enjoyed identifying wildlife and flowers. The boat is specially equipped for disabled people and it is possible to take a rest during the trip. Why not join us next year?<p>
                                                 Caroline Platt<p>

<h3>Editorial</h3>

Distribution of HERMES to around 500 local M.E sufferers has been possible up to now because of a few generous donations. Not least of these are recent contributions of £500 by the Boddington's St Georges Day Society and £100 by AAH Pharmaceuticals, for which we are very grateful. We cannot rely on the continuation of such donations though, so we must move to a more stable situation where a higher proportion of our income comes from recipients of HERMES and the other services the Group provides. Hence the importance of the membership <p>
Continuing this monetary theme, we desperately need the help of a bookkeeper/accountant, whether to join the Committee or just to offer occasional guidance. If you can help please contact Jean. .<p>
You will probably have noticed a slightly different look to this page. We have incorporated Ralph Morris's neat logo to standardise with other literature put out by the Group.<p>
I am always pleased to hear from people who have made full recoveries, and will gladly pass on tips. I listened with eager anticipation to a recent success story - the key: getting pregnant! Not a guaranteed panacea, judging by the response of certain Committee members!  <p>
Please send any articles, cartoons, etc. for the next issue to me, David Carter, 29, Devonshire Road, Heaton Moor, Stockport SK4 4EF by November 21st Small ads may also be included at a cost of £1, but please ring the editor to see whether space is available. <p>Opinions expressed in HERMES are not necessarily those of the editor or of the Stockport ME Group. Nor does the Group recommend particular treatments<p>
David Carter   <a href="mailto:106036.1066@CompuServe.COM">  106036.1066@CompuServe.COM</a><p>


<hr>
<a name="info"></a>
<h3>Young Person's Group</h3>
For the late teens/twenties. Occasional meetings and visits; friendship, information and support, contact by telephone or letter. For more information contact <b>Inga Taylor on 0161-285-7583 (pm only)</b><p>
<h3>Parents' Group</h3>
For parents of children and teenagers with M.E. Periodic meetings, telephone contact, moral support and advice on therapies, tuition at home etc. For more information contact <b>Libby Jackson on 0161-442-9061</b><p>
<h3>Welfare and Benefits Advice</h3>
<b>Jean Holt</b>, who founded the Group and is an ex-District nurse, is available to give intitial advice on welfare and benefits. Contact her (during school hours only please) on <b>0161-432-0390</b> Anyone having difficulties obtaining benefits should contact Jean or the <b>Stockport Welfare Rights Unit on 0161-474-3091 (Mon - Fri, 9am to 1pm)</b> A guide to completing the IB50 form 'Incapacity for Work Questionaire', can be obtained from the Group Library.<p>
<h3>M.E. Counselling Service</h3>
Talk over your problems and worries in confidence with a skilled counsellor, someone who cares and is 'M.E. aware' in the comfort of your own home.<p>
Free of charge to paid-up Group members, a voluntary donation to cover the counsellor's travelling expenses is welcome if you can afford it. For further information contact <b>Elaine Mayall on 0161-487-3637</b> (leave a message if she is not available)<p>


<h3>The M.E. Group Library</h3>

The Library, started some years ago, is still live and kicking - though finding people who are fit enough both to administer it and take it to all the Group meetings is turning out to be a bit of a problem. As any reader will know, 'bad days' strike at the most inconvenient times, but subject to such vagaries, there is now a plan for bringing members and books etc. into contact on a regular basis. The 'etc.' is intended to include magazines, pamphlets, articles and tapes (voice and video).<p>
The Library will be available, subject to the state of the Librarian (currently me!), at each of the monthly meetings at the Alma Lodge. You may borrow books free of charge  until the next meeting. In theory, there will be a fine to pay if books are kept beyond the following meeting. In practice, we will be reasonable, recognising that it is just as likely that a borrower will have a 'bad day' as it is for the Librarian. However, I think we might take the view that keeping a book beyond two meetings is somewhat unreasonable of the borrower.<p>
The mechanics of borrowing a book is exactly the same as it was in Public Libraries in the days before computers: each book has a Card and members have Tickets. You take a book: we keep your Ticket with the Card in it. You can have as many Tickets as you want (but please remember that we don't have enough books to let everybody take half a dozen).<p>
The only proviso is that, except in special circumstances, you must be a Paid Up Member to make use of the Library. Or to put it another way, one of the benefits of your subscription is access to the Library. Some part of your subs will go towards buying new books. If you wish to suggest additions, please let me know. Even better, if you want to contribute books, copies of related magazines which you receive, information pamphlets from (for example) the Benefits Agency I will be delighted to take them from you at the meetings.<p>
And finally ... please don't make me write to ask for books to be returned ... any expenditure on postage simply means less to buy more books.<p>
                                                                    Ralph Morris<p>



<h3>Supporting National M.E. organisations</h3>
We try to raise funds locally to support both our Group and the work done nationally in providing information and research into the causes and cure for M.E.<p>
Useful periodicals and medical/therapy information packs are available and we recommend that sufferers join one or both of the organisations (cheap/free membership is available from the M.E. Association in cases of financial hardship).<p>

<h3>Wheelchairs: what and where</h3>
<h4>Free:</h4><p> <b>Your doctor</b> can prescribe a wheelchair on the NHS if you need one 'permanently'. Manually propelled wheelchairs are provided for outdoor use. Electric, self-operated ones may be supplied for indoor use only.<p>
<b>The Red Cross</b> provide ordinary wheelchairs on short-term loan. This is free on a first-come-first-served basis. In Stockport contact Mrs Marsden of the Stockport Branch (483-4872). In opther areas see your Yellow Pages or ring the Manchester Branch (792-5040) for details of your local loan centre. A donation is appreciated.<p>
<h4>To Hire:</h4><p>
<b>Local disability shops</b> often have pavement vehicles and wheelchairs. See Yellow Pages or check the Disabled Living Centre (entry below). Check insurance.<p>
<h4>To buy:</h4><p>
<b>Motability</b> - Gate House, Westgate, The High, Harlow, Essex CM20 1HR (0129-635666) - has HP schemes to enable those on DLA to buy new electric wheelchairs and pavement vehicles (scooters).<p>
<b>Banstead Mobility Centre</b> - Danson Way, Orchard Hill, Queen Mary's Avenue, Carshalton, Surrey (0181-770-1151) - do a useful leaflet comparing makes of wheelchairs and pavement vehicles. They also make indivual assessments and have basic overnight accommodation.<p>
<b>Mobility Matters Network</b> - Dept. PR, Freepost, Kettering NN16 8BR (0990-13431) publish a free booklet 'The In's and Out's of Buying a Mobility Vehicle' which will help you choose the right power chair or pavement vehicle.<p>
<b>Manchester Disabled Living Centre</b> - Red Bank House, 4 St. Chad's Street, Cheetham M8 8QA (832-3678) have a wide variety of wheelchairs and vehicles for you to try and will give you independent advice.<p>
<b>Stockport Disabled Living Centre</b> - St. Thomas' Hospital, Shaw Heath (419-4476) - provide independent advice and have a list of reputable local dealers.<p>
<h3>Other Equipment</h3>
<h4>Free equipment:</h4>
<b>Stockport Home Equipment Store</b> run by the Health Authority and Stockport Council, St. Thamas' Hospital, Shaw Heath (419-4480) - provides specialised equipment free on long-term loan. Requests must be made via a District Nurse, GP, Social Worker, Occupational Therapist or Rehabilitation Officer.<p>
<b>The Rehabilitation Officer</b> for Stockport Council, Mrs Roberts (427-7011) will assess what equipment you may need to borrow and whether adaptions need to be made to your home. There may be a small charge for minor adaptions (ie installation of stair-rails and bath hand-rails) but mafor ones are means-tested.<p>
<b>The Red Cross</b> has a small amount of basic equipment (eg commodes, back-rests, blanket rests, bedpans and bath seats) for loan. Contack Mrs marsdem (483-4872).<p>
<h4>To buy:</h4>
<b>Disabled Living Centres</b> will advise you what is available and what to buy. The Stockport centre is at, St. Thomas' Hospital, Shaw Heath (419-4476), they also have a list of reputable dealers.<p>
<h4>Further Information</h4>
<b>The Disability Handbook</b> from the Disability Alliance ERA, 1st floor East, Universal House, 88-94 Wentworth Street, London E1 7SA (0171-247-8776) costs £9.95 (discounted if you are on any SS Benefits) or browse in main reference libraries.<p>
<a href="../charity/sdg.html">Stockport Disability Group</a> can help with questions about any disability issues from holidays to wheelchairs and publish a useful guide in association with <a href="../charity/signpost.html">Signpost Stockport</a><p>

Compiled by Caroline Platt<p>
<h3>Housebound - Fed up</h3>
Try the Home Library Service. They deliver to you once a fortnight, bringing books of the type which you request. Large print available in many titles for those that find reading small print difficult. They also have a large collection of cassette tapes. I had 'Round the Horne' - listened to all four sides one afternoon and enjoyed a really good laugh - best therapy of all!<p>
The service is available to Stockport residents who are unable to get to the public libraries because of disability, age or illness, and who have no-one to visit the library for them.<p>
They are based at:<br>
Torkington Lodge,<br> Torkington Road,<br> Hazel Grove, <br>Stockport (456-4200). <br>Enquiries to Elizabeth Young, S[pecial Services Librarian.<p>
<h3>Useful Services from BT</h3>
If you have weak hands and arms you can have a free Directory Enqiries Service. Dial 150 for details. I found them so helpful and no hassle at all to obtain the service which I now use regularly.<p>
If your telephone is your lifeline you can also have a repair service arrangement with BT, who guarantee to come out within 4 hours, day or night, and if they're not able to repair your phone there they will leave you with a mobile phone until the fault is corrected. Again this is a free service, just dial 150.<p>
Kareen Dayes<p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<ul>
<li><a href="index.html">UK ME-Web Front Page</a>
</ul>
