<html>
<head>
<title>Tameside Carers Centre</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<blockquote><hr>
<h1 align=center>Tameside Carers Centre</h1>
<hr>
<h2 align=center>Who we are - What we do</h2>
<p>

<b>Tameside Carers Centre</b> was opened in March 1995 to provide a wide range of services to Carers of people living in the Tameside area.
<p>


<h3 align=center>What is a Carer?</h3>

A Carer is a person who looks after, or helps to look after, a relative, neighbour or friend who is disabled, sick or elderly. A Carer takes on this role for many reasons, but it is not as part of any contract of employment. It doesn't matter where the Carer lives as long as the person they care for lives in the Tameside area.
<p>
<br>
<br>
<h3 align=center>What does Tameside Carers Centre Provide?</h3>
<p>
<b>Tameside Carers Centre provides services around three main areas:</b><p>

<h3>Information and Advice</h3>

The centre has information on disabilities and illnesses which may give Carers a better understanding of the problems they face on a day to day basis. e.g. Dementia, stroke, MS, etc. Information is kept on services and schemes in local authority, private and voluntary services. The centre can help Carers access the services they might need. Advice and assistance with filling in benefit forms is also offered.  We can  help Carers to arrange holidays which meet their needs and their pocket.  Where there is a need, we can help with applications for funding of holidays too. <p>

Because each Carer's information need is different, we keep a wide range of information which is constantly being added to as requests come into the centre. Whatever information is asked for, if we haven't got it....... we'll get it.<p>

There is also a 'Resource Library' at the centre containing books, audio tapes, video tapes, research etc., which will be useful to Carers and those working with Carers. There is a leaflet on <b>Tameside Carers Centre Information And Resource Library</b>  which you can send for.<p>

<b>"Looking After Someone"</b>  Tameside's guide for Carers is available FREE from the centre. <p>

<br>
<h3>Support</h3>
<p>
Support is provided to Carers in many ways. <b>Tameside Carers Centre</b> is involved in setting up a number of support groups. This gives Carers, and those who have been Carers in the past, an opportunity to get together to exchange experiences, discuss problems and support each other. It is intended that each group will run itself and decide how it wants to operate. It may be that some groups will want to include 'social activities'  others will not. But each group will run independently.
<p>
Carers often find it a help to talk through their worries and concerns with someone who has the time to listen and actively help. Where there is a need, workers from the centre will support Carers on an individual basis, offering a listening ear and, when required, information and advice. <p>
<br>

<h3>Advocacy</h3>

For some Carers, talking about their needs at care planning meetings, hospital discharge meetings and during an assessment, can be difficult. Staff from the centre will help Carers look at issues they might want to raise at these meeting and, if necessary, speak on their behalf.
<p>
There are also issues and concerns which are shared by a number of Carers. <b>Tameside Carers Centre</b> actively pursues these issues on behalf of Carers across the borough.
<p>
<br>
<br>
<h3 align=center>Is there anything else I should know about?</h3>
<p>
<h3>The Carers Register</h3>

<b>Tameside Carers Centre</b> has a Carers Register, and we encourage all Carers to join it. The Carers register is just like a mailing list, so it means we can send out regular information to Carers, make sure they know about new developments or changes to services. Registered Carers also receive any new information on issues nationally and locally which may help them in their caring role, as well as our newsletter <b>'Signpost'</b>. We inform Carers of any meetings they might want to attend, and help them to obtain sitting services
to enable them to go.
<p>
It is very easy to join the <b>Carers Register</b>, there is a simple form to fill in, that's all. The Register is a confidential mailing list, Carers names and addresses will not be passed on to <b>anyone</b>, without the Carers permission being sought first.
 <p>
<b>Tameside Carers Centre</b> is a new service, it is constantly changing to meet the needs of Carers. New areas of work are being undertaken and there is always something new and interesting happening. Everyone  on our Carers Register is kept up to date with all developments.
<p>
<h3>The Carers Card</h3>

<b>This scheme is jointly run by Tameside Carers Centre and Tameside Police. </b>
<p>
Carers have expressed concern about the possibility of them having an accident or being taken suddenly ill when they are away from the person they care for, e.g. out shopping, and no-one knowing the person they care for has been left alone and might be 'at risk'. <b>The Carers Card</b> aims to give Carers the reassurance that, should this happen, someone will ensure that the person they care for is looked after. Yet the scheme ensures Carers do not need to carry any information around with them on themselves or the person
they care for There is a leaflet you can send for about <b>The Carers Card Scheme</b>, which explains the scheme fully.
<p>

<h3>Carers Forum </h3>

Four times a year,  <b>Tameside Carers Centre</b> hosts a Forum day. All Carers are invited to attend, with alternative care arrangements made for the person they look after, if this is needed.  This is an opportunity for Carers to share their every day experiences with Senior Managers from Health and Social Services. We also use this meeting to talk about development in
services, and changes that will affect Carers, and those they care for. 
<p>
Alternative care arrangements can be made for the person you look after to make sure you can attend Forum meetings.<p>
<br><br>

<h3 align=center>Can I Use Tameside Carers Centre?</h3>
If you are a Carer, or if your work brings you into contact with Carers, then the answer is....... yes, and we look forward to hearing from you. Students are also welcome to use our library for research and project work.<p>
<br><br>
<h3 align=center>Is there a charge?</h3>


No............ all services are free. All it will cost you is a stamp, the cost of a phone call, or you can call in person anytime during opening hours. 
<p>

If you want more information.......... any of the leaflets mentioned above, or your <b>free</b> copy of <b>"Looking After Someone"</b> contact the centre.
<p>
<h3 align=center>Tameside Carers Centre<br>
Ryecroft Hall<br>
Manchester Road<br>
Audenshaw<br>
Manchester M34 5GJ<p>


<IMG SRC = "http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/phone.gif" align=middle hspace=5> Tel (voice & minicom) 0161 371 8963</h3><p>

<h4 align=center>The centre opens Monday to Friday from 9.30am to 4.30pm An answer machine is available outside office hours.</h4>
<hr>

<ul>

<li><a href="../charity/">The Charity Pages Index</a>
<li><a href="http://www.community-care.org.uk/">Community-Care Front Page</a>
<li><a href="../health/">Internet Health Resources</a>
</ul>
<hr>
  
</blockquote>  
<hr>
<h5 align=center>This page created and maintained for Tameside Carers Centre by<br> Community-Care <a href="mailto:carers@community-care.org.uk"> carers@community-care.org.uk</A></h5><h5 align=center> You are visitor number [ <b>58 </b> ]</h5>
<hr>
 



</body>
