<head>
<title>The M.E./CFS Charities Alliance</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif>
<blockquote>
<h1>The M.E./CFS Charities Alliance</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Statement of Objectives</h2>
<p>
The M.E./CFS Charities Alliance was established on 23rd November 1995. It was set up to ensure 
that M.E. Charities work in a collaborative and complementary way, and to present a united front 
on issues where this would be of benefit to people with M.E./CFS.
<p>
Its members currently include the four main M.E./CFS charities in the UK; The ME Association, 
Action for M.E., The National M.E. Centre and Westcare.
<p>
The aim is to work together to secure improved recognition, care, support, and information for all 
those whose lives are affected by M.E./CFS.
<ul>
<li>The objectives of the Alliance are:

<li>to foster a spirit of co-operation and mutual encouragement among member organisations

<li>to secure increased recognition and understanding of M.E./CFS

<li>to promote the collection and exchange of information on M.E./CFS

<li>to inform and influence policy-makers about the needs and circumstances of people with 
M.E./CFS

<li>to act as a channel for mutual collaboration on models of care and research

<li>to work in such a way as to establish and sustain a high standing for the Alliance
</ul><p>
Following extensive discussion on the nomenclature of the condition the Alliance agreed the 
following:
<p>
<h3>General</h3>

The M.E./CFS Charities Alliance (The Alliance) endorses the findings of the Report of the 
National task Force on Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS), Post Viral Fatigue Syndrome (PVFS), 
Myalgic Encephalomyelitis (M.E.) (Tyrell 1994).

<h3>Names and Definitions</h3>

The main names currently in use are Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS) and Myalgic 
Encephalomyelitis (M.E.).
<p>
Neither name is fully satisfactory. Chronic Fatigue Syndrome is easily confused with Chronic 
Fatigue and this can lead to the severity of the illness being underestimated. Further, patients 
frequently report that fatigue is not the most troublesome of their symptoms. The problems with 
the name M.E. are that it implies a disputed aetiology (no inflamation of the myelin can be 
detected) and myalgia is not universal.
<p>
The name M.E. can be used either as an alternative name for CFS or as a name for a specific 
condition described by Dr. Ramsey (1988) among others and recognised by many physicians in 
clinical practice. This condition may be regarded as a sub-group of CFS.
<p>
There is need for better names and continuing research on the merits of different definitions.
<p>
Until a better name is found The Alliance accepts both names.
<hr>
<a href="index.html"><img src="/images/icons/back.gif"></a>
</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
