<html>
<head>
<title>Guidelines for Sufferers and Carers</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif">
<blockquote>
<h4 align=center>Action for M.E.</h4>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>Coping with M.E.</h1>
<hr>
<h2 align=center>Guidelines for Sufferers and Carers</h2><br>
<h3>Q. What is M.E.?</h3>

M.E. stands for myalgic encephalomyelitis. It is listed as a disease of the nervous system by the World Health Organisation and recognised by both the Departments of Health and Social Security. The most recent research suggests that its symptoms are caused by a dysfunction of the immune system but other researchers believe that M.E. is due primarily to a persistant viral infection (though no single virus has yet been identified). Both immune system dysfunction and viruses may play a role. Much more research is urgently needed.<p>
The 'diagnostic' symptoms of M.E. are:<p>
<blockquote>
<li>exercise-induced fatigue precipitated by trivially small exertion - physical or mental -compared to the patient's previous capacity. Even walking up and down the stairs, a short walk to the shops - or even a long conversation - can put someone with M.E. in bed for days or cause a major relapse. The reaction may be immediate or delayed as much as 72 hours.<p>
<li>impairment of short-term memory and concentration.<p>
<li>fluctuation of symptoms, usually (but not necessarily) caused by physical or mental activity. Symptoms may vary from day to day, or even within a day.<p>
</blockquote>
People with M.E. also experience: fatigue not relieved by sleep, disturbed sleep, visual problems, mood swings, poor balance, severe headaches, muscle and joint pains, nausea, feeling alternatively hot and cold, allergies, constipation, diarrhoea, gas and bloating.<p>
As these latter symptoms could be caused by any number of illnesses, they only help to confirm M.E. when the three main symptoms above have been present for at least three months.<p>

<i><b>N.B.</b> People react to M.E. differently. It is not necessary to have <i>all</i> of these latter symptoms to have M.E. and some people with M.E. experience other symptoms.<p></i>
<br>
<h3>Q. What causes M.E.?</h3>
M.E. is usually triggered by a viral illness such as 'flu, glandular fever or even a cold, but other triggers such as vaccinations, exposure to chemicals, stress and accidents have been reported. For others, M.E. sets in gradually with no obvious cause.<p>
For more information on M.E., ask for 'What is M.E.' by Dr. Anne Macintyre or read her book 'M.E./Postviral Fatigue Syndrome - How to Live with it' (available from Action for M.E. Trading at £7.99, or the publishers, Thorsons - see 'Addresses' below).<p>
<br>
<h3>Q. Are there any other names for M.E.?</h3>
In the U.K., M.E. is also called postviral fatigue syndrome (PVFS). When first publicised by the U.S. media, M.E. was nicknamed 'yuppie 'flu' but, thanks to pressure from Action for M.E. and other patient organisations, this term is now less commonly used.<p><br>
<h3>Q. What should I do if I think I have M.E.?</h3>
<ol>
<li><b>Join Action for M.E.</b>As a member you will have access to many free advice sheets, advice on available therapies, a telephone helpline, our journal InterAction (three times a year), and a network of local support groups, see 'Addresses below.<p>

<li><b>Rest</b>. In the initial acute stage and during relapses or periods of viral infection, when even minor exertion brings on poisoned, 'flu-like feelings, it is important to have a period of <i>complete</i> rest. This maximises your chances of recovery. Unless you have these periods of complete rest your M.E. could go 'chronic' and, at worst, you could work yourself into a hospital bed or wheelchair and permanent disablement.<p>
Complete rest during these stages is essential, but going to bed for an extended period can be just as damaging as trying to do too much before you are ready for it. Unused muscles and fitness can sometimes deterioate, bringing further problems. When you feel well on the road to recovery, experiment with some gentle activity, e.g. sitting up in bed, reading, hydrotherapy, yoga, a short walk.<p>
Never push yourself to go to your limit but restrict yourself  to 70% of what you think you could manage and then see how your body reacts over the next 72 hours - the reaction is often delayed. If the poisoned 'flu-like feelings, muscle pains and total exhaustion recur, you've overdone it. But don't be afraid - you will not have done any permanent damage. With rest, the symptoms will disappear and you can try again - next time more gently. Listen to your body to find your own level. When you have managed <i>that</i> level several times, try a <i>little</i> more, and so on.<p>

<b>Beware.</b> Because M.E. tends to affect fit, healthy people who were enjoying their life and work, most people with M.E. find the above advice <b>very</b> difficult. the typical pattern for someone with M.E. is: feel bad, rest a bit, feel a bit better, <b>overdo</b> it, feel worse for longer, rest a bit more, feel a bit better, <b>overdo</b> it again, feel much worse for much longer, etc. etc.<p>

In this society, this is the hardest advice of all. For personal, cultural or financial reasons, most of us feel that it is almost impossible to take a complete break, perhaps of several months. But in M.E., it is this pressure to forever achieve and be productive, and this cycle, which has to be broken down for recovery to happen.<p>

<i><b>N.B.</b> Different people react to M.E. more or less severely. Some can manage a one mile walk quite early on whilst others can do little for months. Your reaction to exercise is the best indicator as to whether you have M.E. or not. Anyone - healthy or ill - will feel tired after a one mile run, but it is a healthy, satisfying tiredness, not the poisoned, 'flu-like feelings people with M.E. experience.<p>
</i>

<li><b>Diet</b>. Ensure that your diet is as 'clean' as possible by avoiding refined foods, junk foods, sugar, salt, alcohol, coffee and tea, dairy and wheat products (potentially allergy-promoting) and unfiltered water. Stop smoking. The less energy your body needs to process the food it's given, the more energy it has to heal itself.<p>

<i><b>N.B.</b> These are general guidelines. Everyone reacts to diet differently and many people with M.E. develop the most unexpected food sensitivities. Experiment to see what helps you and what doesn't. For more information on diet and nutrition, see Action for M.E.'s 'Diet Factsheet' and 'Vitamins & Minerals Factsheet' - see 'Addresses' below.</i><p>

<li><b>Keep a 'Medical Diary'</b>. Your best hope of getting a diagnosis of M.E. from your GP is to make a <i>'week in the life' diary</i> of your illness. Record in great detail - hour by hour and day by day - your activities, symptoms, sleep patterns, feelings and difficulties. Get it witnessed and signed by your carer, a friend or relative. If at all possible, get it typed up so that it is easy to read.<p>

<li><b>Your GP</b>. The key person in M.E. is your GP. It is really important to make them a friend and supporter. A diagnosis is essential. Without it, getting paid time off work, taking time off school, qualifying for state benefits, even winning the sympathy and support of friends and family, may be extremely difficult.<p><br>

</ol>
<h3>Q. How should I approach my GP?</h3>

Take your 'week in the life' diary with you and try and take your GP through it. Do not tell him or her what illness you think you have - GPs believe that it's <i>their</i> job to decide that. If they admit to being completely stumped (our members report that 61% of GPs are still unable or unwilling to recognise M.E,), suggest, 'Could it be this postviral/chronic fatigue thing I've read about?' The terms 'postviral fatigue syndrome' and 'chronic fatigue syndrome' are less specific than 'M.E.' and far more acceptable to the average GP at present.<p>
<b>Important</b>. Be open to the possiblity that you do not have M.E. but a disease or condition with similar symptoms. There are many, many illnesses which look like M.E. and it is the GPs job to exclude all these other possibilities.<p>
<br>
<h3>Q. What diagnostic test are there?</h3>

No conclusive diagnostic tests for M.E. have been developed as yet. Diagnosis is made on a careful history and by excluding the many other diseases and conditions with similar symtoms.<p><br>
<h3>Q. What treatments are available?</h3>

No magic cure or definitive treatment for M.E. has been found as yet. If your doctor admits that s/he does not know what to advise apart from rest and diet, say that you will try to find out whether there is a national patient organisation which can provide advice and that you will get back to him or her.<p>
Research has proven that two therapies bring relief for many people with M.E.: magnesium injections and the nutritional supplement Efamol (a combination of evening primrose oil and marine oil). Action for M.E. has factsheets on both - see 'Addresses' below.<p>
Although these have not been scientifically assessed, our members report being helped by other therapies. These include hydrotherapy (79%), relaxation techniques (79%), massage (64%), anti-candida treatments (55%), healing (54%), aromatherapy (51%), anti-depressants (49%), Allergy Desensitisation (49%) and vitamin and mineral supplements (49%). Action for M.E. offers factsheets on a wide range of therapies - see 'Address' below.<p><br>

<h3>Q. Is M.E. another form of depression?</h3>

No. Because depression can cause very similar symtoms to M.E. this question has been the subject of a vast amount of research which has increasingly shown that they are <i>not</i> the same. On the other hand, it is not surprising that, given the severity, chronicity and unpredictability of the disease with its remission-relapse-remission pattern, some people with M.E. get a little depressed sometimes. Symptoms of depression in M.E. may also arise as a result of losing so much of life or as a direct result of brain disturbance caused by the disease.<p>
But the facts speak for themselves. M.E. tends to affect happy, positive people in the prime of their lives and in challenging professions such as teaching, nursing and social work - positive, dedicated professionals who feel great responsibility to their patients, clients, employees or pupils and try to push through the illness rather than listen to their bodies. And, even with M.E., a surprisingly low number become depressed (23% compared to 27% in cancer and multiple sclerosis).<p><br>
<h3>Q. My GP doesn't believe in M.E. what can I do?</h3>

Change their GP's mind, change GP, or get referred to a consultant who does!<p>

<ol>
<li><b>Try to change your GP's mind</b>. It depends how open your GP is to new ideas. Most people find it difficult to admit that they are wrong, once they have pronounced their view or that they do not know about something they think they should know about - GPs are no exception! However, it's always worth a try.....Perhaps on the second visit (after you have 'gone away to find out whether here is a patient organisation which can provide advice,), tell your GP that you have found out that:<p>
<ul>

<li>the World Health Organisation lists M.E. as a disease of the nervous system in its 'International Classification of Diseases' (ref. G93.3),<p>

<li>Davidson's 'Principles & Practice of Medicine' (p.882) lists M.E. under 'Infections of the Nervous System',<p>
<li>Both the Departments of Health and Social Security recognise M.E. as a 'debilitating and distressing condition' with a physical basis,<p>
<li>M.E. is listed under 'Certain Neurological Disorders' in the DSS's 'Disability Handbook',<p>
</ul>

and show him or her the Action for M.E. leaflet 'M.E. -The Physical Evidence' which lists the most recent research demonstrating the organic basis of M.E./PVS/CFS.<p>
If s/he is resistant, <i>be assertive.</i> This means being positive and clear and saying what you want <i>without</i> being aggressive. Offer the information and say, "I know you have little time to spare but I would appreciate it very much if you would read this information on M.E." or "Could I have another appointment with you. It would be useful if you would read this information beforehand."<p>
<b>Important.</b> Check whether it is that your GP doesn't believe in M.E./PVS/CFS or doesn't believe that <i>you</i> have M.E./PVS/CFS. There are many diseases and conditions with similar symptoms and it is the GP's job to exclude all other possibilities.<p>

<li><b>Change GP</b> If your present GP still won't accept M.E./PVS/CFS, try to change onto the list of one who does. Approach other doctors in your area and ask whether they recognise M.E. When you find one, politely ask if you may join their list. If you have trouble findiing a GP, contact your local Family Health Service Authority (FHSA) for help (address and telephone number in Yellow Pages under 'Health Authorities'). Local M.E. Support Groups also often keep listts of sympathetic and unsympathetic GPs based on members' experience. For a list of local M.E. support groups near you, and also a copy of 'If you are unhappy with your GP factsheet', contact Action for M.E.<p>
The FHSA is also the place to go if you wish to make a complaint about the way a GP has treated you. Help in writing the complaint is available from the local Community Health Council (address and telephone number in Yellow Pages under 'Community Health Council').<p>

<li><b>Getting referred to a consultant for a second opinion</b>. If you have trouble finding a consultant who recognises and understands M.E., Action for M.E. maintains a database of consultants reported to be sympathetic by two or more of its members.<p>

<li><b>Your MP or the Health Ombudsman</b>. If all else fails, there is always their MP or the Health Ombudsman (address from the local Citzens' Advice Bureau or library). When you write, don't forget to include a copy of your 'Diary' and to keep a photocopy of your covering letter.<p>
</ol><br><p>

<h3>Q. What should I do if I am prescribed anti-depressants or referred to a psychiatrist and don't like the idea?</h3>

The first thing is to be extremely honest with yourself. Depression can cause symptoms very much like M.E. and you need to be very clear whether this could be the cause in your case or not. If this is the main cause - and it isn't being dealt with - no other treatment will have more than a passing effect.<p>
There is nothing shameful about being depressed. So-called 'psychological' illnesses are as real and damaging as any so-called 'physical' illness and, indeed, these days most GPs and psychiatrists recognise that trying to make a distinction between 'physical' and 'psychological' is a nonesense. Most illnesses contain elements of both and both can lead to each other. However, because, mainly through fear and poor understanding, our society still discriminates against people who have a psychological illness, it is important to ensure that the patient's medical records lists M.E as the principle diagnosis and <i>cause</i> and (e.g.) 'depression' or 'depressive illness' as the <i>effect</i>.<p>
If you are clear that your M.E. was not triggered and that recovery is not being held back by an underlying depression, state that view forcefully and, if your GP insists, ask for a second opinion. Some GPs refer patients to psychiatrists simply because thay don't want to admit that they don't know what is wrong.<p>
However, it may be worth accepting a visit to a psychiatrist simply to get a clean bill of mental health and some extra support anyway. Many are extremely good doctors who understand that illness cannot be divided black and white into 'physical' and 'psychological' and will certainly understand how an unpredictable and chronic disease like M.E. can make its victims depressed.<p>
Being prescribed anti-depressants does not necessarily mean that your GP thinks you have not got M.E. or that you won't benefit. Many people with M.E. have found that <i>very low</i> doses of some anti-depressants - particularly tricylics such as amitriptylene, dothiepin, doxepin and trimipramine - help with sleep, brain function, muscle pain and weakness, mood swings and allergies because they help increase levels of a vital brain chemical - serotonin - which is depleted by M.E. If you have become slightly depressed - quite understandably - because of your M.E., a low dose of anti-depressants may make all the difference between coping and battling on or not coping and the depression getting worse.<p><br>

<h3>Q. What if I am prescribed a graded activity or graded exercise programme?</h3>

Only accept if you feel you are well on the way to recovery. Given that there is some evidence of <i>persistant</i> viral infections in people with M.E., graded activity/exercise programmes should not be seen as a treatment but only as <i>part of the rehabilitation process</i> after the initial acute stage has passed and there is no ongoing viral infection. Only agree to stay on a programme provided that increases in the level pf activity are determined by <i>your</i> ability rather than the dictates of the programme and that, if you do relapse from trying too hard, you are allowed to return to a lower level which you can cope with without bringing on a relapse up to 72 hours after the activity/exercise.<p><br>

<h3>Q. Is M.E. infectious?</h3>

Where M.E. has been triggered by a virus, that virus may well be infectious but, once the virus has passed, the resulting M.E. is not known to be. Many people with M.E., however, are prone to viral infections and these, of course, may be infectious as well.<p><br>

<h3>Q. Can young people get M.E.?</h3>

Whereas 10 years ago, M.E. in young people was extremely rare, a growing number are now contracting it- even as young as 4 and 5 years old. No research has explained this phenomenon conclusively but it is suggested that either there is a growing disposition to the immune dysfunction which causes M.E., that the increasing degradation of our environment - air, water, food lifestyle - is having its toll, or both. Action for M.E. pruduces two factsheets for children: 'Advice for Young Sufferes, their Parents and Guardians' and 'M.E. - Guidelines for Schools', see 'Addresses' below.<p><br>
<h3>Q. What are the chances of a full recovery?</h3>

Clinical observation suggests that 20% of people with M.E. make a full recovery within 1-2 years: these tend to be those who were able to find a sympathetic GP, get a diagnosis, take a complete break at the outset and follow the advice above! 60% learn how to manage their illness theough careful diet, pacing themselves and leading reduced lifestyles: few can handle a full-time job. 20% sadly, gradually deterioate and become permanently disabled.<p><br>

<h3>Q. Can you die from M.E.?</h3>

Yes, but it is extremely rare and usually due to complications with a parallel illness or because, in some cases, M.E. can weaken the heart. There have been cases of accidental death due to M.E. symptoms such as loss of balance, blackouts and memory loss. Some people with M.E., deprived of understanding, help or support, resort to suicide.<p><br>

<h3>Q. Can I qualify for State Benefits with M.E.?</h3>

Yes. The Departments of Social Security and Health both recognise M.E. as 'a disabling and distressing condition (with) a physical basis' and it is listed under 'Certain Neurological Disorders' in the DSS's 'Disability Handbook'. State benefits are therefore available dependent upon your level of disability and many people with M.E now recieve some.<p>

However, for a variety of reasons (mostly bad) there are more - even some severely disabled by their M.E. - who have been refused benefits. All you can do is try. Before you apply, it is essential to get a diagnosis of <i>physical</i> disability and the committed support of a GP or, better still, of a consultant. Even this, astonishingly, gives no guarantee of success.<p>

As well as the normal benefits available to those unable to work or on low incomes, there are several benefits available to the disabled such as Disability Living Allowance, Invalidity Benefit, Severe Disablement benefit, Equipment & Services for the Disabled, Disability Working Allowance, Attendance Allowance (for over 65's) and Invalid Care Allowance.<p>

Leaflets on all of these should be available from local post offices, DSS offices, social services and Citizens' Advice Bureaux but it is often simplest to write and request a full set from the DSS Leaflet Unit - see 'Addresses' below.<p>
Other ways of making life easier include: help with the Council tax, NHS prescription and dental costs, sight tests, travel to hospitals and legal aid; holidays, home helps, meals on wheels, disabled driver 'orange' badges, special housing, laundry and telephone needs (from the local social services); British Rail disabled railcards, local bus and train disabled concessions, 'door to door' guides and support lines (from British Telecom).<p>

If you feel unable to cope with the paper maze surrounding state benefits - often too much for the fit and able - Citizens Advice Bureaux are an excellent source of help as are your local Wefare Rights Unit. As well as helping with the forms, they can also sometimes supply 'advocates' to speak on your behalf to DSS officials and at appeals. Action for M.E. does not, sadly, have the resources to help with individual cases at present.<p><br>



<h3>Q. Are there any disability aids suitable for people with M.E.?</h3>

Yes, such as specialist walking sticks, walking frames and shopping trolleys, electric scooters and wheelchairs, kitchen, bathroom and cleaning aids. Most are available on prescription or on long term loan from your local Council or Red Cross. The first ports of call are your GP, your DSS office and your local council's occuptional therpy unit for needs assessments. Help and advice are also available from local organisations for the disabled (contact details in Yellow Pages or from the local social services department), The Disabled Living Foundation and the local Disabled Living Centres. See 'Addresses' below and Action for M.E.'s 'Disability Aids & VAT Exemption' factsheet.<p><br>
<hr>
<ul>
