<html>
<head>
<meta name="Sasyfras" content="A New mailing list for sufferers of M.E.">
<meta name="keywords" content="CFS, CFIDS, M.E., support">
<title>Sasyfras</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/map.gif>
<blockquote>
<h1 align=center>Sasyfras</h1>
<h5 align=center><IMG SRC = "../images/icons/eyes.gif"></h5>
Sasyfras is a discussion list for people who have the disease variously known as Myalgic Encephalomyelitis (M.E.), chronic fatigue-immune dysfunction syndrome (CFIDS), chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS), and Ramsay's Disease -- and for those with allied illnesses (fibromyalgia, Gulf War Syndrome, Multiple Chemical Sensitivities, Post-Polio Syndrome), or with an interest in learning more about M.E./CFIDS/Ramsay's.

<h3 align=center>   ***This discussion list is dedicated to the memory of***</h3>
<h2 align=center>                        JOAN IRVINE</h2>
<h3 align=center>   ***who was our dear friend "Sasyfras" on the Internet***
</h3>

Sasyfras is managed by an administrative committee consisting of Gary Calvert, Phyllis Griffiths, Kay Robinson, Mary Schweitzer (list-owner), and Suellen Tritt.  All of us have CFIDS/M.E., and we can be reached at: Sasyfras-Request@home.ease.lsoft.com
<p>
Only subscribed members can receive or send posts to Sasyfras.  It is not
gated to USENET.
<p>
The following is a list of guidelines for posting:
<p>
1.  Be polite.  If you wouldn't say it in person in public, don't
say it here.
<p>
2.  Assume that other posters mean well but may have misspoken.
<p>
3.  No selling or advertisements.
<p>
4.  No "flames" -- personal insults, insulting innuendo, the sort of
thing that starts fights.  A person who consistently participates in
"flaming" may be set to "review" (so an administrator can screen his/her
postings) or asked to leave the group.
<p>
5.  If you think YOU have been flamed -- do not respond on the list.
Write to one of the administrators about it
(at Sasyfras-Request@home.ease.lsoft.com).
<p>
6.  If you believe someone from the list is abusing you through private
email, let the administrators know.  Someone who consistently abuses
others on the list, either publicly or privately, may be asked to leave
the group.
<p>
7.  Make an effort to avoid foul language.  People will be on the
list from various age groups and backgrounds and we need to respect that.
<p>
8.  Do not repost messages from Sasyfras without permission of the
original sender (unless the message was an announcement clearly
intended for general broadcast).
<p>
9.  Do not repost messages from other groups or private correspondence
TO Sasyfras without permission from the original sender (unless the
message was an announcement clearly intended for general broadcast).
<p>
10.  When replying to messages, please do not quote the previous message
in its entirety.  Some people pay by the line for incoming mail, and
long quotes from older postings needlessly cost them money.  Also,
some members have limited storage space and overlong postings tie it
up so they can't receive new messages.  Try to be considerate of them.
<p>
11.  If you have an interesting, informative message to send that is
more than 100 lines long, run it by one of the administrators first.  There
are several ways to make a long message available to the members who want
to read it, without causing problems for those who pay by the line or who
have limited mailbox space.
<p>
12.  Always feel free to question these rules or to suggest others!
Administrative ideas are always welcome.  Feel free to ask any questions
you want of the administrators about how all this works.
<p>
Enjoy the group; get to know people.  If you've been on the Internet
or lists for a while, help out the newbies.  If you're new -- go ahead
and ask questions.  This is one place where your questions will always
be welcome.  And never worry about spelling mistakes or mis-statements:
we all have brain fog (CFIDS cognitive dysfunction; fibro-fog) here!
<p>
<hr>

To make it easier on subscribers, we ask that posters try to use the
following three special topic headers (words that the computer
recognizes and can treat separately) to begin the subject line when
writing a post correspnding to one of the three:
<p>
      MED: -- for discussion of medical information<br>
      ACT: -- for discussion of political activism and CFIDS/M.E. advocacy<br>
      LONG: -- for postings over 100 lines<br>
<p>
The computer calls messages without special topic headers "OTHER", but
you don't have to use that unless you want to send a message to
multiple headers.
<p>
You must put the colon at the end of the word for the computer to
recognize that it is a special topic header.  If you want, you can
use more than one -- separate them by a comma, no space, and leave the
colon until the very last word.
<p>
For example, if you want something to go out to the special topics
MED and ACT, you would begin the subject line with:<br>
      MED,ACT:
<p>
And if you wanted it to go out to ACT and just everybody in general,
you would send it to:<br>
      ACT,OTHER:
<p>
If you are replying to a post, try to double-check the topic header to
make sure that you are still on the same subject.  But everyone should be
understanding if posters make mistakes.
<p>
It doesn't matter where the "RE:" goes in relationship to the topic
headers when you reply to a special topic.
<p>
Subscribers are automatically set to MED, ACT, LONG, and no-topic
(what the computer calls "OTHER").  If you do not wish to
receive topics sent under MED, LONG, or ACT, send a message to:<br>
      listserv@home.ease.lsoft.com
<p>
That says:<br>
      set sasyfras topics -MED    (you will not receive MED postings)<br>
      set sasyfras topics -LONG   (you will not receive LONG postings)<br>
      set sasyfras topics -ACT    (you will not receive ACT postings)<br>
<p>
If you do not wish to read all the extra discussion that does not fall
into one of those three topic headers (which would include misposted
messages from time to time), then use the command:<br>
     set sasyfras topics -OTHER  (you will not receive postings without
                                  MED, LONG, or ACT in the header)
<p>
Conversely, a command such as<br>
     set sasyfras topics +MED will reverse the command and you can go back
                              to receiving MED postings
<p>
If you find this confusing, simply write a note to the managing committee
at sasyfras-request@home.ease.lsoft.com, and we can set it for you.
<p>
<hr>

Glossary for beginners:
<p>
CFS = chronic fatigue syndrome<br>
CFIDS = chronic fatigue and immune dysfunction syndrome<br>
M.E. = myalgic encephalomyelitis<br>
CFS, CFIDS, and M.E. are different names for the same disease.<br>
FM = fibromyalgia<br>
GWS = Gulf War Syndrome<br>
PPS = Post-Polio Syndrome<br>
MCS = Multiple Chemical Sensitivities<br>

PWC = person with CFIDS/M.E.<br>

DD = the "d----d disease" (insert your favorite "d" word) -- a handy
     nick-name for CFIDS/M.E.<br>
<p>
<hr>

If you would like to find out more about CFIDS/M.E., try the following
books:<p>
     Bell, David S., The Doctor's Guide to Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (1994)<br>
     Berne, Katerina, Running on Empty (1995 edition)<br>
     Johnson, Hilary, Osler's Web (1996)<p>

We also suggest the following web sites:<p>

The CFIDS Association of America<br>
     http://www.ybi.com/cfids/<p>

WECAN (Worldwide Electronic CFIDS/M.E. Action Network)<br>
     http://www.community-care.org.uk/ME/wecan.html<p>

Listening to CFIDS: Works by PWCs and others who care<br>
     http://wwcoco.com/cfids/<p>

The UK ME-Web<br>
     http://www.community-care.org.uk/ME/<p>

CFS/ME<br>
     http://www.alternatives.com/cfs-news/index.htm<p>

Children and CFIDS<br>
     http://www.bluecrab.org/health/sickids/sickids.htm<p>

Co-Cure<br>
     http://www.human-nature.com/co-cure/co-cure.htm<p>

<hr>
