<html>
<head>
<title>Making Space News</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<h1 align=center><img src="../images/logos/space1.gif" alt="Making Space"><blockquote><hr>News * Views * People<br> Plans for the Future</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Major New Initiative to Bring Relief to Carers</h2>
Making Space hopes to play a key role in a series of mental health research initiatives planned by the Department of Health. The Department has made £1.2 million available and invited proposals for research into seven areas of mental health with projects which could extend from 18 months to three years.
<p>
Ably supported by Professors Peter Huxley and Nick Tarrier, Making Space is preparing a bid to study "How to reduce the burden carried by informal carers of severely mentally ill people," one of the seven areas of research envisaged by the Department of Health.
<p>
It could lead to an invaluable extension of research work already carried out by the professors and that planned by Professor Tarrier and Making Space in South Manchester, where a new Family Support Worker is to be appointed to work in conjunction with clinical psychologists.
<p>
Under Making Space proposals submitted to the Department of Health, research would focus on the work of Family Support Workers.
<p>
Half of them would be given special training to educate, inform and advise parents of the severely mentally ill on how to cope with the negative symptoms of schizophrenia - withdrawal, apathy and lack of volition.
<p>
"All these create particular stresses for parents," said Making Space Director, David Lyne. Family Support Workers would be involved with Manchester University staff to train in how best to intervene with parents to help them cope.
<p>
"After a period, the quality of life of carers and their ability to bear the burdens of care would be compared with that of another control group who would have been receiving the services of Family Support Workers who had not undergone this formal training in psychological intervention," David explained.
<p>
"If the research demonstrated that the special training for Family Support Workers was successfull in further easing the burdens on carers, Making Space would hope to extend it to include all our Family Support Workers," he added.
<p>
All concerned parties welcome the Department of Health's intention to support research in so many areas of mental health and a final short-listing of proposals should be completed by November.
<p>
Once decisions have been made, it is expected that approved research projects should be commissioned by next spring.
<p>
The Department's official notes on reducing the burden carried by informal carers acknowledges: "The welfare of informal carers, usually relatives, of severely mentally ill people has been relatively ignored, despite their crucial role in community care. Few programmes aimed at helping them have been developed and very few have been evaluated."
<hr>
<h3>Network of Support Expands</h3>
Making Space is continuing to expand its network of Family Support Workers and their roles are already proving vital as direct sources of help for carers and sufferers in many districts.
<p>
Several new posts, including Sefton, Blackburn and Stretford, should be established within the next few months to build upon the impressive achievements of existing Family Support Workers working from 19 bases in the North-West and Yorkshire. Their skills, commitment and personalities in general have attracted praise from many directions.
<p>
Carers are delighted with the direct, "grass-roots" wealth of assistance which the Family Support Workers have been providing for families in so many ways. These include help in solving worrying problems, the representation of a family's views to statutory bodies like the health and social services, the provision of information on a wide range of issues and a sensitive presence to talk to and confide in.
<p>
Fellow professionals have been equally impressed and the Family Support Workers are succeeding in many cases to win the acceptance by and better relationships with local authorities and a host of other organisations in the professional and voluntary sectors.
<p>
In one case, for example, a Family Support Worker, backed by other Making Space officers, combined with them to give such an impressive presentation to a council's housing department that the staff actually dug into their own pockets to raise the money for us!
<p>
That exercise is one of many initiatives Family Support Workers are employing to improve relations with bodies with whom they have to negotiate on behalf of carers and sufferers.
<p>
"There is no doubt that our experiences to date have confirmed what vital roles Family Support Workers are playing in the ever-growing network of expert assistance that we are determined to provide for carers and sufferers," said Making Space Director, David Lyne.
<p>
"Like any other organisation seeking to offer the best and widest range of services to clients, Making Space has to cut its clothes according to its cloth, but we are pushing ahead as quickly as possible to obtain the financial resources needed to reach our ultimate goal of ensuring that the services of a Family Support Worker are available to all carers and sufferers linked to us," he pledged.
<p>
"So far, the activities of our Family Support Workers have more than confirmed, too, the evaluation of their work carried out by research psychologist, Ashley Weinberg, in which he praised their "unique and valuable" roles and endorsed all our efforts to extend this service," David added.
<p>The health and social services and consumer bodies are placing substantial orders for Ashley Weinberg's study, entitled "Making More Space". Copies are still available from Making Space head office in Warrington at a cost of £2.80, including post and packing.
<hr>
<h3>Drive for rights of sufferers</h3>
A new initiative aimed at solving the problems of who can best represent the interests of people with mental health problems is being presented in the Wigan and Leigh areas. A prime mover in the search for the most effective advocacy scheme, acting on behalf of both sufferers and carers, is Making Space's Wigan-based Family Support Worker, Carol Garrett.
<p>
She was approached by a mental health officer from the nearby Billinge Hospital, Angela Schofield, who was also worried that the area had no patient advocacy service as such. The result was a meeting of many interested parties including hospital staff, the local making Space Carers' Support Group, the Community Health Council, MIND and representatives of many other users' and carers' groups.
<p>
"Most of the 30-odd people who attended had very different ideas about what was needed and how something could be done, so it was decided to form a steering committee to organise a special conference, inviting expert speakers already involved with advocacy services elsewhere," said Carol.
<p>
"Although I already play an advocacy role to the best of my ability, there are still, clearly, many people with mental health problems and carers who badly need someone to stand up for them," she pointed out. "Our ultimate hope is to create an advocacy team covering all aspects of mental health. We understand that there may be finance available to do this and people should not have to go it alone, be they sufferers or carers," added Carol, who also paid tribute to the excellent commitment to such a project shown by senior staff from Billinge Hospital.
<hr>
<h3>New Flats Development</h3>
Making Space and Warrington Community Care shortly hope to be celebrating the breaking of new ground in the financing of new accomodation developments.
<p>
With the help of Trevor Gallop, Managing Director of Warrington-based Design and Buildings Projects Limited, they are taking a major step in this direction with his company's completion of Warrington Community Care's brand new Salisbury Street flats project in the town.
<p>
Mr. Gallop actually acquired the Salisbury Street site privately. It will be leased from him by Warrington Community Care and the concept has been adopted because it is becoming harder to raise finance for such community developments from traditional sources.
<p>
Mr. Gallop said it was the organisation's first move to enter into a legal contract with a private individual and he was hoping the arrangement would prove an excellent precedent for the way in which future developments were undertaken, considering the general financial climate.
<p>
He said, "In terms of obtaining finance, government policies are certainly not helping developers and that includes those seeking to develop for the best of causes, such as Making Space. Even housing association funds are now being squeezed, so I do see the Salisbury Street flats project arrangement as being a major step forward for the future."
<p>
Mr. Gallop and his firm have been involved with schemes undertaken for us since the earliest days, when Making Sapce was known as the North West Fellowship.
<hr>
<h3>Bids for 20 New Projects</h3>
Making Space plans to submit bids for nearly 20 new supported housing schemes.
<p>
Development Manager, Dave Mathews, is already assured of the success of a number of the bids, which cover projects in Cumbria, Lancashire, Manchester, Merseyside and Cheshire. He points out, however, that all bids must have prior support from local housing departments and should be increasingly be in accordance with local community care plans and planning strategies involving local authorities and the NHS.
<p>
"The situation is becoming more complex and labour-intensive for myself and my colleagues with an increasing expectation that we should liaise directly with housing departments and secure support from health and social services," he explains.
<p>
Despite the extra demands and challenges posed by the variety of new procedures surrounding community care issues, Dave is still pleased that Making Space continues to maintain the momentum of its drive to provide the most appropriate facilities for sufferers over such a wide geographical area.
<p>
Projects bid for, most in conjunction with housing association partners, include units of various sizes for Windermere, Lancaster, Chorley, South Ribble, Blackpool, Wyre, Pendle, Rossendale, Oldham, Bury, Tameside, South Manchester, Wigan, St Helens, Warrington, Chester, Vale Royal, Widnes and Macclesfield.
<hr>
<h3>Help for the Deaf</h3>
Making Space is taking a new initiative to help people with mental illness who are also deaf. Through the Manchester Housing Association, it hopes to make a bid for Housing Corporation funding for a scheme of flats for the deaf mentally ill.
<p>
This follows talks between Making Space and the John Denmark Unit at Prestwich Hospital where consultant psychiatrist Dr. Paul Davidson, estimates that 20 deaf mentally ill patients each year are in need of supported accomodation in the community.
<p>
If such flats were available, he believes they would help his unit to offer a more efficient and widely available service to such people.
<hr>
<h3>Important Pledge Won for Users and Carers</h3>
Making Space recommendations to ensure that users and carers should be involved at every stage in the development of a care programme have won national adoption.
<p>
Our Director, David Lyne, was appointed member of a national project group set up by the Department of Health to review and evaluate the contributions of social services departments to the care programme approach and procedures surrounding the discharge of patients from hospitals into the community.
<p>
Making Space members in Yorkshire contributed some of their experiences and the project group accepted Making Space views that if care programmes were to be as effective as possible for each individual, then users and carers should be involved at all stages.
<p>
"We are delighted to have been involved for the first time in helping to formulate the most appropriate criteria for the ways in which care programmes should be developed," said David. "Our members should now recognise that the Department of Health does consider that the involvement of users and carers in care programmes is essential. In some areas examined, the approach being implemented by some health authorities seemed to be almost actively discouraging this. Now we have national approval of the need to push very hard to achieve greater recognition of the rights and needs of users and carers by the actual service providers."
<hr>
<h3>Cumbria Day Centre Take-over</h3>
Making Space has agreed to take over the management responsibility for the Aglionby Day Centre, set up and run for the past eight years by the North Cumbria Mental Health Fellowship.
<p>
The day centre has proved essential for mentally ill people in the Carlisle area and is very popular. The problem is that members of the Fellowship, which is affiliated to Making Space, are growing older and finding it increasingly demanding to administer the project.
<p>
The Making Space 'take-over' is set to be ratified by its annual general meeting. Hazel Coates, Treasurer and a prime mover behind its formation and activities, said; "It is a tremendous relief to know that Making Space is behind us and that the day centre will continue to be run along the lines that we have so successfully established."
<hr>
<h3>Understanding Special Needs in Lancs.</h3>
Local authority 'bureaucracy' can sometimes be frustrating to deal with, but Leigh-based Family Support Worker, Cathy Devine and other Making Space officers, have certainly won many hearts among Housing Department staff at Leigh.
<p>
At first, while negotiating with the department on behalf of Making Space clients, Cathy did not always find the understanding she expected. Andrew Hunt, one of the Housing Officers, appreciated the situation, however, and said that housing staff would like to know more about the problems of people with special mental health needs.
<p>
So Cathy obliged with a training session-style presentation by herself, Sue Hopkins and Jean Garlick, to the whole of the Housing Department staff to improve relations by enhancing their awareness of needs. Their talks on behalf of Making Space went down so well that the staff decided to hold a collection for our funds and £130 was raised.
<p>
"I'm delighted by the gesture and even more so by being given the chance of helping more local authority staff to understand more about what mental illness and its associated problems are all about." said Cathy.
<hr>
<h3>Making More Friends Does Pay Dividends</h3>
Successful expansion is reported from both of Making Space's volunteer befriending schemes. Called 'Making Friends', the schemes are based in Leeds and in the Wigan and Leigh district. Both are aimed at the recruitment and training of volunteer befrienders to provide social support for individuals with long-term mental health problems.
<p>
Since last November, when Ursula Klingel became co-ordinator of the Voluntary Befriending Scheme serving south-east Leeds, she has been busy trying to recruit volunteers through newspaper publicity, leaflets, posters, word-of-mouth and volunteer bureaux.
<p>
Nine volunteers, who have all successfully undertaken two-month training courses, are already visiting people and six more are currently awaiting training. "They come from all walks of life - students, people who have retired and people who are unemployed, but have the background and commitment to suit the befriending role," said Ursula.
<p>
Under her supervision, the volunteers are providing listening ears and practical help and friendship to mental health sufferers whose conditions might have caused them to lose confidence in achieving enjoyment of community life and to become socially isolated.
<p>
"The results, so far, are very encouraging indeed and prove the need for such a scheme," said Ursula, who is also liaising with the social services to create a 'drop-in' centre. A monthly social group meets to plan entertainments and outings. Accreditation is being sought to enable volunteers to train for the scheme at the local College of Further Education from next month and Ursula is so pleased with overall progress that she wants to extend the project area from its current four villages in south-east Leeds towards the inner city areas.
<p>
Said Chris Carter, Yorkshire Regional Officer for Making Space; "Ursula is always too modest. She has been very successful indeed in both attracting and motivating the volunteer befrienders. We are looking to extend the catchment areas for the scheme and expecting more referrals for the service."
<p>
Excellent progress is also reported by Sue Hopkins, co-ordinator of Making Space's Wigan and Leigh Volunteer Befriending Scheme. Thanks to her various recruiting ploys, no fewer than 43 people have already requested application forms because they are keen to become befrienders.
<p>
Fourteen suitable people, from various age groups and backgrounds, have so far taken special induction training courses. Eight volunteers are in action, befriending sufferers on a regular basis, and the other six are in the process of establishing 'partnerships'. "Another six people are poised to start another training course shortly and I should stress that these courses are designed to really test their commitment." said Sue.
<p>
Becuase of the vulnerable nature of the client group, potential volunteers are 'vetted' extremely carefully, having to provide references from two reliable sources, declare any criminal convictions and take part in an intensive interview. Only after they have completed a six-week induction course, spread over one evening each week, are they introduced to people waiting to use the befriending scheme and their association with them only continues if it proves to be of mutual satisfaction.
<p>
Sue said the concept of the project was so attractive that they already had more clients than volunteers among sufferers keen to have a befriender. To maintain everyone's interest while training courses continue, Sue has also organised weekly social group meetings which have already led to a number of outings being planned.
<p>
"We are trying to plough on at full speed with the help of outside professionals to expand the project as quickly as possible because it is in such great demand," said Sue. "We are receiving lots of referrals from the community mental health services and certainly have more demand than we can meet." she adds.
<p>
Sue also runs a monthly support group for volunteer befrienders, explaining; "I feel it is valuable for them to get together to share their experiences on a fairly regular basis, because some could start to feel a little isolated from the general stream of things when involved in a one-to-one social relationship with an individual client."
<hr>
<h3>Asian Study</h3>
Measures to investigate the mental health needs of a district's Asian community are being spearheaded by Making Space staff in West Yorkshire. The Calderdale Social Services Department has commissioned Making Space (Yorkshire) to manage the special project, another indication of the increasing recognition by local authorities and other bodies of our staff's knowledge and expertise in the field of mental illness. Making Space has short-listed three organisations, one of which is expected to be chosen shortly to carry out the research under our supervision and oversight.
<p>
"We are very flattered to have been chosen to lead this research," said Chris Carter, Yorkshire Regional Officer for Making Space. "Clearly, there are unmet needs to be identified and ways of overcoming as many problems as possible will have to be examined with the co-operation of the Calderdale racial Equality Council," she said.
<p>
All districts with significantly-high ethnic populations had been and still were finding it very difficult to ensure that such people understood and took full advantage of all the health and social services available to them, Chris pointed out.
<p>
A Social Services spokesman told us; "When trying to deal with ethnic minorities and with mental health problems in particular, barriers of language and culture are usually harder than ever to surmount, so we attach great significance to this research project and eagerly await its findings."
<hr>
<h3>Lottery Cash Bid for Kendal</h3>
Making Space is still hoping to succeed in its bid for National Lottery cash to help to fund a new project at Kendal. It involves establishing a bed-and-breakfast facility run by people with severe mental health problems for others with mental illnesses and our Employment Manager, Kate Byrne, and Sue Jackson have already visited Edinburgh to study a similar scheme at work.
<p>
"Members have reacted enthusiastically to the plan and my hopes have been raised because the National Lottery Charities Board has contacted us asking for more information, which is a good sign," said Making Making Space Director, David Lyne.
<p>
The Board has some £167 million to allocate to charities this October. Thirty thousand application forms were requested and 11,000 actual bids have been submitted asking for a total of £875 million, so there are countless organisations across Britain keeping their fingers crossed at the moment.
<p>
Funding for the Kendal B&B project is also being sought from another source, the Tudor Trust, a national charity which has already supported various voluntary sector schemes in Lancashire over the past few years.
<hr>
<h3>Financial Forecast is Good</h3>
With income from all souces totalling over £3.5 million, Making Space has enjoyed yet another successful financial year, according to audited accounts for 1994/1995.
<p>
Director of Finance John Davies, not only forecasts that income will rise above £4 million during the current financial year, he is also introducing other moves to produce major savings and to make many operations more effective and 'user-friendly' at the Warrington headquarters.
<p>
Income has increased as more schemes, especially flats, have come on stream and this also means that more money can be used to boost Making Space's equipment replacement reserve. According to John, this itself is a welcome reassurance that the organisation is in an even b
</DOC>
