<html>
<head>
<title>Making Space News</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<h1 align=center><img src="../images/logos/space1.gif" alt="Making Space"><blockquote><hr>News * Views * People<br> Plans for the Future</h1>
<hr>
<h3>New graduate, Emma will help research</h3>
Already in action is Making Space's new graduate trainee, 23-year-old Emma Armstrong, from Preston. Emma, who recently won an MA in sociology at Ediburgh University, is reporting directly to Making Space Director, David Lyne.
<p>
On his behalf, she will be carrying out a wide variety of research and evaluation projects relating to the activities of departments within Making Space.
<p>
"Her work will also bring her into contact with many members and her involvement should lead to her acquiring a great deal of knowledge about how Making Space works in every sector," said David.
"Within days of joining us she had her babtism of fire by helping us to conduct a presentation in support of our tender for a major new nursing home project," he added.
<p>
Emma, who comes from Preston, is keen to work in the voluntary sector. During her four years at university, she was an active member of The Action Group, an Edinburgh-based charity, working with people with learning difficulties, which she thoroughly enjoyed.
<p>
She has personal experience of how mental illness can suddenly strike a family and the problems it can pose. A cousin living with his parents in Zimbabwe started to become "disruptive and unsettled" at the age of 18, but the medical authorities there would not recognise him as schizophrenic.
<p>
"He came over here where his condition was recognised. Appropriated treatment was devised and he's now back with his family, everyone concerned being better advised and equipped to provide the most suitable care and support," said Emma.
<hr>
<h3>All Aboard</h3>
Members of the Knutsford and Macclesfield Group are fortunate to have Lillian McPhee as a member, say Group Organisers, Brian and Barbara Lambert.
<p>
When members staged a sponsored walk along the Macclesfield Canal, Lillian and her husband Don, allowed them to use their beautifully painted narrowboat as a refreshment point.
<p>
The sequel to this was an invitation to the group to enjoy a day trip on the boat and twenty members took up the McPee's kind offer this summer.
<p>
"It was bright and dry when we set off in the morning from Higher Poynton, and a few brave souls, including Captain Don, braved the decks for the trip to Bollington where refreshments were provided in a canal-side pub," said Brian.
<p>
"The weather went downhill afterwards and the return trip was made below decks with the exception of the skipper, but many a salty yarn was shared with numerous cups of tea on the two hour journey back, making the day well worthwhile and enjoyed by all," said his wife Barbara.
<p>
The Lamberts pay tribute to the generosity of the McPhee's, and Warrington Day Centre's Women's Group recently enjoyed similar hospitallity from them - when the weather was kinder!
<hr>



<h3>Honour awaits Lily?</h3>
Our long-serving Bury Group Organiser, Lily Reid, has been honoured by being nominated for the accolade of "Lancashire Woman of the Year." Whether she clinches the title will not be known until she attends a special luncheon this month, organised by the sponsors, British Aerospace and Soroptomists International.
<p>
"I don't suppose I stand a cat in hell's chance of being chosen as the ultimarely successful nominee, but I am very flattered to be among the finalists because it is yet another opportunity to win good publicity for our cause," said Lily, who runs an active 80-member support group.
<p>
Lily's involvement with Making Space, and its predecessor organisation, the North West Fellowship, stemmed from the fact that her own son suffererd from mental illness. Her group meets not once, but twice evry month and carries out hospital visits.
<p>
Simultaneously, pensioner Lily, finds the time and energy to be on the Board of Directors of the Crossroads scheme in Bury (of which she was a founder-member); on the Executive of the Bury and District Disablement Advisory Council; a member of the town's Mental Illness and Housing Support Group; and of Bury Mental Health Forum, which represents all mental health interests in the area.
<p>
"I welcome my latest nomination as far as publicity is concerned because it is vital to keep trying to make everyone more aware of the problems faced by sufferers and carers - I realise just how many people there are who need support," said Lily.
<p>
"I try to help others from my own experience and better education surrounding mental health issues is so very important. For example, many years ago, even I thought the phrase 'schizophrenic' had criminal connotations, so what do lots of people still think? We as parents must not brush things under the carpet, we must take every chance of publicising the needs of sufferers and carers and fostering a greater public understanding," she added.
<hr>
<h3>Sponsored Walk Success</h3>
Members, officers and friends turned out in force yet again to give excellent support for Making Space's annual sponsored walk. Yet again, the sun shone all day as almost 150 people enjoyed a lovely canalside walk from Lancaster to Glasson Dock on the coast.
<p>
"Many thanks, as usual, to everyone who helped to make the event such a success," said Making Space Director, David Lyne. "Over £6,000 has been raised so far as the result of the sponsored walk and even more money is still coming in as we go to press."
<hr>
<h3>Striking the right Chord!</h3>
A rare concert by a gifted organist has helped to raise over £500 for our South Manchester Group's holiday fund.
<p>
Making Space members and staff from near and far travelled to St Paul's church at Kersal, Salford, to enjoy the concert, given by the talented Edward McHale, a fundraising sale and an excellent supper. Jean Garlick, our Member Support Worker for Manchester, and her mum, took two car-loads to join members, staff and church people at the concert. Donations were also sent from people who couldn't make it.
<p>
The special event was the idea of member, Sue Hill, a friend of the organist's family, and the opportunity was also taken to erect a display to make local people more aware of the aims and activities of Making Space.
<p>
"It was an evening to delight the ear, with Edward McHale pulling out all the stops, if you will forgive the pun." said Sue. "His introductions and delivery were perfectly balanced to provide us with an extremely pleasant and amusing evening."
<p>
"Our many thanks go to everyone who made a contribution to the evening's success, especially Edward, who so generously offered his services to benefit Making Space, to the Rev. Stephen Fletcher, who allowed us the use of his beautiful church and to the ladies who prepared some delicious and welcoming refreshments," Sue added.
<p>
Management Committee member and South Manchester Group Organiser, Eileen Bell, echoed the thoughts of most people who attended, saying; "It was all just brilliant - Edward is a very nice young man and an extremely good organist."
<hr>
