<head>
<title>WorkSpace News</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<h1 align=center><img src="../images/logos/space1.gif" alt="Making Space"><blockquote><hr>News * Views * People<br> Plans for the Future</h1>
<hr>
<h2>"Workspace" Achieves its Main Aims</h2>
Our Workspace factory in Warrington continues to succeed in its ongoing drive to provide suitable employment for people with special mental health needs.
<p>
An in-depth evaluation shows the factory has achieved all the aims and objectives set for it in its annual plan. These include reaching financial targets, an increased workforce, the attraction of domestic contracts from the general public, and venture into the "ready-made" market, supported by improved marketing techniques, says Factory Supervisor, Pauline Doorbar.
<p>
Before starting with Workspace, most workers were unable to keep down a job for any length of time. At Workspace, however, a remarkable rise in attendance reliability and regularity has been registered, with six out of seven workers with attendance rates of well over 90%. One has even achieved a 100% attendance record, reports Employment Development Worker, Pat Hartley, who carried out the latest factory evaluation.
<p>
The factory aims to provide suitable employment for people who have completed two years of training in the Workplace sheltered workshop. "The attendance records, together with the results of a questionaire, indicate that the workers are satisfied with their jobs and their working conditions, really benefiting from the support and understanding shown by our staff, sympathetic to the needs of people with mental health problems," said Pat.
<p>
The factory produces curtains, bedding, cushion covers and a variety of other soft furnishings, mainly in flame-retardent fabrics, and is unique in that it is totally self-sufficient. It is able to complete contracts for Making Space homes and flats schemes and for other voluntary organisations at extremely competitive rates, saving them time and money because instant advice and information is available "on-site".
<p>
At the time of the latest evaluation, the factory was supplying 62% of its products to Making Space, 26% to other organisations and 12% to the private order market. But there is an ever-increasing emphasis being placed on winning orders from outside companies and individuals.
<p>
The factory has recently completed a contract to supply curtain insets for the prestigious Hartwood furniture range and this could win it international exposure for its work. For the range is going on sale at Habitat stotes in England and France, giving European exposure to the skills of Workspace employees.
<p>
"We are hoping that a lot of similar orders might follow," said Employment Manager, Kate Byrne. "We have even successfully completed a major contract for a dance school by manufacturing a number of tailor-made stage costumes," added Pat Hartley.
<p>
Irene Reid, Care Co-ordinator for Warrington Community Care, was asked for her opinions about the factory as part of the evaluation exercise. She said that since the factory opened she had seen an improvement in the mental health of the workers. "It certainly does raise morale, it gives a structured day which some people need, it gives them a purpose to get out of bed and a good feeling to earn a living," she observed.
<p>
Asked if she considered that this type of scheme exploited the mentally ill, she said it depended on from which side you viewed it. "To someone who wants to work and earn extra money, but cannot get employment elsewhere, you would be filling a gap and a need. From a union point of view, it is cheap labour, but from my point of view it is good for the majority of those who use the service because it provides a positive part of their lives," she explained.
<p>
The overall evaluation points out that Workspace is the only employment project that supports people with mental illness in the Warrington area. Opportunities in open employment are often difficult to secure and, to date, are usually only offered on a temporary basis.
<hr>
<h3>Kendal Wins Job Placements</h3>
Although it has only been operating for just over a year, our Workspace project for Kendal and district is already winning job placements in the community for its trainees.
<p>
Its standards have also won the confidence of the Department of Employment which has granted the project a contract as an employment rehabilitation provider. The Department intends to refer people with mental health problems to Workspace for short term rehabilitation programmes.
<p>
"After all the hard work which went into launching the project, it is very heartening to be winning placements for trainees and official recognition of what we have to offer from prestigious organisations like the Department of Employment," said Sue Jackson, Kendal and District's Employment Developmeny Officer and Day Care Services Worker for Making Space.
<p>
The number of trainees has risen to eight at Workspace's self-contained base in an area of Kendal's Whinfell Adult Training Centre. From here, it operates a printing service for local individuals and organisations requiring such items as business or membership cards or function tickets.
<p>
Currently, there are trainees on placements with a local architect and designer, a printing firm and in Kendal's Barnardo's shop. Good links have been established with Kendal College where several courses are being made avaiable to trainees, including word-processing and computer-aided design skills.
<p>
"A number of our trainees now have the confidence to go to the local college to enhance their skills and this must be a major step towards them winning ultimate chances of full employment," said Sue.
<p>
Sue Jackson also manages a Kendal day centre for peopple with mental health problems, and this too, is going from strength-to-strength in all terms of popularity and activities. Membership has built up to the 30 mark since Making Space took over the centre's management.
<p>
Members have been attracted by the breadth and attraction of the range of activities and outings which the centre offers. Apart from trips out to local beauty spots, they have visited the set of Granada's Coronation Street, watched the "That's Entertainment Show" during a day in Blackpol and a behind-the-scenes tour of ASDA to see what it is like working in a supermarket.
<p>
Activities at the centre have included, aromatherapy, cake-decorating, decorative painting, a visit from Bodyshop experts to give "make-overs", and from the fire service, local community psychiatric nurses and first-aiders.
<p>
Sue's final verdict on Kendal's Workspace project so far is; "The people involved say it has transformed their lives and enabled at least one of them to reduce medication.
<hr>
<h3>Council will fund trainee</h3>
Just before leaving her post as Family Support Worker for Leigh, Cathy Devine has helped to break new ground for Making Space and Workspace.
<p>
In close liaison with Employment Manager, Kate Byrne, Cathy has succeeded in persuading the local authority's Social Services Department to fund a place for a female client from Leigh at Warrington-based Workspace.
<p>
Until now, clients attending Workspace at Warrington have all come from the Warrington district. "It is nice to have helped set up a major first before I leave but it has certainly not been easy to achieve," said Cathy. "It has taken almost a year of negotiations with the social services over whether a Workspace place was essential for the young lady involved and there have had to be a lot assessments carried out."
<p>
"Finally, we succeeded because they felt that they could not offer her any suitable extended training beyond nine weeks locally; there were no facilities to suit her case in the Wigan area so they have agreed to provide the funds necessary to enable her to travel daily from Leigh to Warrington to take up a Workspace place."
<p>
Cathy, ho already has a degree in psychology, has decided to go back to college to extend her knowledge and qualifications in the fields of social care, health studies and psychology with a view to teaching them. "I've really enjoyed a year working for Making Space, but it has been a sad year in terms of my private life because I have lost a sister and a brother. My job helped to keep my mind occupied, but I feel that I am now ready for new challenges." she added.
<hr>
<h3>Ex-para Leads the way</h3>
Ex-paratrooper Ralph James is living proof that mental health sufferers can lead rewarding lives and help others into the bargain!
<p>
After army service which included attachment to the SAS abroad, Ralph returned to 'civvy street' to spend over 30 years working as a contract electrician. But, for 23 of those years, Ralph struggled against manic depression, finally losing the battle and giving up work in 1991.
<p>
After three years at home, including a computer course he failed to complete because of his illness, he discovered that Making Space and Workspace had arrived in Kendal and district. "My life has certainly changed for the better," said 56 years old Ralph, who lives at nearby Arnside.
<p>
"At first I did various tasks in the Workspace workshop before drawing up a business paln for our printing operations with the help and encouragement of Sue Jackson, our Employment Development Officer," said Ralph. "We share a site with Whinfell Adult Training Centre, so, on placement one day per week I took on the task of doing 80-odd staff wages and users allowances for them," said Ralph, a member of MIND for the past three years.
<p>
"My confidence and general condition seemed to be improving all the time and when Kendal's MIND was without an official co-ordinator, I did the job for seven weeks on placement until they appointed a new one," he explained. He also carried out the banking arrangements for Workspace and the Adult Training Centre. Now he's breaking new ground by working on placement at Barnardo's charity shop and starting an NVQ3 Lancaster University course in Customer Care.
<p>
Apart from helping others with his work with MIND, he has also launched the Kingfisher Club at Arnside for people with mental health problems. Making Space Family Support Worker, Liz Nelson, has lent her backing to the project and members meet monthly to socialise and to plan outings.
<p>
Ralph has also raised £3,500 from sponsors for Kendal MIND by completing the Cumbria 1,000 mile walking marathon at the rate of 20 miles-a-day.
<hr>
<h3>St. Helens funds a new post</h3>
Anxious to expand the benefits of our Workspace concept to more districts, Making Space is now confident of funding form the social services for the appointment of an Employment Development Officer in St. Helens.
<p>
It is hoped to make an appointment before the end of the year, with the officer being available to advise and support local people with mental health needs to gain more effective access to education, training or employment.
<p>
"We hope that the post will be the first step in the development of the Workspace concept in St. Helens, ultimately involving the establishment of a training workshop and a factory," said Making Space Director, David Lyne.
<p>


<hr>
