<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bill Who??</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/bkground.gif"><blockquote>
<H1><PRE>            </PRE>WELCOME!</H1>

<PRE>

</PRE>
<H2><PRE>       </PRE>"Bill Who?"<PRE> I hear you asking</PRE></H2>

<PRE>    </PRE>Those amongst you who were curious enough to follow this link may very
well wonder who I am, and why I've put "Facing Huntington's Disease" up on
the WWW.
<P>
<PRE>    </PRE>The reasons are very simple; one of the 1/10,000 people who are affected
by HD is my wife of 25 years, Jan. In November of 1994, my brother-in-law George
suffered what was thought to be a manic-depressive episode and was hospitalised.
Subsequent tests and brain scans showed that, in fact, he was in the early stages of
HD, even though there had been no <EM>obvious</EM> prior history in the family.
Over the next three months, Jan and I attended counselling sessions run by the genetics
clinic at the Western Infirmary in Edinburgh, culminating in a pre-symptomatic blood
test. On March 20th, 1995 we were told that Jan did indeed have the enlarged gene on
chromosome pair four which means that she will eventually develop the disease, although
there are no signs of it as yet.
<P>
<PRE>    </PRE>I emphasised above no <EM>'obvious</EM>' prior history; in the months
since, after discussions involving everyone in the family, we have come to the
conclusion that the only possible source of transmission was Jan's mother, who died
20 years ago after many years of cardiac trouble, which we think could have blinded us
to any HD-related symptoms. Anyway, there we were - and what now?  Our first reaction,
after the initial shock had worn off, was to try to find out as much about the disease
as we could; we obtained news-sheets and booklets from the Scottish Huntington's
Association, and attended their meetings to meet people in similar situations to ours.
<P>
<PRE>    </PRE>I confidently (and with approval!) started searching cyberspace for
references to HD, feeling certain that a vast body of information would be available
at the click of a mouse. Imagine my astonishment when all I could come up
with was the initial entry in the
<A HREF="http://dem0nmac.mgh.harvard.edu/neurowebforum/HuntingtonsDiseaseMenu.html">
MGH NeuroWeb Forum on Huntington's Disease</A> which had been started in March, and
which at that time had only the owner's plea for discussion on the subject.
<P>
<PRE>    </PRE>In an attempt to generate the flow of more information and discussion
on HD, I asked approval to reproduce <A HREF="facinghd.html">"Facing Huntington's Disease"</A>
on the Web from the Association, since I feel that it is the best booklet I have yet
found for explaining in clear and non-technical language, the implications which face
people whose lives are touched by HD. I am <EM>not</EM> an expert on HD, a social worker,
psychiatrist, or anything else - just an ordinary husband who is facing the fact that
our lives have been changed irrevocably, and whose job with IBM has given me free
access to the Web and its population.
<P>
<PRE>    </PRE>The kind folks at MGH have donated the space on one of their servers
so that I could offer this information (and this rambling page!) to all who may be
touched, or just interested, by HD, so join in the WebForum and help spread
knowledge and understanding about the disease.

<P>
<a href="mailto:bmcmenemy@vnet.ibm.com">Drop me e-mail</a>
(<b>bmcmenemy@vnet.ibm.com</b>) if you want to chat...<P>
Jan, 1996

<ul>
<li><a href="facinghd.html">Return to Huntington's Disease Index</a>
</ul>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
</html>
