<HTML>
<TITLE>Facing Huntington's Disease : Chapter 1</TITLE>
<BODY background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/bkground.gif">
<A NAME="chapter1"><H2>Chapter 1 - MEDICAL FACTS</H2></A>

<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#C1.1">The illness</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C1.2">Difficulties of diagnosis</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C1.3">Reaction to the diagnosis</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C1.4">Planning for later stages</A>
</UL>
<P>
  <A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to Contents</A>
<PRE>
























</PRE>
<H4><A NAME="C1.1">The Illness</A></H4>

   The condition  Huntington's  Disease  got its name  because it was  first
  described by George Huntington, a physician in New York, in 1872.  It used
  to be commonly known as Huntington's Chorea -  chorea being the Greek word
  for  dancing and  describing  the strange movements of the sufferer.  Most
  people now  refer to it as  Huntington's  Disease  or  HD  for short.  The
  illness  probably  occurs  all  over  the  world,  though it has  not been
  thoroughly  researched  in  many places,  particularly  in  underdeveloped
  countries.
<p>
   The illness begins gradually, usually in one or the other following ways:
  by  a change  in  usual  behaviour,  for example,  depression,  moodiness,
  unreasonable outbursts of anger out of character for the individual, or by
  unusual jerky,  fidgety movements and perhaps unsteadiness of the hands or
  feet  causing falls and a  tendency  to be clumsy.  These are early signs,
  they are mild and increase so slowly that they may go unnoticed  and it is
  only  much  later,  when looking back,  that relatives realise all has not
  been well for some years.
<p>
  These changes are thought to come about because of a disturbance of one of
  the  chemical substances  concerned in  normal  functioning of  the brain,
  though it is not known exactly which chemical is involved.  Over the years
  the  illness  goes  on  getting  more severe,  though the rate at which it
  progresses  varies  from  individual  to individual.  However, once it has
  started, it goes steadily on. The ungainly jerky movements, over which the
  sufferer has  no  control,  increase,  causing falls  and  making  walking
  difficult. Speech usually becomes slurred and swallowing difficult.  Some,
  though  not all,  will at times become  confused and  forgetful,  at other
  times angry and  unreasonable and  possibly violent.  Alternatively,  some
  some  people become  quite passive.  But the illness has its ups and downs
  and some days the  ungainly  movements  and  irritability  are less.  This
  changing state is  confusing and frustrating  for both sufferers and their
  families.   At present there is no known cure,  though medicine may lessen
  the jerky movements,  and sympathetic and  understanding care  can help to
  keep  the  sufferer  less  agitated  and  so  less  liable to unreasonable
  behaviour.  Ultimately,  it  may  become  too  difficult  to  care for the
  sufferer at home.
<p>
   The illness usually lasts 15 - 20 years,  although it may be considerably
  longer. Death is often from pneumonia  because sufferers cannot cough well
  enough to clear the chest if they have infections.  The most common age of
  onset of the illness is betwee the age of 30 and 50 years, although it can
  manifest itself at almost any age.  Both men and women are affected and it
  is estimated that perhaps 6,000 people  now have the illness in the United
  Kingdom.  HD  is hereditary  and runs in families  in a way  that is  well
  understood.   It  is  called  dominant  disorder  and  the   mechanism  of
  inheritance is described in the next chapter.
<p>
   The beginnings of the illness, particularly if the family is not familiar
  with it  and if the  diagnosis is long delayed,  can be very puzzling. For
  example, Mr. A, a married man with two sons,  was a regular soldier,  fit,
  keen on  physical exercise and popular with his friends and relations.  In
  his early forties,  he seemed depressed  and began to find energetic work,
  particularly  drilling,  tiresome.  Because of his popularity  his friends
  covered  up  for  any  shortcomings  and  he  was  able to finish his army
  engagement because for the last two years he was given light duties in the
  regimental office. He was discharged with an excellent record and soon got
  a civilian job.  However,  he became forgetful,  lacked concentration, had
  several  road accidents  and lost several jobs.  He had no apparant family
  history of HD;  it was several years later that the diagnosis was made and
  then it was  realised that his  father  was  probably also affected.  Soon
  after that Mr. A was unmanagable at home  and finished his days  in a long
  stay  hospital  for  the  psychiatrically  ill.  The  significance  of the
  diagnosis  for  his  sons  is  described  in  the  next chapter. Mr. A was
  fortunate in that  lighter work was found  for him when the first symptoms
  made his job too difficult.
<p>
   In the next example,  the sequence of events was different.  Mr. B worked
  in a car showroom  where many cars were displayed  on platforms of varying
  levels and all the walls of the  showroom were sheets of plate glass.  His
  wife had noticed  that he was  irritable and forgetful;  she knew too that
  his mother had died  in a  mental hospital,  though she  did not  know the
  cause.  Mr. B's employers noticed no change in his moods,  but they had to
  terminate his employment  because he could not get up and down the display
  platforms and the unsteadiness of his  gait made other staff and customers
  anxious that he would fall through a sheet of plate glass.


<H4><A NAME="C1.2">Difficulties of diagnosis when it is known that HD is in the family</A></H4>

   In these circumstances,  relatives may be on the alert for signs and this
  can lead to real dilemmas. If they can see signs, should they take action?
  How  severe  should  such  signs  be  before action is taken?  What if the
  sufferer is sure that he is  not  ill and  refuses to  co-operate?  He may
  really think that he is not ill or may perhaps be so afraid of getting  HD
  that he cannot admit the possible presence of symptoms. What if he refuses
  to see a doctor?  It may be that another person less close than husband or
  wife or parent can help.  The family doctor may be ready to do what he can
  but all too often  it is just a case of waiting  for the illness to become
  more obvious. Since there is no curative treatment, as far as the sufferer
  is concerned nothing may be lost by the delay,  but the family will suffer
  from prolonged  anxiety  and  uncertainty,  and there are implications for
  needed benefits and services.  It is often a fact that relatives  familiar
  with the illness  will recognise  it before the doctor does.  On the other
  hand,  understandably,  many relatives  knowing the family history,  worry
  unnecessarily about minor signs which may be nothing at all to do with  HD
  and which many of us exhibit.  Knowing that HD is in the family,  however,
  will make it more likely that the diagnosis will be made relatively early.

<H4>Difficulties of diagnosis when it is not known that HD is in the family</H4>

  When there is  no  family history  of  HD,  diagnosis may be long delayed.
  There are no specific tests to  confirm with certainty the presence of the
  illness,  though there are tests to find out  whether or not it is another
  of the various illnesses which can be confused with HD. The direct genetic
  test (described in the next chapter) may be used to confirm the diagnosis,
  along with other tests, such as a brain scan. The genetic test itself does
  not  prove  that someone is showing signs of  HD,  just that they have the
  faulty gene.  Even when doctors suspect  HD, they may be reluctant to make
  the  diagnosis  until they are  absolutely  certain,  because it is such a
  severe illness which in time will entirely change the life of the sufferer
  and because it is incurable. If you are anxious because of indecision or a
  long delay by your family doctor,  ask him whether a second opinion from a
  neurologist can be arranged.  Those specialists who are  familiar with  HD
  will recognise it even in its early stages.

<H4><A NAME="C1.3">Reaction to the diagnosis</A></H4>

  Whatever  it is  that finally  causes the  diagnosis  to be made,  it will
  probably come as a great and unpleasant shock.  Those families who already
  know the illness also know what it means for them;  those who do not, want
  to go on asking questions,  searching in libraries for more facts and feel
  a great need to find out what is in store for them. The immediate reaction
  to the knowledge  is often disbelief,  or a sense of outrage that one,  or
  one's relatives,  should be faced with such a future.  Many relatives find
  this the most  difficult  time in the  illness,  especially when they feel
  they  cannot discuss it with the sufferer,  or because they regard it as a
  mental illness and so cannot discuss it with friends and neighbours.  More
  about the  shock of first  learning the diagnosis  and the ways of getting
  through this difficult period is discussed in Chapter 3.
<p>
   In the early  stages sufferers will  continue to work as long as the can,
  particularly  if  employers  can  give them suitable work.  Sometimes work
  difficulties will be for physical reasons, for instance a delivery man who
  cannot move  well  enough to carry the packages,  or psychological, as for
  instance, an accountant whose memory for figures is unreliable.  Of course
  most  people  find  it  hard  to  accept  the fact that they are no longer
  capable  of  work.  An  example  of  this  is  the  dockyard  worker whose
  employment was  terminated because  he lacked  strength  and was  confused
  mentally.  Because  he did  not  accept that he had  no  job to go to,  he
  continued to go daily to the bus stop to catch the bus for work.  A kindly
  local policeman knew of the situation and each day brought him gently back
  home.
<p>
   The  kind  of  reactions  and  problems  described  here  have  all  been
  experienced by families we have known.  On the other hand,  other families
  have had no such problems.  It is plain that the  severity  of the illness
  and the speed at which it  progresses are  variable.  Some  sufferers have
  affected movements early,  most have psychological problems too.  There is
  no  way  of  predicting  early  in  the  illness how quickly a person will
  deteriorate;  neither is the  form  the illness takes in  one  member of a
  family  a  guide  as  to  how  it might affect other relatives.  All these
  factors  as  well  as  the  personalities  in the family and  particularly
  conditions under which they are  living affect  the way in which  they are
  able to cope with HD.


<H4><A NAME="C1.4">Planning for later stages of the illness</A></H4>

  Plans  for  the  future  should be  considered,  if possible, in the early
  stages;  if the  sufferer  is well enough,  and he may be early on,  it is
  right that he should be involved in the plans. For instance, if the person
  is the  breadwinner,  future  financial arrangements  must be  considered.
  Could  moving  house  be  helpful?  Plans  for  the  sufferers  care  need
  consideration  -  is he to attend a  hospital specialist  or is the family
  doctor to be responsible for his care?  Who is to monitor any changes? Who
  will advise about  medicines?  Is the sufferer likely to be in any sort of
  danger to himself or  anyone else at work?  If so,  should his employer be
  informed? If not, at what stage should they be informed?
<p>
   No two situations are alike and much heart searching will need to go into
  every decision.  These considerations  bring  responsibilities for all the
  family;  they can strain family relationships,  especially if the sufferer
  is unco-operative.  Difficulties will be eased with some  knowledge of the
  condition and tolerance for the sufferers plight.
<P>
<A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to Contents</A>
</BODY>

</DOC>
