<HTML>
<TITLE>Facing Huntington's Disease : Chapter 2</TITLE>
<BODY background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/bkground.gif">
<A NAME="chapter2"><H2>Chapter 2 - HOW HD IS PASSED ON</H2></A>
<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#C2.1">Chromosomes and genes</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C2.2">HD - a dominant disorder</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C2.3">Prediction</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C2.4">Age and the changing risk</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C2.5">Making decisions</A>
</UL>
  <P>
  <A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to Contents</A>
<PRE>























</PRE>
<H4><A NAME="C2.1">  Chromosomes and genes - units of inheritance </A></H4>

  We inherit all our genetic characteristics from our parents,  half of them
  from our fathers and  half from our mothers.  The  'blue-prints' for these
  characteristics are carried on tiny rod-like structures called chromosomes
  in every cell in the body.  We each have 46 chromosomes which are arranged
  in pairs,  one member of each  pair having come  from our  father  and the
  other  from our mother.  Chromosomes,  though  tiny,  can be seen  under a
  powerful microscope;  each individual individual  chromosome is recognised
  by its  size  and staining pattern  under the microscope.  For convenience
  scientists  have  numbered  the  pairs  from  1 - 22  with  the  23rd pair
  determining  whether the child is a  girl who has two X chromosomes,  or a
  boy who has one  X and one Y  chromosome. Every chromosome carries, spread
  out along  its length,  hundreds  of  genes,  each  gene producing a vital
  substance which has a specific task to perform in the body's chemistry. It
  is when one, or perhaps more, of the vital chemical substances is missing,
  ( perhaps part of a chromosome has been lost ),  or is changed in some way
  and so is not able to perform its function,  that genetic disorders arise.
  Genes are  too  small to be seen,  even with the most powerful microscope,
  although scientists  are beginning  to learn on  which of the  chromosomes
  genes are situated.  They are also discovering the positions of some genes
  along  the length of  the chromosome  and this technique  has proved to be
  important for HD.  For some time  researchers have known that the gene for
  HD was  near the end of chromosome 4.  In March 1993  the gene itself  was
  finally identified.
<p>
   As said above, all chromosomes (and so all genes) are in pairs,one member
  of each  pair having come from  either parent.  When a  parent  passes  on
  chromosomes to a child (half every time of the total number he has)  it is
  a matter of absolute chance which member of a pair is passed on. Genes are
  normally passed on  unchanged from parent to child,  but very occasionally
  the copying process  goes wrong  and the child  gets a  changed gene which
  causes an inherited disorder. This is known as mutation, and although such
  mutations are rare events they are occurring all the time.  Very few cases
  of HD  are due  to fresh  mutation,  the large  majority being  due  to an
  affected parent.
<p>
   Some  inherited disorders  show themselves when a changed gene is present
  on  only one member of a chromosome pair (dominant inheritance); some when
  there is a  changed gene on both members of a pair (recessive inheritance)
  some  only   when  there  is  a  changed  gene on the  female X chromosome
  (X-linked inheritance);  and some when  several  genes interact  with each
  other and cause the disorder  (polygenic inheritance).  Where the disorder
  is dominant,  the first individual to  carry the changed  (mutant) gene is
  affected even  though  his parents are normal,  and in this rare event his
  or her children will now be at risk of inheriting the disorder.

<H4><A NAME="C2.2">  HD - a dominant disorder </A></H4>

   It is  known  for certain  that  HD  is a  dominant disorder and that the
  abnormal gene needs  to  be  present on only one member of a gene pair for
  the individual  to develop  the  disorder.  This means  that each  time an
  individual who  has the gene for HD  ( though he may not yet have signs of
  it ) has a child, there is a 1 in 2 chance that the child will inherit the
  HD gene.  There is also a  1 in 2  chance that  the child will inherit the
  normal gene. Everyone who inherits the HD gene will eventually develop the
  disorder unless  he or she  dies from some  other cause  before the  signs
  appear.
<p>
   Without genetic testing there is no way of discovering which members of a
  family have  inherited the  HD gene  before signs  of the  illness appear.

  Because they are like  their affected parent in,  say,  stature or skin or
  eye colour, some people fear they may also have inherited the HD gene too.
  Physical  or  temperamental  likeness  to  an  affected  parent  does  not
  imply that the child  has also inherited  the HD gene;  nor does it change
  the  1 in 2  risk.  It  can  only  be  said  that,  on  average,  half the
  children of a  sufferer will  inherit the gene.  This does  not mean,  for
  example, that precisely 2 out of 4 or 3 out of 6 children in a family will
  inherit it, but that every child has a 1 in 2 (or 50:50) chance of getting
  it.  Some families are lucky and  perhaps 4 out of 4 children will escape;
  other  families,  less  fortunate,  demonstrate  that  4 out of 4  can  be
  affected; but the chance for any other child remains 1 in 2.
  When  large  numbers  of  families  containing many  children are studied,
  the proportion of 1 in 2 (or 50:50) affected is regularly seen.

<H4><A NAME="C2.3">  Prediction</A></H4>

   Since the discovery  of  the  HD gene in 1993  a  new predictive test has
  been developed.  This can identify  the carriers of the faulty gene before
  they  develop  the illness.  After a number of  counselling  sessions at a
  genetic clinic,  blood samples are taken from  the person who wishes to be
  tested.  The  DNA  which is extracted  from  the blood is then analyzed in
  a special laboratory. Occasionally the result falls in a 'grey area' where
  it is still uncertain whether the person will develop HD or not. Even when
  the test does  show that someone  has the  faulty gene,  it still does not
  show the age at which the disease will start to develop.
<p>
   There is a  different type of test  which can be carried out on a foetus.
  This test analyses DNA from several family members using markers linked to
  the gene.  It  shows  whether the baby is at  low  risk of  inheriting the
  faulty gene or at the  same risk as the  parent who is at  risk but so far
  unaffected.  If you are  considering this  option, do seek advice from the
  genetic clinic before starting a pregnancy.
<p>
 These tests are very helpful to some families, particularly where the result
 is  negative,  or where people  feel that uncertainty is worse than knowing.
 It will be right for those who  wish to have it to do so,  but the wishes of
 those who  would rather  not know have  to be respected,  and no pressure to
 take the  test must be  put on anyone  who does not want it.  An explanatory
 leaflet on the predictive test is available from the H.D. Association.

<H4><A NAME="C2.4"> Age and the changing risk</A></H4>

  Although the dominant inheritance of HD is well understood and is straight-
 forward, there are complicating factors.  It is often difficult to know when
 signs of the  illness are truly present  because they begin so mildly and so
 gradually. However, as we have said, the risk for the child of a sufferer is
 1 in 2 and will not change significantly until he gets to age 50 after which
 the risk decreases rapidly with each year that passes without him developing
 the illness.  If he gets to age 70  and an expert can see no signs,  then he
 has most probably escaped.  This means many years of  anxiety for those with
 the 1 in 2 risk;  some neurologists  will be willing  to check them annually
 for signs.
<p>
  There are  special problems for  those who have a grandparent but no parent
 affected.  For example,  Mrs C,  aged 29,  has a maternal  grandmother and a
 maternal uncle affected.  The intermediary through whom  Mrs C might inherit
 the gene is her mother who is aged 60.  But so far, Mrs C's mother has shown
 no signs at all of HD. What then are Mrs C's chances of having inherited the
 gene?  Mrs C's  mother's  chances at age 30 were 1 in 2,  now at age 60 they
 have reduced to about  1 in 8.  Mrs C's  risk at any age is half that of her
 mother,  so that at the time of the  enquiry her chances are about  1 in 16;
 considerably better than 1 in 2, and if she can wait a few more years before
 deciding  about  children  her  risks go on  getting less  whilst her mother
 remains symptom-free.  These risks by age figures are arrived at by studying
 the age of  onset of the  illness in large groups  of sufferers  to see what
 proportion  of them get the illness at each particular age.  The figures can
 not be precise but they are a useful guide.
<p>
  If you  have an  elderly parent  who is  at risk,  it is  advisable that an
 autopsy,  including a DNA test,  is performed  when they  die to ensure that
 they were not  affected by  Huntington's Disease.  It is advisable to notify
 your GP that, on death, an autopsy, done by a qualified neuropathologist, is
 of the utmost importance.
<p>
  Although dominant inheritance is relatively straightforward it is difficult
 for people to comprehend  all aspects of it fully at first,  particularly if
 they  have  scant knowledge  of human biology.  It does not matter if you do
 not fully understand the mechanisms of inheritance,  but you do need to know
 how the  pattern of  dominant  inheritance  affects you  personally and your
 family.  Young  people  should  know how  the facts  affect them and this is
 discussed more fully in Chapter 4.  Over the years the situation will become
 plainer and you will  probably find  yourself  explaining matters clearly to
 others.  Do not  be afraid  to ask  questions  when you see the doctor. Take
 written questions with you if this helps.

<H4><A NAME="C2.5"> Making Decisions</A></H4>

  Research into the basic defect is going on in many centres around the world
 studies  into the best  way of  caring for  sufferers are also  being  made.
 Meantime it is  important for family members  to see that everyone who is at
 risk,  their  spouses and  potential  spouses,  know about  the  pattern  of
 inheritance of  HD  so that they are fully informed when making decisions on
 marriage and family planning. If people in your family want more information
 geneticists  are the doctors who study the  inheritance of disease;  not all
 hospitals  have  geneticists but  there will be  one in your  Health Region.
 Please ask your GP for details of your nearest Genetic Clinic
<P>
<A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to Contents</A>
</BODY>

