<HTML>
<TITLE>Facing Huntington's Disease : Chapter 3</TITLE>
<BODY background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/bkground.gif">
<A NAME="chapter3"><H2>Chapter 3 - LEARNING THE DIAGNOSIS</H2></A>
<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="#C3.1">First reactions</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C3.2">Telling the sufferer</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C3.3">Telling the children</A>
  <LI><A HREF="#C3.4">Looking to the future</A>
</UL>
  <P>
  <A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to Contents</A>
<PRE>



























</PRE>
<H4><A NAME="C3.1">  First reactions</A></H4>

  It is a terrible shock when you first learn that  HD is in the family.  The
 news comes to people in many different ways.  You may have grown up with the
 knowledge that a grandparent has HD,  and now you are faced with the illness
 in your parent.  Perhaps you  married  someone at risk to HD hoping that all
 would be well, and now HD has been diagnosed and your world is turned upside
 down.  You may have had suspicions for many months, even years, that all was
 not well and have had your  family life  disrupted by  early  symptoms which
 were not  recognised  to be HD.  You may have  known  nothing of  HD and the
 diagnosis  comes as a  bolt from the blue.  However the news comes,  you may
 find it very hard to believe and some common initial reactions are described
 in Chapter 1.
<p>
  The  consultant who makes the  diagnosis will  probably think it  unwise to
 tell the  person who is ill  straight away  and want to  meet them  again to
 assess their possible reactions,  or support they have from their family. He
 may share it first with the husband,  wife,  or a close relative.  Or he may
 write to the family doctor  and leave him to inform the most suitable family
 member or members.  This is a very hard situation  for spouse or relative to
 be in.  Even if HD was suspected,  it is a great shock to hear the diagnosis
 confirmed and shock leaves one feeling numbed and bewildered.  It takes time
 to recover from the shock and to absorb this unpleasant knowledge and no one
 should feel  ashamed or  worried if they  find it  difficult to  take in the
 information and its implications.  If you cannot talk freely at home,  it is
 really important at this point to find  someone you can trust and who can be
 relied  on  to  listen  sympathetically.  It  may  help  to  ask  to see the
 consultant's social worker,  who will probably have time to talk things over
 more slowly,  to answer your questions and to sort out what you need to know
 and what can wait.
<p>
  Many people,  especially those who have married into an HD family, feel not
 only deep grief and depression ,  but real anger if they find that they were
 not told the whole truth;  or come to realise that they did not want to hear
 the whole truth. Some people feel extreme bitterness against a parent-in-law
 for not being more open.  Some people may react by searching unrealistically
 for a cure or seeking further opinions.  All such feelings and reactions are
 natural,  but they are also very  painful and they  have to be lived through
 before the reality can be accepted.

 <H4><A NAME="C3.2">Telling the sufferer</A></H4>

  When and how to tell the  diagnosis to the person who is ill is a difficult
 decision to take, and probably the doctor will want to discuss how it should
 be done with the  patient's  closest relative.  Generally there is no hurry,
 because  sufferers are not  deprived of  treatment  through not  knowing and
 because many  people with HD do not want to know  the truth  immediately and
 are  better able to absorb  the  knowledge over time.  It may comfort you to
 think that the  person with HD does not  want to know what is the matter and
 although  this is  often  the case,  there is a  danger in  taking  this for
 granted.  In fact,  the person who suffers may be aware of what is happening
 and may be  depressed at the though of being ill,  and if he or she suspects
 HD,  at the prospect of  losing a job  or of not being able  to care for the
 family  in  the  future.  It is  sometimes  right  to  protect  people  from
 knowledge  with which they  cannot cope,  but our own  fears and anguish may
 make us overprotective.  In this way we condemn the  sufferer to loneliness,
 and to being unable to express all  that affects him or her  most deeply. It
 is  sensible, early on,  to prepare to share the  diagnosis and to talk over
 with the consultant or your GP how this can be best done.  You may find that
 one you are  prepared to be open,  you will create the kind of atmosphere in
 which the  person who is ill can  begin to ask questions,  then with support
 from your  doctor you can  gradually talk about HD.  Alternatively,  you may
 decide with your doctor  that he or she is the person to tell the diagnosis,
 whilst you give  support to the  sufferer.  However it is done,  the patient
 will be shocked, as you were,  and will need help, especially over the first
 few days and weeks.  But,  at the same time,  he or she may also feel a deep
 sense of relief  that there is at last an explanation  for all that is going
 wrong.
<p>
  It is far from easy  for those who are well  to imagine  what it is like to
 learn that one has a fatal  illness.  The reaction  of the HD  sufferer will
 depend on many factors;  what he may already know or have experienced of the
 illness;  what he stands to lose  - career,  money,  sporting activities,  a
 better standard of living;  what he fears to lose  -  the love of a partner,
 control of his  movements and of his mind;  the kind of  personality he has.
 He too may feel deeply angry that fate has singled him out for this terrible
 blow, and wonder what he has done to deserve it.  He may be depressed, or he
 may become very  active to avoid facing his  distressing feelings.  What can
 you do to help?  Be patient and try not to take angry remarks personally, or
 to deny the  person the right to be  sad or depressed.  If you can share the
 sorrow and anger together,  that is good,  but if this is not possible don't
 feel ashamed of finding someone outside the family to help. As said earlier,
 it is  often  easier to talk to a  person  outside the close  family circle,
 perhaps someone from your church, a trusted relative, or a good friend.
<p>
  As we stress  throughout  this booklet,  each person has  different ways of
 coping. There are sufferers who accept their illness with great courage from
 the  outset,  retaining a love of life  and a  sense of humour  even as they
 become  severly  disabled.  One  young man,  on losing his job,  saw this as
 giving him an  opportunity to indulge a  great love of music,  while a young
 nurse who could no longer work  took up yoga and  helped in an advice centre
 for the disabled.
<p>
  On the other hand  there are a few  people whose fear is so great,  perhaps
 because of a very  unhappy  experience as a child,  that they  cannot accept
 knowledge  of their illness.  Such  individuals may earlier  have kept their
 feelings to themselves,  and can now cope only by denying the symptoms. This
 may be right for them, but it can be most distressing for the spouse who can
 become the target for anger  deriving from deep  feelings of frustration and
 despair.  Although difficult to cope with, given understanding and tolerance
 this phase usually passes  and the sufferer will gradually become willing to
 accept help and even to talk about the diagnosis.


 <H4><A NAME="C3.3">Telling the children</A></H4>

  Those of you who are parents face another worry, what to tell your children.
 Much will depend on what age they are, and whether or not they are living at
 home.  If you decided  knowing  the risk,  to have your  children and if the
 the presence of HD has not been hidden in your family, then your task may be
 easier.  Even so,  all parents are  likely to feel guilty that they may have
 been responsible for  passing on the gene as well as  anxious that the lives
 of their children may be threatened. It is probably wiser to accept from the
 start that at some time in the future your children or youmg people will get
 to know anyway, and that keeping important facts from them may injure family
 relationships.  Indeed,  children who are deliberately kept in ignorance can
 turn  against  parents if they  discover the truth  for themselves  in a way
 which shocks and distresses them. Nowadays there is discussion about genetic
 illnesses in school and on television and radio,  so the truth will come out
 eventually whether you wish it or not.
<p>
  In deciding  how much to tell children,  it is important always to tell the
 truth but not  necessarily the  whole truth and  certainly  not all at once.
 Don't lie to children,  but don't burden them with  information beyond their
 understanding.  That is why it is so  important  not to wait for  'the right
 time' to tell.  There is no  'right time' ,  and the danger of waiting until
 adolescence or  later is that  either the  young person  will find  out in a
 distressing way or  else you will find  yourself forced to tell because your
 young person  has a steady boy or girl friend,  is planning marriage,  or is
 already pregnant.  It is better for  children to learn about difficult facts
 in their  lives as young  as possible,  so that they  can get  used to  them
 before they come to realise the full implications. If parents can create the
 kind of atmosphere  in which it is  alright to ask questions,  then children
 will  generally  ask as  much as  they want  to know and  no more.  Ideally,
 children should  absorb the facts about  HD with other important facts about
 their lives.
<p>
  Some of you  may be able to face  this task on your own,  but most  parents
 will find it  difficult and may need to find  someone with whom to talk over
 their own feelings  and the needs of the child.  This could be a relative or
 close friend,  doctor,  social worker or other professional.  There are also
 genetic  counselling  clinics in each health authority  region where help is
 available.  The important thing is to  find someone with an understanding of
 both of HD and of children,  who will give good advice and help you work out
 the best approach.  It may help too,  to get together with other parents and
 share your ideas, provided you don't feel that everyone must agree on how to
 act,  because each  family will have  different circumstances.  You can meet
 other parents through joining the HDA or contacting its Family Services.
<p>
  Children can cope better than adults think, but parents need to be sensitive
 to the way in which children  react to information which makes them anxious.
 If the child is old enough,  and especially  if there is some reason why you
 must explain quickly,  distressing information about HD needs to be balanced
 by more  optimistic  descriptions of the  research into  HD now and possible
 future  developments in predictive tests,  care and treatment.  It is a fact
 that many young people  can cope with knowledge of  HD without undue anxiety
 and find a  partner  willing to share  the risk.  There  may be few who feel
 overwhelmed, even seriously depressed, who may need professional help to see
 them over a bad period.  If you have talked over this possibility beforehand
 with someone  outside the family,  you will be able  to get help  quickly if
 needed.


 <H4><A NAME="C3.4">Looking to the future</A></H4>

  Finally,  life does not stop because  HD has come into your lives or closer
 to you. True,  it brings a major change and the need to plan accordingly. It
 may help at this early  stage to talk to  others who have  been in a similar
 situation and have  found ways of coping with it.  Looking ahead to find out
 what  help  will  be  available,  whether  financial  or  in caring,  can be
 reassuring. It takes courage to do this, and it may not be right for everyone.
 Some find it best to live each day as it comes, in the realisation that HD
 is a very slow illness and that in a few years treatment may have improved
 and the outlook be very different from now. Many people with HD and those they
 love can still get pleasure from life and even a renewed sense of the value of
 living it to the full. Relationships can be strengthened and compassion increased.
 Not nearly enough support is yet available to help families face this task,
 but gradually our needs are getting known. Some of the help available now is
 described in Chapter 5.
<P>
<A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to Contents</A>
</BODY>

