<TITLE>Facing Huntington's Disease : Chapter 5</TITLE>
<BODY background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/bkground.gif">
<A NAME="chapter5"><H2>Chapter 5 - THE COURSE OF THE ILLNESS</H2></A>
As described in Chapter 3, learning that a member of the family has HD
can sometimes cause an almost overwhelming emotional reaction. After a
while, although strong feelings may come and go, practical aspects have
to be considered. Making plans for the future can help you to cope with
the disease, as each phase is thought out beforehand makes it less
frightening. This chapter is addressed to the carer on whom the well-being
of both sufferer and children will chiefly depend
<P>
    <UL>
    <LI>Part I
      <UL>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.1">Jobs and income</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.2">Care in the Community</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.3">Sharing the care</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.4">Needs of children</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.5">Responsibility for relatives</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.6">HD in children</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.7">Respecting your own limits</A>
      </UL>
    <LI>Part II
      <UL>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.8">The later stages</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.9">The sufferer at home</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.10">Residential care</A>
       <LI><A HREF="#C5.11">Grieving</A>
