<H3>PART I</H3>

<H4><A NAME="C5.1">Jobs and income</A></H4>

The sufferer's ability to continue working is frequently a critical issue.
The length of time someone can work will depend on the progression of the
disease and the kind of job. Occupations which are potentially dangerous
such as welding, or intellectually demanding such as accountancy, may have
to be given up earlier than others. Some employers can be sympathetic and
may be able to offer alternatives, though this may not be acceptable to the
sufferer in terms of income or status. Other employers will not be so
understanding and you may feel that the illness should be kept from them
as long as possible, providing the person is not putting himsefl or others
in danger. It may be difficult for the person concerned to admit that he
or she can no longer do the job, and may need some help to accept that
there is a problem. Th HD Association may be able to advise you on the
best way forward.
<P>
The employment of the carer is also an important factor. You may already
have been the main earner in which case you will have to decide whether
to carry on as before while bearing the extra stresses of organising the
home and looking after the sufferer. If you were the secondary or part-time
earner before, you will have to think about whether your income will be
sufficient to maintain the family, or how you can supplement it. If you
were not going out to work at all, you may consider whether a job is an
option or whether family demands are too great. Although working outside
the home brings its own problems and worries about what is happening in
your absence, it can also be a relief from the demands of home and in fact
help you cope with the physical and emotional problems because you are not
subjected to them all the time.
<P>
As well as thinking about employment, there may be other ways of safeguarding
an adequate income. These are well worth going into before finance becomes
a problem. Normal outgoings can be set against expected income. New expenses
may have to be taken into account, for example, extra heating if the house
has not been used in the daytime before. Some people move to a house or
ground-floor flat which is phsycically more practical and cheaper to run,
though this can be disruptive to neighbourhood social life. Probably some
financial sacrifices will have to be made, though different people have
different priorities as to which they should be. If existing income is
obviously going to be insufficient or if you wish to apply for special
benefits, then welfare rights need to be explored. You will find leaflets
at your local Post Office or Benefits Agency Office, but it would be best
to consult a social worker or Citizens Advice Bureau on the benefits
available and your elegibility for them.

<H4><A NAME="C5.2">Care in the community</A></H4>

In 1993 the government's new arrangements for "Care in the Community" were
introduced. Local Authorities now have the responsibility for assessing
the care needs of disabled people and their carers, in order to help them
stay in their homes. You have the legal right to ask your local Social
Services Departments in different parts of the country to carry out an
assessment to establish what help you need. Social Services Departments
in different parts of the country have varying ways of offering assessments.
Although you have the legal right to the assessment, the Local Authority
does not have a legal duty to provide all the services to meet your
assessed needs. Some councils provide some free services but generally you
will be required to pay towards at least part of the cost. Id special
equipment or adaptations to your home are needed, then an Occupational
Therapist may carry out part of the assessment. Some Local Authorities
employ community carers to help you, others may put you in touch with a
private agency. Voluntary organisations, such as Crossroads schemes, also
give practical help.

<H4><A NAME="C5.3">Sharing the care</A></H4>

Once a sufferer has left work, it can be all too easy for him to lapse into
depression, apathy and a feeling of uselessness. Some drugs can cause
sleepiness and it is sometimes tempting to regard the sufferer as just a
patient rather than a whole person. Although HD certainly can show itself
in mood swings, irritability, even violence, such emotional upsets can be
accentuated by frustration. Someone used to being active and effective
finds it very difficult to be dependent on other people to carry out all
his needs and wishes. It is a good idea, as early as possible, to find out
about local facilities for daytime activities - whether your Local Authority
has a suitable day centre which the sufferer could attend and whether they
provide transport to it. All disabled people should be encouraged to do as
much as they possibly can for themselves and be shown that the contributions
they do make are still valued. Also important for the person concerned, and
the family as a whole, is the contribution of a social life. Relatives will
probably already know about the disease and will react in various eays.
Some can be supportive, but others may withdraw because of their worries
about being at risk or because of their previous experience of the illness.
<P>
If withdrawal persists, little can be done other than realise and accept
that there are those who are unable to tolerate the disease. Friends and
neighbours will probably need to know something of the illness and its
different stages. Friends can be very concerned and helpful once they
understand the problem; if they are not told they may feel puzzled and
rejected. Neighbours will also react better if they know about HD - the
story about a sufferer mistaken as being drunk is a common one. Children
may also feel less embarrassed bringing their friends home if they can
explain that their parent's strange behaviour is an illness. The sufferer
will benefit by other people being around to talk and to listen and the
carer will find relief from what could become a restricted domestic life.
It is important for later on that there are people the sufferer knows and
trusts who could look after him or her when the main caring person is
not there.
<P>
It is very important that carers do have regular opportunity for breaks
from their responsibilities. If you are working during the day, then you
have that time away, but you also need social contacts of your own where
you can just relax and enjoy an evening out without feeling guilty. For
anyone at home, particularly if there are young children, the effects of
constant caring can be claustrophobic. You may feel that you never get
away from other people's demands and needs, and in fact lack the energy
to do anything anyway. However much organisation it takes, and however
much you hate asking for help, it is worth getting a few hours to yourself
in the wider world to be a person in your own right. Avoid the trap of
coming to feel that you only exist to look after other people or that
<EM>you</EM> are the only person capable of looking after the sufferer. If
relatives, friends or neighbours cannot help, you could contact a local
organisation for volunteers, so that perhaps a volunteer could get to know
your family and look after them while you were out. For longer breaks,
from which the sufferer and carer may benefit, there are specially designed
holidays for the disabled. You should go to your community social services
office or to a hospital social worker to get agreement that you need a
break so that it can be financed by the local authority.
<P>
We said at the beginning that your initial feelings about HD may subside
and then return. These fluctuations may continue and are a normal reaction.
You are grieving for the loss of the person you used to know. Couples who
have discussed possibilities beforehand, and who continue to be close, may
find it easier to be sad together sometimes but also positive about the
opportunities still open to them. Those sufferers who are demanding and
difficult need tolerance and understanding but they also may need some
firmness and explanation of their behaviour on you. On the other hand each
sufferer has his own troubles and cannot be expected to sympathise with all
the problems of the carer. An outsider who will listen is very valuable, be
it friend, doctor, clergyman, social worker or anyone else. You may want
advice or just to talk to someone about the difficulties, but either way
it is a help to feel that someone else can share your worries.

<H4><A NAME="C5.4">Needs of children</A></H4>

Children are bound to be affected by living with a parent with HD. If HD
started while they were very young, then they will grow up always knowing
the parent as an ill person; if it started later, they will be upset and
confused by the changes that take place. The well parent may have to give
a considerable ammount of attention to the ill one which could otherwise
be given to the children. The issue of telling children about HD has been
discussed in Chapter 3, but it is worth reiterating that the younger they
know the better. If they know that their parent is ill rather than just
behaving oddly, then they are less likely to be upset. Many children are
embarrassed about anything that is strange about themselves or their families,
and they need to be able to give some sort of explanation to their friends.
If they don't understand, they may also dislike or despise the sufferer for
not being like other people's mothers or fathers, and see him or her as
inferior to their well parent. With the opportunity for open and understanding
discussion, the child can be helped considerably and a caring relative or
family friend can be a valuable outside support for a child to turn to.

<H4><A NAME="C5.5">Responsibility for relatives</A></H4>

In this chapter so far we have written about a husband or wife relationship.
This same situation could, of course, apply in some respects if it is a
parent or other relative who is affected. It is difficult to see a mother or
father on whom you have depended in the past become dependent on you. You may
have to make the decision as to whether you should take on the full time care
of a parent or other relative, and may even be pressed into doing so by other
members of the family. You have to be realistic about this and work out the
long term effects on yourself and your family before making such a decision.
In any event do not make a hurried decision. This is not only best for the
potential carer but may also help the sufferer's self-esteem if he can
manage alone as long as possible. Adequate care may be provided by some of
the services already mentioned, such as home help, and these can be arranged
by the family doctor. You can also explore the idea of sheltered accommodation,
and perhaps an informal neighbourhood network of people dropping in.

<H4><A NAME="C5.6">HD in children</A></H4>

Some people dread more than anything that their child will get HD. It is
extremely rare in young children, but understandably parents do worry about
a child who is clumsy or not getting on as well as expected. Parents should
take advice if they are worried, though usually their anxieties prove to be
unfounded. Parents have hopes and ambitions for their children and it is
very hard to accept that these may not be fulfilled. Parents may also feel
guilty that they may have caused the child to be ill, whether or not they
knew the risk at the start. There are also practical problems, particularly
if one parent is already caring for the other. However, HD in young children
<em>is</EM> very rare and brings special problems beyond the scope of this
guide; specialist advice and help need to be sought.

<H4><A NAME="C5.7">Respecting your own limits</A></H4>

It is very understandable that some people do not feel able, or cannot,
care for someone with HD, or that there is a serious conflict between the
needs of the children and those of the sufferer. A marriage may already
have been difficult before the diagnosis was made. The situation may have
been tolerable while the affected person was still working but not
afterwards, or there may be one particular aspect of the illness which
develops that the carer cannot cope with. Society puts a lot of pressure on
husband, wives, children and parents to care for each other even when
affection has gone and the circumstances are very bad. In some cases it may
be preferable for such carers to put themselves first and separate from the
sufferer. An obvious example is where violence occurs, but there are also
other aspects which people cannot live with. In some instances the sufferer
may lose a degree of normal social inhibition, and demand sex frequently or
without regard to circumstances. To make matters worse, the unaffected person
may feel revulsion at the idea of having sex with a now unattractive person.
There are no easy answers - some people find solutions, others compromise,
and others find it totally unbearable. This happens particularly when the
husband or wife did not know about HD, or was wrongly informed before marriage,
so that bitterness and resentment play a large part. It is difficult to leave
someone who is dependent on you, and it is a good idea to discuss this
possibility beforehand with a sympathetic outsider. There may be some way of
improving the present situation, but if not, you will have reduced your
feeling of guilt by clarifying your reasons for leaving and by making what
provision you can for the sufferer.

<P>

<A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to contents</A>

<PRE>






























</PRE>
<H3>PART II</H3>

<H4><A NAME="C5.8">The later stages</A></H4>

Each stage of the illness brings its own problems and while for one family the
last years of the sufferer's life may bring the greatest challenge and stress,
another family may look back on the early years as the most stressful. It may
be that the sufferer's early frustration and despair led to depression and
to anger that could not easily be controlled, and that with the increase of
physical disability these distressing emotions may have died down. On the
other hand, there is the inevitible increase in dependency as the sufferer
begins to need more help with everyday tasks. Some carers can respond to
these needs better than others. It may be easier to women than for men to
gradually make the change for caring for a semi-independent adult to caring
for one whose needs are more childlike, but this is not always so; many men
are truly 'motherly' and are very good at it, while many women are not.

<P>

Whichever kind of person you are, now is the time to look ahead and to think
carefully what sort of help you are going to need. At some time you will
have to face the decision whether you want the person who has HD to stay at
home even if this involves giving up your job to take on the caring more ort
less full time, or whether you feel it would be right to look for long-term
residential care for your HD relative. Here again, it is very important
that you give full weight to your own wishes and capacities, and to be
realistic about what you can and can't do. If your work and career are
important to you and if you have serious doubts about whether you can care
for a very dependent person without exhaustion and resentment then you must
take these feelings into account. Again, it may be that you have children
to think about. If they are very young or still at school, you have to
consider their needs as well as those of the person with HD. It is certainly
difficult to look after young children as well as a disabled and perhaps
disturbed adult, and children can suffer deeply as a result. You have a
responsibility to weigh up the needs of <EM>the whole family</EM>, and to see
what pattern of care will match those needs. No solution is going to be
perfect or match <EM>all</EM> needs, but if you have thought carefully and been
really honest with yourself, then you will be able to live with whatever
decision you arrive at.

<P>

Gradually, the understanding of the needs of HD patients and their families
are being recognised, there are various homes around the country who
specialise in Huntington's Disease. Please contact the HD Association for
further details.

<H4><A NAME="C5.9">The sufferer at home</A></H4>

There are a number of welfare benefits for which you may be eligible - you
should contact your local Citizens Advice Bureau or Social Services
Department to get more information.

<P>

The kinds of problems you are going to face at home are those already
mentioned earlier in this chapter, as well as difficulty in communicating
and in swallowing. Ask your family doctor for a visit from the district
nurse if you want advice about physical care and from the occupational
therapist in Social Services to make sure everything at home is arranged as
handily as possible and that you have all the aids you need. The HDA issues
fact sheets on various aspects of caring, so you might find it helpful to
get these and discuss them with the district nurse or occupational therapist
when she calls. Problems with eating and swallowing, for example, can be
quite frightening for patient and carer if you haven't experienced them
before and you will need to learn how to handle them. Considerable weight
loss is a common problem and HD sufferers can need around 5,000 calories
a day. Do not be ashamed to ask about anything that is worrying you. You
want to make sure you are doing all you can to make life comfortable for
the sufferer, without being too overprotective; sometimes an outsider can
help you sort this out.

<P>

One of the most frustrating features of HD is the difficulty of communicating
once speech becomes too hard to understand. You should take advice in good
time from an occupational therapist or speech therapist to find out what
alternative methods of communication are available. There are now many more
possibilities and these are listed in the HDA's fact sheet on the subject.
Understanding and being understood is essential to maintain human
relationships and a measure of control over one's own life, though this does
not have to be expressed in words. Touch can be as important and can keep
alive a loving relationship when all else fails. Never assume that because
speech is no longer possible the sufferer cannot understand what is going
on around him, but always include him in the conversation and treat him as
a whole person.

<P>

The person with HD naturally feels very insecure and wants to cling to what
is familiar. It may need a good bit of persuasion and determination to
ensure that the sufferer continues at the day centre or allows someone to
sit in while the carer has a break. It is all too easy to make the carer
feel guilty for standing up for his or her own needs! To look after yourself
is <EM>not</EM> selfish; it is essential for everyone's sake. The carer must
be determined at the outset not to be trapped at home. It is emotionally
draining to care without respite for someone who cannot help doing all the
taking and who finds it difficult to feel and express gratitude for the care
given. Emotional exhaustion can make true caring an impossibility. It is
much safer to plan for a helper or friend to come into the house regularly
before the absolute necessity is there, or to insist on a regular day or
two at the day centre, so that the sufferer does not get to depend on one
person alone. If you are convinced that this is the right thing to do, it
will be easier to overcome any reluctance of the sufferer.

<H4><A NAME="C5.10">Residential care</A></H4>

For some people, the difficult decision of knowing when to accept residential
care is taken out of their hands by some crisis at home or by illness
unconnected with HD. However it is clearly better if admission to residential
home or hospital can be planned and if the sufferer can be involved as much
as possible. A family was dreading the date ahead fixed for father's
admission, when through the letterbox came a welcoming letter from the
charge nurse who was to have care of him, inviting the whole family to visit
with the sufferer and tell the staff what had been important for him in the
past, and his present likes and dislikes. In this way the family made friends
with the nurses and felt quite differently towards the hospital, which before
had seemed so frightening and impersonal. Of course, it is better still if
the hospital or home has a policy of short-term care before admission so that
the sufferer himself can get used to his new surroundings gradually, but this
is not always possible and would be helful only where he or she could fully
understand and co-operate with the plan.

<P>

Sometimes the sufferer needs to be in hospital but refuses to go, and the
consultant decides that a compulsory order is not appropriate. These
situations can be heart-breaking, and you will need professional support to
work out what can be done.

<P>

Sadly, there is often little or no choice of residential care for those with
HD, especially in the later stages of the illness. All the same, it is
sensible to know what ideally you are looking for and what are the most
important considerations for you. For example, being near home so that the
family can visit easily may be vital for some sufferers while for others a
stimulating environment may be more important. We are now moving away from
the idea that little can be done to help those with this degenerative disease
and are beginning to realise that a variety of therapies can be used to
maintain the sufferer in better health and spirits for a much longer period.
Daily exercise, good nutrition, recreation and social activities, music,
relaxation therapy, expert help with speech and swallowing, all these can
enhance quality of life. You should ask whether the home or hospital you are
considering has the contribution of a physiotherapist, occupational therapist,
speech therapist, music therapist, as well as a lively nursing staff with a
good sense of mumour! If the care does not come up to your expectations,
perhaps you can bring in some ideas yourself and support the staff in trying
them out. The HDA has fact sheets on many aspects of nursing care, and ideas
in the newsletter may be useful to inspire and encourage those to whom you
have entrusted the care of your HD relative.

<P>

However well the patient has been prepared, there is bound to be a difficult
period of settling in. This may take the form of turning away from the
family, or alternatively of demanding to be taken home, and in this situation
feelings of self-questioning are bound to rise to the surface. It is hard to
go on visiting in the face of anger and distress, but to stay away plays
into what the patient most fears, to be left alone amongst strangers. But
gradually strangers become familiar people, even friends, and the patient
begins to feel at home. The nurses too need support and encouragement, and
you can help them with your knowledge of HD and your appreciation that they
are doing their best, though probably with not enough time to give all the
attention they themselves would wish.

<P>

You may have to make a difficult decision whether or not to take the children
with you when you visit. Some children can cope very well, particularly if
<EM>you</EM> are not too anxious, and this will also depend on how the visit
is arranged, for example, it may be in a cheerful side ward or waiting room
where you can all have tea together. If you should decide that your child is
too nervous or frightened to visit, then it is essential to talk about
Mummy or Daddy and describe your own visits. Children have vivid imaginations;
what is imagined can be worse than the reality. So your children should know
that their ill parent is loved and cared for and is not in pain, even if
theu cannot see these things for themselves. They will realise then that they
will be loved and cared for if they should be ill, and this will counteract
the natural fear that all children have of being in hospital or of losing a
parent. The more open you are with children, the easier it will be to share
your grief with them when their parent dies. As mentioned earlier, it is
advisable that on the death of a parent, an autopsy is performed.


<H4><A NAME="C5.11">Grieving</A></H4>

The sense that a long and weary illness has now ended does not take away
the need to grieve. So often those who have cared faithfully over a number
of years are exhausted, certainly emotionally and probably physically as
well. It is tempting to throw yourself into work for the HDA, perhaps for
the sake of your children, or at the other extreme to turn your back on the
whole experience. But release and renewal cannot come until you have given
yourself time to experience again, or perhaps for the first time, your anger
that this undeserved suffering came to you and the person you loved. You may
have a grievous sense of loss of a life unfulfilled as we understand it.
After all, so many years of coping creates strains and stresses that cannot
be released overnight. It will probably be many months before you feel back
to normal and have sorted out the memories you want to keep. This is the time
when you will need those friends and neighbours whom you kept in touch with
earlier. So again, take your time, forgive yourself for what cannot be mended,
don't rush into new activity but cherish yourself as the person you loved
would have wished, in the patient hope that peace of mind and acceptance
will come in their own good time.

<H4><A NAME="C5.12">Hope for the future</A></H4>

All over the world resarch is going on into Huntington's Disease. One day,
sooner or later, the cause will be better understood and a treatment found.
This may come in the lifetime of our young family members who still have to
face an uncertain future. We all long for the day when the scourge of this
illness, like many others, will be removed from us. In the meantime, families
are joining together worldwide to promote better treatment and understanding
of those who suffer and to make their needs known. The International
Huntington's Association crosses all boundaries of race and language and
links us in a common cause, to face with courage what cannot be changed and
to change what it is in our power to change, working together towards greater
knowledge and better services, and above all creating the sense of fellowship
that overcomes fear and isolation. We have come a long way in the past few
years and there <EM>is</EM> hope for the future.
<P>
<A HREF="facinghd.html#contents">Back to contents</A>
</BODY>

</DOC>
