<html>
<a name="top">
<head>
<title>Breakthrough Campaign</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/sandston.gif">
<h1 align=center><IMG SRC =../images/logos/break1.gif></h1>
<blockquote><ul>
<li><a href="#work">Making Community Care Work</a>
<li><a href="#care">The Community Care Act</a>
<li><a href="#crisis"> People in Crisis</a>
<li><a href="#medicine"> Treatments: Safe and Effective?</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>

</pre>
<a name="work">
<H2>Making Community Care Work</H2>
Since its launch in 1946, MIND has campaigned vigorously for the rights of mentally distressed people and for better care in the community. Yet many people with mental health problems still lose out because the quality of the care and support they receive varies widely between different parts of the country.
<p>
We know, from listening to users of services, that there is overwhelming support for hospital closure and properly planned and resourced community care. In addition, MIND's recent public opinion survey found widespread backing for the principal of community care - although most people thought it would work better if more cash was made available.
<p>
In response to these concerns, MIND has highlighted the importance of unlocking the money tied up in old-style psychiatric institutions in order to fund decent community services.
<p>
This year MIND has stepped up its demands by launching its nationwide Break Through Campaign calling for:
<p>
<ul>
<li>the establishment of national minimum standards for quality community care services, including statutory rights to after-care; access to 24-hour services for people in crisis;
<li>an end to drug prescribing above the recommended dosage levels or in dangerous combinations;
<li>wider availability of counselling and other alternative therapies, for example from GP's surgeries;
<li>the scaling down of the use of ECT and an immediate ban for usage on children.
</ul>
<p>
Jayne Zito, whose husband was killed by Christopher Clunis, a man diagnosed with schizophrenia, joined MIND to launch the campaign, and to "create as much public and political pressure as possible to raise awareness about mental health issues and achieve change in the system". Her story has brought in tens of thousands of messages of support for MIND's Campaign, which has captured widespread public interest and concern.
<p>
<IMG SRC =../images/lobby.gif>
<B>Jane Zito and supporters at Whitehall during the Campaign</B>
<p>
Jayne's journey began in December on the anniversary of her husband Jonathan's death. In the run-up of MIND's Break Through Campaign, she visited City and Hackney, and Islington MIND Associations in London, closely followed by camera crews and radio reporters who were recording the event for the media.
<p>
The next date was a visit to Wales MIND to attend the opening of an exhibition of photographs celebrating the closure of Parc Hospital at Bridgend - the first psychiatric hospital to be shut down in Wales.
<p>
Jayne then took some time out to make the "Dispatches" programme for Channel 4. This was broadcast the night before the Ritchie Inquiry published its findings on the care of Christopher Clunis, the man who killed Jonathan Zito. MIND had previously given evidence to the Inquiry team.
<p>
The programme and the Inquiry's recommendations caused a considerable public stir and Jayne was kept busy for over a week, appearing both on TV and radio.
<p>
She then plunged into a tour of MIND Regions and Local MIND Associations virtually covering the whole country. Wherever she went she moved her audiences deeply and conveyed MIND's policies with enormous conviction.
<p>
In the West Midlands 18 of the 22 Local Groups gathered to hear her speak. The Regional Office also produced a <I>Tools Pack</I> designed to compliment the <I>Break Through Campaign Pack</I> and to provide practical examples of how supporters can become active campaigners.
<p>
Calderdale MIND concentrated on distributing Jayne's Community Care Petition, including the local hospital, the social services departments, the town hall and library in its networking. Leeds MIND used the city's Health Promotion Week to get Jayne's message across.
<p>
Over 100 people attended a debate at Darlington town hall, chaired by Kelvin Rushworth, Director of Northern MIND, which led to the collection of a large number of signatures for the Petition (including 1,500 each from Redcar, and from Washington MIND).
<p>
Cornwall MIND Network achieved impressive media coverage in their April 1994 rally for better community care, addressed by Jayne, and her visits to Bristol and Eastleigh were also well reported.
<p>
On May 17th the first instalment of over 40,000 signatures of the Petition, was delivered to the Prime Minister. After their visit to Downing Street, the delegation - including representatives from the House of Commons, the Lords, UNISON, the British Medical Association and MIND - delivered the Campaign Pack to Virginia Bottomley at the Department of Health.
<p>
The Campaign has also mobilized many of MIND's Local Associations and encouraged thousands of new MIND supporters to lobby in their areas for good mental health services and to use the media to publicize MIND's work to get the message across.
<p>
Their efforts have been boosted by the production of the <I>MIND Break Through Campaign Pack</I> which contains all the relevant facts and figures.
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top">Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>




</pre>
<a name="care">
<p>
<H2>The NHS and Community Care Act</H2>
<p>
The NHS and Community Care Act was meant to ensure appropriate services and support in the community for people coming out of hospital. However, the law is very limited, leaving it to local authorities - many of which are strapped for cash - to care for all the needs of an individual.
<p>
MIND's Community Care (Rights to Mental Health Services) Bill, sponsored by Tessa Jowell MP, makes it a local authority's duty to adopt a number of key services so that an individual can demand help as of right. In addition MIND's Bill spells out the need for national community care standards that encompass respect, justice, avoidance of harm and entitlement to services.
<p>
MIND is building a huge body of support for these proposals. Our survey of Directors of Social Services revealed an impressive 83 per cent thought national standards a good idea.
<p>
To help people make sense of what is currently on offer, MIND has produced an easy-to-read booklet, the <I>A -Z of Your Rights under the NHS and Community Care Legislation.</I> And MIND's Audit and Community Care teams have blazed a trail for excellence with their new packs which provide guidelines not only on how to set up and run an effective care project in the community, but also how to evaluate the service and achieve best practice.
<p>
The importance of collaborating to develop good quality community services has brought together three local MIND Groups in South East Hampshire (Fareham & Gosport, Havant, Portsmouth); jointly with South West MIND Regional office and Hampshire Social Services, they have set up a unique project to pursue the very best in mental health care including consultation with local users of mental health services.
<p>
The same message has been taken up in South Tyneside where our Northern MIND Region was active in forming CONSENSUS, a forum to enable everyone with an interest in providing quality mental health services to contribute to the planning process.
<p>
Trent and Yorkshire MIND initiated a Priority Care Standards project to assess the information needs of service users and their carers. One finding was the lack of community-based services from black and minority ethnic communities and for those in rural areas. Action can now be taken to fill the gaps.
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top"> Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>







</pre>
<a name="crisis">
<p>
<H2>People in Crisis</H2>
<p>
Crisis care is very patchy with only a few cities such as Birmingham, Newcastle and parts of London rising to the challenge. MIND believes this is unacceptable. Following a survey of MINDlink members (MIND's user network) and 230 Local MIND Groups, it became very clear what was needed:
<p>
<ul>
<li>crisis houses providing a refuge from home;
<li>crisis phone lines providing a sympathetic ear to people in distress;
<li>crisis cards on the lines of kidney donor cards outlining what people want or do not want in a mental health emergency;
<li>home treatment teams helping with everything from child care to providing support to the person in crisis.
</ul>
<p>
MIND is now helping to win the argument. Last year the House of Commons Health Committee gave its approval to the use of crisis cards. This year, the influential inquiry into the care and treatment of Christopher Clunis (Ritchie Inquiry), also recommended more crisis services, as did the British Medical Association.
<p>
Some Local MIND Groups have advanced these ideas by actively lobbying for crisis services in their areas. MIND in Camden (North London), for example, is working closely with local health service managers and social services to develop "stay-out" services to keep people in distress out of hospital.
<p>
<IMG SRC =../images/couple.gif> <B>"People want someone to talk to; a homely peaceful atmosphere"</B><br> 
Alison Cobb, MIND policy officer.
<p>
MIND's interest in community housing goes back a long way and explains why so many of our Local Groups are providing exemplary housing schemes for people leaving inappropriate accommodation. For instance, this year, Knowsley MIND together with Mersey Integrated Housing Association, successfully resettled people with mental health problems into more homely surroundings. One resident commented. "It's a nice house - better than next door! I don't feel I stick out like I did in the hostel."
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top"> Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<pre>









</pre>
<a name="medicine">
<p>
<H2>Treatments: Safe and Effective?</H2>
<p>
Medication is far from being the panacea the drug advertisments suggest. Major tranquillizers are estimated to be involved in one death a week, such as that of 26 - year old Munir Yusuf Majothi, who died last summer after receiving ten times the recommended maximum dosage of a major tranquillizer.
<p>
The latest in MIND's series <I>Making Sense of Treatments and Drugs</I> took the debate about the pros and cons of major tranquillizers further by providing users of mental health services with the information they need to make up their own minds whether to take the drugs or not.
<p>
MIND's report <I>Safe and Effective? MIND's Views on Psychiatric Drugs, ECT and Psyhosurgery</I> took the drug companies' claims to task and presented some alternatives to physical treatments, ranging from counselling to practical help and advice. At the same time, MIND used the report to emphasize the emotional damage caused by ECT (Electro-convulsive therapy) and questioned its legitimacy as a response to mental distress - provoking more debate on the use of ECT than has occured for many years.
<p>
The reasons for MIND's call for ECT to be scaled down and for it to be banned completely for children, were hammered home by Judi Clements, MIND's Director:
<p>
<B>"Recent surveys of patients reveal that the benefits, where they exist, are often considered to be temporary - while the negative effects (including memory loss, headaches, disorientation and weakness) often last longer. Our report also shows that women, older people, black people and ethnic minorities tend to feature disproportionately in the treatment figures. Add to this the use of ECT for children - and we feel there is more than sufficient justification for a complete overhaul of the current system."
</B>
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#top"> Back to top of page</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="mind.html">Return to MIND Home page</a>
<li><a href="../health/">Internet Health Resources</a>
<li><a href="index.html">The Charity Pages</a>
<li><a href="http://www.community-care.org.uk/">Community-Care Front Page</a>
</ul>
