<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Book List</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  bgcolor=#fffbf0    text=#400040 >
<H1>Publications from MIND</H1>
<hr>
<H3>Advice Booklets</H3>
<p>
MIND's advice booklets give straightforward practical information on a range of mental health issues. Each booklet offers realistic and positive options and contains a resource list for seeking further help. They all have a clear and accessible layout and reflect the latest thinking about mental distress. In recognition of their clarity, the booklets have won a Plain English Campaign Award.
<p>
The "Understanding" series titles are: Anxiety, Bereavement, Caring, Childhood Distress, Dementia, Depression, Eating Distress, Manic Depression, Mental Handicap, Mental Illness, Phobias and Obsessions, Post-Natal Depression, Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder, Seasonal Affective Disorder, Schizophrenia, Self-Harm, Talking Treatments.
<p>
They cost 50p each, £4.50 per 10, £40.00 per 100, £330.00 per 1000.
<p>
Most of the above series of booklets have been recorded on cassette. They can be borrowed by visually impaired people from RNIB Customer Service, PO Box 173, Peterborough PE2 6WS.
<hr>
<h3>Mental Health Promotion Booklets</h3>
<p>
MIND's new mental health promotion series, "How To..", aims to help people maintain and improve their mental health and prevent mental distress. Each booklet contains positive and straightforward advice, gives a full resource list for seeking further help and offers suggestions for relatives and carers.
<p>
The "How To" series titles are: Assert Yourself, Survive family Life, Cope With Loneliness, Help Someone who is Suicidal, Look After Yourself.
<p>
They cost 50p each, £4.50 per 10, £40.00 per 100, £330.00 per 1000.
<hr>
<h2>Benefits and Employment</h2>
<p>
<B>A to Z of Welfare Benefits for People with a Mental Health Problem:</b> <B><I>Catherine Grimshaw</I></B>
<p>
This easy-to-use A to Z offers a starting point for people who are unfamiliar with the social security system. It is the first publication to concentrate on the benefits and allowances available to people with a mental health problem. This booklet contains an insert listing the changes in benefits in force since April 1995. It is available seperately for 50p.
<p>
MIND, 1992, 0-900557-96-6, pp23, £2.50
<hr>
<B>Balancing the Payments:</b> <B><I>Alison Cobb</I></B>
<p>
This MIND report describes the present social security system as inflexible and slow - adding that inadequate benefits mean that many users live in poverty. It advocates many changes and is a unique campaigning resource for both users and providers.
<p>
MIND, 1993, 1-874690-05-7, pp32, £7.50
<hr>
<B>Claiming Attendance Allowance:</b> <B><I>Martin O'Kane & Sue Wainwright</I></B>
<p>
A practical information pack for people over the age of 65 years using mental health services, their carers and advocates. It includes information about Attendance Allowance and example letters of successful claims.
<p>
Birmingham Uni, 1994, 0-7044-1421-X, pp20, £5.00
<hr>
<B>Claiming Disability Living Allowance:</b> <B><I>Ann Davis, Alex Davis & Martin O'Kane</I></B>
<p>
An information pack for people aged 65 and under using mental health services, their carers and advocates. This information pack has been designed by people who have been successful in helping users of mental health services and their carers claim Disability Living Allowance since its introduction in April 1992. It includes information about the allowance, examples of supporting letters for successful claims and examples of review letters which have resulted in a claim being awarded.
<p>
Dept. Social Work and Social Policy, University of Birmingham, 1993, 0-7044-1354X, pp25, £5.00
<hr>
<B>Mental Health at Work:</b> <B><I>Eds. M Floyd et al.</I></B>
<p>
The contributors to this volume draw on their experience of mental health and employment to explore rehabilitation issues and techniques, improvements in the workplace, employment training, counselling and support, occupational health services and employer initiatives.
<p>
Jessica Kingsley, 1994, 1-85302-177-6, pp154, £18.95
<hr>
<B>MIND Employment and Mental Health Poster</B>
<p>
MIND employment poster with a blank space for your own use
<p>
A3, £2.00 each
<hr>
<B>MIND's Action Pack on Mental Health and Employment - A Guide to Good Practice</B>
<p>
Includes briefings on users' experiences of unemployment, a code of practice for recruitment and selection, special recruitment schemes, information on good practice and a full resource list.
<p>
MIND, 1991, 0-900557-90-7, £6.00
<hr>
<B>Working Out: The MIND Guide to Employment Projects</B>
<p>
This practical directory gives thorough details on employment projects throughout the country and gives guidance for users of mental health services looking for work.
<p>
MIND, 1991, 0-900557-86-8, pp82, £7.00
<hr>
<H2>Care In The Community</H2>
<p>
<B>A to Z of Your Rights under the NHS and Community Care Legislation:</b> <B><I>Catherine Grimshaw</B></I>
<p>
Major changes in the management and delivery of health and social care have been introduced. This A to Z aims to be the starting point to learn more about the reforms of the NHS and the current provision of community care.
<p>
MIND, 1993, 1-874690-07-3, pp24, £2.50
<hr>
<B>Beyond Community Care - Normalization and Integration Work:</B> <B><I>Ed. Shulamit Ramon</I></B>
<p>
Offers a new framework for practice and tackles issues such as user participation in decision making, the implications for professionals and ramifications for putting theory into practice. Written by professionals and service users this book offers a comprehensive overview of the best that is already happening in community care, points out what is missing and indicates further improvements which could be made.
<p>
MIND/Macmillan, 1991, 0-333-51400-9, pp202, £11.99
<hr>
<B>Break Through Campaign Pack</B>
<p>
Break Through is MIND's major campaign for 94/95, focussing on the right to good community care with adequate support and safe treatments. The campaign pack contains briefings on crisis services, the introduction of national minimum standards for community care, MIND's Community Care (Rights to Mental Health Services) Bill, action notes for campaigning locally, a poster and a leaflet.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 1-874690-24-3, £6.00
<hr>
<B>Break Through Campaign Poster</B>
<p>
Displays MIND's demands for the Break Through Campaign.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 60p each, £5.50 per 10
<hr>
<B>Community Care - A Reader:</B> <B><I>Eds. Bornat, Pereira, Pilgim & Williams</I></B>
<p>
This comprehensive volume on community care brings together leading writers and researchers to contribute a variety of articles containing writings from historical, sociological and psychological perspectives. An ideal book for the professional, the student and the lay person.
<p>
Macmillan/OUP, 1993, 0-333-58715-4, pp346, £11.50
<hr>
<B>Community Care Video Directory</B>
<p>
A comprehensive list of community care videos available covering everything from advocacy to work and housing. Also gives details of accomanying notes and prices.
<p>
Mental Health Media, 1993, pp43 £6.00
<hr>
<B>Community Mental Health:</B> <B><I>Steve Morgan</I></B>
<p>
With the growing emphasis on community care, it is now time to develop services in the community which are both beneficial and acceptable to the people who receive them. This text calls for more effective collaboration between professionals in health authorities, local authorities, the voluntary sector, the various informal carers at home, and, above all, those needing care themselves.
<ul>
<li>client-centred practical approach
<li>addresses advocacy and user empowerment
<li>case studies are included throughout
</ul>
<p>
Chapman & Hall, 1994, 0-412-46940-5, pp252, £14.99
<hr>
<B>Discharged from Mental Hospitals:</B> <B><I>Philip Bean & Patricia Skinner</I></B>
<p>
The decarceration movement involved in the closing down of mental hospitals has gathered pace during the 1990s. vast numbers of mental patients have been discharged to the community, some to other institutions, some to families; others however, have been sent to low quality housing and poor quality hostels. The fare of these people, and some of the impications of this mass exodus of people from the hospitals, are the subjects of this book.
<p>
MIND/Macmillan, 1992, 0-333-44788-3, pp188, £11.99
<hr>
<B>Homelessness and Mental Health Poster</B>
<p>
Explains why there are so many homeless people with mental health problems.
<p>
A3, £2.00 each
<hr>
<B>Housing with Care Support - A Quality Action Guide:</B> <B><I>Louise Villeneau</I></B>
<p>
Consisting of a set of good practice guidelines, studies of local MIND Associations, and recommendations on the implementation of policies, this book will be useful to any agency providing supported housing. Can be used in conjunction with "Home Video" (see "Tapes & Videos" below).
<p>
MIND, 1992, 0-900557-931, pp182, £12.50
<hr>
<B>Housing - The Foundation of Community Care:</B> <B><I>Alison Wertheimer</I></B>
<p>
This document includes information on planning, development, management finance and monitoring, plus details on co-ordinated and related housing support services. Managers, planners and practitoners in the statuary and voluntary sectors will find, in this book, many of the tools which are needed to provide good quality housing.
<p>
MIND/NFHA, 1989, 0-86297-151-9, pp108, £8.95
<hr>
<B>Housing and Mental Health</B>
<p>
MIND Policy Paper which sets out MIND's policy on housing and mental health.
<p>
MIND, 1992, 0-900557-97-4, pp12, £1.50
<hr>
<H2>Child Abuse</H2>
<p>
<B>Breaking Down the Wall of Silence:</B> <B><I>Alice Miller</I></B>
<p>
Dealing with many of the traumatic situations children may have endured, includind sexual and physical abuse and the subsequent refusal to admit neglect and abuse, this book offers an overview of the subject of child abuse.
<p>
Virago, 1993, 1-85381-3, pp182, £6.99
<hr>
<B>Breaking Free - Help for Survivors of Child Sexual Abuse:</B> <B><I>Carolyn Ainscough & Kay Toon</I></B>
<p>
Two clinical psychologists draw on their experience and on survivors' accounts to offer a book of useful information about child abuse and its consequenses. The book gives practical suggestions for overcoming the effects of abuse.
<p>
Sheldon Press, 1993, 0-85969-644-2, pp266, £9.99
<hr>
<B>Surviving Secrets:</B> <B><I>Moira Walker</I></B>
<p>
Much attention has been paid to the subject of child abuse in childhood, much less to what happens to the vast number of women and men who have reached adulthood with painful experiences haunting them. Moira Walker allows the survivors to speak for themselves, about the effects of the abuse on their lives and about the help on offer.
<p>
Open University Press, 1992, 0-335-09763-4, pp211, £11.99
<hr>
<H2>Drugs And Treatments</H2>
<p>
<B>Between Art and Science - Essays in Psychotherapy and Psychiatry: </B> <B><I>Jeremy Holmes</I></B>
<p>
This collection of essays discusses the wider application of psychotherapy within psychiatry and suggests that psychoanalysis needs to take into account contemporary advances in cognitive science, family therapy and the realities of psychiatric work in a public health setting.
<p>
Routledge, 1994, 0-415-08308-7, pp227, £14.99
<hr>
<B>Carbamazepine and Manic Depression</B>
<p>
