<p>
Lithium Information Centre, revised edition, 1990, pp31, £4.00
<hr>
<B>A Complete Guide to Psychiatric Drugs - A Layman's Handbook:</B> <B><I>Ron Lacy</I></B>
<p>
A clear and accessible guide to the benefits, adverse effects and hazards of the complete range of psychiatric drugs. This book is designed to help users understand prescriptions, cut down on the risk of dependency, get the best from doctors and play an active part in recovery. With special advice on the use of psychiatric drugs in childhood, pregnancy and old age, this is an indispensable handbook for the layman.
<p>
Ebury Press/MIND, 1991, 0-7126-4778-3, pp200, £8.99
<hr>
<B>Electro Shock - The Case Against:</B> <B><I>Dr. Robert F Morgan</I></B>
<p>
This book chronicles the use of shock treatments since the 1960s. Morgan, with the use of carefully documented evidence, argues that no one can reasonably advocate the use of shock treatments.
<p>
IPI, 1991, 0-920702-82-1, pp80, £8.50
<hr>
<B>Lithium and Manic Dperession</B>
<p>
Explains what lithium is, how and why it is used to treat manic depression, and the possible side-effects.
<p>
Lithium Information Centre, 1990, pp31, £4.00
<hr>
<B>Men in Therapy: The Challenge of Change:</B> <B><I>R. L. Meth & R. Pasick</I></B>
<p>
This unique and timely volume demonstrates why change is often so difficult for men. It provides detailed guidelines for helping them initiate and sustain change in their personal, familial, and professional lives. This is an indispensable resource for men to understand their own experiences better and for those who want to help them.
<p>
The Guilford Press, 1994, 0-89862-485-1, pp284, £13.95
