<p>
Taken from the speeches given at a conference on eating distress this book offers a series of accounts based on direct experience. This publication is an important text for anyone who has been through eating distress and for those who work with them.
<p>
Survivors Speak Out, 2nd Edition, 1993, 1-898002-00-2, pp23, £5.00<br>
Discounts to users from SSO directly at 34 Osnaburgh Street, London NW1 3ND
<hr>
<B>Fed Up and Hungry - Women, Oppression & Food:</B> <B><I>Ed. Marilyn Lawrence</I></B>
<p>
Why does food cause women so much distress? What is it that makes so many women in the west preoccupied with their weight and dissatisfied with their bodies? This book is a stimulating, positve collection of essays by women who have had direct experience, personal or professional, of "anorexia nervosa" "bulima" and "compulsive eating". Edited by the author of "The Anorexia Experience" and with a forward by Susie Orbach, the book is useful to therapists and practitioners as well as to any woman who has ever wanted to alter her body shape.
<p>
Women's Press, 1987, 0-7043-4008-9, pp236, £6.99
<hr>
<B>Hunger Strike:</B> <B><I>Susie Orbach</I></B>
<p>
From the author of "Fat is a Feminist Issue" this book examines the struggles of women who suffer from eating distress. In a new introduction Susie Orbach discusses current attitudes towards eating problems and how they have changed over the last few years, and in a newly revised final chapter she proposes an innovative approach to residential treatment.
<p>
Penguin, 1993, 0-14-016978-4, pp184, £6.99
