<h3><a name="control">Voice Control</a></h3>
The voices that we hear vary from individual to individual, and they come in different forms. Some people hear some recognizable voices of people they know, friends, lovers, family, and voices from the past; whilst others hear voices of strangers who they come to know and many hear a mixture of all of these. What many people who experience distressing voices do seem to have in common, is that these voices do have a measure of control over their lives. This negative controlling influence can severely restrict their lifestyle, they can prevent them from having real relationships, from working, from doing the simple everyday things that other people take for granted, like going shopping, sitting in the garden, or even eating, washing or sleeping.
<p>
When you spend all night tossing and turning listening to a chorus of voices outside your window it is very difficult to sleep. Sometimes what I hear can sound like a play on the radio, with a cast of several people. The scenario can range from what the neighbours think and are saying about me, from the police or the DSS or MI5 keeping up surveillance on me. The theme of the drama can be that they think I am an international terrorist, a drug-smuggler, a potential homicidal maniac, or that there are killers already outside waiting to break in and murder me. I can sometimes hear the glass smashing and am on the point of phoning the police, when I am not so sure, and decide it would be better to be killed than to call out the police and have them think I am a "nut-case". It's like watching a film on television and being drawn into it so that it seems so real that you believe it is happening, but once it has finished you know it was only a fictional drama.
<p>
When I go out I feel as if I am being followed by similar characters to the night voices, or fear I am recognized by people I know that despise me and used to bully me. These are the voices that control my actions. They don't tell me directly to do this or that, like the voices of some people. They mostly refer to me as "she" in the third person, "look at her, she's a loony/weirdo" or "I knew she'd turn out like that!", "Why doesn't she just kill herself and put us all out of our misery?". They make walking around so intolerable that I can rarely do it, or even sit in the garden.
<p>
The voices used to control the way I dressed, because I liked bright ethnic clothes, they said I was weird, and kept commenting and bitching about my appearance. Another voice hearer, Rose, found that the voices actually told her what to wear, dictating the colour of her outfits each day and how to back-comb her hair, so that she became unrecognizable even to herself.
<p>
Many of the women I know that hear voices, and a few of the men, have problems with food. The voices tell them that they are fat when they are thin or normally proportioned, and that they are ugly. One woman believes that all her food is poisoned by her mother, so she hardly eats anything. I remember when I was travelling and had to eat in restaurants, how the voices commented constantly about what and how little I was eating. It became such an ordeal that I did stop eating and went from a size 14 to a size 10. I couldn't eat with people watching me and talking about what and how I ate. This happens every time I go travelling. At the moment the voices just say that I am fat and I feel really guilty about my weight.
<p>
I do believe that these bad-mouthing and vitriolic voices come from within myself because I am so conditioned by these attitudes and comments from my family, fellow school pupils, and boyfriends. I am so used to being controlled in one way or another, and although I do fight against it and when they bully me into doing something, I don't always do it, but it is like fighting in a long bloody civil war. You need a lot of strength to overcome the barrage of verbal abuse that's forever coming through your ears.
<p>
<img src="back.gif"><a href="#top">Back to Top of Page</a>
<hr>

<h3><a name="open">An open letter to a worried friend</a></h3>
Dear friend<p>
For twenty years I went in and out of hospital and from job to job. Then, in hospital, I met another patient who put me on the road to full recovery. At the time I was hearing voices, suffering body pains, having my head turned and sometimes seeing visions.
<p>
I had been detained under the Mental Health Act for going from church to church pulling Christ off his cross. In fact, I was in a truly bad way. Then this other patient showed me a path back to sanity. He first told me I had two brains and that I had my dominant brain on the left side of my head since I was right-handed. I also had a submissive brain on the right side. My dominant half used my right half as a subordinate servant or slave.
<p>
I told him he was trying to make me out to be a nut with a split brain. He said "No" - everyone had two brains. The human brain is split down the middle into two separate halves. He told me to look at any photograph of a real brain and that I could see it for myself. But he said, that it was only when people went nuts that the split really showed.
<p>
He said that normal people had one side of their brain larger and stronger than the other, so that they had no trouble keeping it in order and making it obedient. Our trouble - his and mine - was that both sides of our brains were equally strong. Our trouble was that both sides of our brains did not have sufficient clout, so we were unable to control our other halves properly. That's why they bugged us, made us hear voices, and in my case, gave me headaches and pain. He told me to think of my body as a car with two drivers. I had to drive all the time but I had this wicked other half to my brain. It deceived and confused me, and tried to make me give up control so that it could take the steering wheel and drive in my place.
<p>
I was lucky enough at this time to have a lovely person caring for me. I told her what my friend had said about the two drivers. She thought for a long time about it. She then said it could be true. Perhaps my trouble was that I treated my other half badly, I should try being nicer to it. Did I know my voices came from the other side of my head?
<p>
I used to think that my voice came from God, but when it kept letting me down and getting me hospitalized, I decided it was telepathy. I was too aware of what was going on, so I believed the establishment were using telepathy to get me down and make me appear mad. My carer repeated her question. Did I realise my voices came from the other half of my brain? I answered "Sometimes", she replied "Good, you should try talking to your voices, tell them the game is up. You know where they come from. You should listen to their replies and argue with them - not out loud of course."
<p>
I tried talking to my voices, well thinking to them. It did not work, they clammed up and would not talk back. My carer did not give up. "You must go on trying, tell your other half that you are prepared to time-share with it, that you will let it in and give it control." "What on earth do you mean?" "You must give up the driving seat and let your other half drive for a change, give it control of your body. You only need to give it control for a short time each day and in return it should stop bugging you." "How do I let it in?" "You just let go of the controls and let it take over." "How?" "It should be easy. Many people are able to swap over from one side of their brain to the other, good actors for example, they have a domineering side and a submissive side, they put their best side forward to meet the situation they are in. Do you ever lose your temper? That could be your other side showing itself. You must encourage it to come out normally, not just when you are in a tantrum. Do you ever feel like you're being taken over by some telepathic force?" I replied that I did but that I tried to resist. She told me not to, to allow it to take control and then I will have succeeded.
<p>
Eventually I found out how to share with my other half, and I have never looked back. It works out very well. I used to hate getting up in the morning, now I leave it to my other half. I only need to take over when I have to meet someone. It is not very good dealing with strangers, but it is still improving.
<p>
I now have a working partnership with my other half. It no longer sends me voices or bugs me in any way. Since I do not have to fight to prevent my other half taking control, I have much more energy left to live my own life. I am now completely fit and have been without medication for twenty-five years. I do hope you can succeed as I have done. Good luck!
<hr>
<h3><a name="bach">Bach Flower Remedies and "Messages"</a></h3>
Let me introduce myself, I am Philippa Sophia Sanford, and I have been working with Bach Remedies for about 15 years. I don't hear voices as such, but I do have neon lights on a grey background, in my head, words flash up at me on my mental screen. Most of the time when I'm having an attack, and really going through it. I also experience an energy impulse behind these "messages"..so I get messages...Ring any bells?
<p>
Anyway, the Bach Flower Remedies are for varying states of consciousness. Some familiar and some more obscure. I will give you some examples:
Aspen and Mimulas - fear; making the same mistakes over and over again and failing to learn from these mistakes. Chestnut Bud - over-concern for the welfare of others. Red Chestnut - gloom and depression.
<p>
The remedies give you a positive dose of the flowers properties. If a person was very unbalanced emotionally or their mind was jumping about all over the place, Schleranthus would be indicated, for calming and soothing the extremes of this state. Consider a graph with extremely large troughs and heights, this remedy smooths out the extremes so that we have a graph with a more even line making the emotional and mental state more balanced.
<p>
Here's how to make a remedy from flowers. Take the flowers you want to use, some spring water, a glass bowl and you need some sun. You leave the flowers floating on the surface of the water in the sunlight until the water is potentiated with energy from the flowers, for it is energy that we are dealing with here. We call this potentiated remedy, the mother essence, and this is then mixed about 50/50 with brandy for preservation. Drops from this are then mixed with more spring water and brandy for personal use. This remedy may then be taken orally or on the skin.
<p>
When I am hearing messages I have found all of the Bach Flower Remedies useful at one time or another. Here are a few examples of how they have helped me cope with my condition. Cherry Plum, which is for dark thoughts, fear of the mind, giving way and doing fearful things. I sometimes worry that I'm going to kill people psychically and by accident, which is an irrational fear that comes to me a lot. I have no intention of killing people but these thoughts occur, dark and broodingly, and I have found that Cherry Plum is very helpful when I'm feeling like this.
<p>
Aspen has often calmed my vague unknown fears, you know when you feel frightened and don't really know what you're afraid of, but something's really freaking you out. Mimulus is good for known fears, and I've used this in conjunction with fear of dying. I used to get a morbid fear that I was going to die, sometimes this remedy was the only thing that could allay my fears. Sometimes this remedy didn't work but it always gave me a greater objectivity about my fears of dying.
<p>
To sum up, Flower Remedies work at more subtle levels than the physical. They heal mental emotional and spiritual imbalances, they work in the aura of the body, healing illness before they reach the physical body. I feel that in years to come, as the subject of vibrational healing reaches mainstream medicine, I wouldn't be surprised to see these remedies being prescribed by doctors for people with mental health problems. For, as I hope you can see, these little friends have helped me considerably.<p>
<img src="back.gif"><a href="#top">Back to Top of Page</a>
<hr>
<h3><a name="child">Having a child gave me a life</a></h3>
I must stress that this is an article based entirely on personal experience. At the time I conceived I was in, what psychiatrists would term, a psychotic state.
<p>
I had believed myself to be in love with a man who had been a good friend of mine for a period of nearly a year but who happened tohave a girlfriend who was also a friend of mine. I believed that he and I were in telepathic communication and that what he was telling me telepathically was what he felt in reality. Both friendships came to an end when I declared my love for this man through a series of what must have appeared to be disturbed letters in which I made frequent reference to the content of my voice hearing experience which had coloured my feelings for this man.
<p>
Once I had declared my love and found it to be unrequited I ran away from home. I believed I was already pregnant although I hadn't had physical intercourse for a year. Due to the belief that I was pregnant I found myself in the situation of having unprotected sex with someone I mistook for the man I loved. The voice in my head was his voice telling me that this other man was in fact the man I loved even though it didn't look like him.
<p>
This time I really did conceive and went determinedly ahead with the pregnancy because I thought I would be able to find my man friend again and present him with his child which we could bring up together.
<p>
Throughout the entire pregnancy I went through periods of elation and suicidal depression always tainted by irrational thinking and ideas. I would interrupt conversations with people in front of me to break off and reply to a voice in my head. Frequently the voice would be of the man with whom I was in love.
<p>
My child, Adam was born May 1st 1988 weighing 8lbs 14ozs - he was 11 days overdue. Five days after his birth he was taken off me and taken to a place of safety - the social worker had not even let me try to manage at home. No one prepared me for this, I was given no warning that this would happen whatsoever.
<p>
In order to get my child back, whom I already loved, I agreed to go into Withington Mother and Baby Unit for assessment with my child. I had to go back on vast quantities of neuroleptic medication or lose my child, and there was no hearing voices movement in England then to help me. I was still hearing voices despite high doses of medication. Nobody attempted to discuss the voice content and find out that all my problems stemmed from unrequited love. This I had to cope with on my own.
<p>
After four months in hospital, Adam and I left and went back to our flat. Adam was still under a ward of court order as he had been virtually from birth.
<p>
Once I had got back to my flat with Adam the care services were very supportive and gave us every possible help to cope with daily life, and gradually the drugs were reduced. I shelved the emotion the voices were causing me, I had to because no-one seemed to be able to provide a solution.
<p>
For me, pregnancy and being a parent has been a really beneficial experience. It has given my life focus. It took six years of listening to distressing voices before I finally sorted out my feelings emotionally, and Adam gave me something to keep going for during that period. I met someone as a hopital inpatient who finally helped me to get over my emotional turmoil. He supported me as a friend until I grew strong again.
<p>
I also gained a lot of support from working with the Hearing Voices Network from 1990 onwards, and that talking about what I had been through with various other voice hearers and allies was a big help until my friend from hospital finally pulled me out of my pointless longing.
<p>
My hospital admissions have lowered considerably. I have been in hospital only twice in the last seven years, once for four weeks and once for four days. I take a minimum dose of medication, to make sure that the voices I hear still do not lead me to behave irrationally, and to ensure that social services have no grounds for thinking me incapable of raising my child.
<p>
All this leads me to the conclusion that the mentally ill should be helped and supported to bring up their own children. Historically, there has often been strong pressure to sterilise people with a diagnosis of schizophrenia, and sometimes this has been carried out in the past, in America and Germany for example.
<p>
I feel lucky that I have had the chance to bring up a child, and consider that having the label "schizophrenic" rather than "voice hearer" has done much to prevent me finding a suitable marriage partner.
<p>
Since having Adam I have become more responsible, more loving, more tactile, more fulfilled, more independent, more confident and more stable. I also  have had a better relationship with my parents since giving them their only grandchild, and enjoy better friendships in general.
<p>
I write this also to bring some hope for change for people who have lost their fight to keep their children in the past and, subsequently, made their suffering increased. Mental illness should not preclude the joys of motherhood and with therapeutic help for voice hearing it could be a feasible possibility for others like me.
<p>
<img src="back.gif"><a href="#top">Back to Top of Page</a>
<hr>
<h3><a name="story">Crime and Punishment, a short story</a></h3>
Enrico Morales sat with his head in his hands in the sweaty prison cell he shared with Bicho the serial killer. On his lap was a tear stained letter from his wife telling him she couldn't wait for him any longer. She had run off with the man from the taco stand on Segunda Avenida. He couldn't believe it, the bastard, he'd been his drinking buddy for ten years. The times he had spent talking and drinking with him in El Gato Negro. And now he had cuckolded him, the cabron, when he caught up with him he would slice of his testicles.
<p>
Enrico was in prison for ten years for the armed robbery of a shop selling religious artifacts in Guadalajara. He not only stole two million pesos, but he took most of the contents of the shop and this was an unforgivable crime. Violeta, his wife, had sworn that she would stand by him and wait faithfully for him. He swept the tears away from his eyes with his large clumsy hands and swore to avenge his honour. He beat his head and then banged the door to attract the attention of the prison guard. Salvador, the guard, came slowly towards the door, he was feeling pretty spaced out from a pito he had just smoked. His mind was floating free of this ugly prison barracks and up into the hills of the rainforest where his father had been born. As he approached the grill Enrico had already wrapped a length of cotton around his neck and was twisting it tightly so it glued him to the door. Salvador's face turned a bright red and he was gasping for air.
<p>
"Give me the key and I'll stop twisting." Enrico said in a menacing growl. salvador managed to extricate the key from his waist, as he was almost passing out and gave Enrico the key through the bars. The door was soon unlocked and Salvador had passed out, so Enrico had to give a huge push to the door to move his slumped body out of the way.
<p>
Bicho had woken up by this time and was alert to the possibility of escape. They both stepped out gingerly, past the guards at the end of the corridor who were sleeping a deeply drugged sleep. Once out into the compound with the night in their eyes they had to adjust their vision like cats on the prowl. They saw the fence and Enrico stood on Bicho's shoulders and scrambled up catching his hands on the barbed wire, but he didn't feel the barbs tearing at his flesh. Then he was over, and he was free. He twisted his ankle in the long jump, but his adrenalin kept him going. Bicho was beside him now and wordlessly they crept through the grass to the road and across the canyon.
<p>
A few days later he was walking through the streets of Merida, he and Bicho had split up in Oaxaca. Bicho had gone to Acapulco to murder a few more people and Enrico had hitched back from Merida to look for his wife and that pinche pendejo, Pato. He fingered his beard, he wanted a shower and a shave, and a change of clothes. He went to the house of his sister-in-law, Carmelita. She was a bitch but she wouldn't begrudge him a shower and a shave.
<p>
When she saw him she was surprised and shocked. She was a little afraid of him, especially now that Violeta had run off, he was sure to be in a bad mood. Carmelita made him some enchiladas, being careful not to serve him tacos in case this enraged him.
<p>
After Enrico had bathed himself he found some clean clothes that Carmelita had laid out for him, the clothes that had belonged to Luis, his younger brother, who had died last year trampled by an enraged bull in San Luis de Potosi. He blamed Carmelita for his death. Luis would never have gone to work on the hacienda if she hadn't been greedy and expected more and more. His job as hammock salesman hadn't been enough for her, she wanted him to be a vaquero which he wasn't cut out for. Now she had nothing, except for money from the chief of police who visited her twice a week.
<p>
Enrico felt renewed and felt his energy returning. Carmelita refused to tell him anything about Pato and Violeta, even though he threatened to hit her. She was used to violence and didn't care if he did or didn't hit her. So, he went to El Gato Negro to see if he could find anything out there. As soon as he stepped in the door, they were all friendly, buying him drinks and telling jokes.
<p>
When Enrico mentioned Pato a dark shadow passed across their faces as if a black crow had flown above them. Everything went quiet in apprehension and fear. Enrico was renowned for his bad temper. Someone said, "Leave Pato alone Rico, what's past is past, there are plenty of chulas, prettier than Violeta".
<p>
Enrico knocked over his table and grabbed the man by the throat. "What did you say Abuclo? Do you know where they've gone?" The man gasped and clawed the air, "Tizimin." he said eventually.
<p>
"They've gone to his brother's bicycle shop in Tizimin." "Thanks Abuclo", he said, letting him down into his seat. Enrico accepted several more beers and then staggered back to Carmelita's. However, he found the door boarded up so he had to sleep on the pavement. It was a hot, humid night and he passed out into a deep drunken sleep amongst the ants, the cockroaches and other sleeping bodies.
<p>
The next day he set of for Tizimin in the back of a pick-up. The journey was slow because the driver insisted in stopping off at every bar in every town they came to. His driving became erratic and slurred and Enrico was glad to get out when they eventually arrived. There weren't many bicycle shops in Tizimin so he soon found where Pato and Violeta were staying. As he approached the shop the rage he felt surged from his solar plexus radiating through his body. His mind was full of the words in the letter and he was ready to explode.
<p>
He went into the shop but there was no sign o
</DOC>
