<hr><p><br><br><br><br>
<h2><a name="dins">Dyslexia Institute</a></h2>
Provides advice and counselling, Educational Psychologist's assessments, Specialist Learning for all ages and talks from experienced staff. Contact can be made with the Institute at:<p>
<h4 align=center>74, Victoria Crescent Road<br>Dowanhill<br>Glasgow G12 9JN<p>Telephone: 0141-334-4549<p>or at Perth on 01738-444373</h4><br><p>
<h3>Dyslexia Institute Bursary Fund</h3>
Subsidises School Fees incurred in connection with the Dylexia Institute and in particullar the teaching of people who have been assessed as Dyslexic. More information can be obtained from the Bursary Fund Administrator, <b>Shirley Dunlop</b> at the address for the Dyslexia Institute above.<p>
<h3>Other useful sources of advice</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Scottish Examination Board (0131-663-6601)</b> - The Board has a progressive and sympathetic policy to dyslexic pupils who may be allowed additional time, large scale examination papers, the use of a scribe or a reader, and the use of a word processor.
<li><b>"A Parent's Guide to Special Educational Needs"</b> - Obtainable from the Scottish Office by calling <b>0131-244-4502</b>
<li><b>Information on Computers and other Learning Aids</b> - Contact the Scottish Council for Educational Technology on <b>0141-337-5000</b>
<li><b>Reading Through Colours</b> - Anne Peck, 49a Lockhart Avenue, Edinburgh EH14 1BB, Telephone: <b>0131-443-4322</b>
<li><b>National Association of Educational Guidance</b> - 1a Hilton Road, Glasgow G2 7DN
</ul><p>
<h3>Local Authority Advisors for Learning Support</h3>
Advice can be obtained from Local Authority Advisors for Learning Support and these are listed under Schools and Education Authority contacts.<p>
