<a name="derek"></a>
<H4> Love Is The Time, Just Before</H4>

 Love is the time you are high as a kite,
 Just before you wonder, were you right.

 Love is the time when you're together,
 Just before your heart feels deader.

 Love is the time of happiness and hope,
 Just before you realize, you cannot cope.

 Love is the time when nothing else matters,
 Just before loneliness your heart batters.

 Love is the time you're light as air,
 Just before you begin to wonder, does anybody care.

 Love is the time you say goodbye to your friends,
 Just before you realize, you and your love want different ends.

 Love is the time you can move a mountain,
 Just before you feel like you've fallen into a fountain.

 Love is the time when you put her before yourself,
 Just before you get put on the shelf.

                                            Derek Morgan



<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>

































<a name="mary"></a>
<H4> Crescendo</H4>

 Red hearts and crosses
 Butterflies
 Moons and Stars
 Flowers, leaves, letters
 Utter lies

 Green leaves and grasses
 Bittersweet
 Spices and herbs
 Bones, sticks, bottles
 Litter in the street

 Grey men and women
 Battered wives
 Shout and scream
 Kick, punch, rape
 Shattered lives

        Mary Rigby June 1988

<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>





























<a name="jeremy"></a>
<H4> Untitled</H4>

 My beauty rides slowly and softly
 The rails firm but vulnerable
 I knew me, so many times before
 I never met me, ever, at all.

 A thin line stretching from head to toe.
 One vulnerable soul
 Fragile, ready to break.

 Watching stones
 Ready to fall
 All over the boredom
 All across this moment.
 A cork prised by pressure
 Bursts open upon this sadness
 A tube of paste
 Squeezed from the heart
 Releasing it's torment.

 I'll stay where I am
 For I'm going nowhere
 But I'd rather go somewhere
 And nowhere today
 Than somewhere tomorrow.

 "Don't trample on my head,
 Can't you see the dents, you left before!"
 I've tried to tell the truth, time and again
 But the world would not understand.

                                         Jeremy Law





<H4> Standing Outside The Boundries Looking At A Picture ?</H4>

 A selfish scent of sad colours
 Blends into one watery void
 The agony of rebellion
 The pain inside.....

                        Jeremy Law



<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>





























<a name="paulb"></a>
<H4> MAD</H4>

 Mad, mad it's bad to be mad!
 Nothing quite like it for making you sad.
 So follow me - follow
 Down to the hollow,
 And there let me swallow
 A pill that will make me less MAD.

                                       Paul Burke



<H4> ODE TO THE BARDS</H4>

 There is a breed from Man whom I shall name,
 Whose names by ne are vaunted o'er all men;
 They are the Bards from Heaven disengaged,
 To feed the ground with subtlety enraged,
 Softened, whispered, trumpeted with braid;
 Clarion to mute vespers of the colonnade;
 The haughty houses of the vain might stand,
 If Fate denied the voice to such a noble band.

 The ponds of meditation fathomed quite,
 Soothing Melody by Industry's tired light,
 They plotted the course for Humanity's Common Soul,
 And breathed the balm of Virtue's hidden scroll;
 Eremetic vigour set o'er yon flesh-worn frames,
 Of antique heros, tyrants and unutterable names;
 In febrous fealty to the wan forlorn,
 Yet to the importunate bequeathed their trophy-laden morn.

 The myriad vitriol murmurings of lesser men,
 Made sacral by Genius' sceptre-scourging pen,
 From raging sinew, raised inviolate; welled,
 Then layered on the brow-enchanted - Heaven-Spelled!
 The lush leviathon labours of the meek,
 From crepitatous breath - star-anchored to the weak;
 They winnowed grace from earth-deflected Hells,
 And fed on Poesy ripening in their consecrated cells.

 Their lattice songs wreathed into air abound:
 Tamasic tremblings raised in Sattwic sound:
 A burgeoning billow; their's no timorous schemes:
 Mystic muslin woven from their noble dreams,
 They lent to piety the fruits of fructuous wills:
 Confounding node to the harbinger's tired trills;
 Intimidating hard-blown ill-crested men
 With thoughts that honour might yet live again.

 This ancient brood whose wisdom kneads the clay
 Of youth's untainted spectral little day,
 Their noiseless virtue set in mortal moiety,
 Eschewed their grace to harness Love's annuity;
 With moulded metres draped in pascal pleasure,
 They lulled the tender storm with melodious measure,
 O would that from the concourse some proud form repeat
 The noble round: intactile sacral meat;

 That from the trembling hearth would idly spring,
 Embalmed loveliness from a poet's wing;
 Soaring Sattwic with rajasic fervour,
 To set in metres a hinder to Minerva.
 O! where the Keatsian titan to condone
 With verbiage rare my love (though not my own)
 For wisdom, genius and arcadian dreams
 And all that's bright made brighter by their names!

                                        Poll de Burca 1995


<H4> ODE TO A PROUD LADY</H4>

 (Bitter words on hearing of the imminent death of an unfaithful lover)

 Thou who wert the darkening of mine eyes
 Feeding thy canker with the eyes of men
 With hate's hard verse I stoop to prosodise
 Thy palsied beauty, to scorn with raging pen
 Such antique loveliness; seeming to each;
 Though doubtless too it fed each caustic eye
 With silken hues of choice and fairest peach
 But thy soul waxed foul as swill infects the sty.

 For ne'er did pity light upon thy brow
 Didst e'er thy heart constrict for love of men?
 Thou didst not ever care for me, I trow
 And I can never grieve for thee again
 The heady dews that bound me once in thrall,
 Time's spigot pramed a saffron fetid hag
 Thy jewelled rayment has become thy pall
 Thy gilded vestment, but a skin-soiled rag.

 Then Verminous Leper, thou must rue in turn
 As Nature festering calcines thy cheeks to clay
 Thy highest thoughts a clipped fool could discern
 From sweeter conclaves than thy venomous lay
 Of pouting judgement, let sophistry despair!
 For thou canst neither feel nor comprehend
 My storied measure, suffering with the faire
 The sacral motive, nor the name of friend.

 Should Mercy's veil light o'er thy scorpious heart
 With mortal pangs for pain which thou hast wrought
 And thy soul wax tender with penitant smart
 And muses bless thee with the grace I sought
 When thou didst fester in temples of vice
 And vaunted thy dominion o'er the tame
 And didst thou weep as felines grieve for mice
 Thy tender slaughter would still bear thy name.

 Then look upon the charter of thy span,
 And read with Terror's eyes my harsh decree,
 And count it not the judgement of a man,
 But God's affection thus despising thee
 And bow in shame that he may look on thee
 In thy last unchronicled hour and pity find
 And with thy sated breath construct a plea
 That mercy wilt prove faire and thus be blind.

                                      Pol de Burca 1995



<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>



























<a name="michelle"></a>
<H4> The Boys</H4>

 Many years ago today
 Two small boys were hard at play
 Gavin was just ten months old
 Neil was three and brave and bold.

 Neil was being "Robin Hood"
 And Gavin's attention would be good.
 He plonked Gav' on the window sill,
 Took one deep bow, then stopped quite still...

 Gav' was nowhere to be seen,
 Just Farley's rusks where he had been,
 Downstairs Mum sat happily
 Studying a recipe.

 She gazed outside, then gave a scream,
 Surely this must be a dream.
 "DAD DAD"! come quick, we've got to rush
 Our Gavin's in the gooseberry bush!

 They raced outside, then had to laugh,
 For sitting there besides the path
 Gavin hooted, bawled and cried,
 Not with pain, but wounded pride.

 Ahh, there my love don't make a fuss
 At least it proves you're one of us.
 She brushed the moss from his backside,
 "Now mucky, lucky lad - inside!

                                 Michelle Wilson




<H4> Empty Parcels</H4>

 I went a walk the other day,
 And met a man made out of clay.
 I told him of my deepest fears.
 But clay men only cry clay tears.
 
 Then as I walked a little more,
 I met a man made out of straw.
 But when I pressed him to my heart
 He pulled away, then fell apart.

 And then I met a man of wood.
 I talked to him and it felt good.
 But so he couldn't hear me
 He turned into a tree.

 So now, when I go for a walk.
 I see these men but never talk.
 For when they say they'll be my friend.
 I know they're playing "let's pretend".

                          Michelle Wilson



 The above poems have been included as a 
 Memorial to Michelle Wilson who sadly died 
 on 26th March 1995 aged 34





<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>



































<a name="kelvin"></a>
<H4> No Scrap Heap</H4>

 Rows and rows of cabbages
 And none of them are green
 Because they've been through life's displeasures
 They have seen what they have seen.
 It isn't wrong to be so ill
 So why are they all so hurt?
 They need a bit of self-respect
 Not treated just like dirt.

                                              Kelvin




<H4> I Moved On</H4>

 I met a man with a needle in his arm.
 He said "Try this boy, it'll do you no harm".
 I said not a thing but felt sick inside -
 Since that day my friend has died.
   I moved on,
        No one's killing ME.

 I passed through a group. They all wanted "crack",
 But I knew a guy once who was cranking up "smack",
 He said "Try this", I said "I'm no fool,
 You want ne hooked, but I'm gonna stay cool".
   I moved on,
        No one's killing ME.

 I knew a guy once who saved my life,
 But he went back to "skag", he's in paradise;
 Then he found it too much, had to go and kill himself,
 Put his head on the track, now he's an urn on a shelf.
   I moved on,
       'Cos no b*****s killing ME that way.

                                                Kelvin




<H4> The Holy Man</H4>

 Here comes the Holyman, dealing out his scrips,
 Here comes the Holyman, hey doc give me a fix,
 Nurses bow down to his shadow,
 Patients wait patiently,
 For some mystic prophecy,
 From his reverend saintedly.

 (What it is to be a "trick-cyclist",
 I shall never know,
 For I went under God's right-hand man,
 Eleven years ago).

 There's no escape, he holds the trumps,
 The dice they are all loaded,
 God I hate psychiatrists,
 And their frigging toadies.

                                             Kelvin




<H4> Mr. R. E. Volting</H4>

 I was on the ward four weeks, two days, three hours:
 I was sinking fast.
 I thought "anything is better than this".

 Then Mr. R. E. Volting came up to me and said,
 "Listen boy, I can save you, 
 Just sign this little form and you'll be cured".

     So like a fool I signed the form.

 They took me upstairs, put a needle in my arm,
 Then when I was high enough, they took me in a room,
 They strapped me to a bed, put leather between my teeth,
 They then touched electrodes to my head, 

    20,000 volts right through my brain.

 I think some brain cells died, I really don't know.
 After three more courses I refused further treatment,
 Because I'd never felt so bad.

                                                 Kelvin



(ECT is now illegal in the USA and most civilised countries, 
but is still widely practised in the UK.)




 Dear Mrs. Thatcher,

 In reply to your call for support in the Gulf, 
 I'm sorry to say that I am too mentally ill to kill women 
 and children.

                                     Apologies,

                                                       Kelvin



 The above work has been included here as a 
 Memorial to Steven Ormerod   who sadly died in 
 August 1994 aged 40



<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>



































<a name="arnold"></a>
<H4> I'm Depressed</H4>

 I want to be left alone,
 But near people that care
 About me, my troubles and worry.

 The world is an empty barren place, needs
 Love expressed without words or touching.

 My lonely heart, hurt by people, who sometimes don't
 Even know they have hurt.
 I think, it is better to never, never care -
 To be hard and cynical.
 But my heart still loves - still cares deeply.

 My heart rises above all the pain.
 I will be hurt again.
 But for now, love reigns.

 To hold someone close
 To touch a friend
 To buy one a coffee
 Or give a cigarette
 Establishes me as a human again.

                                      Arnold Hulme

<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>

























<a name="mike"></a>

<H4> More Fun</H4>

 It's nice to be independent
 With a place to call your own
 And someone to share the 
 Friendship there,
 More fun than being alone.

                 Mike "Elvis" Moran








<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>







































<a name="kevan"></a>
<H4> Tainted Smile</H4>

 In the gathering gloom of life's bitter mist
 Came a girl of brightness, reaping her fate,
 But darkness spelt an eternal doom
 For this girl with a tainted smile.

 A hand from Hell came out of the shadows
 And clutched her heart in a vampire grip.
 And behind the hand, a demon sneered
 As he maimed this girl with a tainted smile.

 Lost in a wasteland of dry bitter sorrow
 With no light to guide her, or path to follow.
 She circled endlessly the sands of grief,
 And shaped therin, her bitter pill to swallow.

 Then despair did come on wings of fire,
 Searching out her barren soul.
 And cloaking her with it's mighty wings,
 It smothered this girl with a tainted smile.

 Slitting her throat on the wasteland sands,
 Her blood ran dry beneath a bleaching sun.
 Lifeless and still, her body rotted white,
 And now on her face, bone engraved a tainted smile.

                                             Kevan Foulds



<H4> Straight To Hell</H4>

 To love in Hell and shallow dreams,
 To watch her die before my eyes;
 To climb the stairs, and walk away
 What sorry state of love, behind me lies.

 I killed her nightly in my dreams,
 And resurrected her with hate.
 What shallow lies I told
 And golden dreams I stole.

 Sell me witches, or broken jewels.
 It matters not, not now.
 For in the twisted darkness of my mind
 Love has sent me straight to Hell.

                                    Kevan Foulds



<H4> Vicissitude</H4>

 Moments of pain, and anguish: grief.
 Breath deeply, lulling Child of the Sun.
 For dawn is rising over distant hills,
 And shadows cast will soon be gone.

                                     Kevan Foulds





<H4> Friend In Grief</H4>

 She stroked her boyfriend's grave
 With outstretched white-washed hand,
 And crying out loud,
 Her mouth stretched wide,
 She shed her tears
 In dizzy grief.
 And fell upon the burial mound.

 Clutching soil
 With frantic fingers.
 Digging deep
 To claim anew
 Her boyfriend's withered corpse.

 This, for an outraged heart,
 Which - in all the world -
 Wanted only her boyfriend back.

                                     Kevan Foulds



<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>

































<a name="veronica"></a>
<H4> Counselling</H4>

 It isn't very easy,
 To just sit down and talk,
 When all I want to do
 Is just get up and walk -
 Away.

 It isn't very easy to smile and hide
 All the hurt and feelings
 That are locked up deep inside.
 It isn't very easy,
 To know what to do for the best,
 To suffer in silence,
 Or lay all the ghosts to rest.

 So what is the answer?
 I wish to God I knew.
 Do I just sit here in silence,
 Or put all my faith and trust -
 In you?

                    Veronica Brierley

<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>

















                                                                                                                                                                                    

<a name="duke"></a>
<H4> Feelings</H4>

 Why are feelings that are so strong
 Never seem to last very long
 There was a happy smiling face
 Why is it now out of place
 Tinged with sadness and hate
 Plagued by your ills
 Then they fill you full of pills
 But feelings are always there
 Why are they so hard to bear

                               Duke



<h4>  Another Psychiatry Poem</h4>

 Who invented psychiatrists
 I don't know
 Some beaucrat probably
 And anyway
 I wish I never met
 One
 Because I am
 Worse than I ever
 Was
 That's his fault
 I think
 Do you.

                             Duke





<h4> Feeling</h4>

 What's feeling
 Happy or sad
 People want me to
 Be glad
 I don't
 Why's that
 Am I unsure
 I think so
 Maybe
 My mind says
 So
 Everyone else
 Says no
 I say let my head control
 My life
 It helps me through
 Trouble and strife.

                    Duke



<h4> Untitled</h4>

 They fill you full
 of pills
 Will they get rid
 of your ills
 No
 They just drug you
 up
 Or is it to shut
 you up
 Will psychiatry make
 you well
 I don't know I
 can't tell
 But it still
 carries on
 The pills and
 the therapy
 When will it stop
 I hope it gets the 
 chop
 I'm never ill
 Just rattling with pills.

                       Duke





<h4> Soul</h4>

 You see a flower
 Growing in the earth,
 Or a fire burning
 In a hearth.
 Is that your soul burning?
 Slowly disappearing,
 Or reappearing?
 Do you want to rescue it
 from the fire,
 And free your mind
 From the illness that is unkind?

                             Duke



<img src="../images/logos/mouse.gif"><a href="#content"> Back to Contributor's list</a>



















































<a name="judith"></a>
<H4> Mad Matrix</H4>

 You think you are mad and society is not mad
 You think you are not mad but society is mad
 You think you are mad and society is mad
 You think you are not mad and society is not mad

 They think you are mad and society is not mad
 They think you are not mad but society is mad
 They think you are mad and society is mad
 They think you are not mad and society is not mad

 You think they think you are mad and society is not mad
 You think they think you are not mad but society is mad
 You think they think you are mad and society is mad
 You think they think you are not mad and society is not mad

 They think you think you are mad and society is not mad
 They think you think you are not mad but society is mad
 They think you think you are mad and society is mad
 They think you think you are not mad and society is not mad

 They think they are not mad and society is not mad
 They think they are mad and society is mad
 They think they are not mad but society is mad
 They think they are mad and society is not mad

 Guess what anyone thinks
 Like them perhaps
 Like you perhaps

                                Judith Elliss 13-6-93



