<html>
<head>
<title>HERMES Meeting Reports</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif>
<blockquote><hr>
<h1 align=center>HERMES</h1>
<h3 align=center>Health and Education Regarding M.E. in Stockport</h3>
<p>
<h4 align=center>[ <a href="#aloe">Say Aloe to..</a> ] [ <a href="#endoc">It's all in the Endocrines</a> ] [ <a href="#anaes">Anaesthesia & M.E.</a> ] [ <a href="#tax">M.E. & the Taxman</a> ]<p> [ <a href="#relax">Relaxation Techniques</a> ]</h4><p><br><hr><br><br><br>
<a name="aloe"></a>
<h3>Say Aloe to...</h3>
<b>Alex Turner</b> gave a talk to the Stockport ME Group and suggested we should 'Say Aloe..to the Natural Healer!'. There was a full house for his presentation and it was pleasant to find that Alex did not sell Aloe Vera as the panacea for all ills, but reckoned that it probably helped ME sufferers because it cleaned up the digestive system and left more energy available for other things.<p>
Both the FDA (US) and MAFF (UK) have given Aloe Vera a clean bill of health, but there are no clinical trial results to prove that the gel is useful to ME sufferers. Nevertheless, people were obviously interested in the presentation, and several jars were bought afterwards. A letter from a fellow sufferer, attached to the handout, spoke of 'Aloe Vera Nectar' in glowing terms - so there is at least one satisfied customer - and he does not have the same name as the owner of the company selling it!<p>

<hr>
<a name="endoc"></a>
<h3>It's all in the Endocrines</h3>
<b>Joan Bullock</b> gave a talk to the group about the endocrine system and in particular how ME might be related to problems within it. The prompt for the talk was an interesting consensus that the hypothalmus may provide a base from which other problems extend.<p>
Joan took us through the interaction between the hypothalmus and the pituitary gland; and the way in which the pituitary triggers the adrenal, thyroid, pancreatic and other elements in the endocrine system. As she spoke it was possible to see why a problem in the hypothalmus could result in such a range of symptoms from headaches, muscle pains, heart and breathing abnormalities to a bad stomach - and all those other little glitches which we are so familiar with. For example, body temperature is, in part, controlled by the thyroid gland. And an under-active thyroid can result in lowered body temperature.<p>
<blockquote>Did you know that a high (-ish) percentage of ME sufferers have a depressed body temperature? Instead of being 98.4 degrees F it can be a degree or so lower. Joan is presently researching this effect.</blockquote><p>
Another of the endocrine system's more pervasive components is the adrenal gland. Most of us know that getting worked up often gets the adrenaline flowing, and helps us deal with attack. In the olden days it controlled our ability to fight and triggered the chemicals which helped us run fast when we were losing. Now, an over-active adrenal system can create some of the symptoms experienced by ME sufferers, and so it is possible that food supplements which reduce adrenal activity might help relieve some ME symptoms. Joan linked this train of thought with the other generally accepted view that ME is associated with an over-active immune system. Or, as she put it, an aover-stressed system. This, in turn, can lead to sleep irregularities, increased sensitivity to some foods - and digestive problems.<p>
Digestive problems are Joan's particular area of interest and for the rest of her talk, she concentrated in this area, sharing her experiences of treating a whole range of symptoms through controlling diet. She also startled one or two members of the audience by proposing that <b>meat</b> should be an essential part of our diet. We are all individuals and 'one man's meat is another man's poison'. dairy products cause all sorts of problems for some - for others they are the only foods which go down when they are having a particularly bad patch. As Derek Vernon put it in his closing remarks, ME affects people in different ways and for those who have severe digestive problems, a dietry approach can be very beneficial - as it was for him. For others it may not help at all.<p>

<hr>
<a name="anaes"></a>
<h3>Anaesthesia and M.E.</h3>
<b>Dr. John Watkins</b> heads a unit whose remit is to look at 'odd' diseases and 'strange' presentations of diseases. M.E. being what it is, this formed the basis for an immediate rapport, which he cemented by promising to give "..the Watkins definition of M.E.."<p>
Using slides, he gave us a run down on the way our immune system works and the effect that anaesthetics have on it. They showed that our immune system can take up to a week to recover from an anaesthetic, its various organisms having been put to sleep just as effectively as our consciousness. It is, apparently to compensate for this unconscious state that the cocktail of drugs which most anaesthetists pump into us contain antibiotics in profusion.<p>
And therin lies (one of) the rubs. If, as many now believe, ME involves an over-active immune system, excessive antibiotics could create some 'interesting' effects. In fact, Dr. Watkins tends to the view that antibiotics should probably excluded from the anaesthetic cocktail.<p>
Unfortunately, it is well nigh impossible to conduct meaningful tests, because the trauma caused by the surgery itself, not to mention the effects of anxiety, may outweigh any consequence of the anaesthetic. Some tests which have been carried out on 'whole body' systems (and in particular the gut) indicate that 'winding up' a person can create as much imbalance in the endocrine system - and hence on the immune system - as anaesthesia.<p>
Nevertheless, he suggested that it would be prudent to ask for <b>propofol</b> as the hypnotic and to have <b>adrenalin-free anaesthetics at the dentist.</b> There is no evidence that M.E. patients are more at risk from anaesthesia than the general population.<p>
In response to questions about the disturbed digestive systems after operations, Dr. Watkins was adamant that the problems were almost certainly due to surgical trauma and anxiety - not the anaesthetic.<p>
The elevated incidence of mental, emotional and muscular symptoms in M.E. patients is consistent with increased post-operative stress, but there is no proof due to the uncertain nature of the condition. His view is that post-operative problems are probably due to glutamine imbalance in the gut, and it 'would do no harm' to experiment with glutamine supplements.<p>
<hr>
<a name="tax"></a>
<h3>M.E. and the Taxman</h3>
A couple of our members thought that they would probe the Inland Revenue to see if people with M.E. could exploit a little known archaic clause, whereby a married man can claim an additional personal allowance in respect of his wife if she is totally incapacitated by physical or mental infirmity (wives cannot claim for their husbands, because when the clause was drafted in the 19th century husbands took no part in looking after the children). This was the crux of their reply.<p>
"Ther is no statutory definition of 'totally incapacitated'. The Inland Revenue give these words their ordinary meaning. The test is hard for the wife to meet, especially if she cannot carry out any of her normal household duties as a wife and mother for the whole year, that is, if the house is run as though she was not there.<p>
Strictly, the allowance should not be given until after the end of the year when it has been confirmed that the wife has remained incapacitated for the whole year. In practice, however, the allowance can be given in advance if it is likely that the conditions will be met."<p>
So, if any wives out there think you are going to be unable to look after the kids for the next year, maybe you shoild apply to your tax office!<p>

Report by Ralph Morris<p>
<hr>
<a name="relax"></a>
<h3>Relaxation Techniques</h3>

<b>Ros Edlin</b> gave a talk at our July meeting on Stress Management and Relaxation, including a couple of examples of Relaxation techniques, which many present found helpful. The following chair-based relaxation is one of them, based on the principles of the Alexander Technique. For details of courses run by Ros contact her on 980 7373<p>

Start by learning how to relax sitting in an ordinary upright chair. Take off your shoes, put on warm, loose socks, loosen any tight clothing.
<ol>
<li>Sit well back in the chair so that your back is well supported.  Place a small cushion or folded towel or jumper in the small of your back if that feels more comfortable.
<li>Move the lower legs forward so that the whole weight of your upper leg is settled on the seat of the chair. If the chair is too high, use a pillow/cushion/book under your feet to support them.
<li>Allow your knees and thighs to roll outwards.
<li>Make sure that your buttocks are soft and spreading and your abdomen loose and soft, so that as you breathe in and out, your tummy rises and falls somewhere in the region of your waist.
<li>Think of your shoulders dropping down towards your waist so that you feel more space between your ears and shoulders and back of your neck feels long. This is a good feeling to keep with you at all times.
<li>Make sure that your elbows are not pressed into your sides and let your hands rest heavily on your thighs. Your hands should not be clenched nor touching each other.
<li>Your head should be perfectly balanced at the top of your spine - not leaning back, poked forwards or over to one side. If your chair has a high back, place a folded towel or jumper behind your neck to adjust the position of your head correctly.
<li>Make sure your teeth are not touching each other.
<li>Your tongue should be at the bottom of your mouth.
<li>Keep your lips soft, lightly touching each other and thinking of the beginning of a smile which leads to a feeling of width going out to the ears.
<li>Close your eyes lightly if it is appropriate. If not, focus your gaze on something still across the room. Keep your eyeballs still and imagine that your eyes are getting further apart. This leads to a feeling of width going out to the temples. Let the expression come off your face.
<li>Imagine your forehead getting higher, wider and that this feeling of smoothness is spreading over your scalp and down the back of your neck.
<li>Let your body sink down into the chair and enjoy the feeling.
<li>Just sit as long as you want to. If you feel fidgety then stretch your arms and legs and get up but do persevere with the practice - you will find that in time you will be able to sit for longer periods without fidgeting.
</ol>
Use this technique or parts of it whenever you sit down so that the feeling of relaxation becomes absorbed into your everyday life.
Parts of this technique (eg face, shoulders) can be used when standing, walking, talking, doing jobs around the house, driving etc. 

<hr>
