<head>
<title>HERMES NEWS</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif">
<br><blockquote><hr>
<h1 align=center>HERMES</h1>
<h3 align=center>Health and Education Regarding M.E. in Stockport</h3>
<hr><br>
<h4 align=center>[ <a href="#survey">Survey of Stockport GPs</a> ] [ <a href="#what">What can we do about M.E.</a> ]</h4>
<a name="survey"></a><br><br>
<h3>Attitude of Stockport GPs to M.E.</h3>
A quarter of GPs in Stockport responded to a questionaire, adapted from one drawn up by Action for M.E. The most positive feedback from the survey was that all bar two would be prepared to refer patients to a specialist clinic at Stepping Hill Hospital.<p>
Doctors were asked how many patients they have with M.E. Responses varied from 0 to 20, which may in part be due to the range of understanding and belief in M.E. Scaling up these figures for the 75% of GPs who did not reply, gives us an estimate of about 600 people with M.E. in Stockport. This closely matches the figure we would expect, based on a study done in Glasgow.<p>
The Range of understanding mentioned above can be gauged from the answers to questions about the nature of M.E., who it affects, and how long it can last.<p>
Only 70% of GPs recognised M.E. as a severe debilitating disease. Others thought it a relatively mild condition, or failed to answer the question. Answers on age range affected often cut out younger and older age ranges. Over half said that people over 60 are not affected, and 20% said that teenagers are not affected. Many people in both categories are in fact known to us.<p>
Nearly half of the GPs who replied said that M.E. can only last ten years at most, and three said that the maximum is about six months. Hence it is clear from this illuminating survey, that we have a lot still to do in educating the medical profession about the nature of M.E.<p>
<b>David Carter</b><p>
<hr>
<a name="what"></a>
<h3>What can we do about M.E.</h3>
Often people with M.E. have had health problems in childhood. Then, later on, something went very wrong. there may have been an acute or chronic infection, surgery, drugs, hormone treatment, chemical damage, an accident, bereavement, divorce or exposure to harmful radiation. The reserves of vitamins, minerals or other nutrients ran dry. They are not available to deal with the toxic substances we all breathe in, eat or drink. So the toxins do damage to different body systems.<p>
At this stage the person has M.E., but it may well not be recognised, and more damage is often done with inappropriate drugs, or invasive medical investigations. Wide spectrum antibiotics may be prescribed, which kill off valuable bacteria in the gut, so that candida fungus grows to fill the vacuum, and produces toxins inside the body.<p>
<h4>Nutrients</h4>
Since the problem is related to lack of nutrients, the priority is to replace these. Nutrients are vitamins, minerals, fatty acids and amino acids, which are parts of protein. In particular, we must replace the detoxifying nutrients. For example; Zinc, calcium, selenium and vitamin C deal with toxic heavy metals. Vitamin B5 protects against certain allergies.<p>
Nutrients have to be used carefully, as zinc and copper, copper and molybdenum, iron and zinc, iron and molybdenum, chromium and vanadium, calcium and magnesium, and vitamin B2, vitamin B6 and magnesium have to be kept in balance. Certain fatty acids may be needed, like linoleic acid from safflower and sunflower oils, or omega three acids from leaves and fish.<p>
<h4>Diet</h4>
Because the body's ability to detoxify has been reduced, harmful chemicals in food have to be reduced, like boron, aldehyde, genetic material, alcohols, lectins in seeds, sugar and caffeine.<p>
The diet should be rotated, with different food eaten on different days. water should be filtered to remove some of the contaminents.<p>
<h4>Allergens and Pollution</h4>
Moulds and housedust should be avoided, and chemicals like polyurethane foam in furniture, North sea gas, felt pens, coal smoke, cigarette smoke, food additives, paints and varnish. Electromagnetic pollution, from visual display units, televisions, remote control devices, radio transmitters, mobile phones, storage heaters and night water heaters should be minimised. It is important to go outdoors, to receive the full spectrum of the suns light. The bed may need to be moved, if it is in a harmful place.<p>
Some doctors give neutralisation, which is very dilute drops or injections of substances, at doses tested individually. This can be done for chemicals, moulds, foods, tap water, and even nutrients, so the body deals with them better. A similar process can be used for electromagnetic pollution, using tubes of oscillating water, or a special watch. Enzyme potentiated desensitisation can be used, but it is slower.<p>
<h4>Candida</h4>
Where someone has a chronic candida infection, acidophilus and bifido bacteria can be used to repopulate the gut, caprylic acid can be used to kill the infection, and vanadium levels can be increased in the body, to make it inhospitable to the fungus. Biotin prevents it from changing into its invasive form. Molybdenum, zinc and vitamins B2 and B3 deal with toxins made by candida.<p>
Chromium, manganese, vanadium, biotin and vitamin B3 can stabilise blood sugar levels, reducing craving for sugar and caffeine. The amino acids, phenylalanine anf methionine can help the adrenal glands produce adrenaline. Phenylalanine can also reduce cravings, by making a person feel full.<p>
<h4>Tests</h4>
Immune function can be improved by removing toxic mercury fillings, but a test should be done first. Fillings should be removed in the right order, a dam used, and dietry supplements provided to remove mercury.<p>
Lab tests can be useful, provided that they lead to decisions on treatment and that they do no harm. Possible tests are for gut fermentation, for parasites; gut permeability, to see if harmful substances pass through the gut wall; a sulphite test, to check on molybdenum levels; hair analysis, to check on useful and harmful minerals; and tests for digestive enzymes.<p>
Tests can be used to check on the need for various supplements, although it may be cheaper simply to try out the supplements, and see if they help.<p>
<h4>Summary</h4>
In the first stages of M.E., a person feels down all the time, and is unable to see what is doing the damage. As recovery starts, there are ups and downs, and it becomes possible to notice what foods or chemicals provoke reactions. It is necessary to accept that things can become worse before they improve, and that sometimes treatments can be tried which are unsuccessful for a particular person, so that other techniques are needed.<p>
Special diets, a careful lifestyle, and taking supplements may have to go on for a long time. Treatment is complex, and needs to be supervised by a knowledgeable person. With determination and patience, people can recover, to work hard, and live a fulfilling life again. It require discipline, but it is worth it.<p>
<b>Margaret Moss</b><p>

