<head>
<title>"Isn't ME just depression?"</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif">
<h1 align=center>"Isn't ME just depression?"</h1>
<hr>
Depression isn't just being unhappy or sad about unhappy or sad things,
there's nothing 'just' about it. It's a pathologically low mood, and yes,
people who have ME can and do get depressed.  People who have had strokes,
heart attacks, multiple sclerosis, Parkinson's, head and spinal injuries
often get clinical depression too. Some of it can be blamed on the action
of the disease process, some of it on the effect of the illness on that
person's life. The side effects of antidepressant drugs can help with
specific ME symptoms, and the intended effect can help any depression as a
result of the disease process or the impact of ME on one's life. Cognitive
behaviour therapy can help sufferers cope better, and give those who are
recovering confidence, in just the same way as it can help people with
other illnesses. Finding that a drug or therapy is helpful is not the same
as finding the cause of the illness.
<p>

It is perfectly reasonable that depression should be considered as another
possible diagnosis when a patient presents with symptoms of ME as many of
them overlap, and of course ME sufferers may already have clinical
depression by the time they seek help - in particular those who are
referred to consultants. Given the prevalence of clinical depression in the
general population, the prevalence of ME and the higher prevalence of
clinical depression amongst people with chronic ill health, it would be
remarkable if clinical depression were extremely rare in people with ME.
But correlation is not causation. It is a common problem in research
studies that ME is confused with chronic fatigue - which is like trying to
find out about brain tumours by looking at people with headaches.
<p>

Treating ME sufferers as if they 'only' have clinical depression does not
seem to improve their health any more than treating them as if they have an
illness which is not primarily psychiatric, but neurological, hormonal,
immunological, or auto-immune or just of unknown cause. Attitudes toward
mental illness remain more judgmental than those toward physical illness
and society as a whole is less willing to provide assistance to those who
suffer in this way - anyone who doubts this should look at the exclusions
on disability insurance policies and the allocation of state benefits. Some
ME sufferers will reject a psychiatric theory for the illness because of
prejudices they share with the rest of society, but many more reject it
because it offers them no more hope, on no more evidence. Some of them have
suffered genuine clinical depression in the past and know what it feels
like.
<p>

We understand how hard it is for others to believe that we are not just
lacking in motivation - most of us have been through (and still go through)
phases where will tell ourselves (and believe it) that this is all in our
minds, that more exercise and positive thinking will help and that we
should not be so easily discouraged, some of us take antidepressants. We
are sometimes described as perfectionists and overachievers, and no wonder
because we do want to stress that we *are* motivated people who have been
capable in the past, because our illness is seen by some as laziness. We
won't really know until a study is conducted amongst the general population
to see what sort of people develop ME, because maybe only the overachievers
and perfectionists with ME will fight a simple depression diagnosis. Maybe
only those in well paid careers who have insurance with exclusions for
mental illness and were not on benefit anyway will feel it worth fighting
against a simple depression diagnosis.
<p>

Treating ME as just depression is putting the cart before the horse.
<hr>
<a href="personal.html"><img src="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/back.gif"></a>
</body>
</html>
