<html>
<head>
<title>CFS/ME vs Depression</title>
</head>
<body background="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif">
<blockquote>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>CFS/ME vs Depression</h1>
<hr>
The most oft heard complaint from sufferers of CFS/ME is "My doctor says I'm just depressed." However, although depression and CFS/ME share many similarities, an examination of these shows some major differences. Even considering that most sufferers of chronic and debilitating illnesses, be it AIDS, cancer, arthritis, MS, Huntington's disease or one of the myriad other illnesses that take away a person's quality of life, leave them dependent on others and give them little hope of a cure, will suffer bouts of depression as they see their world crashing around them with little hope of ever regaining their former fit and active selves.<p>
In the case of CFS/ME in particular, the problem is really tragic. The illness, being somewhat new and having had such a 'bad press' during it's relatively short history, is still being extensively researched, with new theories as to it's cause being suggested every few months.<p>
This tragedy is not helped by the sheer weight of information that general practioners have a need to read and most of them just do not take the time to read newly published research papers, even in abstract, unless they have one particular illness in which they take a special interest. This fact is very evident where CFS/ME is concerned.<p>
As yet, no research study has ever (to my knowledge) shown evidence that CFS/ME is depression, in fact most research studies into the illness have shown evidence that the two are indeed unrelated. Therefore, it is blatantly obvious that  - <i>any doctor who claims that CFS/ME is just depression is merely stating his or her personal opinion, moreover that that opinion is not a considered opinion - that he or she has never taken the trouble to discover the known facts regarding the illness</i>.<p>
This simple and disturbing fact, a fact which soon becomes obvious to those who suffer from the illness, explains why so many sufferers begin to lose confidence in the medical profession, and why so many consider suicide as a viable option to their continued suffering and some even take that option.<p>
People who suffer from clinical depression do not painsakingly devote their time and energy to researching their own illness; do not actively engage themselves to furthering public awareness of their condition; do not search for new fields of endeavour in order to continue a desired participation in life.<p>
The (to a sufferer) dreaded 'F' word, fatigue, is bandied about by the medical profession who are always quick to point out that people who are depressed, people who are recovering from an infection and people suffering from many minor illnesses also suffer from fatigue. However, there are varying states of fatigue and the word itself does not, cannot, convey any understanding of the fatigue to which a sufferer of CFS/ME suffers from.<p>
To most people fatigue is that tired 'washed out' feeling that comes after a hard days effort, either physical or mental, a tiredness easily recovered from by a stroll to the local pub for a quiet drink or an evening watching the match on the TV. To an athlete it's much more, it's that state he/she is left in when they've just run that marathon, when they turn to jelly and fall down with their muscles in spasm and they're in so much pain they can but lie where they fall. For the athlete however, a short rest will see them recovered sufficiently to wearily walk up to collect their award. Such fatigue as this can and is suffered by those with CFS/ME after a short walk to the corner of the block, or even after the effort of making a snack. For the sufferers of CFS/ME however, the affect isn't always immediate, and the recovery is never complete. The act of getting dressed in the morning can leave a sufferer feeling as if they've just spent hours 'pumping iron' in a gym, a hairbrush, a cup can seem to be one hundred times it's weight. This is fatigue as experienced by no other than the sufferer of this vile illness or those at deaths door.<p>
Clinically depressed we are not. Lethargy and lassitude do not describe our fatigue nor does the ache of an overworked muscle describe our pain, that ache is with us day and night already, relentless and spread throughout our bodies, sleeping, waking, sitting or lying.<p>
Here then are some of the findings of researchers, more will be added later.<p>
<hr>

Hickie I, Lloyd A, Wakefield D, Parker G<br>
The psychiatric status of patients with CFS.<br>
Br J Psychiatry 1990 Apr;156:534-40<p>
      The prevalence of psychiatric disorder in 48 patients with chronic
      fatigue syndrome (CFS) was determined. Twenty-two had had a major
      depressive (non-endogenous) episode during the course of their illness,
      while seven had a current major (non-endogenous) depression. The
      pre-morbid prevalence of major depression (12.5%) and of total
      psychiatric disorder (24.5%) was no higher than general community
      estimates. The pattern of psychiatric symptoms in the CFS patients was
      significantly different to that of 48 patients with non-endogenous
      depression, but was comparable with that observed in other medical
      disorders. Patients with CFS were not excessively hypochondriacal. We
      conclude that psychological disturbance is likely to be a consequence of,
      rather than an antecedent risk factor to the syndrome.<p>
      
      MCM: Notes that the CDC/Straus criteria for CFS are too restrictive in
      excluding patients with psychiatric disorders or on psychotropic
      medications (up to 95% of potential patients with CFS are excluded). 
      Presents a broader set of criteria and 48 patients meeting them, compared
      to controls with non-endogenous depression.  19 CFS pts had psych or
      neuropsych symptoms with 24 warranting a psych dx at some point in their
      illness (depression 22, panic attacks 5+1=6 or panic disorder 1+2=3,
      somatisization disorder 1.  "Depressive disorders of clinical severity
      were rare in the CFS sample"  with "significantly lower levels of
      neuroticism".  "Psychiatric morbidity in the CFS sample was less severe,
      in addition to being less prevalent, than in depressed patients."  "The
      illness behavior of patients with CFS is characterized by the strong
      conviction that they are physically ill..."  Patients with CFS do differ
      from general practice patients, however, principally in terms of their
      reluctance to accept psychological interpretations of their somatic
      symptoms."  "CFS patients are no more psychologically disturbed before
      the onset of their illness than members of the general population." 
      "...There is no evidence from our well-defined sample to support the
      hypothesis that CFS is a somatic presentation of an underlying
      psychological disorder [or that it] is a variant or expression of a
      depressive disorder.  Instead, our study supports the hypothesis that the
      current psychological symptoms of patients with CFS are a consequence of
      the disorder, rather than evidence of an antecedent vulnerability.<p>

Behan PO, Behan WMH, Bell EJ<br>
The postviral fatigue syndrome-- an analysis of the findings in 50 cases<br>
J Infection 10:211 Oct 1985<br>
Glasgow U<br>
MCM: Included 5 doctors, symptoms up to 22 years.  The primary symptom
      was gross fatigue made worse by exercise.  "The illness was severe, with
      a high morbidity and a disastrous effect on their lives.  Four of the
      doctors were unable to continue work.  
      No muscle weakness could be demonstrated.  Exercise by squeezing a rubber
      ball produced weakness lasting up to one hour.  All 20 had abnormal
      muscle biopsies: scattered necrotic fibers, increased Type II fibers,
      increased mitochondria at the periphery of the fibers, and occasional
      tubular inclusions.  Lymphocyte function was abnormal in 35/50 (70%).  In
      patients with chronic illness, it was helper/inducer (T4) lymphocytes
      which were significantly decreased.  18 had autoantibodies to smooth
      muscle.  Viral tests ere negative except 35 had positive Coxsackie B
      titers >512, 6 with specific IgM Abs.  
      The incidence is more common than ALS and as common as MS.  
      The results suggest "that the syndrome is due to the interaction or viral
      infection and immunological processes which ... result in abnormal muscle
      metabolism, especially on exercise..."<p>

Scheffers MK,Johnson R Jr,Dale JK, Straus SE..<br>
Attention & short-term memory in CFS pts: an event-related potential
      analysis.<br>
Neurology 1992 Sep;42(9):1667-75<br>
Cogn Neurophys Unit, Nat Inst o Neur D& Stroke NIH<br>
We recorded event-related brain potentials (ERPs) from 13 patients with
      chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS) and 13 matched normal controls. To assess
      attentional and memory deficits in CFS patients, we used a short-term
      memory task in which events occurred in different spatial locations and
      the patients made a rapid-response (RT) when a letter in a relevant
      location matched a letter in the prememorized set (Attention paradigm).
      Time-on-task effects on the ERP and behavioral measures were assessed
      over the 2 1/4-hour duration of this task. Both groups also performed a
      visual Oddball paradigm, with an RT, before and after the Attention
      paradigm. The patients' RTs were much more variable and, in nine of 13
      cases, slower than the mean RT of the controls in both paradigms. The
      patients' memory performance was not significantly different from that of
      the controls and there were no group differences in the overall
      amplitude, latency, or scalp distribution of the N1, P2, N2, or P300
      components of the ERP in either paradigm. The ERP and performance data
      from both paradigms suggest that perceptual, attentional, and short-term
      memory processes were unaffected in CFS patients and that the differences
      were limited to response-related processes.<p>
      
      MCM: Event-related potentials were normal for Attention and Oddball
      paradigms but in 9/13 CFS pts (all sporadic), response times were
      significantly slowed.  The P300 amplitudes were normal, unlike major
      depression pts who characteristically are deduced.  "Thus, although
      depression is a prevalent feature of CFS and is thought be some to play a
      role in the causation of CFS, the fact that our CFS pts showed normal
      P300 amplitudes suggests that depression in CFS pts does not arise from
      the same mechanism...  Future studies of CFS pts will have to use even
      more difficult cognitive and motor tasks than were used here, in order to
      demonstrate possible impairments."<p>

<hr>
<a href="index.html"><img src="http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/back.gif"></a>


</blockquote>
</body>
</html>
