<html>
<head>
<title>Frederick Stahl</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif>
<blockquote>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>What is it called...?</h1>
<hr>
<pre>
   "What is the condition called?" He looked at me through Coke-bottle
   glasses, his pupils mere dots like the bullseye target on a three
   hundred metre firing range.  I armed myself for the ordeal.

   "Chronc Fatigue Syndrome, CFS for short, although the English call it
   Myalgic Encephalomyelitis, or ME for short, and some Americans call it
   Chronic Fatigue Immune Dysfunction Syndrome, CFIDS for short. My own
   doctor is more flippant and calls it `Fucked Body Syndrome, FB...'"

   "Yes," he interrupted, his face taking on a vinegar expresson at my
   tasteless humour. "I'll write Chronic Fatigue."

   "No, that's different..."

   "It will do, now what are the symptoms?"

   I looked at the form which was a carry-over from the old IBM 80-column
   punched card days. "There isn't enough space in all those little
   boxes, you'll need a piece of paper."

   "Just tell me, and I'll be the judge of whether we need more paper."

   I shrugged: " Profound fatigue; sleep disturbance; mental confusion
   accompanied by short-term memory loss; febrile episodes; cognitive
   impairment; gastric disorders; myalgia; mood-swings; hunger pangs;
   bloatedness; loss of concentration; visual disturbances; tinnitus;
   arthralgia; general malaise--do you want to know about the variety in
   my bowel motions?"

   "I'd rather not." He began to fill in the squares. It looked like the
   first letters were P-S-Y-C-something. "For how long do you think the
   condition will continue?"

   "I don't know, but I've had it for so long that medical opinion is
   that, at my age, I will not return to useful employment."

   "How many doctors have told you that?"

   "How many do you need?"

   "One is enough."

   "One."

   He made a few more marks in the squares. "What sort of pension are you
   on?"

   "I'm not on a pension, I'm on disability insurance. I don't qualify
   for a pension."

   "So you're not disabled?"

   "Of course I'm disabled, I just told you the symptoms."

   "You're not on a pension, so therefore you're not disabled."

   "You mean I don't qualify?"

   "Precisely." He tore up the form.

   "You mean I don't get a half-price rail pass?"

   The railway clerk looked at me silently, willing me to make space for
   the next claimant. I took the hint.

   As I got up from the table, I tripped over the chair and fell into a
   deep void. I woke up with a start.

   It was then that I realised I hadn't told him about the vivid dreams.

   Frederick Stahl  Adelaide, Australia
</pre>
<hr>
<a href="personal.html"><img src="back.gif"></a>
</blockquote>
</body>
