<title>Julie Ann</title>
</head>

<body background=../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif>
<blockquote>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>People's Reactions</h1>
<hr>


Well, I finally applied for foodstamps today.  It was my one holdout.  I've been on SSI disability since May 1991 for CFIDS.  I don't know, I guess holding off on applying for the foodstamps was my way of denying that I was going to be "chonically" sick for an
unknown amount of time.  And here it is five and half years later and I'm still sick, so I finally broke down and applied.  Anyway, my case worker was amazingly sympathetic to CFIDS, so much so that it shocked me.  Most people, as you all know, don't really care
about us or they think we're just a bunch of whiners or something.  Well, this woman, who said I was the first person she ever met with CFIDS, looked me straight in the eye and told me she'd rather be dead than have CFIDS.  And that was after I'd only told her some of what we go through with this disease.  I was actually happy to get that reaction after having many of my own relatives treat me like a slothful deadbeat.  It makes me wonder what would happen if each of us could speak one on one with as many Senators and
Representatives and garner the same reaction.  Would it help?  Make a difference?  Maybe we all wouldn't be that tree falling in the forest anymore.  Maybe we could make a loud enough sound.
<p>
Julie Ann
<p>

The Riddle of the Cyberspider:  Once upon a midnight dreary, I climbed to the center of the Web, where I sat weak and weary.  Before me lay the great Cyberspider, who told me to solve her riddle before she would let me pass through the middle of the Web. "Ichabod, Alice, Marie, name the common bond that ties thee."  After much thought, I cocked my RPG and replied, "Off with your head, your Majesty."  And I pulled the trigger.<p>
Really cool webpage: http://members.aol.com/juliean130/private/mypage/webpicks.htm<br>

http://home.aol.com/juliean130<p>
