<html>
<head>
<title>Sufferers Views</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/wtile3.gif>
<h1 align=center>On Reading 'Osler's Web'</h1>
<h3 align=center>Some views of Sufferers (PWCs)</h3>
<hr>

"I am only on chapter 7 of this book, and I am in a state of shock."<p>

Claudia<p>

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>

"First, I would like to advise everyone who hasn't read this book, but plans
to, brace yourselves for an emotionally intensive experience."<p>

"I'm almost through the book now. I was
horrified that I may have inadvertently infected my whole family.  I was
also upset about the idea of brain damage.  I knew these things in the back
of my mind before reading the book, but I had been choosing to ignore them.
The book stirred up strong anger in me against all those who had a hand in
manipulating the public opinion about this illness from the beginning."<p>

"Like everything else about this confounded illness, I've learned to live
with what I'm finding out in  Osler's Web.  I just wasn't ready for the
overwhelming emotions I felt while reading the first part of this book."<p>

Cheryl<p>

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>

"Everytime I sit down to read it I get angry. Where else in
government do we allow 'civil servants' (and that's really all
the people are in the CDC/NIH/NIAID...glorified civil servants) to have
so much control over decisions?  Hopefully Congress will get
on top of them (figuratively and literally) now that the book
is out and they can get info from other docs, not just the
'chosen' at the CDC. Seriously, I think we need to get in there
and clean house. My anger is deeper than I can even express....
well, maybe deeper than is 'safe' to express might be a better
way to put it."<p>

Bonnie<p>

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>

"Osler's Web left me both shaken and stirred.  Shaken at the ineptitude of the
government and how their incompetence shaped the view of the medical
profession and society that so undermines our credibility."<p>

But my hope was stirred when I read of the solid research that is being done.
It was encouraging to read of the small number of researchers who understand
our problem and are doing their best to help us.  And I found the saga of the
downfall of researcher Elaine de Freitas to be nearly as tragic as our own.
<p>

"I think that anyone reading the book
would comprehend the scope of the catastrophe that we have lived, and are
living.  It is a huge step forward."<p>

Dragon<p>

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>

"I have just finished reading Osler's Web.  It has stirred so many
different emotions in me that I can't comprehend how I really feel now."<p>

"I need to reach some sort of peace-of-mind with
respect to all that I have read.  Right now I am very angry at our
government and most of the medical profession."<p>

"My daughter has been ill over seven years now (age 21) and is just about
ready to pack it in.  Her husband and I are the only thing that keeps
her alive since she has no "life."  She has become my life since her
illness."<p>

"I have to help lead our support group tonight and put on a happy face so
I can give hope to those other attendees who are less knowledgable than I
of the implications of what this illness does to one's life.  I don't
know if I can do it."<p>

"I admire
Hillary Johnson for all the hard work she did in exposing the system and
medical profession for their closed-mindedness.  I only hope that those
few doctors and researchers that were there then and now will continue to
further the search for an end to this nightmarish illness."<p>

Confused and alone,<p>

Arnette<p>

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>

"I am only half way through the book. I find myself reading it,like I
did 'The Gulag Archipelago' by Alexander Solzhenitsyn, a chapter at
a time. Then I must put it down for awhile and ponder...and
rage...and grieve...and wonder..." *Who* in the hell, *are* these
people?<p>

Are they truely scientists? Are they also, human beings? Does money
and politics and greed and power and ego...*really* come before
the health of this nation and this world? How...have we let it
become so? Where is our humanity?<p>

I see myself on every page of this book. I see my dearest friend, my
mother, my daughters...on every page of this book...I see all of you,
on every page of this book How...is it that these people have 'no
clue'?  Truely, everyone...HOW...is it that they have no clue? What is
*not* functioning in their minds, to *not* 'get it'? Is this explained
further in the book? Am I the only one wondering *how* learned
<huh> scientists can be so moronic?<p>

For those of you that have been reading this book...do you wonder:
if this is true regarding CFS...what *other* things are then true
about the CDC/NIH and the people that work for them? What other
diseases. What other illnesses are they trying to cover-up? What
other monies are they absconding with? Why are they *even*
employeed there? How can they be the mouth piece of National
Health...and make sweeping statements, without the back-up of hard
empirical data. Reasearch?<p>

I am angry and I am not going to take it any more"<p>

Katherine<p>

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>

I think a lot of the bad blood between long-term PWCs and the CDC has
to do more with the treatment they received in the '80s and until very
recently in the '90s.  If you are new to all of this, you might not
understand the vehemence of the anger.
<p>

I feel very lucky myself -- well, not exactly LUCKY -- if they had
known about the symptoms of slow-onset CFS, I might have been able to
get off work and rest much earlier than I did, and I might not be so
phenomenally disabled by CFS today.  But at least, when I fell so
dreadfully ill with the acute form of this DD (October 1994; no major
improvement since), it did not take long to get a CFS diagnosis --
although it was my students, not my gp, who suggested I see someone who
could tell if I had CFS or not.
<p>

There are people who have suffered dreadfully from the
disrespect, the contempt, that a small set of personnel at the CDC had
for CFS.  You can thank the CDC for both the lovely term "yuppie flu",
and also the less insulting, but still stunningly vapid, "chronic
fatigue syndrome".  Imagine trying desperately to get help for someone
who is terribly ill, or to get an answer to why you can no longer do
the work that you loved, and having people laugh at you.  The people
who were SUPPOSED to take an interest in the stories you were telling.
What is in the head of the CDC doctor who told PrimeTime Live that the
Incline Village outbreak was just "mass hysteria"?  That was RECENTLY.
<p>

David Bell's informative (and ironically, already a little out of date)
book, "The Doctor's Guide to Chronic Fatigue Syndrome" (1995), is
dedicated to Skye Kristina Dailor, born January 28, 1979.  Died
September 1, 1990, of a successful suicide attempt.  She was only 16.
She fell ill with chronic fatigue syndrome when she was 12-13.
<p>

It was months (perhaps a year) before she was diagnosed, by Dr. Bell.
When her previous doctors had not been able to find anything, they
began suggesting hypochondria; fear of school; fear of growing up.  But
her mother kept on, trying to find a diagnosis.  Until she found Dr.
Bell.
<p>

Because the CDC felt free to mock CFS, the media felt free to mock CFS.
Because the media felt free, many adults did -- including teachers,
administrators, and parents of other children.  And when the adults
did, so did the children.  A student, in the careless cruelty of
teenagers, had made fun of her that day for always faking illness.  She
went home and took her own life.
<p>

If you are unaware of the heartbreak and heartache that was caused when
the CDC refused to accept that there was an illness out there that THEY
DID NOT UNDERSTAND -- let me tell you this story is the tip of the
iceberg.
<p>

The very same people who mocked and disparaged and insulted people who
were seriously, severely ill, are STILL in charge of CFS research at
the CDC (don't know about the NIH).  Including one who still thinks
it's psychosomatic!
<p>

So the anger, the emotion, the hint of hyperbole you think you are
hearing is not coming from conspiracy theorists.  It is from those who
know the very real damage the CDC did in a very small window of time,
and are in no mood to hear more CYA behavior from bureaucrats.
<p>

Osler's Web IS, quite truthfully, far too pat a story.  There have to
be people at the CDC who are convinced of the seriousness of this
illness, or they would not have ranked it among the five top
(infectious?) diseases last year (we're up there with e.coli,
antibiotic-resistant pneumonia, the virulent strain of staph that
killed Jim Henson, and HIV) (I think I have the other four right).
Johnson was too convinced that this DEFINITELY is a virus -- jury's
still out on that -- and if so, that it definitely is a herpes-type
virus -- jury's out on that, too; could be a retrovirus like Coxsackie
and polio.  I do have to agree with that.
<p>

But the deliberate, unscientific, unprofessional cruelty displayed by
members of the CDC in the first years that physicians had hard evidence
of the seriousness of CFS -- THAT is well-established, and there is
plenty of evidence for it.
<p>

And it is THIS past history that leads many on this list to believe
Hillary Johnson when she argues that funds were DELIBERATELY diverted
-- not in any normal or innocent fashion (and having nothing to do with
the government's apparent ignorance of how universities and research
institutes operate) -- but deliberately, by people who thought the
disease was a silly hoax and the money a gift from dumb politicians too
easily influenced by hysterical constituents.
<p>

Johnson could well be wrong on this one.  And you are right -- Johnson
is not a scholar but a journalist, and journalists as a whole (and
politicians) seem unable to understand the concept of overhead or the
process by which research must proceed.  But there is enough evidence
of poor judgment and misplaced cultural bias on the part of the
individuals involved, that I for one won't know for sure until I see
the results of a well-conducted investigation.
<p>

One more source of the hostility (I am sorry this is like a
book!) -- the Ampligen trials.  Early on, a pharmaceutical company came
out with an intravenous drug called Ampligen, and PWCs were selected
for a double blind trial.  After it was over, the government announced
that there had been no statistically significant positive results, and
ended the project earlier than had been planned.  But most of the PWCs
receiving Ampligen believed it HAD been helpful -- it's just that the
researchers apparently didn't know how to measure the gain, perhaps.
They had been promised they could continue on it.  But the promise was
broken; Ampligen was denied.  The company went belly-up, and still owns
the patent, and up to this point has refused to release it to anyone
else.  There are a bunch of people out there still bitter on this one.
As it turns out, Ampligen may not have been the Magic Pill everyone
thought -- and if the PWCs had NMH, the improvement may have come
mainly from the addition of fluid intravenously several times a week
(which would explain why those on the so-called placebo felt better --
the saline solution was perhaps not a placebo after all!)
<p>

Well, talked too much here.  But I wanted to give this background,
because I think it is important to understand the history between the
CFS community and the government.
<p>

Mary Schweitzer

<h4 align=center>-----------------------------------------------------------------------</h4>


<h3>Osler's Web
Inside the Labyrinth of the Chronic Fatigue Syndrome Epidemic
by
Hillary Johnson
</h3>

If you're a physician or know some one who has Chronic Fatigue Syndrome and
you don't quite believe it  is a real illness,  Hillary Johnson's book will
provide concrete evidence that it does exist , it is real. To read this
book is to be the most currently informed the physician or patient can be,
yet.
<p>
In the style of Randy Shilts book about AIDS, And the Band Played On, Ms.
Johnson has methodically documented the illness beginning with the first
cluster of cases in Incline Village, Nevada  in 1984, and followed the
tragic trail of private doctors trying to do research on this disease who
have been  stymied at every turn by the Center for Disease Control (CDC)
and National Institutes of Health (NIH).
<p>
Even after fielding hundreds of phone call per day from physicians and
patients, CDC still refused to consider it a "real" illness.  It was
considered a psychiatric complaint.  It took funding by private
philanthropy, much of it by the Chronic Fatigue Immune Dysfunction Syndrome
(CFIDS) Foundation, a non-profit organization of over 25,000, mostly
patients, to find  viruses associated with this illness.  This book
documents over 80 articles from medical journals demonstrating the presence
of viruses, yet the CDC and NIH continue to misinform both physicians and
patients about the nature and severity of this illness.
<p>
The physicians who have rightly relied on the CDC for guidelines to treat
their patients will find they have a paradigm change after reading H.
Johnson's reports of research and cited articles in peer-reviewed journals.
In defense of physicians, they simply don't know what to do with these
patients.  They present with "normal" blood work and yet have symptoms that
range from brain tumors to sore lymph glands.  So many of their symptoms
were hard to quantify, aching all over, night sweats, dizziness,and
tinnitis.There are only about a dozen physicians in the United States who
have tackled the difficult task of synthesizing papers from various
journals and finding other like minded physicians and specializing in this
illness.

<p>
This has left thousands of patients fed up with the system or given up out
of sheer frustration.  Ms. Johnson documents this with many examples in her
book.  She also offers hope for the patient and plenty of information for
the doctor to have a clear vision of tests that will scientifically
document the illness.  Further, the names of many of the outstanding
practioners in the U.S. are mentioned. The patient will find explanations
for their myriad symptoms that accompany the disease as Johnson interviews
and follows patients through their misery.
<p>
As a direct result of this book and Hilary Johnson's role as investigator,
Congressman Jerold L. Nadler has last week begun hearings on the apparent
role of CDC and NIH in diverting funding specifically earmarked by Congress
for this disease to other uses. Stay tuned for the fallout from "Osler's
Web".
<p>
Reviewed by:<br>
Beck H. Spelce


