<h1 align=center><img src=../images/logos/space1.gif alt="Making Space"><br>
Making  Space</h1>
<blockquote><hr>
<br><br><br><br>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#who">What is Making Space</a>
<li><a href="mgsn01.html">Making Space in the News</a>
<li><a href="mgsn02.html">People in the News</a>
<li><a href="mgsn03.html">Workspace News</a>
<li><a href="poetcorn.html">Poetry Corner</a>
</ul><br><br><br><br>

<h2><a name="who">What is Making Space</h2></a>
Making Space exists to help schizophrenia sufferers and their families in the North of England. 
We are a charity run by people who have direct experience of schizophrenia. Our objectives are:
<p>
<UL>
<LI>To assist sufferers from schizophrenia resident in the North of England and their families by giving of advice and assistance so that they can cope more effectively with their problems.
<LI>To promote the development of community care facilities such as day centres, housing and employment schemes in order to support sufferers and their families in the community.
<LI>To advance to public understanding of the nature of schizophrenia and its attendant problems.
<LI>To develop self help groups of sufferers and their relatives throughout the region.
<LI>To encourage and undertake research into the causes and consequences of schizophrenic illnesses.
</UL>
<p>
Schizophrenia is a major illness, it affects one person in every hundred in all countries throughout the world. The term schizophrenia decribes a group of disorders which are identified by certain common symptoms, although these may not be the same for every sufferer. Symptoms include disturbance of thought and perception, inappropriate responses to people and situations, delusions and hallucinations. Sufferers may withdraw from others and usually show less will-power, drive and activity than they had previously.

<p>

People usually develop schizophrenia in their early twenties but it may occur at any time in a person's life. Some people suffer only one episode of the illness but for many sufferers and their families, schizophrenia is a life long concern.

<p>

All aspects of a person's life can be affected by schizophrenia. The effects of the illness may make it difficult for the sufferer to maintain employment or accommodation. They may experience difficulty in relating to others or in sharing feelings. For some sufferers, the symptoms may present so strongly that they are unable to take care of basic needs like food, sleep and cleanliness.

<p>

Caring for someone who suffers from schizophrenia can be a life long commitment for families. Coping with schizophrenia is hard - there are many barriers to overcome. Social stigma, prejudice and ignorance can isolate sufferers and their families. Poor services or a lack of access to help when it is needed can contribute to stress and a poor quality of life for sufferers and carers.
<p>
Everyone who has direct experience and knowledge of schizophrenia knows the need to improve services and help for sufferers and carers. This is why we exist.
<hr>
<H3>Achievements</H3>

Making space recognises the very different needs of sufferers and carers. We aim to achieve a wide range of provision in each local area. We manage:
<p>
<ul>
<li>12 Residential Homes
<li>1 Nursing Home
<li>26 Schemes of self contained, supported flats
<li>7 Day Centres
<li>2 Work Schemes
<li>17 Family Support Workers
</ul>



We also provide:

<ul>

<li>Self Help Groups throughout the North of England

<li>Help for individual sufferers and carers

<li>An annual holiday for sufferers

<li>Courses and Conferences about the medical and social aspects of schizophrenia

</ul>

<p>

Our projects are designed to reflect the wishes of our members and allow members the opportunity of being involved in their management.

<p>

All in all we provide high quality supported accommodation for 349 people. We are equally concerned about the day care, employment, and the need for people to be supported in their own homes.

<p>

We are now involved in 72 projects and have secured financial backing for these projects which exceeds £12 million sterling. We consider practical help a priority.

<p>

If you or a member of your family suffer from schizophrenia you may find the document <A HREF="whatis.htm">"What is Schizophrenia"</A> helpful. This is written particularly with the layperson in mind.

<p>

If you have found the information in these pages helpful and would like to know more about Making Space or have any other enquiries, please write to:
<p>
<hr>
<b>Making Space<br>
46 Allen Street, Warrington, Cheshire, England WA2 7JB<br>
Registered Charity No: 512907
<p>

<IMG SRC = "http://community-care.oaktree.co.uk/images/icons/phone.gif" align=middle hspace=10> 01925-571680</b>

<hr>
<ul>
<li><a href="news:alt.support.depression">Depression Support Newsgroup</a>
<li><a href="news:alt.support.schizophrenia">Schizophrenia Support Newsgroup</a>

<li><a href="../health/">Internet Health Resources</a>
<li><a href="../charity/">The Charity Pages Index</a>

<li><a href="http://www.community-care.org.uk/">Community-Care Front Page</a>
</ul>
</blockquote>
