<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Book List Page2</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  bgcolor=#fffbf0    text=#400040 >
<h1>General</h1>
<p>
<B>A Special Scar:</B> <B><I>Alison Wertheimer</I></B>
<p>
The experience of people bereaved by suicide. This volume will be of immense value to members of the caring professions, counsellors and survivors.<br>
"A well researched, competent and highly sensitive account of the pain and problems experienced by survivors of suicide" - Self and Society.
<p>
Routledge, 1994, 0-415-01763-7, £12.99
<hr>
<B>Audit in mental Health Services:</B> <B><I>Jenny Firth-Cozens</I></B>
<p>
This book takes practitioners in the mental health field through the various steps involved in successful clinical audit. Includes team and individual exercises to help select topics for audit, understand the methods most appropriate, set standards, understand the significance of outcomes and to bring about changes as a result. Invaluable for all mental health professionals and purchasers or provider managers interested in clinical audit and the measurement of quality.
<p>
LEA, 1994, 0-86377-311-7, pp112, £9.95
<hr>
<B>Beyond the Patient's Charter - Working with Users:</B> <B><I>Christine Hogg</I></B>
<p>
A practical guide to making the Patient's Charter work for patients. It is based on research on the experiences of users and the standards important to them. The research also considers how the patient's charters might be implemented to meet these standards, based on discussion with professionals and managers.
<p>
Health Rights, 1994, 1-871715-06-7, pp102, £8.50
<hr>
<B>MIND Logo Poster</B>
<p>
A3, 50p each, £3.50 for 10
<hr>
<B>Ethical Issues in Mental Health:</B> <B><I>Eds. Philip J. Barker & Steve Baldwin</I></B>
<p>
Explores key ethical issues of concern to mental health workers including the influence of therapeutic ideologies and the "scientific" status of care and treatment in general.
<p>
Chapman & Hall, 1991, 0-412-32950-6, pp205, £14.99
<hr>
<B>Equal Opportunities Poster</B>
<p>
A statement of how MIND implements its equal opportunities policy.
<p>
MIND, 1995, A3 £1.00 each, £8.00 per 10
<hr>
<B>MIND Guidelines for Journalists</B>
<p>
Guidelines for reporting on mental health issues in the media.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 50p
<hr>
<B>Madness: A Study Guide</B>
<p>
This booklet describes how madness has been viewed throughout the ages, before summarizing more recent moves towards community care and user empowerment.
<p>
BBC Education, 1992, pp32, £3.00
<hr>
<B>The Mental Health Handbook - The Complete Guide to Treatment Care & Resources:</B><br>
<B><I>Tony Drew & Madeline King</I></B>
<p>
A comprehensive and practical guide to "mental illness" and the help available. It describes the roles of GPs, psychiatrists and other health professionals and the help they can offer, covers care in the community with details of relevant support groups, explains what to do in a crisis, provides informatiom for carers and describes the rights of users of mental health services, relatives and carers.
<p>
Piatkus, 1995, 0-7499-14785, pp208, £9.99 (When ordering please state "DK")
<hr>
<B>Mental Health - The Role of the Approved Social Worker:</B> <B><I>Michael Sheppard</I></B>
<p>
Written by an experiences ASW, these research findings seek to develop and clarify the ASW's role.
<p>
JUSS, 1990, 0-907484-12-3, pp162, £7.50
<hr>
<B>MIND General Policy Poster</B>
<p>
A3, £1.00 each, £8.00 for 10
<hr>
<B>MIND Policy Pack</B>
<p>
This pack brings together MIND's policies on key topics in mental health, including employment, discrimination, user involvement, patients' money and housing. Recommendations are made concerning community services, closure of all psychiatric hospitals, and service provision for ethnic minorities.
<p>
MIND, 1993, 1-874690-03-0, £8.50 to small voluntary organisations & user groups, £11.50 all others.
<hr>
<B>MIND Practice Guidelines Pack</B>
<p>
A set of MIND documents designed to enable groups providing mental health services to achieve a consistent form of practice and level of quality. Contents include principles of confidentiality, operational policies and procedures, setting up housing with care and support, financial management, complaints and procedure checklist, strategic planning, fundraising and good practice in employment.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 1-874690-19-7, £25.00
<hr>
<B>MIND Quality Guidelines Pack</B>
<p>
A resource pack designed for local voluntary mental health groups involved in development, planning and service provision. Different booklets discuss basic principles, service context, a model for quality, advocacy, befriending and counselling, service users meetings, outcome measures, service involvement and social clubs, drop-ins, self-help groups and day centres. The pressure that is being put on local voluntary organisations to become major service providers, to tender for contracts, to manage new budgets and become employers on a grand scale makes materials such as these particularly valuable.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 1-874690-20-0, £25.00
<hr>
<B>Preventing Mental Illness:</B> <B><I>Dr. Jennifer Newton</I></B>
<p>
Jennifer Newton reviews the research literature relating to prevention, focusing on depression and schizophrenia.
<p>
Routledge, 1988, 0-415-03902-9, pp275, £12.99
<hr>
<B>Psychiatric Patient Violence - Risk and Response:</B> <B><I>Ed. John Crichton</I></B>
<p>
This book, which grew out of a public enquiry into the death of occupational therapist, Georgina Robinson, brings together leading academics and professionals to provide a comprehensive review of psychiatric patient violence and its management.
<p>
Duckworth, 1995, 0-7156-2661-2, pp160, hardback, £30.00
<hr>
<B>Recovery from Schizophrenia:</B> <B><I>Richard Warner</I></B>
<p>
This book demonstrates how political, economic and labour market forces shape social responses to people diagnosed mentally ill, mould psychiatric treatment philosophy and influence the onset and course of schizophrenia.
<p>
Routledge, 1994, 0-415-09261-2, pp336, £18.99
<hr>
<B>A Sociology of Mental Health and Illness:</B> <B><I>David Pilgim and Anne Rogers</I></B>
<p>
This book explores the sociological issues of race, gender and age in relation to mental health and offers an analysis which has relevance to students of sociology and mental health professionals.
<p>
Open University Press, 1993, 0-335-19013-8, pp198, £12.99
<hr>
<B>Values for Change</B>
<p>
This is the report from a conference on secure psychiatric provision held by MIND and ISTD. The conference focused on how to obtain a better deal for those detained in hospital for treatment. This report contains nearly all the papers presented at the conference and notes on many of the workshops.
<p>
ISTD, 1994, 0-901541-31-1, pp48, £5.00
<hr>
<B>What is MIND?</B>
<p>
Outlining what MIND is, its activities, structure and the benefits to be gained from being a MIND member, this leaflet is an excellent introduction to the organization.
<p>
£5.00 for 100, £40.00 for 1000
<hr>
<B>Winter Blues:</B> <B><I>Norman E. Rosenthal</I></B>
<p>
A survival kit for anyone who suffers from the winter blues. This book describes the many dimensions of seasonal affective disorder and a variety of effective strategies. It includes a comprehensive list of SAD resource centres.
<p>
Guilford Press, 1994, 0-89862-149-6, pp326, £9.95
<hr>
<B>Working With Mental Illness:</B> <B><I>Derek Tilbury</I></B>
<p>
This book focuses on long-term social work with sufferers of mental distress. It explores direct work with the sufferer, work within the clinical team and work with families. Offers practical guidelines in a hitherto neglected field.
<p>
Macmillan, 1993, 0-333-58535-6, pp140, £9.99
<hr>
<H2>Grassroots Perspectives</H2>
<p>
<B>Accepting Voices:</B> <B><I>Eds. Prof. Marius Romme and Sandra Escher</I></B>
<p>
In this excellent piece of research, 13 people describe their experience of hearing voices. "Accepting Voices" illustrates that many people hear voices, that not everyone has recourse to psychiatry, but that there are ways of coping that enable a people to come to terms with their experience. The book focuses on techniques to deal with the voices, emphasizing that personal growth should be stimulated rather than inhibited.
<p>
MIND, 1993, 1-874690-13-8, pp261, £13.99
<hr>
<B>Born a Number:</B> <B><I>Len Harding</I></B>
<p>
A compelling account of a journey through children;s homes and Rampton Special Hospital to a pioneering rehabilitation centre and finally a happy life in the community.
<p>
MIND, 1986, 0-900557-71-0, pp94, £2.00
<hr>
<B>The Catch of Hands:</B> <B><I>Benedicta Leigh</I></B>
<p>
Winner of the 1991 "MIND Book of the Year Award", this autobiography evocatively depicts the life of Benedicta Leigh. Some of the most powerful sections detail her traumatic time spent within the psychiatric system.
<p>
Virago, 1991, 1-85381-191-2, pp186, £5.99
<hr>
<B>Citizen Involvement - A Practical Guide for Change:</B> <B><I>Peter Beresford and Suzy Croft</I></B>
<p>
This book draws on a study of initiatives such as consultation schemes, housing policies, education and community development. It examines the philosophy of participation whilst always emphasizing the practical issues of what works and what doesn't work.
<p>
Macmillan, 1993, 0-333-48301-4, pp296, £9.99
<hr>
<B>Experiencing Psychiatry - Users' Views of Services:</B> <B><I>Anne Rogers, David Pilgrim & Ron Lacy</I></B>
<p>
Drawing on the data obtained through the People First Survey this book describes the experiences and views of people who use mental health services. "Experiencing Psychiatry" is a unique document which should be read by anyone interested in mental health services.
<p>
MIND/Macmillan, 1993, 0-333-45259-3, pp205, £11.99
<hr>
<B>Getting Involved - A Practical Manual:</B> <B><I>Suzy Croft and Peter Beresford</I></B>
<p>
This useful guide is designed for people who want more control over their lives and more to say in the organisations and services which affect them. A how-to-do-it guide, written for anyone who wishs to wmpower themselves.
<p>
Open Services project, 1993, 0-9517554-1-2, pp73, £5.95
<hr>
<B>The MIND Guide to Advocacy in Mental Health - Empowerment in Action</B>
<p>
A clear introduction to the main forms of advocacy, detailing their history, what can be achieved and which organizations can be contacted.
<p>
MIND, 1992, 0-900557-94-X, pp45, £5.00
<hr>
<B>The Monkey's Uncle:</B> <B><I>Jenny Diski</I></B>
<p>
The story of Charlotte, who finds that part of her has talen off to an alternative wonderland - a bizarre internal world where she makes friends with Jenny, a highly-opinionated orang-utan, converses with Marx, Freud and Darwin, and observes Robert Fitzroy, the captain of the Beagle and a amn whose obsessions strangly mirror Charlotte's own.
<p>
Phoenix, 1994, 1-85799-154-0, pp258, £5.99
<hr>
<B>On Our Own:</B> <B><I>Judi Chamberlin</I></B>
<p>
A classic of the American survivors' movement making a strong case for patient-controlled mental health services.
<p>
MIND, 1988, 0-900557-83-4, pp245, £5.99
<hr>
<B>Purchasing Mental Health Services - Self-Help Alternatives:</B> <B><I>Vivien Lindow</I></B>
<p>
Explores purchasing issues and gives examples of community and rehabilitation services provided by users, for users. Contents include: mental health services in the community, why purchase self-help alternative services?, novel features, examples of projects and contracting issues.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 1-874690-22-7, pp33, £6.00
<hr>
<B>Self-Help Alternatives to Mental Health Services:</B> <B><I>Vivien Lindow</I></B>
<p>
Makes information and ideas about self-help alternatives accessible to UK service users and draws together the experiences of service users who have created self-help services. Contents include: organizing user-controlled alternatives, members, finances and examples of projects.
<p>
MIND, 1994, 1-874690-21-9, pp76, £7.00
<hr>
<B>Self-Harm - Perspectives from Personal Experience:</B> <B><I>Ed. Louise Roxanne Pembroke</I></B>
<p>
Public awareness of self-harm is growing and this book is intended to aid awareness of the problems of people who self-harm and look beyond the idea that these people are merely attention seekers. It is a moving collection of personal accounts of people who self-harm. An important text for anyone who has been through self-harm and for those who work with them.
<p>
Survivors Speak Out, 1994, 1-898002-02-9, pp71, £6.00
<hr>
<B>Stopovers On My Way Home From Mars:</B> <B><I>Mary O'Hagan</I></B>
<p>
This is a survivor's reflective journey through her experiences in the mental health system.
<p>
SSO, 1993, 1-898002-0-11, pp103, £6.50<br>Available to survivors at £4.00 from: SSO 34 Osnaburgh Street, London NW1 3ND
<hr>
<B>Under the Asylum Tree - Survivors Poetry</B>
<p>
This new illustrated anthology of poetry contains the work of 95 survivor poets and visual artists. It replaces the first anthology of poetry which was short-listed for the MIND Book Award 1992.
<p>
SSO, 1995, 1-874595-0-11, pp208, £7.95
<hr>
