</head></title>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/cool_til.gif>
<h3><a name="poems">Poems</a></h3>
<pre><b>Quetzal</b>

Mexico was a dream
drenched with light
in the whitewashed glare
of moon, sun-bright.

In an alien land
I was cast, as a stone,
in a land less alien
than my land at home.

Wandering on the wind,
catching ghosts, lost as me
in cenotes of guilt
and Mayan ruins by the sea.

Nightmare in Guate
with nowhere else to run,
I saw a quetzal in a cloud-forest
escape from the guns.


<b>A Dream</b>

From dusk to dawn
is the eternal time
as I drift from good
to bad from the start
of a forgotten dream
where summer nights
were luminous with moonlight
I saw the evening star.

Wandering throughout the
empty streets of a seaside town
down towards a
beautiful burial ground
through the quiet walks
between the graves
I heard the night dew
glistening on my skin.

                   Mark Allcock


<b>She</b>

Will she ever set me free
this voice that is a part of me?
It's no use to struggle and fight
once she's got a grip, she holds on tight.
She twists and tangles up my brain,
She's in control, no good to complain.
Why does she come?
Why does she go?
She makes me feel everyone's my foe.
She makes me hurt myself and others,
to try to escape under the covers.
I feel her close beside me at all times of day;
She makes me sad, she makes me low.
Oh, Dear God please make her go!
I did not invite her,
I wish to make that plain
Yet, she comes here to confuse me
again and again...

                                 Mary Mullen


<b>The Wind and the Kali Yoga</b>

Ships encircle a darkening sea,
Storms are sent to you and me.
Up from the depths a throng shall rise
Blackening, engulfing the bluest skies
"Why?" She asks.

A rift is rent, your time is spent.
The sea of men is clothed with
embarrassment.
As it faces the power that embraces
It will throw you about, as you shout.
It will swell and well the tide
of your fortune.
"When will it end?" She asks.

Tossing and turning, churning, no
learning
Smashing, crashing, thrashing and lashing
Until it has caught and
Brought you to its eerie grave.
"Let's rest." She says.

                                 Cheryl Walker


<b>Listen</b>

Listen
To the wind
Outside rattling the bones
of skeletal trees

Listen
To the rain
Beating against the windows
Tracing a path of tears
Down the hard glass

Listen
To your own words
Whispered softly
In the long silences
The other side of midnight
Forgiving yourself
And others
Again and again.

             Martin Swansy


<b>The Spirit Within</b>

Some time ago, I lived life, as you do.
But soon discovered it was so 
untrue,
I experienced voices in my head
That laid me up in bed.

Once I had awoke, the world looked 
so different,
Than seen before,
For God had opened up the door,
That once was locked within my 
heart.

Now his Spirit guides the way,
And shows one, how to pray,
This may seem bizarre, to none-
believers
A religious fanatic is how you may
percieve us,
But true enough the voices have 
ceased,
Now my spirit has increasee.
An inner voice does call, for I've
found Jesus -
Who is in us all.

                        Susan Clarkson

</pre>
