<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Autism</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><B>Copyright, Plenum Publishing Corporation</B><P>Letter to the editor<H2>Stealth Virus Isolated from an Autistic Child</H2><P>W. John Martin<HR><P>Molecular probe and viral culture-based assays on patients diagnosed as having the chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS) led to the identification of a novel class of cytopathic viruses termed "stealth viruses" (Martin, 1992; Martin, Zeng, Ahmed, & Roy, 1994).  These viruses appear to have been derived from herpesviruses (and possibly from other viruses), by a process of deletion of genes coding viral components normally responsible for evoking antiviral inflammatory responses.  Typically these viruses produce a foamy cell cytopathic effect (CPE) in cells from multiple species.  They do not show normal reactivity with conventional viral typing antisera and often show aberrant responses in low stringency molecular probe-based assays, including the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).  Several stealth viruses have been shown to induce chronic non-inflammatory neurological disease in animals (unpublished data).<P>Although the prototype stealth virus was isolated from a CFS patient, a closely related virus was derived from the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) of a patient with an acute encephalopathy following a 4-year history of a bipolar psychosis (Martin et al., 1994).  Other stealth virus culture-positive patients have had encephalopathies of varying severity (unpublished).  These clinical cases suggest that CFS may represent part of a broad spectrum of neurological and neuropsychiatric manifestations of a persisitent stealth viral illness.  I wish to report the repeated isolation of a stealth virus from an autistic child and to suggest that at least some cases of autism may be attributed to a stealth virus encephalopathy.<P>A 10-year-old boy (I.G.) was initially identified as socially withdrawn at 1 year of age.  Speech did not begin until age 3 and was limited and inappropriate.  He was diagnosed as autistic at age 4 and has received specialized schooling since then.  His educators described him as a severe case of classical autism with lack of interpersonal relationships, frequent stemming and, ritualistic, aggressive behavior.  His speech is limited to echolalia; he displays signs of hypersensitivity to loud or unusual noises; and appears to be photophobic.  He was institutionalized at age 9 because of hitting, biting, and other deviant behavior.<P>With Institutional Review Board approval and signed parental  informed consent, blood was obtained in 1992 and again in 1994.  The blood was cultured on human fibroblasts as described in detail elsewhere (Martin et al., 1994).  A strong CPE was noted on each occasion.  The CPE was characterized by dispersed vacuolated foamy cells with syncytia formation and was typical of that seen with stealth viruses.  The CPE was also readily transferable to animal cell lines.  Molecular characterization of the viral isolates is in progress.<P>Repeated culturing of a stealth virus from an autistic patient does not establish that the virus is responsible for the patient's illness.  Symptoms of autism are, however, consistent with impaired neurosensory functions due to a persistent viral infection and previous attempts to demonstrate viruses in such patients may have failed to detect stealth viruses.  Further efforts are underway to validate these preliminary findings.<P><B>Footnote</B><P>I thank Sally Saenz for her efforts in providing counseling to the patient and parents.  Khalid Ahmed provided excellent technical assistance with extablishing and maintaining the cultures.<P><B>References</B><P>1.  Martin, W. J. (1992).  Viral infection in CFS patients.  In B. Hyde (ED.), The Clinical and Scientific Basis of Myalgic Encephalomyelitis / Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (pp. 325-327).  Ottawa: Nightingale Research Foundation.<P>2.  Martin, W. J., Zeng, L. C., Ahmed, K., & Roy, M. (1994). Cytomegalovirus-related sequences in an atypical cytopathic virus repeatedly isolated from a patient with the chronic fatigue syndrome.  American Journal of Pathology, 145, 440-451.<HR><A HREF="Publications.html"><IMG SRC="back.gif"></A></HTML>   


