<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>CAP</TITLE></HEAD><B>Copyright, College of American Pathologists</B><H2>Stealth Viruses as Neuropathogens</H2><P>W. John Martin M.D., Ph.D.<HR>I have used molecular and tissue culture techniques during the last eight years to search for a possible viral etiology of complex neurological diseases including the chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS).  This work led to the identification of a novel class of cytopathic viruses that have been designated "stealth viruses" because they can induce disease without evoking an inflammatory response.  A prototype stealth virus, repeatedly cultured from a CFS patient, is described in a recently published article in the American Journal of Pathology.(1) The following article outlines methods for detecting stealth viruses.  It also reviews findings that suggest that CFS may be part of a spectrum of infectious neurologic and psychiatric illnesses attributed to stealth virus encephalopathy.<P><B>PCR Assays</B><P> Evidence for atypical viral infections in patients with CFS and other neurological diseases was originally obtained using low stringency polymerase chain reaction (PCR).(2)  By reducing the temperatures for both primer annealing and for hybridization of labeled probes, conditions were established such that a set of cytomegalovirus (CMV) UL83  gene reactive primers would yield positive results, not only with CMV, but also with HSV, EBV, VZV and HHV-6.(2)  Using these low stringency conditions, DNA from blood of approximately 30% of CFS patients gave weak positive responses, whereas DNA from the blood of laboratory personnel were uniformly negative.(2,3) Many CFS patients also gave low, but detectable, responses using primers designed to amplify the tax gene of human T lymphocytotrophic viruses (HTLV).  The potential significance of the marginal responses seen in CFS patients became clearer with the findings of positive PCR responses on cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) samples from two interesting neurological cases. One was a 19 year old boy who three years previously, had suffered extensive brain damage from what had been considered a missed diagnosis of HSV encephalitis.  His CSF had shown no cellular reaction at the time of his initial illness.  Only after extensive and permament brain damage had occurred was Acyclovir administered. When tested in my laboratory, his CSF gave a strong PCR reaction with both the tax gene and the "generic" herpesvirus primers. His CSF was negative, however, using high stringency PCR assays for HSV, CMV and HHV-6. Similar PCR findings were found on the CSF from a 6 month old infant with unexplained seizures and delayed neurological development.  Again, in this infant, there were no other laboratory marker to indicate a probable brain infection.  Additional evidence was soon obtained which more decisively linked a positive PCR result with an atypical viral infection within the brain.  In particular, a low stringency PCR assay was positive on a stereotactic brain biopsy from a dysphasic patient in whom extensive periventricular lesions were identified by magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).  The biopsy showed only mild gliosis without evidence of any inflammatory reaction.  By electron microscopy, however, abundant herpes-like viral particles were seen within the cytoplasm of glial cells.<P><B>Cultures</B><P>Early efforts to culture viruses from CFS patients on various cell lines occasionally provided evidence for a limited cytopathic effect (CPE).  The CPE was best observed in long term fibroblast cell lines, often developing after 1-2 months of culture.  The CPE was transient and often overshadowed by a general deterioration of the cultures.  Attempts to passage the putative viral CPE were generally unsuccessful.  The recipient cultures, however, did exhibit subtle signs of reduced vitality and metabolic activity.  These observations suggested that one or more components in the culture may be competing with virus expression.  To reduce the levels of any possible "inhibitors" and to help overcome the reduced vitality of the cultures, the frequency of refeeding the cultures was increased and an enriched medium (medium 199) with 7% fetal cell serum (FCS) was used in place of Dubecco's medium with 2% FCS. These changes promoted the expression of the CPE and were used to isolate the prototype stealth virus from an HTLV tax  gene PCR positive healthcare worker (D.W.). This patient developed CFS following an acute encephalitis-like illness in July 1990.(1)<P><B>Prototype Stealth Virus</B><P>Human fibroblasts co-cultured with leukocytes from patient D.W., developed into enlarged, rounded cells with prominent syncytia. The cytoplasm appeared to be vacuolated giving the appearance of foamy cells. Although, somewhat suggestive of CMV, the infected cells did not stain with antisera specific for the major immediate-early antigen of human CMV. Moreover,  the CPE was readily transferable to cells of multiple species, whereas that of CMV is largely restricted to human cells. Additional studies showed a lack of immunologic reactivity with other CMV specific antibodies as well as antibodies specific for HSV, VZV and HHV-6/HHV-7. PCR assays for these viruses were also negative. On the otherhand, PCR assays using the HTLV tax  gene primers gave two well defined products. Sequencing of one of the PCR products (GenBank accession # U09212)  identified a region of partial sequence homology to the UL34  gene of CMV. The sequence of the other PCR product (GenBank Accession # U09213) was suggestive of a possible herpesvirus origin, but could not be aligned with any of the known herpesviruses. Viral DNA has been cloned and an overall relatedness to CMV has been confirmed.  The virus lacks the major immediate-early gene of CMV, as well as other genes thought to be involved in evoking an inflammatory reaction.  A lack of immunogens for host cellular immune defenses was also suggested by the absence of a cellular response in a virus positive CSF sample obtained from the patient in 1991.<P><B>Stealth Viruses as Neuropathogens</B><P>Approximately 1,000 cultures performed during the last eight years have provided evidence of a cytopathic effect related to that of the prototype stealth virus.  Molecular studies have been performed on several of the strongly positive cultures obtained from patients with CFS and with other neurological and psychiatric diseases.  Both by PCR and by cross-hybridization, it is apparent that there is considerable molecular heterogeneity between isolates.  At present, therefore, the most useful defining characteristic of a stealth virus is the distinctive foamy cell CPE inducible in cultures of cells from multiple species.  The infected cells do not give typical reactions with conventional viral typing antisera and often show aberrant responses in low-stringency molecular probe-based assays, including PCR.(4)  It appears that, as a group, stealth viruses have been derived from herpesviruses (and possibly other viruses) by a process of major gene deletions and mutations.  These genetic changes presumably account for the lack of an appreciable inflammatory response and for the wide host range of infectable cells.<P><B>Stealth Virus Encephalopathy</B><P>With the development of sensitive tissue culture methods, samples of blood and CSF were requested from neurologists, psychiatrists, rheumatologists and physicians specializing in CFS. Interviews were arranged with a number of patients from whom strongly positive cultures were obtained. From these interviews, it soon became apparent that many of the culture positive patients shared common clinical features in spite of differing diagnostic labels. At one extreme were the patients classified as having CFS.  Many of these patients had experienced difficulty in finding physicians even willing to concede a possible organic basis for their disease. Particularly when accompanied by depression, the patients are often accused of contributing to their own illness through "psychosomatic" mechanisms. Moreover some clinicians felt strongly that any discussion of a possible viral involvement would simply discourage the patient's own efforts to "work off" their disease. In reality, the diagnostic term "chronic fatigue" was obscuring the overwhelming evidence that many of the patients had accompanying mood, cognitive, and neurosomatic symptoms indicative of brain dysfunction.<P>A somewhat different situation existed when medical specialists were faced with patients with highly complex neurological-immunological-rheumatological diseases. Such patients were often passed from one "baffled" specialist to another, with no one having the confidence to explain the patient's overall illness.  While a chronic brain infection was sometimes considered to be a possibility, it was typically dismissed in the absence of supporting CSF findings.  Loose diagnostic terms were often used including the prefixes "possible" or "atypical" before diagnoses such as lupus cerebritis, Parkinson's, multiple sclerosis, psychosis, Alzheimer's, myeloradiculopathy, and encephalopathy.  A history of prior or current drug or alcohol abuse would often be suggested to help explain unusual features.  Many of these patients experienced the fatigue, mood changes, aches and pains, insomnia, and cognitive dysfunctions seen in patients labeled as having CFS or FMS.<P>Even without evidence of positive viral cultures, the clinical overlap between CFS, FMS, depression, anxiety disorder, psychosis, neurological diseases, etc., suggested a <A NAME="spectrum"></A><A HREF="Questions.html#spectrum2">spectrum</A> of illnesses involving the brain possibly with a common underlying pathogenesis.  The positive viral cultures highlighted the possibility that at least a proportion of each of these syndromes could be simply different manifestations of an underlying stealth virus encephalopathy.  <P>According to this paradigm, certain cases of CFS are included within a spectrum of infectious neurological and psychiatric illness characterized by atypical responses to normal sensory input into the brain.  The predominant clinical manifestation could vary simply depending on the actual location and severity of the viral infection.  Rather than attempt to segregate fatigue, pain, mood, and cognitive disorders into discrete, unrelated entities, the possibility exists of overlapping multifaceted expressions of a noninflammatory brain infection.  The disease associations would extend to various illnesses sometimes classified as neurosomatic (4), for example, irritable bowel syndrome, and may even extend beyond that.  For example, by Centers for Disease Control and Prevention criteria, CFS is excluded in any patient diagnosed as having multiple sclerosis.(5)  Again, this segregation obscures the symptoms common to CFS and MS.  It is not unreasonable to suggest that a stealth virus could trigger the autoimmune component in at least some cases of MS.<P>While individual and family case histories will be presented in detail elsewhere, many culture-positive patients have been observed whose clinical histories support the abovementioned paradigm.  For example, patient T.R. was first identified as culture- and PCR-positive in 1988.  She has been diagnosed as having multiple sclerosis, systemic lupus erythematosus, autoimmune myopathy, cluster headaches, and pseudotumor cerebri.  Patient B.H. was diagnosed initially as schizophrenic at age 19.  The diagnosis was changed to bipolar manic depressive illness with delusions.  Four years into her illness, she experienced a near-fatal encephalopathy with cardiac arrest and has remained in a vegetative state for nearly five years.  The viral isolate from her CSF is moleculary related to that of the prototype stealth virus obtained from patient D.W.  The patient from whom the stereotactic brain biopsy had been obtained has been confined to a nursing home because of tetraparesis and aphasia.  In Family W both husband and wife were diagnosed as CFS.  The wife's mother is wheelchair-bound because of an atypical Parkinson's disease while the son has been diagnosed as schizophrenic.  In Family P there is both an autistic and a schizophrenic son.  In Family G there is a father with CFS and an autistic son.(6)  All of these individuals have shown positive stealth viral cultures and have been provisionally diagnosed as having stealth virus encephalopathy.  This term has helped to defuse some of the confrontations between CFS patients and their physicians and between neurologists, psychiatrists, and rheumatologists regarding the potential of a hitherto unrecognized disease process affecting the brain.<P><B>Non-neurologic manifestations</B><P>Although the focus of this article has been on neurological infections, liver, thyroid, muscle, dermatological, salivary gland, gastrointestinal and genitourinary diseases have been also been seen in culture positive patients and some of their family members. Not all of these patients have overt signs of neurological disease, while some have evidence of auto-immunity, including systemic lupus erythematosus, Hashimoto's thryoiditis, vitiligo, dermatomyositis and Sjogren's disease. Virus infections have long been considered a potential trigger of auto-immunity and evidence for both entities, rather than one entity excluding the presence of the other might be expected.<P><B>Asymptomatic Infections</B><P>Culture positive asymptomatic individuals have been identified both among family members of CFS patients and from randomly selected volunteers. While this has presented a stumbling block in efforts to obtain research funding, it does not invalidate the concept of stealth virus encephalopathy. First, a lack of symptoms does not necessarily imply absence of disease since not all disease processes produce symptoms. Second, patients show varying levels of acceptance of various physical and mental discomforts.  Third,  as noted above, stealth viruses are molecularly heterogeneous and differences may well exist in neurotropism and/or neurovirulence of the viruses isolated from symptomatic and asymptomatic individuals. Fourth, the familial clustering of neurologic and neuropsychiatric diseases is consistent with an infectious disease process. Fifth, other investigators have noted what appeared to be atypical viruses in CSF of patients with neurologic and psychiatric diseases.(5-7) Sixth, the stealth viral isolate from patient D.W. induces disease in animals.  Seventh, it is unfair to the many patients afflicted with these illnesses to discount the culture findings and, in particular, the detection of virus within CSF and within glial cells from patients with unmistakable neurological diseases.<P><B>Testing the Hypothesis</B><P>The most direct approach to evaluating the possible role of stealth viruses in neurological and neuropsychiatric diseases is to determine the effects of antiviral therapy in culture-positive symptomatic patients.  Stealth viral isolates are being used to develop and to evaluate antiviral therapies in tissue cultures.  The results will be extended to an animal model and then to seriously ill patients.  In the interim, the potential of noninflammatory stealth viral infections as a cause of both mild and severe neuropsychatric disease should be considered.<P><B>References</B><P>1. Martin WJ, Zeng LC, Ahmed K Roy M. Cytomegalovirus-related sequence in an atypical cytopathic virus repeatedly isolated from a patient with chronic fatigue syndrome. Am J Path. 1994;145:440-451.<P>2. Martin WJ.  Detection of viral related sequences in CFS patients using the polymerase chain reaction. In: Hyde B. ed. The Clinical and Scientific Basis of Myalgic Encephalomyelitis/Chronic Fatigue Syndrome. Ottawa, Nightingale Research Found.1992;325-327<P>3. Martin WJ.  Viral infection in CFS patients. In: Hyde B. ed. The Clinical and Scientific Basis of Myalgic Encephalomyelitis/Chronic Fatigue Syndrome. Ottawa, Nightingale Research Found.1992;325-327.<P>4. Martin WJ. Isolation of a stealth virus from a child with autism. J Autism Develop Disorders (in press).<P>5. Tyrrell DAJ, Parry RP, Crow TJ, Johnstone E, Ferrier IN. Possible virus in schizophrenia and some neurological disorders. Lancet 1979;i:839-41.<P>6. Mitchell DN, Porterfield JS, Micheletti R, Lange LS, Goswami KKA, Taylor P, Jacobs JP, Hockley DJ, Salsbury AJ. Isolation of an infectious agent from bone-marrows of patients with
multiple sclerosis. Lancet 1978;ii:387-391.<P>7. Melnick JL, Seidel E, Inoue YK, Nishibe Y. Isolation of virus from the spinal fluid of three patients with multiple sclerosis and one with amytrophic lateral sclerosis. Lancet 1982;i:830-3.<P>8. Additional details of culture methods can be obtained by writing to  Dr. WJ Martin at USC School of Medicine, 1840 N. Soto St. Los Angeles CA 90033.<P> Dr. Martin is professor of pathology, USC School of Medicine and Director of USC Infectious Diseases and Molecular Pathology Laboratories within USC Clinical Laboratories. He is the Director of the CAP Molecular Pathology Practicum.<HR><A HREF="Publications.html"><IMG SRC="back.gif"></A></HTML>

