<title>Mary Schweitzer</title>
</head>
<body background=../images/backgrounds/map.gif>
<blockquote>
<b>LETTER OF INTEREST-MARY SCHWEITZER</b>
<p>
<i>Date: 96-07-16 14:17:10 EDT</i>
<p>
To the ICC Committee and the WECAN membership:
<p> 
I would be honored at the opportunity to serve as a patient
representative to the CFS-ICC.
<p>
My life in academia as a teacher, scholar, and participant in
professional organizations has  prepared me well to serve my fellow
PWCs as their representative.  I have both professional training and
hard experience in analyzing and articulating problems; reading both
quantitative and qualitative professional literature to assess the
state of current scholarship in an area;  translating what I have read
into English for other scholars; explaining complex issues to college
students (and hence laypersons).  As a historian, I was trained to be
able to read personal accounts and pull together the general from the
specific, to weave as accurate a depiction as possible.  My graduate
training in statistics and economics will also come in handy.
<p>
Although I have never served on a government committee, I have
participated in the usual round of departmental and university
committees; suburban volunteer groups; editorships; and committees in
professional organizations.  My father has a Ph.D. in economic
forecasting and often testified before Congress.  My husband was a
financial economist with the Comptroller of the Currency in the
mid-1970s; he has a Ph.D. in economics with a specialty in financial
regulation, and often consults for the government or serves on task
forces in his field.   Second-hand, I do know a great deal about how
these committees function.
<p>
I have been diagnosed with chronic fatigue syndrome, and I am very
seriously ill.  However, I have found that I can function well in
short-term settings with physical accommodations.  Since having to go
on leave from my position at Villanova, I have attended and presented
papers at four national conferences and the consensus was that it all
went very well (although I crashed when I got back home!)   To put it
bluntly, I do not believe a non-PWC can be in a room with me for five
minutes without sensing the tragedy of our illness; the loss of my
former productivity  and hence of the productive capabilities of us
all.  I dont think it would hurt for the other members of the ICC to
see this!
<p>
My parents were born and raised in Appalachia, but were able to rise
through education.  I have seen and lived with poverty  with my
relatives in Appalachia, and with Hispanic, Samoan, African-American,
and Anglo friends while working for solutions to the problems of
poverty in cities.  My cousins son in West Virginia had to join the
reserves to afford to go to college, but was called up immediately for
service in the Persian Gulf War.  When he came back home, he developed
strong symptoms of what is called Gulf War Syndrome and has never been
able to return to either school or work.  My cousins and my friends are
never far from my thoughts in my concerns that this disease be
aggressively identified, treated, and social services made available
for sufferers and their families immediately.
<p>
Of course, I would see part of my job as communicating back to PWCs
information gained through membership on the committee.  I also have
concerns that I would like to see raised with this group:
<p>
<ol>
<li>An end to the hypochondria (or functional somaticizing) myth.  This
myth gives practitioners carte blanche to totally disregard the
patient's own descriptions of his/her illness, and thus delays
unnecessarily diagnosis and treatment.
 
<li>A more appropriate name for the disease.  The public and the
general medical profession too often perceive "chronic fatigue" and
"chronic fatigue syndrome" to be  interchangeable terms.

<li>An aggressive publicity campaign to inform general practitioners
and HMO family doctors of the seriousness of this disease and its
primary symptoms.  These doctors also need information as to where to
send a patient who is suspected of having chronic fatigue syndrome, and
what the current standards of treatment are.

<li>The *economically perverse* insurance market needs to be regulated
without further delay:  all the economic incentives currently operate
to deny disabled CFIDS sufferers the benefits that they understood they
were to receive when they paid for long-term disability coverage.

<li>There needs to be a way to produce a social security disability
application appropriate to CFIDS (and other similar diseases).  The
unnecessary delays produced by premature denials that in the end are
reversed on appeal are not only cruel and harmful to CFIDS sufferers
and their families, but also costly for the government.  Surely there
is a way to translate the information gained from approved CFIDS
applications at the appeals level into a usable form that can make it
easier for front-line workers to make a proper determination.

<li>The mechanism for distributing research funds needs to be
rationalized and publicized.  There is also critical need for a
clearing house of information -- ALL types of information, from all
sources in the world.  The contenders for causes, tests, treatment
plans, and "cures" for CFIDS are so numerous and so diverse that the
practice of singling out a few and ignoring the rest is not in the best
interests of scientific research  or unlocking the key to this
illness.

<li>There needs to be a concerted effort to construct a diagnostic
criteria for the phenomenon of slow-onset CFIDS.  These patients are
not diagnosed until they are gravely ill. Once a slow-onset patient has
collapsed with the final stage of CFIDS onset, he or she too often is
completely disabled and remains so for many years.  A pamphlet should
be developed describing the warning signs of slow-onset, so that
doctors can begin treatment at an earlier stage, and perhaps some level
of productivity can be maintained by the patient with accomodations and
rest.
 
<li>We now know that CFIDS is definitely not the "yuppie flu".  It is
distributed equally among those of all races, income groups, and
geographic locality.  The ratio of male to female victims is much
closer than originally thought, currently estimated at 60:40.  Yet the
profile of those who have been diagnosed with this disease remains in
the upper income brackets, mostly white, mostly well-educated portions
of the population.  What happens to those in the lower half of income
and wealth in this country if afflicted with this disease, when they
cannot get a diagnosis?   This is perhaps my most serious concern to be
addressed by the CFS-ICC.
 
<li>The ICC itself affords a wonderful opportunity for productive
coordination among the different government agencies concerned with
CFIDS.  I am looking forward to helping create a spirit of cooperation
and action.
</ol>
But the main reason I would like to serve on the CFS-(I)CC is for the
opportunity to tell the stories, and raise the concerns, of the many
PWCs I have been fortunate to meet on Internet over the past year and a
half.
<p>
Dr. Mary Schweitzer, Assoc. Professor, Department of History, Villanova
University (on indefinite medical leave since the end of 1994)
<p>

<b>CURRICULUM VITA - MARY SCHWEITZER</b>
