<blockquote>
<b>LETTER OF INTEREST-JOHN FRIEDLICH</b>
<p>
Date: 96-07-22 09:38:02 EDT
<p>
To whom it may concern:
 <p>
    If enough people thought I could contribute as a  CFSCC PWC
representative, wanted me to take it on, and were willing to form the kind
of communication network I speak of in following piece (attached below), I
would be willing to do so.<p>
    I believe the CFSCC representative positions could be and must be a
truly bi-directional representation. It must be more than just voice for
PWCs; I feel representatives should take an active role in helping to
create that bi-directional communication network of communication.<p>
    The issue isn't whether I would be interested/willing to take on that
role, but what would be best for the CFS/CFIDS/M.E. community. Whoever
takes on such a representative role must do so without any preconceived
agendas or be biased by one groups agendas or another's. I envision an
individual in such a position being far more than merely a PWC acting as a
representative and participating in government meetings behind closed
doors. It's a position with tremendous potential to also unify the PWC
community despite the wide variances of opinions and agendas and to be a
stimulus for actions that could put PWC in the drivers seat of political
advocacy.<p>
    There's a vast reservoir of talent among PWCs and I suspect there are
many who might be more qualified than I am to take on such a role. If a
more qualified individual were willing to take on the kind of role I speak
of, I would prefer to place my support for that individual.<p>
    That said, if enough people truly wanted me in such a position, yes, I
would be willing to take it on.
 <p>
John Friedlich
<p>
<b>BIOGRAPHY - JOHN FRIEDLICH</b>
<p>

<b> Biographical information</b>
<p> 
     For those who don't know me, here is a rather verbose introduction I
 had on my hard drive.
 <p>
     Where to begin? Give me a moment to boot up the gray matter... OK. My
 background in medicine has not always been that of a substitute for an lab
 rat.
<p>
     In my early years I worked for Tufts University providing photographic
 services, for Harvard Medical School in one of their medical film
 departments, and ran a multi media department at Suffolk University.<p>
     Most of my professional career has been in medical photography. This
 work entailed providing photographic services to doctors and hospital
 departments, primarily for research, publication, and continuing education
 purposes -- the kind of photographs seen in medical journals and books. It
 meant working directly with the doctors, gaining an understanding of the
 work they were doing, and finding the clearest ways of photographically
 document the information they wished to convey. What was most thrilling was
 being part of the research team and watching the work evolve, often many
 years before it was publicly disclosed.<p>
     Later, my work evolved to encompass my passion for medical graphics.
 While working in the photo department of a Brigham and Women's Hospital in
 Boston, I started a freelance business providing graphic, computer-graphic,
 and desktop publishing services to doctors and hospital departments.<p>
     Soon I found that the two jobs had taken over my life, consuming well
 over a hundred hours a week so I left my position at the hospital. No, I
 didn't slow down; I just let my own business expand its consumption of my
 life. I took on more employees, expanded my office and services, hired a
 financial consulting firm a law firm, and watched my business growing and
 gaining a significant position in the local market. The medical
 computer-graphic business in the down town Boston area alone was well over
 10 million dollars annually and my company was on the verge of capturing a
 major portion of it when I got sick.<p>
     My work was probably the straw that broke the camel's back. When I
 wasn't working hard I was playing hard. I loved sailing, skiing, scuba
 diving, rock climbing, backpacking, racing a sport car, and generally
 having fun wherever I could find it.  All that changed abruptly with the
 onset of CFS/CFIDS/M.E..<p>
     I had been working over 100 hours a week. I got a flu-like illness, but
 kept working right through it. Then one day I started experiencing numbness
 on my entire left side, didn't know my wife's name, and was getting lost in
 my own home.  That was in 1988 and almost everything has been in boxes ever
 since.<p>
     I was a lucky one though -- I didn't have to endure the medical
 treadmill system of diagnosis -- no hazing or initiation rights to join the
 exclusive ranks of PWCs. My onset was so profound even the most skeptical
 physicians couldn't deny SOMETHING was seriously wrong. After a battery of
 neurologic exams I was sent to the emergency ward and immediately admitted
 to the hospital for more tests -- tentative diagnosis: stroke, brain tumor,
 or MS.<p>
     Instead of years of pinball action from one doctor and lab to another,
 the doctors consolidated the process into 8 glorious days on an intensive
 care floor of Brigham and Women's Hospital. They left no privacy unturned.<p>
     Since it was October the interns had only been doctors for 3 months, my
 illness truly shook up their professional confidence! CFS/CFIDS/M.E. still
 hadn't gotten any significant coverage in their textbooks. I did my best to
 appear appreciative of all the attention, but finally drew the line when an
 intern wanted to do her first spinal on me. I agreed to allow her to do the
 procedure on the condition that I could do one to her. A doctor with
 experience did it and got positive results -- elevated white blood cells
 and slightly elevated pressure -- of course they had no idea why.<p>
     The parade of white coats continued for 8 days. I felt more like a
 street person in Penn Station. I'm still not convince that all those
 doctors were aware that I was in the bed as they endlessly speculated and
 argued about possible diagnosis within ear shot. Eventually my internist
 returned and unknown to me he had been conducting research on something
 called chronic fatigue syndrome -- his name, Dr. Komaroff. Finally
 graduation day came -- the word was they had ruled out everything they
 possibly could and if my symptoms continued for 6 months then I'd get the
 official stamp of approval for "chronic fatigue syndrome." Some of the
 doctors were disappointed at the final diagnosis. I didn't know what to
 think -- I still don't.<p>
     As an adjunct to my professional career I also have had a long history
 of involvement in volunteer work. In the 1970s I played a central role in
 the establishment of a drug and alcohol hotline and crisis center. As one
 of the founders and a member of the board of directors, I worked closely
 with town officials, local hospitals, doctors, lawyers, parents, and local
 youth in the development and administration of the organization. I also
 help on the hotline and in the center.<p>
     Until getting CFS/CFIDS/M.E. I was a member of and chairman of a human
 rights committee monitoring and protecting the rights of mentally
 handicapped individuals in our community.  This work entailed working with
 local agencies, the clients, government agencies, clients' families,
 doctors, and police departments. 
     Some of my less demanding volunteer work has been in a local hospital
 and on a number of emergency relief funds.<p>
     Since 1992 I have tried to contribute as much as I could on FIDONET,
 the CFS area of Genie, the CFS area of Prodigy, the CFS and FMS areas of
 America On-line, and the CFS area of the Apple network. For the past half
 year or so I have been an official "special contributor the CFS area of
 Prodigy.<p>
 
 <b>POST ONSET</b>
 <p>
     I eventually became active in the Mass. CFIDS Association, found myself
 doing the desktop publishing of their quarterly 40 page newsletter, ran a
 support group, participated in two others, was an active board member,
 helped at the quarterly state meetings, was receiving 20-40 patient calls a
 day, and eventually became a vice president for the organization.<p>
     Through my activities I developed an increasing interest in patient
 advocacy and health care politics in general. I began writing frequent
 articles for CFS/CFIDS/M.E. newsletters and writing to medical reporters,
 newspapers, and television producers. I appeared in about half a dozen
 television pieces. Almost all my functional hours while my family was out
 during the days were going into the organization and CFS/CFIDS/M.E. related
 matters. As a recreational outlet I produced cartoons about CFS/CFIDS/M.E..
 I felt my involvement in advocacy and support efforts was the one thing I
 could do that might have an effect on increasing public awareness,
 research, and in turn my future health.<p>
     The local association was a very grassroots organization with a lot of
 internal problems and hesitancy to initiate changes that would have enabled
 it to grow and gain increased respectability among the medical community.
 As CFS/CFIDS/M.E. progressively spilled over into my family time and my
 frustrations with the local association grew I eventually decided that my
 efforts on broader national issues might have more impact so I resigned and
 began working independently.<p>
     In mid 1992 I had many discussions with The CFIDS Association of
 America about utilizing the computer networks and new automated fax
 technology. We discussed the vast possibilities of computer networking.
 When they were unable to set up an area that they felt would meet their
 needs on one of the commercial services they encouraged me to try creating
 a PWC initiated networking effort. I sent out a number of posts on FIDONET,
 Genie, and Prodigy asking for input and PWCs interested in taking part in a
 computer organization to share resources through the Internet, link
 CFS/CFIDS/M.E. computer boards and support groups, create a database of
 PWCs willing to contribute professional resources, and to be a proactive
 organization. The first people involved were Roger Burns, Molly Holzschlag,
 Sandy Shaw, Matt Straznitskas, eventually Maryka Ford, and myself. While it
 became apparent that the effort was gaining momentum, it got off to a very
 rocky start. Because others had far greater computer communications
 experience than I did, which appeared more important to the efforts
 success, and in order to not impede progress, I withdrew from the group.
 Although few of the effort's potentials were ever initiated, it was from
 our initial meetings that the CFIDS Computer Networking Project evolved.<p>
     I have also been active in writing to those in the Senate and Congress,
 government officials, and been an official "special contributor" on the
 Prodigy Medical Support CFS bulletin board.
 <p>
 John Friedlich
<p>
