disguised as a web service</a>
<li><a href="list/">My coldlist</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="list/geek.html">Geek Reference</a>
/ <a href="list/media.html">Media</a>
/ <a href="list/personal.html">Personal Spaces</a>
/ <a href="list/printed.html">Printed Matter</a>
/ <a href="list/search.html">Searching and Collations</a>
/ <a href="list/etc.html">Etc.</a>
</ul>
<li>Random bits of prose and cultural effluvia
<ul>
<li><a href="words/eye">I Went To The Eye Doctor And All I Got Was This Lousy Photo</a>
<li><a href="words/hair.html">Two Amusing Anecdotes About My Hair</a>
</ul>
<li><a href="../../private/">Private stuff</a> (<a href="dont-bother.html">don't bother</a>)
</ul>

<h3>Features</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.sgi.com/grafica/future/index.html">Futurist Programming</a>. If you're of a computer "science" bent at all, check this out. It's a half (perhaps completely?) serious rail against current practices in the field. Check out especailly the translations of popular terms in the <a href="http://www.sgi.com/grafica/future/futnotes.html">notes</a> section.
<li><a href="http://www.webcom.com/~walsh/">Internet Info</a> is a pretty presumptuous name, but the info is pretty interesting; basically this guy tracks domain name registrations and notices interesting trends (like the 133 new domains registered by Kraft during August '95).
<li><a href="http://raindrop.ranma.com/loki/die.html">The Unpleasant Way To
Die Of The Day Page</a>. What more can I say?
<li><a href="http://www.dnai.com/g-think/$$pressrelease.html">Turning the tables on junk mailers</a> or something like that. Patrick Combs is in the middle of a bizarre adventure that began with him depositing a junk mail pseudo-check for about $95,000... and it wasn't rejected!
<li><a href="http://www.xmission.com/~grue/whale">The Exploding Whale</a>. It's not an urban legend, and you can download the movie to prove it.
<li><a href="http://www.sirius.com/~dbh/momias.html">Museo de las Momias</a>. That is, the Museum of Mummies. Not for the faint of heart--it's images from a museum that specializes in what its name suggests.
<li><a href="http://gecko.desires.com/1.2/art/docs/lovegrid.html">The
Lovegrid</a>, self-described as a "shocking photo expos&eacute; of the
lesbian Barbie scene." Not to be missed.
<li><a href="http://thomas.loc.gov/">The Thomas Server: Legislative
Information on the Internet</a>. This includes the full text of
all house and senate bills from the 1994 and 1995 sessions of Congress,
among other interesting things.
<li><a href="http://if.arc.ab.ca/IF.shtml">Idea Futures
Market</a>.
This is a nifty concept I first read about a couple years ago, and some
crazy Canadians went and set one up for real (well, sort of--you use fake
money).
</ul>

<p><hr>
<h2><center>My Book About Me</center></h2>
<center><i>(Remember, it's not a home page unless you have something extremely
self-centered on it!)</i></center>
<p>

I started my career as one of the founders of 
Kaleida Labs (may she R.I.P.), makers of
<a href="http://dev3.info.apple.com/scriptx/index.html">ScriptX</a>
(a pretty cool multimedia programming system, which has lately morphed
into a net-centric Java thingy). More currently,
I am at <a href="http://www.communities.com/">Electric Communities</a>,
working on their distributed programming language <i>E</i>. But
enough about work. (If you
care, you can read my <a href="resume/">resume</a>.)

<p>
When I'm not chained to my computer bringing home the cured pig innards,
I've been known to do digital art (still chained to the computer, but
just not as much innards) in several forms: visual--molesting images
for 
<a href="http://www.sito.org/synergy/panic.html">PANIC</a>
or other
<a href="http://www.sito.org/">OTIS/SITO</a> work
(something I haven't done enough of in ages)
or who knows what else (or just for personal pleasure);
audio--chained also to my musical gear at home, making strange
ambient/industrial/techno noises (if only to get back at the neighbor's
dog). Actually, pig innards may in fact be in my future for music:
I appear on <cite>Children of Mind/Body</cite>; see
<a href="../../fuzzboy/">the Fuzzboy Page</a> for more details.

<p>
When I'm not doing any of the above, I'm probably watching Kung-Fu
movies at <a href="http://www.cameranet.com/">The Towne Theater</a> 
in San Jose, or, even more likely,
getting my earwax flaked out at a 
<a href="http://www.dnx.com/vamp/Gothic/clublist.html">goth</a> or
industrial club</a>
or elsewhere, perhaps to the rhythms of a good band from
<A HREF="http://www.atext.com/people/graham/the-list/"><tt>the-list</tt></a>.

<p>
If you use something of mine from this site, let me know. If it's 
not-for-profit stuff, then just use it and give me credit. 
If it's for-profit, then email me, and we can work something out.

<p>
<address>-dan</address>
</body>
