<head>
<title>Barcode Server</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Barcode Server</h1>
<hr><p>

<p>
Fill in the field below with a 12-digit barcode, y'know, like those
UPC things see on food, or the codes on CDs and tapes. If you want to
have me generate a checksum for you, then just fill in 11 digits.
By the way, those digits you see to the left and the right of
the barcodes are part of the number.
<p>
<form ACTION="barcode-request.cgi" METHOD="POST">
<p>
Number: <input TYPE="text" NAME="num" SIZE=20 MAXLENGTH=18>
<input TYPE="submit" VALUE="Encode it">
<input TYPE="reset" VALUE="Reset form">
</form>
<p><hr><p>
This toy was inspired by the October 2, 1994 edition of
<a href="http://www.nbn.com/youcan/"><cite>You Can With
Beakman and Jax</cite></a>, which featured a 
<a href="http://www.nbn.com/youcan/upc/barcode.html">pretty good 
description of how barcodes work</a>. For the technically inclined,
you can <a href="barcode.c.txt">check out the source code</a>, and
you can even use it if you want to, but you <em>must</em> abide
by the terms given in the header comment. In particular, if you use
it, give me credit and <a href="mailto:danfuzz@milk.com">mail me</a>
to let me know that you are (and give me a URL to check out!), and
finally: I don't have the time or resources to offer support for it,
so please don't ask.
<p>
Enjoy!
<p><hr>
<a HREF="../home/danfuzz/"><address>-dan</address></a>
</body>
